<L>Withouten hors / dayly ye may see:<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Withouten</I>] H, Without L, With oute R.</NOTE></L>
<L N="110">Tilth&euml; were lost, ne wer&euml; hors parde;<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>ne were</I>] ner we H. <I>Tilthe</I>] LH, Tillyng R. <I>were</I>] LH, were we R.</NOTE></L>
<L>The besi Marchant / to his &aacute;vauntage<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>besi</I>] H, best L.</NOTE></L>
<L N="112">Nar shippis &amp; hors / coude make no cariage.<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Nar. .hors</I>] Ner. .horses H. <I>make</I>] LH, haue R.</NOTE>
<PB REF="00000070.tif" N="20"></L>
</LG>
<LG N="17" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(17)</HEAD>
<L N="113">&para; "The shipe, bi liknesse / is clepid an hors of tree<MILESTONE N="69" UNIT="folio"><NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>bi</I>] in H, be R. <I>clepid</I>] LH, callid R.</NOTE></L>
<L>(Ful notably / who can vndirstond,)</L>
<L>To leden men / &amp; carien ouer see<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>carien</I>] carye hem ouer the see HR.</NOTE></L>
<L>As don these hors whan thei are come to lond:<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>hors. .are</I>] horsis they H, horse whan they R.</NOTE></L>
<L N="117">The poor man / ladith vpon a lond<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>vpon</I>] eke in H, eke ledith in R.</NOTE></L>
