<HEAD>&para; The Auctour makith a Lenvoie vpon alle the mateere be-fore said.<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>The Auctour</I>. .] &para; The moralite of the hors, the goose, and the sheepe, trans|lated by Dan Iohn Lidgate, H, in margin.</NOTE></HEAD>
<LG N="78" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(78)</HEAD>
<L N="540">&para; Off this fable / conceivith the sentence;<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>the</I>] this H.</NOTE></L>
<L>At good leiser / doth the mateer see,</L>
<L>Which inporteth gret intelligence</L>
<L>Yiff ye list tak&euml; / the moralite</L>
<L N="544">Profitable to euery comounte,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>co|mounte</I>] comunalte H.</NOTE></L>
<L>Which includith in many sondry wise,</L>
<L>No man shuld / of hih nor lowe degre,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>nor</I>] or H.</NOTE></L>
<L N="547">For no prerogatiff / his neighbore to despise.<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>to despise</I>] despise La, to dispise H.</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG N="79" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(79)</HEAD>
<L N="548">&para; Som man is strong / hardi as a leoun</L>
<L>To bynd&euml; Beeris / or Booris to oppresse,</L>
<L>Wher-as anothir / hath gret discrec&iuml;oun:</L>
<L N="551">Som man hooly / liveth in parfitnesse,</L>
<L>A-nothir besi / to gadre gret richesse;</L>
<L>But with al this / tak heed of this emprise,</L>
<L>No man presume / so hih his hornes dresse,</L>
<L N="555">For no prerogatiff / his neihbour to despise.<NOTE PLACE="foot">548-555] H omits.</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG N="80" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(80)</HEAD>
<L N="556">&para; Trappures of gold / ordeyned were for steedis;<MILESTONE N="77" UNIT="folio"></L>
