<LABEL>.27.</LABEL>
<ITEM>The Prymer in Englissh.</ITEM>
<LABEL>.28.</LABEL>
<ITEM>The Psalter in Englissh.</ITEM>
<LABEL>.29.</LABEL>
<ITEM>A Dyalog betwixt the gentylman and the plowman.</ITEM>
<LABEL>.30.</LABEL>
<ITEM>Ionas In Englissh. And all other suspect bokes, bothe in Englissh and in laten, as well now printed or that here-after shall be printed, and not here afore namyd.</ITEM>
</LIST>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 TYPE="poem">
<HEAD>A Cale of Ryght Nought.</HEAD>
<HEADNOTE><P>[<I>Egerton MS</I>. 1995.]</P></HEADNOTE>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>There was a man that hadde nought;</L>
<L>There come theuys &amp; robbed hym, &amp; toke nought:</L>
<L>He ranne owte, and cryde nought.</L>
<L>Why shoulde he crye? he loste nought.</L>
<L>Here ys a tale of ryght nought.
</L>
</LG>

</DIV2>
<DIV2 TYPE="poem"><PB REF="00000114.tif" N="64">
<HEAD>A Medicine to Restore Nature in a Man.</HEAD>
<HEADNOTE><P>[<I>Lambeth MS</I>. 306, <I>leaf</I> 65, <I>back, col</I>. 2.]</P></HEADNOTE>
<P>Take iij Chekyns or .iiij. as ye lyke, &amp; put them in a coope to feede, as I shall teche you. Fyrste take a quantyte of whete, &amp; put yt in clene watyr, &amp; then gadyr a good quantyte of Snayles that beer howses on them, &amp; put them therto as they be, shelles &amp; all; and yf ye canne fynde no soche snayles, thanne take blak snayles, and so thanne boyle all these to-gyder, the whete &amp; the snayles in water, with the shelles of them that haue shelles; &amp; for lakke of them that haue shelles, boyle the blakke snayles. And whan it is well boylid to-gedyr, then take oute the whete by hym|selfe, &amp; the watyr by hym-selfe, &amp; caste awey the shelles &amp; the corruptyon of the snaylles; And with that whete fede the checons, and with brede a-monge, And let them drynke of the watyr, &amp; of none other watyr. And when ye be dysposyd, ete a Chekyn, one day rostyd, And ij dayes after, a-nother, &amp; so contynue as ye fynde yt doth you good.<NOTE PLACE="end">Probatum est.</NOTE></P>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 TYPE="poem">
<HEAD>For to Dystroy a Wrang Nayle, othewyse callyd a Corne.</HEAD>
<HEADNOTE><P>[<I>Ibid</I>.]</P></HEADNOTE> 
<P>Take wylde tansey, and grynde yt, and make yt neshe, &amp; ley it therto, and it wyl bryng yt owght.
</P>

</DIV2>
<DIV2 TYPE="poem"><PB REF="00000115.tif" N="65">
<HEAD>Of the Seats of the Passions.</HEAD>
<HEADNOTE><P>[<I>Lambeth MS</I>. 306, <I>fol</I>. 118, <I>at foot</I>.]</P></HEADNOTE>
<P>The bones in a man ben in nombre .ij C. xvij. The veynes ben .iij. C. lxv. The tethe in perfyte Age .xxxij. The mynde is in the Brayne. The vndyr|stondyng in the fronte. The Ire in the gawle. Auaryce in the kydney. Loue in the harte. Brethyng in the lownges. Gladnes in the splene. Thought in the harte. Blode in the body. Hope in the sowle. The mynde in the spyrit. The harte in the mynde. The Feyth in the harte. And cryst in the feyth. And whylth it noryssh the body, it is cawlyd Anima, the sowle. This worde Anima hath many significacions, for when it is in con|templacyon, it is sayde a spyrit, <B>Spiritus</B>. And when it savyrth, it is saide Reson or wytte, Animus. And when it felith, it is sayde felyng, <B>sensus</B>. And when it vnderstondyth, it is callyd mynde, <B>Mens</B>. And when it demyth, it is called <B>Reson, Racio</B>. And when it consentyth, it is callyd <B>wylle, Voluntas</B>. And when it recordyth, it is sayde <B>mynde, Memoria.</B>
</P>

</DIV2>
<DIV2 TYPE="poem"><PB REF="00000116.tif" N="66">
<HEAD>A Greeting on New Year's Morning.</HEAD>
<HEADNOTE><P>[<I>Lambeth MS</I>. 306, <I>leaf</I> 136, <I>back</I>.]</P></HEADNOTE>
<LG N="1" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(1)</HEAD>
<L N="1">Iuellis pricious cane y none fynde to Sell</L>
<L>to sende you, my Souerein, &thorn;is newe yeres morowe,</L>
<L>wher-for, [for] lucke and good hanssell,</L>
<L>my hert y sende you, &amp; seynt Iohn to borowe,</L>
<L N="5">that an C yeres withouton aduerssit[e] &amp; Sorowe</L>
<L>ye mowe live: y pray to god &thorn;at ye so moote,</L>
<L>And of all your Dessires, to sende you hastely bot.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="2" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(2)</HEAD>
<L N="8">Beseching you, Dere heret, as Enterly as y cane,</L>
<L>to take en gre this poure gifte Onely for my sake,</L>
<L>as is the custome, &amp; hath ben ma[n]y a Day,</L>
<L>Oo frend to a-nother yeve and take.</L>
<L N="12">Riche is it nat, grete boste of to make,</L>
<L>Saue an hert is reme[m]bratyf to you in eueri stounde</L>
<L>the whiche perisschide ones, yet grene is &thorn;e wonde.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="3" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(3)</HEAD>
<L N="15">That it be youres, trewely it is my liste;</L>
<L>my possesioon and my parte &thorn;er-of y denye;</L>
<L>and as towcheing to &thorn;is olde worlde called 'hadywiste,'</L>
<L>Vnto my lives ende ful y Deffie.</L>
<L N="19">palaman gafe his herte to emely;</L>
<L>He fuched it no better, ne repentide it les</L>
<L N="21">thanne y do of this gifte, god y take to witnes.
<PB REF="00000117.tif" N="67"></L>
</LG>
<LG N="4" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(4)</HEAD>
<L N="22">my purpos hathe ben longe my hert thus to chast,</L>
<L>And til this yeres day y ne durst for schame.</L>
<L>men sei that no thinge is so free as gyfte,</L>
<L>And to take it ayene y were fulle to blame;</L>
<L N="26">But as in that deffaute y wille not lese my name,</L>
<L>So that y yeue ones be yeve for euermore,</L>
<L>For this hath loue and trouth y-lerned me &thorn;e lore,</L>
<L>Euermore without chaung for euer</L>
<L N="30">til body and soule parte and disseuere.
</L>
</LG>

</DIV2>
<DIV2 TYPE="poem"><PB REF="00000118.tif" N="68">
<HEAD>To my Heart's Joy.</HEAD>
<HEADNOTE><P>[<I>Lambeth MS</I>. 306, <I>leaf</I> 137.]</P></HEADNOTE>
<LG N="1" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(1)</HEAD>
<L N="1">My hertes Ioie, all myn hole plesaunce,</L>
<L>whiche that y sarue, and schall do faithfully</L>
<L>with treue Entente and humble obseruaunce</L>
<L>you for to please in that y cane treuely,</L>
<L N="5">besechinge youe, this litil bill and y</L>
<L>may hertely, with som plesaunce &amp; drede,</L>
<L>be Recomaundide moste specially</L>
<L N="8">vnto you, the floure of goodely-hede.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="2" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(2)</HEAD>
<L N="9">And yf ye liste to haue knoweliche of my part,</L>
<L>I am in hel, god thanked mote he be,</L>
<L>as of body, bute treuely nat in herte,</L>
<L>nor nat schall be til tyme y may you see;</L>
<L N="13">but thynketh that y as trewely will be he</L>
<L>that for youre Ease schall do my pouer &amp; my&yogh;te,</L>
<L>And schall be your Deffence in all aduerssite</L>
<L N="16">As though that y were dayly in your sight.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="3" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(3)</HEAD>
<L N="17">I write no more to you, for lacke of space,</L>
<L>but y beseche the holy trin[i]te</L>
<L>you kepe and save, be sopporte of his grace,</L>
<L>and be youre Deffence in all aduerssite.</L>
<L N="21">go, litil bill, and say thoue were with me,</L>
<L>this same day at myne vp-Ryssinge,</L>
<L>where that y be-sought god of merci</L>
<L N="24">tho to haue my Souerein in his kepeing.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="4" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(4)</HEAD>
<L>As wyssely god me save</L>
<L>as y am onely yours,</L>
<L>what payne so euer y haue</L>
<L N="28">And will be at all owres.
</L>
</LG>

</DIV2>
<DIV2 TYPE="poem"><PB REF="00000119.tif" N="69">
<HEAD>To my Lady Dear.</HEAD>
<HEADNOTE><P>[<I>Lambeth MS</I>. 306, <I>leaf</I> 138.]</P></HEADNOTE>
<LG N="1" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(1)</HEAD>
<L N="1">Frische flour of womanly nature,</L>
<L>ye be full gentill and goodly one to se,</L>
<L>And all so stedfaste as any criatur</L>
<L>that is lyuynge in any degre,</L>
<L N="5">fullfyled with all benyngnete,</L>
<L>And an Exsample of all worthynes,</L>
<L>And they that to you haue nessesite</L>
<L N="8">be gracious euer thorough your gentilnes.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="2" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(2)</HEAD>
<L N="9">But y am so bowndon, y may nat stert,</L>
<L>to you complayning in this manere,</L>
<L>Besechinge you euer with myn enterly hert,</L>
<L>And humbly also y you Requer,</L>
<L N="13">As that bethe onely withowten pere</L>
<L>of goodely-hede and of assuraunce,</L>
<L>y that am yours, whethe[r] ye be fare or ner,</L>
<L N="16">Reffuse me nat oute of your R&eacute;me[<I>m</I>]braunce.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="3" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(3)</HEAD>
<L N="17">Concedire, ladi dere, of your pete,<MILESTONE N="138b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>the highe complaynt of my desses,</L>
<L>my gref and myn aduerssite!</L>
<L>ye be my bote &thorn;at may me best please;</L>
<L N="21">schewe me your meke sprite in my desses,</L>
<L>for other louer haue y none,</L>
<L>And euer y well be Redy youe for to plesse,</L>
<L N="24">neuer none to haue bute you alone.
<PB REF="00000120.tif" N="70"></L>
</LG>
<LG N="4" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(4)</HEAD>
<L N="25">None but you, lady and maistras,</L>
<L>fro whos herte with lyue myn may no disseuer,</L>
<L>so faste it is lokyn in &thorn;e locke of stedfastnes</L>
<L>that in your seruice it schall abide for euer.</L>
<L N="29">ye wete well my woo ye may recouere;</L>
<L>my paynes to Rellis may non bute yee,</L>
<L>my lyfe And deth lithe in you euer,</L>
<L N="32">Right as it plesithe you to save or to flee.</L>
<L>lothe to offende! so y may my lady pleas,</L>
<L>welcome payne, And Fie one esse!<NOTE PLACE="end">[On the next folio (139), "Her begyneth the Retenewe of the dowty kynge k Edwarde the thirde, and howe he went to the sege of Callis with his Oste," etc.]</NOTE>
</L>
</LG>

</DIV2>
<DIV2 TYPE="poem"><PB REF="00000121.tif" N="71">
<HEAD>Unto my Lady, the Flower of Womanhood.</HEAD>
<HEADNOTE><P>[<I>Lambeth MS</I>. 306, <I>leaf</I> 137, <I>back</I>.]</P></HEADNOTE>
<LG N="1" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(1)</HEAD>
<L N="1">That pasaunt Goodnes, the Rote of all vertve,</L>
<L>whiche Rotide is in youre femynete,</L>
<L>whos stepes glade to Ensue.</L>
<L>ys eueri woman in their degre!</L>
<L N="5">And sethe that ye are floure of bewte,</L>
<L>Constreyned y am, magre myn hede,</L>
<L N="7">hartely to loue youre womanhede.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="2" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(2)</HEAD>
<L N="8">Your sade, Demewre, appert, goueronance</L>
<L>Of eliquens prengnavnt sauns coloure,</L>
<L>So it Renyth in my Rememberaunce</L>
<L>that dayly, nyghtly, tyde, tyme, and owre,</L>
<L N="12">hit is my will to purches youre fauoure,</L>
<L>whiche, wilde to Crist I myght atteyn,</L>
<L N="14">As ye of all floures Are my Souerayn.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="3" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(3)</HEAD>
<L N="15">Whan Reste And slepe y shulde haue noxiall,</L>
<L>As Requereth bothe nature and kynde,</L>
<L>than trobled are my wittes all,</L>
<L>so sodeynly Renyth in my mynde</L>
<L N="19">your grete bewte! me thynketh than y fynde</L>
<L>you as gripyng in myn armes twey;</L>
<L N="21">Bute whan y wake, ye Are away.
<PB REF="00000122.tif" N="72"></L>
</LG>
<LG N="4" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(4)</HEAD>
<L N="22">Entirmet this with woo And gladnes,</L>
<L>bothe Ioye and sorowe in woo memorall,</L>
<L>for than me thynkithe y see your likenes:</L>
<L>Hit is nat so, it is fantasticall;</L>
<L N="26">the whiche my herte with &thorn;e swarde mortall</L>
<L>that nothinge is, saue uery Dethe,</L>
<L N="28">my wette is thynne, so schortithe my breth.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="5" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(5)</HEAD>
<L N="29">Nowe, lady myn, in whom&euml; Vertus Alle<MILESTONE N="138" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>ar Ioined, and also comprehendide,</L>
<L>as ye of al women y call moste principall,</L>
<L>lette my gref in youre herte be entenderde,</L>
<L N="33">And also my veri treue loue Rememberde,</L>
<L>And, for my treve loue, ayene me to loue,</L>
<L N="35">As welethe nature, and god that setithe Above.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="6" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(6)</HEAD>
<L N="36">Go litill bill, with all humblis,</L>
<L>vnto my lady, of womanhede &thorn;e floure,</L>
<L>and saie hire howe newe troiles lithe in distre&yogh;</L>
<L N="39">All onely for hire sake, and in mortall langoure;</L>
<L>And if sche wot nat whoo it is, bute stonde in erore,</L>
<L>Say it is hire olde louer<NOTE PLACE="foot">The word looks like <I>loli</I> in the MS., but <I>u</I>, with the con|traction for <I>er</I>, is written the same way at the end of <I>disseuer</I> (p. 70, l. 26), showing that louer is the right reading here.</NOTE> &thorn;at loueth hire so trewe,</L>
<L N="42">hire louynge a-lone, not schanginge for no newe.</L>
<TRAILER>EXPLICIT.
</TRAILER>

</LG>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 TYPE="poem"><PB REF="00000123.tif" N="73">
<HEAD>Bewte will Shewe, thow Hornys be Away.</HEAD>
<HEAD>(A LITELLE SHORT DITEY AGAYNE HORNES.) </HEAD>
<HEADNOTE><P>(9 stanzas of eights, <I>abab, bcbc</I>.) [<I>MS. Univ. Lib. Camb. Hh</I>. 4. 12, <I>leaf</I> 84 <I>a, collated with Harleian</I> 2255, <I>leaf</I> 6.]</P></HEADNOTE>
<LG N="1" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(1)</HEAD>
<L N="1">Of god and kynd procedyth all beaulte;</L>
<L>Crafte may shew a foren apparence,</L>
<L>But nature ay must haf &thorn;<SUP>e</SUP> soueraynte.</L>
<L>Thyng countirfetyd<NOTE PLACE="foot">countirfet H.</NOTE> hath non &eacute;xistence;</L>
<L N="5">Twene gold and gossomer is gret difference;</L>
<L>Trew&euml; metall requirith non alay;</L>
<L>vnto purp&oacute;se by clere experience,</L>
<L N="8">Bewtey will shewe, thow hornys be<NOTE PLACE="foot">wer H.</NOTE> away.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="2" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(2)</HEAD>
<L N="9">&para; Riche attyrys of gold and [of] perry,</L>
<L>Charbunclys, rubeys of most excellence,</L>
<L>Shew in derknes lyght, whereso<NOTE PLACE="foot">wher so H., whersouer C.</NOTE> &thorn;ey be</L>
<L>By their natural heuenly influence;</L>
<L N="13">Doblettes of glasse yeue a gret euidence,</L>
<L>Thyng countirfet wyl failen<NOTE PLACE="foot">faylen H., faile C.</NOTE> at assay;</L>
<L>On thys mater, concludyng in<NOTE PLACE="foot">in H., no C.</NOTE> sentence,</L>
<L N="16">Bewte wyll shew, thow hornes be<NOTE PLACE="foot">were H.</NOTE> away.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="3" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(3)</HEAD>
<L N="17">&para; Aleyn remembryght,<NOTE PLACE="foot">remembryth H.</NOTE> hys c&oacute;mplaynt who<NOTE PLACE="foot">who H., whoso C.</NOTE> list see,</L>
<L>In hys boke of famose eloquence;</L>
<L>Cladd all in flowris, and blossummys<NOTE PLACE="foot">blosmys H.</NOTE> of a tre,</L>
<L>he saw Nature in hyr most excellence,
<PB REF="00000124.tif" N="74"></L>
<L N="21">Vpon hyr hede a kerchef of valence,</L>
<L>None othyr riches of countyrfet aray;</L>
<L>Texemplifye by kyndly prouidence,</L>
<L N="24">Bewte wyll shew thow hornys be<NOTE PLACE="foot">wer H.</NOTE> away.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="4" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(4)</HEAD>
<L N="25">&para; Famose po&euml;tys of antiquite</L>
<L>In Grece and Troy, renowmyd<NOTE PLACE="foot">remowmyd C., renoumyd H.</NOTE> of prudence,</L>
<L>Wrote of qwene Helene, and Penolope,</L>
<L>Of Policene with hyr chast innocence;</L>
<L N="29">ffor wyfys trew call Lucrece to presence;</L>
<L>That they were fayre, ther can no man say nay,</L>
<L>kynd wroght hem with so gret[e] diligence,</L>
<L N="32">Theyr bewte cowde shew,<NOTE PLACE="foot">bewte couthe H.</NOTE> thow hornys were cast away.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="5" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(5)</HEAD>
<L N="33">&para; Clerk&euml;s record by gret auctorite,<MILESTONE N="84b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>hornys wer gyffe to bestis for diffence,</L>
<L>A thyng contr&aacute;ry to feminite,</L>
<L>To be mad sturdy of r&eacute;sistence;</L>
<L N="37">But archwyf&egrave;s,<NOTE PLACE="foot">arche wyves H.</NOTE> eger in ther violence,</L>
<L>fferse as a<NOTE PLACE="foot">a <I>om</I>. H.</NOTE> tigre forto make affray,</L>
<L>They haf despite, and agayne consc&iuml;ence,</L>
<L N="40">list not, of pride, theyre hornys cast away.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="6" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(6) Lenvoye (H. <I>om</I>. C.)</HEAD>
<L N="41">&para; Noble princesse,<NOTE PLACE="foot">pryncessys H.</NOTE> thys litell short ditey,</L>
<L>Rudely compilyd, lat it be none offence</L>
<L>To &yogh;owre womanly mercifull pyte,</L>
<L>Thow it be radd in &yogh;owr audience.</L>
<L N="45">Payse euery<NOTE PLACE="foot">Peysed ech H.</NOTE> thyng in &yogh;owre iust aduertence.</L>
<L>So it be no displesance to &yogh;owre pay,</L>
<L>Vndir support of &yogh;owr pac&iuml;ence,</L>
<L N="48">Yeueth example hornes to cast away.
<PB REF="00000125.tif" N="75"></L>
</LG>
<LG N="7" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(7)</HEAD>
<L N="49">&para; Grettest of vertues is humilite,</L>
<L>As Salamon sayth, son of Sapience,</L>
<L>Most was accepted<NOTE PLACE="foot">acceptyd H., accept C.</NOTE> to the deite.</L>
<L>Take hede here-of, gefe<NOTE PLACE="foot">yeuyth H.</NOTE> to thys word credence,</L>
<L N="53">How Maria, who had a preeminence<NOTE PLACE="foot">premynence H.</NOTE></L>
<L>Aboue all women, in Bedlem whan she lay,</L>
<L>At Cristis byrth, no cloth of gret dispence,</L>
<L N="56">She weryd a keuerche; hornys were cast away.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="8" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(8)</HEAD>
<L N="57">&para; Of byrth&euml;<NOTE PLACE="foot">birthe H., byrth C.</NOTE> she was hyghest of degre,</L>
<L>To whom all angelles did obedience,</L>
<L>Of Dauides lyne, which sprong out of Iesse,</L>
<L>In whom all verteu is,<NOTE PLACE="foot">vertues H.</NOTE> by iust conuenience</L>
<L N="61">Made stable in god by gostly confidence.</L>
<L>This rose of Jerico, ther growith non such in May;</L>
<L>Pure in spirite, parfite in pac&iuml;ence,</L>
<L N="64">In whom all hornys of pride were put away.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="9" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(9)</HEAD>
<L N="65">&para; Moder of Ihesu, myrrour of chastite,<MILESTONE N="85" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>In word nor thowght that neuer did offence;</L>
<L>Trew examplire<NOTE PLACE="foot">Trewe exemplaire H.</NOTE> of virginite,</L>
<L>Hede-spryng and well of parfite continence!</L>
<L N="69">Was neuer clerk, by retoryk or<NOTE PLACE="foot">nor H.</NOTE> science,</L>
<L>Cowde all hyr verteus r&eacute;herse to &thorn;is day.</L>
<L>Noble princesse,<NOTE PLACE="foot">Pryncessys H.</NOTE> of meke beniuolence,</L>
<L N="72">By example<NOTE PLACE="foot">Bexample H.<NOTE PLACE="end">["This Ballad," says Mr. Halliwell (who printed it in his edition of Lydgate's <I>Minor Poems</I>, p. 46-9), "has been printed by Sir Harris Nicolas, and in the <I>Reliqui&aelig; Antiqu&aelig;</I>. The present version is from MS. Oxon. Laud. D. 31, N. 683, Bernard, 798; other copies are in MS. Rawl. Oxon. C. 86; MS. Bibl. Coll. Jes. Cantab. Q. &Gamma;. 8, fol. 27; MS. Harl. 2255; MS. Voss. Lugd. 359; and the first four stanzas in MS. Harl. 2251." It was reprinted in the Percy Society's <I>Satirical Songs and Poems on Costume</I>, 1849, with a woodcut of a woman in a horned bonnet on p. 52.]</NOTE></NOTE> of hyr, &yogh;owre hornys cast away.</L>
<TRAILER>&para; Explicit.
</TRAILER>

</LG>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 TYPE="poem"><PB REF="00000126.tif" N="76">
<HEAD>The Parliament of Love.</HEAD>
<HEADNOTE><P>[MS. Univ. Lib. Camb. Ff. 1. 6, leaf 51. Handwriting of the 15th century.]</P></HEADNOTE>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>What so euyr I syng or sey,</L>
<L>My wyll is good too preyse here well.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Now &yogh;ee that wull of loue lere,</L>
<L>I counsell yow &thorn;at &yogh;e cum nere;</L>
<L>To tell yow now is myne entent,</L>
<L N="4">Houth loue made late his parleament,</L>
<L>And sent for ladyes of euery londe,</L>
<L>Both mayde, and wyfe &thorn;at had housbonde,</L>
<L>Wythe gentyll wymmen of lower degre,</L>
<L N="8">and marchauntz wyfes grete plente,</L>
<L>Wythe maidenes eke &thorn;at where theym vndre,</L>
<L>Of wyche there were a rygthe grete numbre.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>And all tho men &thorn;at louers were<MILESTONE N="51b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="12">They had there charge for too be there,</L>
<L>And when they were assembled all,</L>
<L>(yf I the werre sothe sey schall),</L>
<L>with-in a castell feyre ande stronge,</L>
<L N="16">And as y lokyd them amonge,</L>
<L>I sawe a ry&yogh;th grete cumpany</L>
<L>of gentill-wummen that were there by,</L>
<L>The whyche, as the custum was,</L>
<L N="20">Songe a balad stede of the masse</L>
<L>For goode spede of thes folkys all</L>
<L>&THORN;at where assemblede in the hall;</L>
<L>and yf &yogh;e lyst ley too yowre ere,</L>
<L N="24">Rygh[t] thys they songe, as &yogh;ee schall heyre.</L>
<L>"O god of loue! wyche lorde hart and souereyne,</L>
<L>Send downe thy grace a-monge thys louerys all,
<PB REF="00000127.tif" N="77"></L>
<L>Soo &thorn;at &thorn;ey may too thy mercy ateyne.</L>
<L N="28">At thys parlament most in Asspeciall;</L>
<L>as &thorn;ou art oure Iuge, so be egall</L>
<L>Too euery wygth &thorn;at louyth feythefully,</L>
<L>And aftyr hys dyssert grante hym mercy!"</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="32">And whan this songe was songe and done,<MILESTONE N="52" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>Then went these ladyes eueryschone</L>
<L>Vn-too A schambyr where they scholde</L>
<L>Take theire places, yong and olde,</L>
<L N="36">like as &thorn;at they where of astate</L>
<L>For tescheue all maner debate.</L>
<L>There sawe I first the goddesse of loue</L>
<L>In here see sitte, rigth ferre aboue,</L>
<L N="40">And many othyr &thorn;at ther where.</L>
<L>yitt for too tell whom y sawe there,</L>
<L>It passit now rigth ferre my wytte;</L>
<L>But, among all, I sawe one sitte</L>
<L N="44">whiche was the feyryst creature</L>
<L>&thorn;at euer was furmyd by nature;</L>
<L>and here beaute now too dyscryvye</L>
<L>Ther can noo mannes vyttes alywe.</L>
<L N="48">yett as ferre as y can or may</L>
<L>Of<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. Oof.</NOTE> here beaute sum-what too say,</L>
<L>I will applye my wittes all;</L>
<L>For here I am &amp; euyr schall</L>
<L N="52">Too speke of schape and semelynesse,</L>
<L>Off stature &amp; of goodlynesse;</L>
<L>here sydes longe with myddyll smale,</L>
<L>here face well coulord and not pale,</L>
<L N="56">With white and rode ryth well mesuryd;</L>
<L>And ther-too schee was well emyred,</L>
<L>And stode in euery mannes grace,<MILESTONE N="52b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>This goodly yong and fresche of face;</L>
<L N="60">and too speke of condicion,</L>
<L>Coude noo man fynde in noo region
<PB REF="00000128.tif" N="78"></L>
<L>One of soo grete gentillnesse,</L>
<L>Of curtaise and lowlynesse,</L>
<L N="64">Of chere, of port, and dalyaunce,</L>
<L>And mastres eke of all pleasaunce;</L>
<L>All-soo welle of secretenesse,</L>
<L>The werray merroure of stedfastnesse.</L>
<L N="68">Of onest merth sche cowde rith mosche,</L>
<L>Too daunce and synge and othre suche;</L>
<L>Soo well assuryd in here hert,</L>
<L>That none il worde from here scholde stert.</L>
<L N="72">And thus on here y set my mynde,</L>
<L>And left all othre thyng by-hynde</L>
<L>As touchyng too these louers all,</L>
<L>whysche on here causes fast kan call.</L>
<L N="76">and for too tell theire all cumplayntes,</L>
<L>In sothe too me the matire queynte is;</L>
<L>For as too hem i toke none hede.</L>
<L>But in myne nowne<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Sic</I> in MS.</NOTE> causes<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Sic</I> in MS. Read 'cause.'</NOTE> to prosede,</L>
<L N="80">I drowe me by [my] sylf allone,</L>
<L>And into a corner gan too gone,</L>
<L>And there I satte me downe a while,</L>
<L>A litle bill for too compile</L>
<L N="84">Vn-too thys lady wych was soo faire,<MILESTONE N="53" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>and in her doyng soo debonaire.</L>
<L>And if ye list too hyre &amp; rede,</L>
<L>Theffect of whych was thus in dede:&mdash;</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>[<I>The little Song</I>.]</HEAD>
<L N="88">"O souereyn<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. soueuereyn.</NOTE> prince of all gentillnesse,</L>
<L>Too whom I haue and euyr-more schall bee</L>
<L>Trewe seruant with all maner humblenesse;</L>
<L>What peyne I haue or what aduersyte,</L>
<L N="92">yett &yogh;ee schall euyr fynde suche feyth on me</L>
<L>&THORN;at I schall doo that may be your plesaunce,</L>
<L>If god of his grace list me so a-vaunce.
<PB REF="00000129.tif" N="79"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>"And yow I pray, as lowly as I can,</L>
<L N="96">Too take my seruice if hyt myth yow please;</L>
<L>And if &yogh;ee list too reward thus yowre man,</L>
<L>Than mygth hee say he were in hertis easee;</L>
<L N="99">For by my trouth y wulde not yow displease</L>
<L>For all the goode &thorn;at euer I hadde or schall,</L>
<L N="101">By my goode wille, what euer me be-fall.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="102">"And if I haue seide any<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. my.</NOTE> thynge amysse</L>
<L>Too pardon me I yow be-sech and pray;</L>
<L>For as wischli as euer y cum too blisse,</L>
<L>My will is goode what euer y write or say."</L>
<L N="106">Go, thow litle songe, thow hast a blisfull day;</L>
<L>For sche &thorn;at is the floure of wommanhode</L>
<L N="108">At her oown leyser schall the syng and rede.<NOTE PLACE="end">[<I>La Belle Dame sans Merci</I>, p. 80. See on this, Prof. Skeat's Introduction, Text, and Notes, in his pseudo-Chaucerian pieces, vol. vii. (1897) of his edition of Chaucer's Works, pages li.-lv., 300-326, 517-520, and H. Gr&ouml;hler's earlier notice of Sir Richard Ros in <I>Englische Studien</I>, x. 206, and his dissertation "Ueber Richard Ros' mittelenglische ubersetzung des gedichtes von Alain Chartier, La Belle Dame sans Mercy," Breslau, 1886. Nichols, in his county history of Leicestershire, ii. 37, says that the Sir Richard Ros, who was presumably the poet, was born in 1429, and is known to have been alive in 1450, when he was 21 years old. The date of his englishing is probably about 1460. As the family of Roos or Ros were lords of Hamlake and Belvoir in N.E. Leicestershire, not far from Grantham in Lincolnshire, and Bourne, whence Robert of Brunne gets his name, Prof. Skeat (p. liii.) says there was something of a Northern element in Sir Richard's language, as shown by his ryme <I>long&egrave;s</I> with <I>song&egrave;s</I> in ll. 53-5, and his use of the Northern possessive pronoun <I>their</I>. This leaves little doubt that the Trinity manuscript's <I>awn</I> (ll. 455, 475, 608) for own&mdash;which Prof. Skeat adopts, no doubt from Thynne&mdash;is Sir Richard's own form of the word. The Harleian text of the poem, which I printed in our first issue of the <I>Polit., Rel. and Love Poems</I>, was copied from a MS. of which the leaves had been misplaced, as I found when comparing it with Chartier's French, at Prof. Skeat's request, on Jan. 21, 1895. He had none of the editions of Chartier, ab. 1490, 1526, 1527, 1617, etc., at Cambridge.]</NOTE>
</L>
</LG>

</DIV2>
<DIV2 TYPE="poem"><PB REF="00000130.tif" N="80">
<HEAD><B>La Belle Dame sans Merci</B> englisht by Sir Richard Ros from the French of Alain Chartier.<NOTE PLACE="foot">&OElig;uvres de M. Alain Chartier, 1617, p. 502. The heading in H is "La Belle Dame sanz Mercy, translated out of French by Sir Richard Ros."</NOTE></HEAD>
<HEADNOTE><P>[<I>MS. Ff</I>. 1. 6, <I>University Library, Cambridge</I> (U), <I>leaf</I> 117.] [Collated with MS. R. 3. 19, Trin. Coll., Camb. (T), and Harleian 372, leaf 61 (H).] Prologe [<I>by Sir R. Ros, in</I> 4 <I>stanzas of Sevens, ababbcc</I>.]</P></HEADNOTE>
<LG N="1" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(1)</HEAD>
<L N="1">Halfe in a dreme, not fully well a-waked,</L>
<L>The golden slepe me wrapt vndir his wyng</L>
<L>yet nat<NOTE PLACE="foot">UH not, <I>om</I>. T.</NOTE> for-thy I rose,<NOTE PLACE="foot">arose UH.</NOTE> and welny naked,</L>
<L>All sodenly my-self&euml; R&eacute;membryng</L>
<L N="5">Of a mat&eacute;r, leuyng all othir thyng</L>
<L>Which I schuld do, withouten more delay,</L>
<L N="7">ffor hem<NOTE PLACE="foot">hyr T, them H.</NOTE> &thorn;e which<NOTE PLACE="foot">UT, to whom H.</NOTE> I durst nat dysobbey.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="2" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(2)</HEAD>
<L N="8">My charge was &thorn;is,<NOTE PLACE="foot">UH, thus T.</NOTE> to translat by and by,</L>
<L>(All thyng foryif<NOTE PLACE="foot">foryeuyn T, forgiven H.</NOTE>), as part of my penaunce,</L>
<L>A boke call&euml;d "la belle dame sans mercy,"</L>
<L>which maister Alayn made, of R&eacute;membraunce,</L>
<L N="12">Chefe secretary with the kyng of fraunce.</L>
<L>And here-vpon, a while I<NOTE PLACE="foot">I UH, <I>om</I>. T.</NOTE> stode musynge,</L>
<L N="14">And in my-selfe gretly ymagynynge</L>
</LG>
<LG N="3" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(3)</HEAD>
<L N="15">What wyse I schuld perfourme &thorn;is said processe,</L>
<L>Consideryng, by gode a-vys&euml;ment,</L>
<L>Myn vnkonnyng and my gret<NOTE PLACE="foot">UT, <I>om</I>. H.</NOTE> symplesse,</L>
<L>And ayeynward, &thorn;e streyt commaund&euml;ment</L>
<L N="19">which &thorn;at I hade; and &thorn;us, in myn entent,</L>
<L>I wasse vexid, and turnyd vp and doun;</L>
<L N="21">yet att the last, as In conclusyoun,<NOTE PLACE="foot">HT, conclusy U.</NOTE>
<PB REF="00000131.tif" N="81"></L>
</LG>
<LG N="4" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(4)</HEAD>
<L N="22">I cast my cloth&euml;s on, and went my way,&mdash;<MILESTONE N="117b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>This forsaid charge hauyng in r&eacute;membraunce,&mdash;</L>
<L>Til I cam to<NOTE PLACE="foot">UT, into H.</NOTE> a lusty grene valey</L>
<L>fful of floures; to se, a grete plesaunce;</L>
<L N="26">And so, bolded<NOTE PLACE="foot">UH, voldyd T.</NOTE> with &thorn;air benyng suffraunce</L>
<L>That Rede<NOTE PLACE="foot">UH, to Rede T.</NOTE> &thorn;is boke, touchyng &thorn;is<NOTE PLACE="foot">UT, the H.</NOTE> said matere,</L>
<L N="28">Thus I bygan,<NOTE PLACE="foot">begynne H.</NOTE> iff hit please yow to here:</L>
</LG>
<LG N="5" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(5. <I>The Poem, in</I> 50 <I>stanzas of eights, ababbcbc</I>.)</HEAD>
<L N="29">Not long ago, Rydyng an<NOTE PLACE="foot">UH, on a T.</NOTE> esy paas,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><Q><L>N'agueres cheuauchant pensoye,</L><L>Comme homme triste &amp; douloreux,</L><L>Au dueil o&ugrave; il faut que je soye</L><L>Le plus dolant des amoureux;</L><L>Puis que, par son dart rigoureux,</L><L>La mort me tolli ma Maistresse,</L><L>Et me laisse seul langoureux</L><L>En la conduiste de tristesse.</L></Q> <I>&OElig;uvres de M. Alain Chartier</I>, 1617, p. 502.</NOTE></L>
<L>I fill in &thorn;ought, of ioy full desperat,</L>
<L>With gret disease and payn, so &thorn;at I was</L>
<L>Of all lou&eacute;rs &thorn;e most vnfortunat,</L>
<L N="33">Sith by<NOTE PLACE="foot">UT, with H.</NOTE> his dart most cruell, full of haat,</L>
<L>&THORN;e<NOTE PLACE="foot">UH, <I>om</I>. T.</NOTE> dethe hath<NOTE PLACE="foot">UH, Det hath fro me T.</NOTE> take my lady and maystres,</L>
<L>And left me sole, thus<NOTE PLACE="foot">UH, thys T.</NOTE> discomfort and mate,</L>
<L N="36">Sore languischynge, and in way of distresse.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="6" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(6)</HEAD>
<L N="37">Then said I &thorn;us: hit falleth me to cesse,</L>
<L>Ey&thorn;er to ryme, or dytes for to make;</L>
<L>And I, seurly,<NOTE PLACE="foot">UH, yet therwith T.</NOTE> to make a fulle promesse</L>
<L>To laughe no more, but wepe in cloth&euml;s blake.</L>
<L N="41">My ioyfull tyme, alas! now is hit<NOTE PLACE="foot">UH, hit is T.</NOTE> slake,</L>
<L>ffor in my selfe I fele no maner ease;</L>
<L>lat hit by<NOTE PLACE="foot">be H, by U (by is an allowable spelling, but apt to confuse a reader).</NOTE> wryten, siche fortune I take,</L>
<L>which neyther me, nor doth non other,<NOTE PLACE="foot">UH, non other doth T.</NOTE> please.
<PB REF="00000132.tif" N="82"></L>
</LG>
<LG N="7" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(7)</HEAD>
<L N="45">Iffe hit wer so,<NOTE PLACE="foot">UH, so that T.</NOTE> my will or myn entent<MILESTONE N="118" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>wer c&oacute;nstreyn&euml;d a ioyfull thyng to wryte,</L>
<L>my penne couth neuer hau&euml;<NOTE PLACE="foot">neuer have U, haue no T, haue H, with 'neuer know' in margin. [Neuer = ne'er.]</NOTE> knolege what hit ment;</L>
<L>To speke &thorn;erof, my tunge hathe no delyte;</L>
<L N="49">And with my mouth, iffe I laugh myche or lyte,</L>
<L>Myn yne schuld make a countynaunce vntrue;</L>
<L>Myn hert also wold haue &thorn;erof despyte;</L>
<L N="52">the wepyng ter&euml;s haue so large issue.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="8" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(8)</HEAD>
<L N="53">Thes seke louers, I leue &thorn;at to hem longes,</L>
<L>whiche lede &thorn;air<NOTE PLACE="foot">her HT.</NOTE> lyfe in hope of &aacute;llegeaunce,<NOTE PLACE="foot">Fr. <I>allegement</I>.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;at is to say, to make balade<NOTE PLACE="foot">UH, baladys T.</NOTE> or songes,</L>
<L>Eueryche of hem, as &thorn;ei fele her<NOTE PLACE="foot">theyr T, &thorn;er H.</NOTE> grevaunce;</L>
<L N="57">ffor sche &thorn;at wasse my ioy and my plesaunce,&mdash;</L>
<L>whos soule, I pray god of his mercy saue,&mdash;</L>
<L>Sche hath myn wyle, my hert&euml;s ordeynaunce,</L>
<L>which lithe with hir vnder her toumbe in<NOTE PLACE="foot">in H, y T, &amp; U. Which lyeth here, within this tombe ygrave. Skeat, from 3 MSS.</NOTE> graue.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="9" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(9)</HEAD>
<L N="61">ffro &thorn;is tym forthe, tyme is to hold my pees;</L>
<L>It weryth<NOTE PLACE="foot">werieth H.</NOTE> me &thorn;is mater for to trete;</L>
<L>lat other louers put hem selfe in prees;</L>
<L>Thair sesoun is; my tym is now<NOTE PLACE="foot">UH, nygh T.</NOTE> for-yete;</L>
<L N="65">ffortune, by<NOTE PLACE="foot">UT, with H.</NOTE> strenght, &thorn;e forser hath<NOTE PLACE="foot">UH, hath the forser T.</NOTE> vnschete,</L>
<L>Wher-in wasse sparde<NOTE PLACE="foot">H, <I>margin: text</I> spradde; sperryd T, spred U.</NOTE> all my worldely<NOTE PLACE="foot">H, wordely U.</NOTE> Rychesse,</L>
<L>And all &thorn;e goodys which &thorn;at I haue gete,</L>
<L N="68">In my best tyme of youth and lustynesse.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="10" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(10)</HEAD>
<L N="69">Loue hath me kept vndir his gouernaunce:<MILESTONE N="118b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>Iffe I mysdid, god graunt me for-yifnesse!
<PB REF="00000133.tif" N="83"></L>
<L>Iffe I did well, yit felt<NOTE PLACE="foot">UH, fele T.</NOTE> I no plesaunce;</L>
<L>hit caused neither ioy nor<NOTE PLACE="foot">UH, causeth no but T.</NOTE> hevynesse;</L>
<L N="73">ffor when sche dyd&euml;, &thorn;at wasse<NOTE PLACE="foot">whyche was T, that was H, &thorn;at wasse all U.</NOTE> my maistresse,</L>
<L>All my<NOTE PLACE="foot">HT, My gode U.</NOTE> welfare then made<NOTE PLACE="foot">UT, made then H.</NOTE> &thorn;<SUP>e</SUP> sam purchasse;</L>
<L>&THORN;e deth hath set my boundis, of wytnesse,<NOTE PLACE="foot">La mort m'assist illec la bourne.</NOTE></L>
<L>which for no thyng myn hert schall neuer passe.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="11" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(11)</HEAD>
<L N="77">In &thorn;is gret &thorn;ought, sore trowbled in my mynde,</L>
<L>Allon &thorn;us rode I<NOTE PLACE="foot">H, I rode T, rode &amp; U.</NOTE> all &thorn;e morow tyde,</L>
<L>Tyll, at &thorn;e last, hit happed me to fynde</L>
<L>The place wher-In I cast me to a-byde,<NOTE PLACE="foot">UT, I purposid me to hide H.</NOTE></L>
<L N="81">when &thorn;at I had no fer&thorn;er for<NOTE PLACE="foot">UT, forth H.</NOTE> to ryde.</L>
<L>And as I went, my loggyng to purvey,</L>
<L>Ryght sone I herd, but lytell me be-syde,</L>
<L N="84">In a gardyn, wher mynstrells gan to play.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="12" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(12)</HEAD>
<L N="85">With &thorn;at anon I went me bakkermore;<NOTE PLACE="foot">Si me retray.</NOTE></L>
<L>My selfe and I, me &thorn;ought we wer Inow;</L>
<L>But tweyn,<NOTE PLACE="foot">UH, y. T.</NOTE> &thorn;at wer my frendis her-byfore,<NOTE PLACE="foot">UH, tofore T.</NOTE></L>
<L>had me espi&euml;d, and I wot<NOTE PLACE="foot">UH, wyst T.</NOTE> not how.</L>
<L N="89">Thai cam for me: aweyward I me drow,</L>
<L>Sum-what by force, sum-what by &thorn;air request,</L>
<L>That in no wyse I couthe<NOTE PLACE="foot">UH, cowde T.</NOTE> my selfe rescow,</L>
<L N="92">But<NOTE PLACE="foot">HT, bud U.</NOTE> nede I must cum In, and se &thorn;<SUP>e</SUP> fest.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="13" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(13)</HEAD>
<L N="93">At my commyng, the ladyse euerychon<MILESTONE N="119" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>Bade me welcom, god wot, ryght gentilly,</L>
<L>And made me chere, euerych by on and on,</L>
<L><NOTE PLACE="foot">These lines transferred in Trinity MS.</NOTE>A gret dele better &thorn;en I wasse worthy;</L>
<L N="97"><NOTE PLACE="foot">These lines transferred in Trinity MS.</NOTE>And, of &thorn;air grace, schewd me gret courtesy
<PB REF="00000134.tif" N="84"></L>
<L>with good disport, by cause I schuld not morne.<NOTE PLACE="foot">UH, mone T.</NOTE></L>
<L>That day I bode<NOTE PLACE="foot">UH, abode T.</NOTE> still in &thorn;air cumpany,</L>
<L N="100">which wasse to me a gracyous soiourne.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="14" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(14)</HEAD>
<L N="101">The boord&euml;s w&eacute;r spred in ryght<NOTE PLACE="foot">UH, full T.</NOTE> lytell space;</L>
<L>The ladyse sat, eche as hem semyd best.</L>
<L>were<NOTE PLACE="foot">were H, wher U, Ther were T.</NOTE> non &thorn;at dide seruyse<NOTE PLACE="foot">UT, &thorn;at serued H.</NOTE> with-In &thorn;at place,</L>
<L>But chosen men, ryght of &thorn;<SUP>e</SUP> goodlyest;</L>
<L N="105">And sum &thorn;er were, paraunter<NOTE PLACE="foot">parauenture H.</NOTE> most<NOTE PLACE="foot">more T, <I>om</I>. H.</NOTE> freschest,</L>
<L>That saw &thorn;air Iuges syttyng full demure,</L>
<L>without semblant, o&thorn;er<NOTE PLACE="foot">UH, ey&thorn;er T.</NOTE> to most or lest,</L>
<L N="108">Not with standyng<NOTE PLACE="foot">UH, But not . . T.</NOTE> &thorn;ai had hem vndur cure.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="15" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(15)</HEAD>
<L N="109">Among all oder, on I gan aspye,</L>
<L>which in gret thought full often cam and went,</L>
<L>As on<NOTE PLACE="foot">UT, man H.</NOTE> &thorn;at had bene rauysched vttirlye,</L>
<L>In his langage not gretly dylygent;</L>
<L N="113">Hys countynaunce he kept with gret turement,</L>
<L>But his desir far passed his resoun,</L>
<L>ffor euer his yie<NOTE PLACE="foot">ey T, yee H.</NOTE> went after his entent</L>
<L N="116">ffull many a tyme, when hit wasse no sesoun.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="16" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(16)</HEAD>
<L>To make gud chere, ryght<NOTE PLACE="foot">UH, full T.</NOTE> sore hym selfe he payned.<NOTE PLACE="foot">he peyned H, payned U, he feynyd T.</NOTE><MILESTONE N="119b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>And outwardly<NOTE PLACE="foot">UT, outeward H.</NOTE> he feyned gret gladnesse;</L>
<L>To syng also, by force he wasse constrayned,</L>
<L>ffor no plesaunce, but<NOTE PLACE="foot">UH, for T.</NOTE> verrey schamfastnesse;</L>
<L N="121">ffor the compleynt of his most hevynesse</L>
<L>Cam to his voyce alway with-out request,</L>
<L>lyke as &thorn;<SUP>e</SUP> sown of byrd&euml;s doth expresse,<NOTE PLACE="foot">UH, doutles T.</NOTE></L>
<L N="124">when &thorn;ai syng lowd, in fryth or in<NOTE PLACE="foot">in UT, <I>om</I>. H.</NOTE> for&eacute;st.
<PB REF="00000135.tif" N="85"></L>
</LG>
<LG N="17" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(17)</HEAD>
<L N="125">Othir &thorn;er wer &thorn;at seru&euml;d in the halle,</L>
<L>But non lyke hym, as after<NOTE PLACE="foot">hym . . H, hym for soth to T, as after U.</NOTE> myn avyse;</L>
<L>ffor he wase pale, and sumwhat lene with-all;</L>
<L>his speche also tremlyd<NOTE PLACE="foot">UH, he spake also tremblyng T.</NOTE> in ferefull wyse;</L>
<L N="129">And euer allon, but when he dyde seruyse.</L>
<L>All blake he ware, and no deuyse but playn;</L>
<L>Me &thorn;ought by hym, as my wyt couth<NOTE PLACE="foot">UH, wyll cowde T.</NOTE> suffyse,</L>
<L N="132">hys hert wasse no thynge<NOTE PLACE="foot">UH, then not T.</NOTE> in his awn demayn.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="18" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(18)</HEAD>
<L N="133">To feste hem all, he did his dilygence;</L>
<L>And wel he couth,<NOTE PLACE="foot">couthe H, cowde T.</NOTE> ryght as hit semyd me;</L>
<L>But euermor when he wasse in presence,</L>
<L>his chere wasse do,<NOTE PLACE="foot">UH, done T.</NOTE> it wold non other<NOTE PLACE="foot">UH, no bettyr T.</NOTE> be:</L>
<L N="137">his scolemaystres<NOTE PLACE="foot">scole-maister UH, scolemaystres T.</NOTE> hade siche autoryte,</L>
<L>That, all the while he stode<NOTE PLACE="foot">UH, that while he bode T.</NOTE> still in &thorn;<SUP>e</SUP> place,</L>
<L>Speke couth<NOTE PLACE="foot">coude H, cowde T.</NOTE> he nat; but vpon her beaute</L>
<L N="140">he lokyd still, with Ryght<NOTE PLACE="foot">UH, ryght with T.</NOTE> a pytous face.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="19" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(19)</HEAD>
<L N="141">With &thorn;at, his hede he turned att&euml;<NOTE PLACE="foot">at the T.</NOTE> laste,<MILESTONE N="120" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>ffor to biholde &thorn;e ladies euerychon;</L>
<L>But euer in one he sette his ye<NOTE PLACE="foot">ey T.</NOTE> stedfaste</L>
<L>On hir, &thorn;e which his &thorn;ought was most<NOTE PLACE="foot">UH, euer T.</NOTE> vppon;</L>
<L N="145">And of his yen,<NOTE PLACE="foot">yen H, eyen T.</NOTE> the shot<NOTE PLACE="foot">UT, sighte H, [Fr. <I>trait</I>].</NOTE> y knewe anon,</L>
<L>Which federid was with right humble requestis.</L>
<L>Then to my self y seyd, 'by god allon,</L>
<L N="148">Sich on was y, or that y<NOTE PLACE="foot">or y that y U, I that there H, I or euer y T.</NOTE> sawe &thorn;ese gestes.'</L>
</LG>
<LG N="20" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(20)</HEAD>
<L N="149">Out of the prees he went full esily,</L>
<L>To make stabill his heuy contynaunce;
<PB REF="00000136.tif" N="86"></L>
<L>And wite ye wele, he sigh&euml;d tenderly</L>
<L>ffor his sorowes and wofull r&eacute;membraunce.</L>
<L N="153">Then in hym self he made his ordynaunce,</L>
<L>And forth-with-all cam to bryng in the mes;</L>
<L>But, for to Iuge his<NOTE PLACE="foot">UH, But to beholde with T.</NOTE> moste rewfull semblaunce,</L>
<L N="156">God wot it was a petous entremes.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="21" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(21)</HEAD>
<L N="157">After dyn&eacute;r, anone they hem avaunsed</L>
<L>To daunce aboute, these<NOTE PLACE="foot">UH, the T.</NOTE> folk&euml;s euerychon;</L>
<L>And forth-with-all &thorn;is heuy lover<NOTE PLACE="foot">louer HT, <I>om</I>. U.</NOTE> daunced,</L>
<L>Sumtyme with tweyne, and sum tyme but with on:</L>
<L N="161">Vnto hem all, his chere was after<NOTE PLACE="foot">UH, euer T.</NOTE> on,</L>
<L>Now here, now there, as fill by &aacute;uenture;</L>
<L>But euer among,<NOTE PLACE="foot">among HT, anone U.</NOTE> he drow to hir allon,</L>
<L N="164">Which he most dredde,<NOTE PLACE="foot">UH, louyd T.</NOTE> of lyuyng cr&euml;ature.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="22" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(22)</HEAD>
<L N="165">To myn avise, god<NOTE PLACE="foot">good H.</NOTE> was his puruiaunce<MILESTONE N="120b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>When he hir chase<NOTE PLACE="foot">UH, chose T.</NOTE> to his maystres allone,</L>
<L>If &thorn;at hir herte were sette to his plesaunce</L>
<L>As moche as was hir beauteous persone;</L>
<L N="169">ffor who &thorn;at euer setteth<NOTE PLACE="foot">sett H, wyll set T.</NOTE> his trust vppon</L>
<L>&THORN;e r&eacute;porte of thair yen, withouten<NOTE PLACE="foot">UH, such oon then without T.</NOTE> more,</L>
<L>he myght be dede, and grauen vnder a<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>om</I>. HT.</NOTE> stone,</L>
<L N="172">Or euer she<NOTE PLACE="foot">UT, he H.</NOTE> shuld, his hertis ease restore.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="23" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(23)</HEAD>
<L N="173">In hir fayl&euml;d no thyng, &thorn;at y couthe<NOTE PLACE="foot">as I koude H, &thorn;at I cowde T.</NOTE> gesse<NOTE PLACE="foot"><Q><L>En la dance ne failloit riens</L><L>Ne plus auent ne plus arriere</L></Q></NOTE></L>
<L>O wyse nor other,<NOTE PLACE="foot">On vice ner othir H, In any wyse nether T.</NOTE> pryue nor apert;<NOTE PLACE="foot">or perte H, ne perte T.</NOTE></L>
<L>A garnyson<NOTE PLACE="foot">UH, gramyson T.</NOTE> sche was of all goodnesse,<NOTE PLACE="foot">UH, goodlynesse T.</NOTE></L>
<L>To make a frounter<NOTE PLACE="foot">Fr. <I>frontiere</I>, front rank (make an attack on).&mdash;Skeat.</NOTE> for a louers herte;
<PB REF="00000137.tif" N="87"></L>
<L N="177">Right &yogh;onge and fressh, a woman full couert;</L>
<L>Assured wele<NOTE PLACE="foot">UH, wele with T.</NOTE> hir port, and eke hir chere,</L>
<L>Wele<NOTE PLACE="foot">UH, went T.</NOTE> atte hir ease, withouten wo or smert,</L>
<L N="180">All vndirnethe the standart of daungere.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="24" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(24)</HEAD>
<L N="181">To se the fest, it weryd me full sore;</L>
<L>ffor hevy ioye dothe the herte sore<NOTE PLACE="foot">sore the herte T, soore the hurte H.</NOTE> trauaylle.</L>
<L>Out of the prees y me withdrow therfore,</L>
<L>And sette me down allon, behynde a trayll</L>
<L N="185">ffull of leu&egrave;s, to se, a gret mervayll:</L>
<L>with grene wythies ybounden<NOTE PLACE="foot">UH, ybounde full T.</NOTE> wundirly;</L>
<L>The leues were so thik, withouten fayll,</L>
<L N="188">That thoroughout myght no man me<NOTE PLACE="foot">UH, man T.</NOTE> aspye.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="25" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(25)</HEAD>
<L N="189">To his lady he cam full curteysely,<MILESTONE N="121" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>Whan he<NOTE PLACE="foot">UH, he hym T.</NOTE> &thorn;ought tyme to daunce with hir a trace;</L>
<L>Sith in an herber made full plesauntly</L>
<L>Thei rested them, fro thens but lytill space;</L>
<L N="193">Nigh hem were non, a certeyn of compace,<NOTE PLACE="foot">UH, certeyn space T.</NOTE></L>
<L>But onely they, as fer as y couthe se;</L>
<L>And safe<NOTE PLACE="foot">saue HT.</NOTE> the trayll, there y<NOTE PLACE="foot">UH, there as T.</NOTE> hadde chose my place,</L>
<L>Ther was nomore betuyxt hem tweyne<NOTE PLACE="foot">UH, ij. T.</NOTE> and me.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="26" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(26)</HEAD>
<L N="197">I herde &thorn;<SUP>e</SUP> louer sighyng wondir sore;</L>
<L>ffor ay &thorn;e ner, &thorn;e sorer it hym sought;<NOTE PLACE="foot">UH, thought T.</NOTE></L>
<L>his<NOTE PLACE="foot">UH, whos T.</NOTE> inward payn he couthe<NOTE PLACE="foot">UH, cowde T.</NOTE> not kepe in store,</L>
<L>Nor<NOTE PLACE="foot">ne HT.</NOTE> for to speke, so hardy was he nought;</L>
<L N="201">his leche was nere, &thorn;e gretter was his &thorn;ought;</L>
<L>he mused sore, to conquere his desire,</L>
<L>ffor noman may to more penaunce be brought,</L>
<L N="204">&THORN;en in his hete to bryng hym to &thorn;e fire.
<PB REF="00000138.tif" N="88"></L>
</LG>
<LG N="27" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(27)</HEAD>
<L N="205">&THORN;e herte began to swelle withyn his chest,</L>
<L>So sore streyn&euml;d for anguysh and for payn,</L>
<L>That all to pecis almost it to-brest,</L>
<L>When bothe at ones, so sore it did constrayn;</L>
<L N="209">Desire was bold, but shame it gan<NOTE PLACE="foot">can H, dyd T.</NOTE> refrayn;</L>
<L>&THORN;e ton<NOTE PLACE="foot">UH, That oon T.</NOTE> was large, the tother<NOTE PLACE="foot">UH, that other T.</NOTE> was full cloos;</L>
<L>No lytyll charge was leyd on hym,<NOTE PLACE="foot">UH, on hym was leyd T.</NOTE> certeyn,</L>
<L N="212">To kepe such ware,<NOTE PLACE="foot">werre H.</NOTE> and haue so many foos.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="28" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(28)</HEAD>
<L N="213">fful often tyme to speke, hym self he payned,<NOTE PLACE="foot">UH, feynyd T.</NOTE><MILESTONE N="121b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>But shamefastnes and drede seid euer 'nay;'</L>
<L>yit atte the last, so sore he was constreyned,</L>
<L>When he full longe hadde putte it in delay;</L>
<L N="217">To his lady, right thus then gan he<NOTE PLACE="foot">UH, he gan to, T.</NOTE> say</L>
<L>With dredfull voys, wepyng, halfe in a rage,</L>
<L>"ffor me was purueied an vnhappy<NOTE PLACE="foot">UH, happy T.</NOTE> day</L>
<L N="220">Whan y first hadde a sight of youre vysage!</L>
</LG>
<LG N="29" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(29)</HEAD>
<L N="221">"I suffre peyn, god wot, full hote<NOTE PLACE="foot">UH, sore T.</NOTE> burnyng,</L>
<L>To cause my dethe, all for my trew seruice;</L>
<L>And y se wele, ye reche<NOTE PLACE="foot">UH, rek T.</NOTE> therof nothyng,</L>
<L>Nor take non hede of it in no kyns<NOTE PLACE="foot">UH, therof hede in no maner T.</NOTE> wyse;</L>
<L N="225">But when y speke, after my best avise,<NOTE PLACE="foot">UH, deuyse T.</NOTE></L>
<L>ye set it at<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>om</I>. HT.</NOTE> nought, but make therof a game;</L>
<L>And though y sue<NOTE PLACE="foot">UH, shew T.</NOTE> so grete an entirprise,</L>
<L N="228">It peireth<NOTE PLACE="foot">UH, apeireth T.</NOTE> not your wurship nor your fame.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="30" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(30)</HEAD>
<L N="229">"Alas! what shuld be to you preiudice,</L>
<L>yf &thorn;at a man do loue you faythefully,</L>
<L>To your<NOTE PLACE="foot">UH, euery T.</NOTE> wurship, eschuyng euery vice?</L>
<L>So am y youres, and will be<NOTE PLACE="foot">UH, shalbe T.</NOTE> verely;
<PB REF="00000139.tif" N="89"></L>
<L N="233">I chalange nought<NOTE PLACE="foot">UH, shall nat T.</NOTE> of right, and resoun why,</L>
<L>ffor y am hole submyt to youre seruyse;</L>
<L>Right as ye lyste it be, right<NOTE PLACE="foot">euyn H, <I>om</I>. T.</NOTE> so will y,</L>
<L>To bynde my selfe, where y was<NOTE PLACE="foot">UH, am T.</NOTE> in fraunchise.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="31" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(31)</HEAD>
<L N="237">"&THORN;ough it be so,<NOTE PLACE="foot">be so I cannot H, so be &thorn;at I can hit nat T.</NOTE> &thorn;at y cannot deserue<MILESTONE N="122" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>To haue youre grace, but alwey leue<NOTE PLACE="foot">ay to lyve H, alwey lyue T, alwey to leue U.</NOTE> in drede;</L>
<L>yit suffre me you f&oacute;r to loue and serue</L>
<L>without magr&egrave;<NOTE PLACE="foot">mauger H, mawgre T.</NOTE> of youre most goodlyhede;</L>
<L>Bothe feyth and trouth y yeue<NOTE PLACE="foot">yeue T, to gif H, ye U.</NOTE> your womanhede,</L>
<L>And my seruise, without ayen-callyng;</L>
<L>Loue hathe me bounde, without&euml; wage or mede,</L>
<L N="244">To be your man, and leue all othir thyng."</L>
</LG>
<LG N="32" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(32) LA DAME.</HEAD>
<L N="245">When this lady hadde herde all his<NOTE PLACE="foot">UT, this H.</NOTE> langage,</L>
<L>She yaf<NOTE PLACE="foot">yaf hym U, <I>om</I>. hym HT.</NOTE> answere full softe and d&eacute;murely,</L>
<L>Without chaungyng of Colour or corage,</L>
<L>Nothyng in haste, but mesurab&euml;ly:</L>
<L N="249">"Me thynketh, sir, your &thorn;ought is<NOTE PLACE="foot">your hert is T, ye doo fulle H.</NOTE> grete foly.</L>
<L>purpose ye not your labour for to sees?</L>
<L>ffor thynketh<NOTE PLACE="foot">thynk ye, HT.</NOTE> not, whils &thorn;at ye leue and<NOTE PLACE="foot">ye . . and HT, I . . an U.</NOTE> y,</L>
<L N="252">In this<NOTE PLACE="foot">UH, your T.</NOTE> matier to sette youre hert in pees."<NOTE PLACE="foot">UH, ese T.</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG N="33" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(33) LAMANT.</HEAD>
<L N="253">"&THORN;er may non make &thorn;<SUP>e</SUP> pees, but only ye,</L>
<L>Which ar the ground and cause<NOTE PLACE="foot">cause and grounde HT.</NOTE> of all this war;</L>
<L>ffor with youre yen &thorn;<SUP>e</SUP> letters writen be,</L>
<L>By which y am defied<NOTE PLACE="foot">UH, deferryd T.</NOTE> and put a-fer,</L>
<L N="257">youre plesaunt looke, my very lod&euml;sterre,</L>
<L>was made heraud of thilke same<NOTE PLACE="foot">thilke same H, &thorn;e same U, thys saunce T.</NOTE> diffiaunce
<PB REF="00000140.tif" N="90"></L>
<L>which vtterly behight me to forbar<NOTE PLACE="foot">forbarre (loodsterre, aferre, werre) H.</NOTE></L>
<L N="260">Mi feythefull trust, and all my affiaunce."</L>
</LG>
<LG N="34" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(34) LA DAME.</HEAD>
<L N="261">"To leue in wo, he hathe gret fantasie,<MILESTONE N="122b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>And of his hert also hathe sliper hold,</L>
<L>That, only for byholdyng of an ye,<NOTE PLACE="foot">yee H, ey T.</NOTE></L>
<L>Cannot abide in pees, as resoun wolde.</L>
<L N="265">Other, or me,<NOTE PLACE="foot">UH, ne T.</NOTE> yf ye liste to biholde,</L>
<L>Oure yen<NOTE PLACE="foot">yeen H, eyen T.</NOTE> ar made to loke: why shuld we spare?</L>
<L>I take no kepe, nether of yong ne olde;</L>
<L N="268">who feleth smert,<NOTE PLACE="foot">UH, seketh harme T.</NOTE> y consayll hym by<NOTE PLACE="foot">be H.</NOTE> ware."</L>
</LG>
<LG N="35" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(35) LAMANT.</HEAD>
<L N="269">"If it be so,<NOTE PLACE="foot">UH, so be T.</NOTE> one hurt an other sore,</L>
<L>In his defaut &thorn;at feleth the<NOTE PLACE="foot">the HT, no U.</NOTE> greuaunce,</L>
<L>Of very right a man may do no more;</L>
<L>yit resoun wuld it were in r&eacute;membraunce.</L>
<L N="273">And, sith fortune nat only (by his chaunce)</L>
<L>hathe caused me to suffre all this payn,</L>
<L>But your beaute, with all &thorn;e sircumstaunce,</L>
<L N="276">Whi list you<NOTE PLACE="foot">ye HT.</NOTE> haue me in so grete disdeyn?"</L>
</LG>
<LG N="36" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(36) LA DAME.</HEAD>
<L N="277">"To your persone ne haue y non<NOTE PLACE="foot">UH, <I>om</I>. T.</NOTE> disdeyn,</L>
<L>Nor neuer hadde, truly; nor nought<NOTE PLACE="foot">ner neuere H, ne neuer T.</NOTE> will haue,</L>
<L>Nor right gret loue, nor hatrede, in certeyn;</L>
<L>Nor<NOTE PLACE="foot">UH, Ne T.</NOTE> youre consayll to knowe, (so god me saue!)</L>
<L N="281">If such beleue<NOTE PLACE="foot">UH, conseyte T.</NOTE> be in your mynde y-graue,<NOTE PLACE="foot">UH, graue T.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;at lytell thyng may do you gret plesaunce,</L>
<L>you to begyle, or make<NOTE PLACE="foot">UH, mok T.</NOTE> you for to rave,</L>
<L N="284">I will not cause non<NOTE PLACE="foot">noon H, no T.</NOTE> such &eacute;ncomberaunce."</L>
</LG>
<LG N="37" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(37) LAMANT.</HEAD>
<L N="285">"What euer hit be &thorn;at hath me<NOTE PLACE="foot">UT, me hath H.</NOTE> &thorn;is purch&aacute;cyde,<MILESTONE N="123" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>Wenyng hath noght deseyued me,<NOTE PLACE="foot">UH, <I>om</I>. T.</NOTE> sertayne;
<PB REF="00000141.tif" N="91"></L>
<L>But feruent loue so sore me hath I-chasede,<NOTE PLACE="foot">UH, hath me enbrasyd T.</NOTE></L>
<L>That I,<NOTE PLACE="foot">UH, <I>om</I>. T.</NOTE> vnware, am casten<NOTE PLACE="foot">UH, cast T.</NOTE> in your chayne;</L>
<L N="289">And sith so is, as<NOTE PLACE="foot">UH, hyt ys that T.</NOTE> fortune lyste<NOTE PLACE="foot">UH, lyste so T.</NOTE> ordayne,</L>
<L>All my welfare is in your handys falle,</L>
<L>Inn &eacute;schewyng of more mysch&eacute;vous payne;</L>
<L N="292">Who sunnest dieth, his care is leste of alle."</L>
</LG>
<LG N="38" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(38) LA DAME.</HEAD>
<L N="293">"&THORN;is<NOTE PLACE="foot">UH, The T.</NOTE> sykenesse is ryght<NOTE PLACE="foot">UH, full T.</NOTE> esy to endure,</L>
<L>But few peple hit causeth for to dye;</L>
<L>But what &thorn;ei meane, I know hit<NOTE PLACE="foot">it H, <I>om</I>. T.</NOTE> verrey sure,</L>
<L>Of mor comf&oacute;rt to draw the remedye.</L>
<L N="297">Sych be &thorn;er now,<NOTE PLACE="foot">nought H, lew T.</NOTE> playnyng full pytouslye,</L>
<L>That fele<NOTE PLACE="foot">UH, faylen T.</NOTE> (gode wote) not al&thorn;er<NOTE PLACE="foot">UH, all the T.</NOTE>-grettyst payne;</L>
<L>And<NOTE PLACE="foot">Are UT.</NOTE> iffe so be, loue hurtes<NOTE PLACE="foot">hurte H, hurt T.</NOTE> so grevously,</L>
<L>lesse harme hit were, wone sorouful, &thorn;en twayn."<NOTE PLACE="foot">tweyne HT, wayn U.</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG N="39" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(39) LAMANT.</HEAD>
<L N="301">"Alas, madame! iffe &thorn;at hit<NOTE PLACE="foot">UT, I H.</NOTE> myght you please,</L>
<L>mych better wer,<NOTE PLACE="foot">UH, hyt were bettyr T.</NOTE> by way of gentyllesse,</L>
<L>Of won sory,<NOTE PLACE="foot">UT, sorwe H ('sory' <I>in margin</I>).</NOTE> to make twayne<NOTE PLACE="foot">UH, ij. T.</NOTE> well at ease,</L>
<L>Then hyme to strye<NOTE PLACE="foot">stroye H, dystroy T.</NOTE> that lyueth in destresse.</L>
<L N="305">ffor my desyr is no&thorn;er mor ne lesse,</L>
<L>But my seruysse to<NOTE PLACE="foot">UH, I T.</NOTE> do, for your plesaunce,</L>
<L>In &eacute;schewyng al maner doublenesse,</L>
<L N="308">To make too Joys insted of won<NOTE PLACE="foot">oo HT.</NOTE> grevaunce."</L>
</LG>
<LG N="40" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(40) LA DAME.</HEAD>
<L N="309">"Of loue I seke no&thorn;er plesaunce nore<NOTE PLACE="foot">UT, ne H.</NOTE> ease,<MILESTONE N="123b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>Nor Ryght gret loue,<NOTE PLACE="foot">Nor gret desire HT.</NOTE> nor<NOTE PLACE="foot">UH, ne T.</NOTE> ryght gret affyaunce.</L>
<L>&thorn;ough ye be seke, hit dothe me no thyng please;</L>
<L>Also, I take none hede to your plesaunce.
<PB REF="00000142.tif" N="92"></L>
<L N="313">Chese who-so wyle, &thorn;air hertys to a-vaunce,</L>
<L>ffre am I now, and fre wyll I endure;</L>
<L>To be Rulyd by mannys gouernaunce,</L>
<L N="316">ffor erthly gode, nay! that I you ensure."</L>
</LG>
<LG N="41" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(41) LAMANT.</HEAD>
<L N="317">"Loue, which &thorn;at<NOTE PLACE="foot">UT, <I>om</I>. H.</NOTE> ioy and sorow doth depart,</L>
<L>hath set &thorn;e<NOTE PLACE="foot">UH, yow T.</NOTE> ladyes out of all seruage,</L>
<L>And larg&euml;ly doth graunt hem, for &thorn;air<NOTE PLACE="foot">&thorn;ar H, youre T.</NOTE> part,</L>
<L>Lordschip and rule of euery maner age.</L>
<L N="321">The pore seruaunt noght hath of<NOTE PLACE="foot">UH, hath noon T.</NOTE> &aacute;vauntage</L>
<L>But what he may get only of purch&aacute;ce;</L>
<L>And he &thorn;at ones to loue dothe his om&aacute;ge,</L>
<L N="324">ffull often<NOTE PLACE="foot">ofte H, oft T.</NOTE> tyme, der boght is the rechace."<NOTE PLACE="foot">UT, dere his richesse boughte has H. O. Fr. <I>rachatz;</I> Mod. Fr. <I>rachat</I>, redemption, ransom.&mdash;Skeat. '<I>Rachapt</I>, a redemp|tion, redeeming, rebuying, recovery of a thing sold, by paying that for which it was sold.'&mdash;Cotgrave.</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG N="42" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(42) LA DAME.</HEAD>
<L N="325">"Ladyes beth not so symple (&thorn;us I mene),</L>
<L>So dulle of wyte, so sotyd<NOTE PLACE="foot">sottid H, dotyd T.</NOTE> of folye,</L>
<L>That, for wordes which said ben of<NOTE PLACE="foot">UT are, <I>om</I>. H.</NOTE> &thorn;<SUP>e</SUP> splene,</L>
<L>In fayr lang&aacute;ge, paynted ful plesantlye,</L>
<L N="329">Which ye and mo<NOTE PLACE="foot">UH, me T.</NOTE> holde scolys of<NOTE PLACE="foot">UT, scoolys holden H.</NOTE> dailye,<NOTE PLACE="foot">dulye U, dieulye <I>margin</I>, daily H.</NOTE></L>
<L>To make hem all<NOTE PLACE="foot">UT, of H.</NOTE> grete wondyrs to suppose;</L>
<L>But sone thei cane, away her hedes<NOTE PLACE="foot">UT, &thorn;er hedys away H.</NOTE> wrye,</L>
<L N="332">And to fayr speche, lyghtly &thorn;air yer&euml;s close."</L>
</LG>
<LG N="43" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(43) LAMANT.</HEAD>
<L N="333">"&THORN;er is no man &thorn;at iangulith bysily<MILESTONE N="124" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>And sette<NOTE PLACE="foot">UT, settith H.</NOTE> his hert and all his mynd &thorn;erfor,</L>
<L>&thorn;at be reason may playn so pytously</L>
<L>As he &thorn;at hath myche hevynesse in store.</L>
<L N="337">Whose hede is hole,<NOTE PLACE="foot">UH, nat sore T.</NOTE> and saith &thorn;at hit is<NOTE PLACE="foot">UT, is nat T.</NOTE> sore,</L>
<L>his fayned chere is hard<NOTE PLACE="foot">UH, herde T.</NOTE> to kepe in mewe;
<PB REF="00000143.tif" N="93"></L>
<L>But thoght, which<NOTE PLACE="foot">UH, that T.</NOTE> is vnfayn&euml;d euermore,</L>
<L N="340">The word&euml;s previth<NOTE PLACE="foot">preven H, present T.</NOTE> as the wark&euml;s sewe."<NOTE PLACE="foot">shew T, sewe <I>margin</I>, shew H.</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG N="44" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(44) LA DAME.</HEAD>
<L N="341">"Loue is sotyle, and hath a grete awayte,<NOTE PLACE="foot">UT, abaite H, <I>margin</I> awayte.</NOTE></L>
<L>Scharpe in worchyng, in gabbyng gret plesance,</L>
<L>And cane hyme venge of<NOTE PLACE="foot">UH, on T.</NOTE> siche as, by deceyte,</L>
<L>Wold fele and know<NOTE PLACE="foot">UT, knowe &amp; fele H.</NOTE> his secrete gouernance;</L>
<L N="345">And makyth hem to abey<NOTE PLACE="foot">obeye H.</NOTE> his ordynance</L>
<L>By cherfull wayes,<NOTE PLACE="foot">weies H, wyse T.</NOTE> as In hem<NOTE PLACE="foot">UT, hym H.</NOTE> is supposed,</L>
<L>But when &thorn;ei<NOTE PLACE="foot">UT, &thorn;at &thorn;ei H.</NOTE> fallen in-to<NOTE PLACE="foot">UH, vnto T.</NOTE> r&eacute;pentance,</L>
<L N="348">Then, in a rage, &thorn;eir councele is disclosed."</L>
</LG>
<LG N="45" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(45) LAMANT.</HEAD>
<L N="349">"Sith, for-as-mych as gode and eke natur</L>
<L>hathe loue avaunced<NOTE PLACE="foot">Skeat MSS. avaunced loue.</NOTE> to so hye degre,</L>
<L>Mych scharper is the poynte, &thorn;is<NOTE PLACE="foot">UH, thus T.</NOTE> am I sure,</L>
<L>yete<NOTE PLACE="foot">UT, hit H.</NOTE> greueth mor the faute, wher-euer hit be.</L>
<L N="353">Who hath no colde, of hete hathe no deyntye;</L>
<L>&thorn;e tone for &thorn;e toder, axed is expresse;</L>
<L>And of plesaunce knothe non<NOTE PLACE="foot">noon H, not UT.</NOTE> &thorn;e serteyntye,</L>
<L>Bot hit be<NOTE PLACE="foot">be H, <I>om</I>. UT.</NOTE> wonen with thought and hevynesse."</L>
</LG>
<LG N="46" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(46) LA DAME.</HEAD>
<L N="357">"As for plesaunce, hit is not alway wone:<NOTE PLACE="foot">on (one) H.</NOTE><MILESTONE N="124b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>That you<NOTE PLACE="foot">UH, to you T.</NOTE> is swete, me thynketh<NOTE PLACE="foot">thynketh HT, thynke U.</NOTE> a bytter payne;</L>
<L>ye may not me constrayn, nor yet ryght none,</L>
<L>After your lust to loue,<NOTE PLACE="foot">UH, lyue T.</NOTE> &thorn;at is bot vayne.</L>
<L N="361">To chalange<NOTE PLACE="foot">UH, shall T.</NOTE> loue by ryght, was neuer<NOTE PLACE="foot">UH, men T.</NOTE> sayne,</L>
<L>But hert assent, by-fore bonde or promyse;</L>
<L>ffor strenght nor force may not ataine, sertayne,</L>
<L N="364">A wylle &thorn;at stant enfeffyd in<NOTE PLACE="foot">in HT, on U.</NOTE> franchyse."
<PB REF="00000144.tif" N="94"></L>
</LG>
<LG N="47" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(47) LAMANT.</HEAD>
<L N="365">"Ryght fayr lady, god mot<NOTE PLACE="foot">UT, myghte H.</NOTE> I never please,</L>
<L>Iffe I seche o&thorn;er ryght, as in &thorn;is case,</L>
<L>But for to schew you playnly my disease,</L>
<L>And your mercy to<NOTE PLACE="foot">UT, <I>om</I>. H.</NOTE> abyde, and eke your grace.</L>
<L N="369">Iffe I purp&oacute;se your honour to defface,</L>
<L>Or ever dide, gode and fortune me schende,</L>
<L>And that I never ryghtwysly<NOTE PLACE="foot">rightwisly H.</NOTE> purch&aacute;ce</L>
<L N="372">On only ioy, vn-to my lyv&euml;s ende!"</L>
</LG>
<LG N="48" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(48) LA DAME.</HEAD>
<L N="373">"ye and o&thorn;er, that sweere such oth&euml;s faste,</L>
<L>And so condempne and cursen to and fro,</L>
<L>ffull sykerly, ye wene your oth&euml;s laste</L>
<L>No lengur then the word&euml;s beth<NOTE PLACE="foot">UH, byn T.</NOTE> ago;</L>
<L N="377">And gode, and eke his saynt&euml;s, laugh<NOTE PLACE="foot">UH, dysplesyn T.</NOTE> also.</L>
<L>In siche sweryng &thorn;er is no stedfastnesse;</L>
<L>And &thorn;es wreches &thorn;at haue ful trust &thorn;er-to,</L>
<L N="380">After, &thorn;ai wepe and waylen in destresse."</L>
</LG>
<LG N="49" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(49) LAMANT.</HEAD>
<L N="381">"he hath no corage of a man, truly,<MILESTONE N="125" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>That sechith plesaunce, worschip to despyse;</L>
<L>Nor to be callyd forth, is not worthy</L>
<L>The erthe to toche the ayre in no-skynnes<NOTE PLACE="foot">UH, ne the . . . no kyns T.</NOTE> wyse.</L>
<L N="385">A trusty harte, a mouth without fayntyse,</L>
<L>Thes ben the strenght of euery man of name;</L>
<L>And who &thorn;at laith<NOTE PLACE="foot">latith H, lesyth T.</NOTE> his faith for lytel price,</L>
<L N="388">he lesith bothe his worschip and his fame."</L>
</LG>
<LG N="50" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(50) LA DAME.</HEAD>
<L N="389">"A currysche hert,<NOTE PLACE="foot">Fr. Villain cueur.</NOTE> a mouthe<NOTE PLACE="foot">UH, among T.</NOTE> &thorn;at is courteys,</L>
<L>ffull wel ye wote, &thorn;ei be<NOTE PLACE="foot">UH, these byn T.</NOTE> not &aacute;cordynge;</L>
<L>yet fayn&euml;d chere ryght sone may &thorn;eim<NOTE PLACE="foot">UH, they may T.</NOTE> apeyse,</L>
<L>Wher of malece is sete al her<NOTE PLACE="foot">there H, theyr T.</NOTE> worchynge:
<PB REF="00000145.tif" N="95"></L>
<L N="393">ffull fals semblant &thorn;ei bere, and trew semynge;<NOTE PLACE="foot">UT, meuyng H (semyng <I>in margin</I>).</NOTE></L>
<L>&thorn;aire name, &thorn;aire fame, &thorn;air tong&euml;s be bot<NOTE PLACE="foot">UT, not H (but <I>in margin</I>).</NOTE> fayned;</L>
<L>Worschip in heme is put in f&oacute;rgetynge,<NOTE PLACE="foot">forgetyng T, foryeting H, for etynge U.</NOTE></L>
<L N="396">Noght r&eacute;pentyd, nor in no wyse complayned."</L>
</LG>
<LG N="51" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(51) LAMANT.</HEAD>
<L N="397">"Who thynketh ylle, no good may hyme be-fale:</L>
<L>Gode, of his grace, grawnt yche mon his desert!</L>
<L>But, for his loue, among your<NOTE PLACE="foot">UH, hys T.</NOTE> thought&euml;s alle,</L>
<L>As thenke opon my wofull sorous<NOTE PLACE="foot">sorowe H.</NOTE> smert;</L>
<L N="401">ffor, of my payne, whedre<NOTE PLACE="foot">UT, where H.</NOTE> your tendre hert,</L>
<L>Of swete pyt&euml;, be noght &thorn;er-with a-grevyde,</L>
<L>And iffe your grace to me wer<NOTE PLACE="foot">UT, be H.</NOTE> discou&eacute;rt,</L>
<L>Then, be your meane, sone<NOTE PLACE="foot">UH, <I>om.</I> T.</NOTE> schuld I be releuyde."</L>
</LG>
<LG N="52" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(52) LA DAME.</HEAD>
<L N="405">"A lyghtsome hart, a folye of plesaunce,<MILESTONE N="125b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>Ar myche better, the lasse whyle &thorn;ei abyde;</L>
<L>Thei make you thynk,<NOTE PLACE="foot">thyng U, thynk H.</NOTE> and bryng you in<NOTE PLACE="foot">UH, into T.</NOTE> a traunce;</L>
<L>But &thorn;at sykenes will sone be remedyde.</L>
<L N="409">Respyte your thought, and put all &thorn;is a-syde;<NOTE PLACE="foot">UT, on side T.</NOTE></L>
<L>ffull goode disport&euml;s werith<NOTE PLACE="foot">weriethe H.</NOTE> men al daye;</L>
<L>To helpe nor hurt, my wille is not aplyde;</L>
<L>Who trouthe<NOTE PLACE="foot">trowith H, troweth T.</NOTE> me not, I<NOTE PLACE="foot">HT, <I>erasure in</I> U.</NOTE> let hit pase awaye."</L>
</LG>
<LG N="53" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(53) LAMANT.</HEAD>
<L N="413">"Who hath a byrde, a faukyn or a hounde,</L>
<L>That folowith hyme for loue in euery place,</L>
<L>he cherische<NOTE PLACE="foot">cherisithe H, cherysseth T.</NOTE> hyme, and kepith hym<NOTE PLACE="foot">UT, <I>om.</I> L.</NOTE> ful sounde;</L>
<L>Out<NOTE PLACE="foot">UH, But T.</NOTE> of his syght he wol hym<NOTE PLACE="foot">hym UT, <I>om.</I> H.</NOTE> note enchace.</L>
<L N="417">And I, &thorn;at sette my wytt&euml;s, in this case,</L>
<L>On you allon, withouten any chaunge,</L>
<L>Am<NOTE PLACE="foot">UT, And H (Am <I>in margin</I>).</NOTE> put vnder, myche for&thorn;er out of grace,</L>
<L N="420">And lese set<NOTE PLACE="foot">UT, sette lesse H.</NOTE> by, &thorn;en o&thorn;er &thorn;at be straunge."
<PB REF="00000146.tif" N="96"></L>
</LG>
<LG N="54" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(54) LA DAME.</HEAD>
<L N="421">"Though I make chere to euery man a-boute,</L>
<L>ffor my worschip, and of myn awne fraunchyse,</L>
<L>To you I nylle do so, withouten doute,</L>
<L>In &eacute;schwyng all maner preiudyse.</L>
<L N="425">ffor, wett you well,<NOTE PLACE="foot">ye well HT, you will U.</NOTE> loue is so<NOTE PLACE="foot">UH, <I>om.</I> T.</NOTE> lytle wyse,</L>
<L>And in be-leue so lyghtly wyll<NOTE PLACE="foot">wil H, wyll T, wel U.</NOTE> be broght,</L>
<L>That he taketh, al at his awne devyse,</L>
<L>Of thyng (god wot) &thorn;at serueth hym of noght."</L>
</LG>
<LG N="55" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(55) LAMANT.</HEAD>
<L N="429">"Iffe I, by loue and by my trew seruyse,<MILESTONE N="126" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>lese the good chere &thorn;at straungers haue alway,</L>
<L>Wher-of schuld<NOTE PLACE="foot">shuld H, I schuld UT.</NOTE> serue my trouth in any wyse</L>
<L>les &thorn;en to heme<NOTE PLACE="foot">hem H, theym T.</NOTE> &thorn;at come and go alday,</L>
<L N="433">Which hold<NOTE PLACE="foot">UH, had T.</NOTE> of you no thyng, &thorn;at is no<NOTE PLACE="foot">non H, to no T.</NOTE> nay?</L>
<L>Also in you is loste, to my semynge,</L>
<L>All courtesy, which of<NOTE PLACE="foot">UH, of all T.</NOTE> Resoun will<NOTE PLACE="foot">UT, wolde H.</NOTE> say,</L>
<L N="436">That loue by<NOTE PLACE="foot">for Skeat.</NOTE> loue were lawfull d&eacute;seruynge."</L>
</LG>
<LG N="56" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(56) LA DAME.</HEAD>
<L N="437">"Courtesye is allied wondir nere</L>
<L>To<NOTE PLACE="foot">UT, with H.</NOTE> worschip, which hyme louyth tendurly;<NOTE PLACE="foot">UT, best &amp; tendirly H.</NOTE></L>
<L>And he will not be bound, for no prayere</L>
<L>Nor for no<NOTE PLACE="foot">UT, <I>om.</I> H.</NOTE> yifte, I say you verely,</L>
<L N="441">But his good chere depart ful larg&euml;ly</L>
<L>Wher hyme lyk&eacute;th, as his conseit wil falle:</L>
<L>Guerdoun constraynt, a yifte done thankefully,</L>
<L>Thes twayn<NOTE PLACE="foot">UH, ij. T.</NOTE> may not a-cord, nor neuer schale."</L>
</LG>
<LG N="57" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(57) LAMANT.</HEAD>
<L N="445">"As for guerdoun, I seche<NOTE PLACE="foot">UH, seke T.</NOTE> none in &thorn;is case;<NOTE PLACE="foot">UH, place T.</NOTE></L>
<L>ffor &thorn;at desert, to me it<NOTE PLACE="foot">UT, <I>om.</I> H.</NOTE> is to hye;</L>
<L>Wherfor I asche<NOTE PLACE="foot">ashe H, ax T.</NOTE> your pardoun and your grace,</L>
<L>Sith me by-houyth deth,<NOTE PLACE="foot">H, <I>om.</I> UT.</NOTE> or your mercye.
<PB REF="00000147.tif" N="97"></L>
<L N="449">To yiue the good<NOTE PLACE="foot">good H, god U.</NOTE> wher hit<NOTE PLACE="foot">UH, that it T.</NOTE> wanteth, treulye,</L>
<L>That wer Resoun, and &aacute;<NOTE PLACE="foot">UT, <I>om.</I> H.</NOTE> courteys manere;</L>
<L>And to your awn myche bettyr were worthy,<NOTE PLACE="foot">UH, worth T.</NOTE></L>
<L>&thorn;en to straungers, to schew heme louely<NOTE PLACE="foot">H, lowly T, lonely U.</NOTE> chere."</L>
</LG>
<LG N="58" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(58) LA DAME.</HEAD>
<L N="453">"What call ye good? fayn wold I &thorn;at I wyste!<MILESTONE N="126b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>That plesith on, an-o&thorn;er<NOTE PLACE="foot">UH, and other T.</NOTE> smertyth sore;</L>
<L>But, of his awn, to large is he &thorn;at liste</L>
<L>yiue myche, and lese all his goode fame &thorn;erfore.</L>
<L N="457">On schuld not make a graunt, lytele nor more,</L>
<L>But &thorn;<SUP>e</SUP> request were ryght wele &aacute;cordynge;</L>
<L>yif worschip be not kept and set byfore,</L>
<L N="460">All &thorn;at is lefte, is but a lytell thynge."</L>
</LG>
<LG N="59" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(59) LAMANT.</HEAD>
<L N="461">"In-to &thorn;is world was neuer formyd non,</L>
<L>Nor vndur heven cr&euml;ature<NOTE PLACE="foot">UT, o creature H.</NOTE> I-bore,</L>
<L>Nor neuer schall, saffe only your parson,<NOTE PLACE="foot">persone H.</NOTE></L>
<L>To whom your worschip toucheth half so sore;</L>
<L N="465">But me, which haue no sesoun, les ne more,</L>
<L>of youth nor age, but styll in your seruyse,</L>
<L>I haue non yne,<NOTE PLACE="foot">yeen H, eyen T.</NOTE> no wyt, nor mouth in store,</L>
<L N="468">But all beth<NOTE PLACE="foot">But . . byn T, that ne alle ar H.</NOTE> yiuen to &thorn;e same offyse."</L>
</LG>
<LG N="60" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(60) LA DAME.</HEAD>
<L N="469">"A full gret charge hath he, with outen fayle,</L>
<L>&thorn;at his worschip kepyth in sykernesse;</L>
<L>But in daunger he settyth his trauayle,</L>
<L>That feffith hit with othyrs<NOTE PLACE="foot">UH, other T.</NOTE> bysynesse.</L>
<L N="473">To hym &thorn;at longeth honneur and noblesse,</L>
<L>Vpon non othir schuld not<NOTE PLACE="foot">UH, <I>om.</I> T.</NOTE> he awayte;</L>
<L>ffor of his<NOTE PLACE="foot">UT, <I>om.</I> H.</NOTE> awn, so mych hath&euml;<NOTE PLACE="foot">hathe he HT.</NOTE> &thorn;e lesse,</L>
<L N="476">That, of othir, mych folouth the conseit."
<PB REF="00000148.tif" N="98"></L>
</LG>
<LG N="61" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(61) LAMANT.</HEAD>
<L N="477">"your yen<NOTE PLACE="foot">yeen H, eyen T.</NOTE> haue set the prynte<NOTE PLACE="foot">UH, theym present T.</NOTE> which &thorn;at y fele<NOTE PLACE="foot">Fr. Voz yeulx out si empraint leur merche.</NOTE><MILESTONE N="127" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>withyn myn herte, &thorn;at, wher-so-euer<NOTE PLACE="foot">where-sum-euer H.</NOTE> y goo,</L>
<L>If y do thyng &thorn;at sowneth<NOTE PLACE="foot">sowndithe H.</NOTE> vnto wele,</L>
<L>Nede must it<NOTE PLACE="foot">UH, it must T.</NOTE> come from you, and fro no mo.</L>
<L N="481">ffortune will thus, &thorn;at y, for wele or wo,</L>
<L>My lyfe endure, your mercy &aacute;bidyng;</L>
<L>And very right, will &thorn;at y thynk also</L>
<L N="484">Of your wurship, aboue all other thyng."</L>
</LG>
<LG N="62" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(62) LA DAME.</HEAD>
<L N="485">"To your wurship se wele, for &thorn;at is nede,</L>
<L>&thorn;at ye spende not your seasoun<NOTE PLACE="foot">UT, ye your sesoun spende not H.</NOTE> all in vayn.</L>
<L>As touchyng myn, y rede you take non hede,</L>
<L>By your foly, to putte your-selfe in peyn.</L>
<L N="489">To Ouercom is good, and to restreyn</L>
<L>An herte which is deseyved folyly;</L>
<L>ffor wers it is to breke &thorn;an<NOTE PLACE="foot">UH, the T.</NOTE> bowe, certeyn,</L>
<L N="492">And better bowe, than falle to sodenly."</L>
</LG>
<LG N="63" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(63) LAMANT.</HEAD>
<L N="493">"Now, faire lady, thenk, sith it first began,</L>
<L>&thorn;at loue hadde sette myn hert vndre his<NOTE PLACE="foot">your H, <I>om.</I> T.</NOTE> cure,</L>
<L>It neuer myght, nor<NOTE PLACE="foot">I . . ne H, It not UT.</NOTE> treuly y ne can,</L>
<L>None othir serue, whils y shall here<NOTE PLACE="foot">UT, here I shal H.</NOTE> endure;</L>
<L N="497">In most fre wise, therof y make you sure,</L>
<L>which may not be with-drawe: this is no nay.</L>
<L>I must abide all maner &aacute;uenture;</L>
<L N="500">ffor y may nought putte to, nor take away."</L>
</LG>
<LG N="64" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(64) LA DAME.</HEAD>
<L N="501">"I holde it for no yifte, in sothefastnes,<MILESTONE N="127b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>That one offereth, where &thorn;at it is forsake;</L>
<L>ffor suche yifte is abandonnyng expresse,</L>
<L>That, with wurship, ayen may not be take.
<PB REF="00000149.tif" N="99"></L>
<L N="505">he hathe an hert full fell,<NOTE PLACE="foot">Thynne (Sk.), hertis full fele UT, hurte ful fele H.</NOTE> &thorn;at list to make</L>
<L>A yift lightly, &thorn;at put is in refuse;</L>
<L>But he is wyse &thorn;at suche conseyt will slake,</L>
<L N="508">So &thorn;at hym nede nether stodie nor<NOTE PLACE="foot">UT, neuer to stody ne H.</NOTE> muse."</L>
</LG>
<LG N="65" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(65) LAMANT.</HEAD>
<L N="509">"he<NOTE PLACE="foot">UT, Who H.</NOTE> shuld not muse, &thorn;at hath<NOTE PLACE="foot">hath HT, <I>om.</I> U.</NOTE> his seruyse spent</L>
<L>On hir which is a lady honour&aacute;ble;</L>
<L>And yf y spende my tyme to &thorn;at entent,</L>
<L>yit atte the lest y am nat r&eacute;preu&aacute;ble</L>
<L N="513">Of fayl&euml;d herte: to thynk, y am vnable,</L>
<L>Or me mystoke whan y made this request,</L>
<L>By which loue hathe, of entirprise not&aacute;ble,</L>
<L N="516">So many hertis getyn bi conquest."</L>
</LG>
<LG N="66" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(66) LA DAME.</HEAD>
<L N="517">"yf &thorn;at ye liste do after my Counsayll</L>
<L>Secheth faycrer,<NOTE PLACE="foot">UH, ferther T.</NOTE> and of more hier fame,</L>
<L>Which in seruice of loue will you prevayll</L>
<L>After your &thorn;ought, acordyng to the same.</L>
<L N="521">he hurteth both<NOTE PLACE="foot">both HT, <I>om.</I> U.</NOTE> his wurship and his name,</L>
<L>&thorn;at folyly for tweyn<NOTE PLACE="foot">UH, ij. T.</NOTE> hym-selfe will trobull;</L>
<L>And also he les&eacute;th his after game,</L>
<L N="524">That surely cannot sette his poynt&euml;s double."<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>After-game</I>, return-match . . . I believe l. 524 to mean, 'who cannot thoroughly afford to double his stakes.' To <I>set</I> often means to stake. The French is:&mdash; <Q><L>'Et celuy pert le ien d'attente</L><L>Qui ne scet faire son point double.'</L></Q> &mdash;Skeat, vii. 519.</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG N="67" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(67) LAMANT.<NOTE PLACE="foot">Fr.: Le conseil que vous me donnez.</NOTE></HEAD>
<L N="525">"This your Counsell, by ought &thorn;at y can se,<MILESTONE N="128" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>Is better seid than done, to myn avise.</L>
<L>Though i beleue it not, foryif<NOTE PLACE="foot">UH, foryeue T.</NOTE> it me;</L>
<L>Myn herte is suche, so hele<NOTE PLACE="foot">hoole THU.</NOTE> withoute fayntyse,</L>
<L N="529">That it may not<NOTE PLACE="foot">TU, <I>om.</I> H.</NOTE> yeve credence, in no wyse,</L>
<L>To thyng which<NOTE PLACE="foot">UH, thynke that T.</NOTE> is not sownyng vnto trouth:
<PB REF="00000150.tif" N="100"></L>
<L>Other Councell, it<NOTE PLACE="foot">other counsail it H, others counsayles hit T, hit <I>om.</I> U.</NOTE> are but fantasise,<NOTE PLACE="foot">UH, fantasyes T.</NOTE></L>
<L N="532">Saf of<NOTE PLACE="foot">of HT, <I>om.</I> U.</NOTE> your grace to shewe pit&euml; and routhe."</L>
</LG>
<LG N="68" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(68) LA DAME.</HEAD>
<L N="533">"I holde hym wise, &thorn;at wurcheth folyly,</L>
<L>And, whan hym list, can leue<NOTE PLACE="foot">And . . leue UH, when he can leue T.</NOTE> and part therfro;</L>
<L>But in konnyng he is to lerne, trewely,</L>
<L>&thorn;at wold hym selfe condit,<NOTE PLACE="foot">conduyte H, condute T.</NOTE> and cannot<NOTE PLACE="foot">cannat HT, canno U.</NOTE> so.</L>
<L N="537">And he &thorn;at will not after Conseyll do,</L>
<L>his sute<NOTE PLACE="foot">UT, suerte UH (sute <I>in margin</I>).</NOTE> he putteth in des&eacute;[s]peraunce;</L>
<L>And all the good, which<NOTE PLACE="foot">goodys T, good which H.</NOTE> &thorn;at shuld fall hym to,</L>
<L N="540">Is lefte as<NOTE PLACE="foot">UH, all T.</NOTE> dede, clene out of r&eacute;membraunce."</L>
</LG>
<LG N="69" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(69) LAMANT.</HEAD>
<L N="541">"yit will y sue this matier faythfully</L>
<L>whils y may leue, what-euer be<NOTE PLACE="foot">UH, what oon by T.</NOTE> my chaunce;</L>
<L>And if it happe &thorn;at in my trouth y die,</L>
<L>&thorn;at dethe shall not do me no displesaunce.</L>
<L N="545">But when &thorn;at y, by your full hard<NOTE PLACE="foot">UT, your harde H.</NOTE> sufferaunce,</L>
<L>Shall die so trewe, and with so gret&euml;<NOTE PLACE="foot">UT, grete a H.</NOTE> peyne,</L>
<L>yit shall it do me moche the<NOTE PLACE="foot">UT, moche H.</NOTE> lesse grevaunce,</L>
<L N="548">&thorn;en for to leue a fals louer, sertayn."</L>
</LG>
<LG N="70" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(70) LA DAME.</HEAD>
<L N="549">"Of me gete ye right nought, this is no fable;<MILESTONE N="128b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>I nyll<NOTE PLACE="foot">UH, wyll T.</NOTE> to you be nether hard nor streyght;</L>
<L>And right wil nat, nor maner Custum&aacute;ble,</L>
<L>To thynke ye shuld be sure of myn conseyt.</L>
<L N="553">Who secheth sorow,<NOTE PLACE="foot">UH, sorowys T.</NOTE> his be<NOTE PLACE="foot">is by H ('his bi' <I>margin</I>), by T.</NOTE> the reseyt.</L>
<L>Other Counceyll can y not fele nor se;</L>
<L>Nor for to lerne, y cast not to awayte:</L>
<L N="556">Who wyll therto, late hym assay, for me."
<PB REF="00000151.tif" N="101"></L>
</LG>
<LG N="71" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(71) LAMANT.</HEAD>
<L N="557">"Ones must it be<NOTE PLACE="foot">UH, it must be T.</NOTE> asaied, &thorn;at is no nay,<NOTE PLACE="foot">Fr.: Vue fois le fault essayer.</NOTE></L>
<L>with suche as be of reputac&iuml;oun</L>
<L>And of trewe loue the right deuoyr<NOTE PLACE="foot">UT, duetes H.</NOTE> to paie,</L>
<L>Of fre hertis, getyn by due Raunsom;</L>
<L N="561">ffor fre will holdeth this opynyon,</L>
<L>&THORN;at it is grete dures and discomfort</L>
<L>To kepe an hert in s&oacute; streyt a presoun,</L>
<L N="564">&THORN;at hathe but on body for<NOTE PLACE="foot">UH, to T.</NOTE> his disport."</L>
</LG>
<LG N="72" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(72) LA DAME.</HEAD>
<L N="565">"I knowe so many Cases<NOTE PLACE="foot">UT, caases H (causes <I>margin</I>).</NOTE> meruelos,</L>
<L>That y must nede, of resoun, thynk certeyn,</L>
<L>&THORN;at suche entre<NOTE PLACE="foot">UH, entent T.</NOTE> is wondre perelous;</L>
<L>And yit wele more, the comyng bak ageyn;<NOTE PLACE="foot">bak ageyn H, abak certeyn U, bak certeyn T.</NOTE></L>
<L N="569">Good or wurship therof is seldon seyn;</L>
<L>Wherfore y wil not make none suche aray,</L>
<L>As for to fynde a plesaunce but bareyn,</L>
<L N="572">When it shall coste so dere, &thorn;<SUP>e</SUP> first asay."</L>
</LG>
<LG N="73" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(73) LAMANT.</HEAD>
<L N="573">"ye haue no cause to doute of this matiere,<NOTE PLACE="foot">Fr.: Vous n'auez cause de douter.</NOTE><MILESTONE N="129" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>Nor you to meve with non suche fantasise</L>
<L>To putte me far all<NOTE PLACE="foot">all, <I>om</I>. T.</NOTE> out, as a straunger;</L>
<L>ffor youre goodnes can thynk<NOTE PLACE="foot">thynk H, thynke T, thyng U.</NOTE> and wele avise,</L>
<L N="577">&THORN;at y haue made a prefe<NOTE PLACE="foot">prese U.</NOTE> in euery wise,</L>
<L>By which my trouth sheweth open evidence:</L>
<L>Mi long abidyng and my trew seruice</L>
<L N="580">May wele be knowe by playn experience."</L>
</LG>
<LG N="74" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(74) LA DAME.</HEAD>
<L N="581">"Of very right, he may be called trewe,<NOTE PLACE="foot">Fr.: Il se peut loyal appeller.</NOTE></L>
<L>(And so must he be take in euery place)</L>
<L>&THORN;at can deserue, and let as he ne knewe,</L>
<L>And kepe the good, yf he it may purch&aacute;ce.
<PB REF="00000152.tif" N="102"></L>
<L N="585">ffor who &thorn;at prayeth or sueth in any cace<NOTE PLACE="foot">UH, place T.</NOTE></L>
<L>Right wele ye wot, in<NOTE PLACE="foot">in, <I>om.</I> T.</NOTE> &thorn;at no trouth is preued:</L>
<L>Siche hathe ther bene, and<NOTE PLACE="foot">and H, an U.</NOTE> are, &thorn;at geteth<NOTE PLACE="foot">UH, getyn T.</NOTE> grace,</L>
<L N="588">And lese it sone, whan they it haue acheuyd."</L>
</LG>
<LG N="75" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(75) LAMANT.</HEAD>
<L N="589">"yf trouth me cause, bi vertu souerayn,</L>
<L>To shewe good loue, and all-wey fynde contr&aacute;ry,</L>
<L>And cherissh &thorn;at at<NOTE PLACE="foot">that H.</NOTE> slethe me with &thorn;<SUP>e</SUP> payn,</L>
<L>&THORN;is is to me a louely aduersarie.</L>
<L N="593">when &thorn;at pite, which longe aslepe dothe tarye,</L>
<L>hathe set &thorn;<SUP>e</SUP> fyn of all myn hevynesse,</L>
<L>yit her comfort, to me most necessarye,</L>
<L>Shuld sette my wille more sure in stabilnesse."</L>
</LG>
<LG N="76" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(76) LA DAME.</HEAD>
<L N="597">"&THORN;e<NOTE PLACE="foot">UH, A T.</NOTE> wofull wight, what may he<NOTE PLACE="foot">ye UT, he H.</NOTE> thynk or say?<MILESTONE N="129b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>&THORN;e contrarie of &aacute;ll ioye and gladnesse.</L>
<L>A seke body, his thought is all away<NOTE PLACE="foot">UH, bodyes thought is alwey T.</NOTE></L>
<L>ffro hem &thorn;at fele no sorow nor sekenes.</L>
<L N="601">&THORN;us hertis<NOTE PLACE="foot">hurtes H. Skeat.</NOTE> bene of dyuerse besynes</L>
<L>which loue<NOTE PLACE="foot">loue UH, <I>om.</I> T.</NOTE> hathe putte to right gret hynderaunce,</L>
<L>And treuthe also put in foryetfulnes,</L>
<L N="604">when they so sore begynne to sigh askaunce."</L>
</LG>
<LG N="77" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(77) LAMANT.</HEAD>
<L N="605">"Now god defende, but he be hau&euml;les<NOTE PLACE="foot">De tous soit celuy deguerpiz.</NOTE></L>
<L>Of all wurship or good &thorn;at may befalle,</L>
<L>&THORN;at to the wurst turneth, by his lewdenes,</L>
<L>A yift of grace, or ony thyng atte all</L>
<L N="609">That his lady<NOTE PLACE="foot">his lady H, this lady U, ys T.</NOTE> vouchesaf vppon hym calle,</L>
<L>Or cheryssheth<NOTE PLACE="foot">cherysshe TH, cheryssheth U.</NOTE> hym in honorable wyse!</L>
<L>In &thorn;at defaut, what-euer he be &thorn;at fall,</L>
<L N="612">Deserueth<NOTE PLACE="foot">Deserueth H, Derserueth U.</NOTE> more, then dethe to suffre twyse."
<PB REF="00000153.tif" N="103"></L>
</LG>
<LG N="78" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(78) LA DAME.</HEAD>
<L N="613">"There is no Iuge yset of<NOTE PLACE="foot">UH, on T.</NOTE> suche tresp&aacute;ce,</L>
<L>By which, of right, one may recouered be;</L>
<L>One curseth faste, an-other dotbe man&aacute;ce,</L>
<L>yit dieth non, as fer as y can se,</L>
<L N="617">But kepe her cours all-wey, in one degre,<NOTE PLACE="foot">one degre H, oo degre T, ordre U.</NOTE></L>
<L>And euermore<NOTE PLACE="foot">euermore UT, euere newe H.</NOTE> there labour dothe encrece,</L>
<L>To brynge ladise, bi their grete<NOTE PLACE="foot">grete UT, <I>om.</I> H.</NOTE> sotelte,</L>
<L N="620">ffor othirs gilt, in sorow and disese."</L>
</LG>
<LG N="79" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(79) LAMANT.</HEAD>
<L N="621">"All-be-hit<NOTE PLACE="foot">Though hit be T, Al be it H.</NOTE> so, on do so gret offence,<NOTE PLACE="foot">Fr.: Combien qu on n'arde ne ne pende, p. 518.</NOTE><MILESTONE N="130" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>And be not dede, nor put to no Iuyse,</L>
<L>Ryght wele I wot, hym gayneth no deffence,</L>
<L>But he must ende in full mysch&eacute;uous wyse,</L>
<L N="625">And all &thorn;at euer<NOTE PLACE="foot">euer UH, <I>om.</I> T.</NOTE> is gode will hym despyse;</L>
<L>ffor falshode is so full of cursydnesse,</L>
<L>That highe<NOTE PLACE="foot">theyr T, her H.</NOTE> worschip may<NOTE PLACE="foot">may U, <I>om.</I> T, shall H.</NOTE> never haue enterprise</L>
<L N="628">Wher hit rayneth, and hath the wylfulnysse."</L>
</LG>
<LG N="80" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(80) LA DAME.</HEAD>
<L N="629">"Of<NOTE PLACE="foot">Yef T, Off H.</NOTE> that haue &thorn;ei<NOTE PLACE="foot">&thorn;ei haue T, haue &thorn;ei H.</NOTE> no gret fere now of<NOTE PLACE="foot">a TH.</NOTE> dayes,</L>
<L>Siche as wyll<NOTE PLACE="foot">wyll T, wel U, wil H.</NOTE> say, and maynten hit &thorn;er-to,</L>
<L>That stidfast trouth is nothyng for to preyes<NOTE PLACE="foot">preys H.</NOTE></L>
<L>In hem &thorn;at kepe hit longe, for weile or wo.</L>
<L N="633">&THORN;aire bysy hertes passen to and fro,</L>
<L>&THORN;ai be so wele reclaymed to the lure,</L>
<L>So well lorned hem<NOTE PLACE="foot">hem H, theym T, &amp; U.</NOTE> to with-holde also,</L>
<L>And all to chaunge, when loue schuld best endure."</L>
</LG>
<LG N="81" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(81) LAMANT.</HEAD>
<L N="637">"When won hath sett his hert in stable wisse,</L>
<L>In siche a place which is boeth gude and trewe,
<PB REF="00000154.tif" N="104"></L>
<L>he schuld not flytte, bot do forth his seruyse</L>
<L>Alway, with-outen<NOTE PLACE="foot">without the T, withoute H.</NOTE> chaunge of any newe.</L>
<L N="641">As sone as loue by-gynneth to remew.<NOTE PLACE="foot">renew T, remewe H.</NOTE></L>
<L>All plesaunce goth anon, in letel space:</L>
<L>As for my party, &thorn;at schal I<NOTE PLACE="foot">UT, For my party, al H, that I shal H.</NOTE> eschewe,</L>
<L>Whils &thorn;at my<NOTE PLACE="foot">my T, the UH.</NOTE> sowle abydythe in his place."</L>
</LG>
<LG N="82" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(82) LA DAME.</HEAD>
<L N="645">"To loue trewly, ther as ye oght of ryght,<MILESTONE N="130b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>ye may not be mysse-taken, dout[&euml;]lesse,</L>
<L>Bot ye be fowle deceyued in your syght,</L>
<L>By lyghtly vndurstandyng, as I gesse;</L>
<L N="649">yet may ye wel repeale your bysynesse,</L>
<L>And to resoun, some-what haue &aacute;tendaunce,</L>
<L>myche better &thorn;en to abyde, by fole<NOTE PLACE="foot">sole T, foly H.</NOTE> symplesse,</L>
<L N="652">The feble socour<NOTE PLACE="foot">UH, socours T.</NOTE> of desesperaunce."</L>
</LG>
<LG N="83" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(83) LAMANT.</HEAD>
<L N="653">"Resoun, councell, wysdam, and good avyse</L>
<L>Bene vndur loue a-restyd<NOTE PLACE="foot">UH, arestyn T.</NOTE> euerychone,&mdash;</L>
<L>To which I can acord in euery wyse;&mdash;</L>
<L>ffor &thorn;ai be not rebell, bot still as<NOTE PLACE="foot">UH, as a T.</NOTE> stone;</L>
<L N="657">Their will and myne ar<NOTE PLACE="foot">myne ar T, mynd as U, myn ben H.</NOTE> medeled al in won,</L>
<L>And &thorn;er-with bownden with so stronge a cheyne,</L>
<L>That, as in hem,<NOTE PLACE="foot">theym T, heuen U, hem H.</NOTE> departyng shal be none,</L>
<L N="660">But pyt&euml; breke the myghty bonde a-tweyn."</L>
</LG>
<LG N="84" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(84) LA DAME.</HEAD>
<L N="661">"Who loueth not hym-selfe, what-euer he be,</L>
<L>In loue he stant<NOTE PLACE="foot">UH, standeth T.</NOTE> for-yet in euery place;</L>
<L>And, of your woo, if ye haue no pyte,</L>
<L>Othirs pyte be-leue not to purch&aacute;ce,<NOTE PLACE="foot">purches UH.</NOTE></L>
<L N="665">But bethe fully assur&egrave;d in this case,</L>
<L>I am al-ways vndur on ordynaunce,</L>
<L>To haue better: trysteth not after grace,</L>
<L N="668">And al &thorn;at leueth,<NOTE PLACE="foot">UH, loueth T.</NOTE> take to your plesaunce."
<PB REF="00000155.tif" N="105"></L>
</LG>
<LG N="85" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(85) LAMANT.</HEAD>
<L N="669">"I haue myn hope so sure and so stedfast,<NOTE PLACE="foot">Fr.: I'ay mon esperance fermee.</NOTE><MILESTONE N="131" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>That sich a lady schuld not faile pyte;</L>
<L>But now, alas, it is schit vp so fast,</L>
<L>That daunger schewth on me his cruelte.</L>
<L N="673">And iffe sche se &thorn;e<NOTE PLACE="foot">that T, the H.</NOTE> vertu fayle in me</L>
<L>Of trew seruyse, &thorn;en sche to faile also</L>
<L>No wondir wer; but &thorn;is is the seurte,</L>
<L N="676">I must suffre, which way &thorn;at euer hit<NOTE PLACE="foot">I T, it H.</NOTE> go."</L>
</LG>
<LG N="86" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(86) LA DAME.</HEAD>
<L N="677">"leue<NOTE PLACE="foot">Loue T, Leve H.</NOTE> this purpos, I rede you for your best;</L>
<L>ffor, lenger that<NOTE PLACE="foot">UH, the lenger T.</NOTE> ye kepe hit &thorn;us in vayn,</L>
<L>The les ye gete, as of your hert&euml;s rest,</L>
<L>And to reioisse hit, schal ye neuer attayne.</L>
<L N="681">When ye abyde goode hope, to make you fayne,</L>
<L>ye schal be founde a-sotyde<NOTE PLACE="foot">UH, bounde assured T.</NOTE> in dotage</L>
<L>And in the ende, ye sch&aacute;ll know for sertayne,</L>
<L>That hope schall pay &thorn;e wrecches for &thorn;er wage."<NOTE PLACE="foot">&thorn;er wage H, your wage T, your waye U.</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG N="87" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(87) LAMANT.</HEAD>
<L N="685">"ye say as fallyth most for your plesaunce,</L>
<L>And your power is grete; al &thorn;is I se;</L>
<L>But hope schall neuer out of my R&eacute;membraunce,</L>
<L>By which I felt so grete aduersyte.</L>
<L N="689">ffor when nature hath set in you plente</L>
<L>Of all goodnes, by vertu and by<NOTE PLACE="foot">UH, hygh T.</NOTE> grace,</L>
<L>He<NOTE PLACE="foot">He UT, Ne U.</NOTE> neuer assembled hem, as semyth me,</L>
<L N="692">To put pyte out of his dwellyng place."</L>
</LG>
<LG N="88" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(88) LA DAME.</HEAD>
<L N="693">"Pyte of ryght ought<NOTE PLACE="foot">oweth T, aught H.</NOTE> to be reson&aacute;ble,<MILESTONE N="131b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>And to no wyght of gret dis&aacute;uauntage:<NOTE PLACE="foot">disauauntaye . . domaye U.</NOTE></L>
<L>Ther as is nede, hit schuld be<NOTE PLACE="foot">by U, be HT.</NOTE> profyt&aacute;ble,</L>
<L>And to the pytous, schewyng no domage.<NOTE PLACE="foot">disauauntaye . . domaye U.</NOTE>
<PB REF="00000156.tif" N="106"></L>
<L N="697">Iffe a lady will do so gret outr&aacute;ge</L>
<L>To schew pyte, and cause her awn debate.</L>
<L>Of siche pyte comyth dispytous Rage,</L>
<L N="700">And of &thorn;e loue also ryght dedly<NOTE PLACE="foot">UH, dewly T.</NOTE> hate"</L>
</LG>
<LG N="89" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(89) LAMANT.</HEAD>
<L N="701">"To coumfort hem &thorn;at lyue<NOTE PLACE="foot">UH, byn T.</NOTE> all coumfortles,</L>
<L>That is non harme, but worschip to your name;</L>
<L>But ye, &thorn;at bere an hert of syche dures,</L>
<L>A fair body I-fourmyd<NOTE PLACE="foot">And a fair body formed. Thynne, Skeat.</NOTE> to the same,</L>
<L N="705">Iffe I durst say, ye wyn all &thorn;is diffame</L>
<L>By cruelte, which sittyth you full ylle,</L>
<L>But iffe pyte, which may al &thorn;is atame,<NOTE PLACE="foot">may . . attame H, may not al &thorn;is attame U, all this may attame T.</NOTE></L>
<L N="708">In your hye hert may reste and tary stylle."</L>
</LG>
<LG N="90" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(90) LA DAME.</HEAD>
<L N="709">"What-euer he be &thorn;at saith he loueth me,&mdash;</L>
<L>And paraunter I leue<NOTE PLACE="foot">UH, beleue T.</NOTE> &thorn;at hit be so,&mdash;</L>
<L>Ough[t] he be wroth, or schuld I<NOTE PLACE="foot">wrother schuld I T, wroth or I schuld U.</NOTE> blamyd be,</L>
<L>Though I did not as he wold haue me do?</L>
<L N="713">Iffe I medlyd with siche, or othir mo,</L>
<L>hit myght be called 'pyte maner-les;'</L>
<L>And aftirward, iffe I schuld lyue in wo,</L>
<L N="716">Then to repent hit were to late, I gesse."</L>
</LG>
<LG N="91" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(91) LAMANT.</HEAD>
<L N="717">"O marbre<NOTE PLACE="foot">marbil H, marble T.</NOTE> hert, and yet mor hard<NOTE PLACE="foot">UH, mor hardyr T.</NOTE>; pardye,<NOTE PLACE="foot">Ha! cueur plus dur que le noir marbre.</NOTE><MILESTONE N="132" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>Which mercy may not perse,<NOTE PLACE="foot">parte T, perce H.</NOTE> for no labour,</L>
<L>mor strong<NOTE PLACE="foot">UH, stronger T.</NOTE> to bow then is a myghty tre,</L>
<L>What vayleth<NOTE PLACE="foot">UH, avayleth T.</NOTE> you to schew so gret rygour?</L>
<L N="721">please it you mor, to se me dye &thorn;is oure</L>
<L>By-for your yne,<NOTE PLACE="foot">eyne T, yeen H.</NOTE> for your disport and play,</L>
<L>Then for to schew some comfort or socour</L>
<L N="724">To respyte dethe, which chaseth me alway?"
<PB REF="00000157.tif" N="107"></L>
</LG>
<LG N="92" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(92) LA DAME.</HEAD>
<L N="725">"Of your disease ye may haue &aacute;-legeaunce;<NOTE PLACE="foot">allegeaunce T, allegeance H.</NOTE></L>
<L>And as for myn, I lat hit ouer-schake.<NOTE PLACE="foot">UH, slake T.</NOTE></L>
<L>Also, ye schall not dye for my plesaunce,</L>
<L>Nor for your hele<NOTE PLACE="foot">UH, lyfe T.</NOTE> I cane no suerty make.</L>
<L N="729">I wyll<NOTE PLACE="foot">UH, wold.</NOTE> not hate myn hert for o&thorn;er<NOTE PLACE="foot">othyrs T, othirs H.</NOTE> sake:</L>
<L>Wepe &thorn;ei, laghe &thorn;ei,<NOTE PLACE="foot">UH, or laghe T.</NOTE> or syng, &thorn;is<NOTE PLACE="foot">UH, thus T.</NOTE> I warant,</L>
<L>ffor this mater so wele to<NOTE PLACE="foot">weel to H, wyll I T, wele I U.</NOTE> vndur-take,</L>
<L N="732">&THORN;at none of you schall make &thorn;er-of avaunt."</L>
</LG>
<LG N="93" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(93) LAMANT.</HEAD>
<L N="733">"I can no skylle of song: by god allone,</L>
<L>I haue mor cause to wepe in your pres&eacute;nce;</L>
<L>And wel<NOTE PLACE="foot">wel T, wele H, wil U.</NOTE> I wote, avaunter am I none,</L>
<L>ffor certaynly,<NOTE PLACE="foot">UH, in certeyn T.</NOTE> I loue better sylence.</L>
<L N="737">On schuld not loue by his hertis cred&eacute;nce,</L>
<L>But he wer suer to kepe hit secretly;</L>
<L>ffor &aacute;vaunter is of no reuerence</L>
<L N="740">When &thorn;at his tonge is his most enemy."</L>
</LG>
<LG N="94" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(94) LA DAME.</HEAD>
<L N="741">"Male-bouche in court hath gret comaund&euml;ment;<MILESTONE N="132b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>Ech man studith to say the wurst he may.</L>
<L>Thes fals louers, in &thorn;is tyme now pres&eacute;nt,</L>
<L>Thai serue to bost, to Iangle as a Iay.</L>
<L N="745">&THORN;e most secret wylle wele &thorn;at sum man<NOTE PLACE="foot">men TH.</NOTE> say</L>
<L>how he mystristed is on sum partyse;<NOTE PLACE="foot">UH, in . . parte T.</NOTE></L>
<L>Wherfor, to ladyse what men speke or pray,<NOTE PLACE="foot">UH, wherfor these louers whatsoeuer they say T.</NOTE></L>
<L N="748">It schuld not be byleuyd in no wyse."</L>
</LG>
<LG N="95" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(95) LAMANT.</HEAD>
<L N="749">"Of good and yll, schall be, and is alway;</L>
<L>the world is sich; &thorn;e erth it is nat playn.</L>
<L>Thay &thorn;at be good, the preef schewth euery day,</L>
<L>And othir-wyse, gret vylany, sertayn.
<PB REF="00000158.tif" N="108"></L>
<L N="753">Is hit reson, &thorn;ough on his tonge distayn,</L>
<L>with cursyd spech, to do hym-selfe a schame,</L>
<L>&THORN;at such<NOTE PLACE="foot">such T, suche H, sichur U.</NOTE> refus schuld wrongfully remayn</L>
<L N="756">Vpon the good, Renomyd in &thorn;air fame?"<NOTE PLACE="foot">UH, renewyd in his name T.</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG N="96" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(96) LA DAME.</HEAD>
<L>"Sich as be nought, when &thorn;ai her[e] tydyngs newe,</L>
<L>That eche trespace schall lyghtly haue pardon,</L>
<L>Thai &thorn;at purp&oacute;sith<NOTE PLACE="foot">purpose T, purposen H.</NOTE> to be goode and trewe,</L>
<L>(Wele set by noble disposic&iuml;oun</L>
<L N="761">To c&oacute;ntynue in goode condyc&iuml;oun)</L>
<L>Thai ar the first &thorn;at fallith<NOTE PLACE="foot">fall T.</NOTE> in dam&aacute;ge,</L>
<L>And full frely &thorn;air hert&euml;s<NOTE PLACE="foot">UT, theym H.</NOTE> &aacute;bandone</L>
<L N="764">To lytell fayth, with soft and fair<NOTE PLACE="foot">UT, faire &amp; softe H.</NOTE> langage."</L>
</LG>
<LG N="97" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(97) LAMANT.</HEAD>
<L N="765">"Now know I welle, of verrey sertaynete,<MILESTONE N="133" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>Though<NOTE PLACE="foot">Though TH, Iff U.</NOTE> on do trowly, yit<NOTE PLACE="foot">yet H, ye T.</NOTE> shal he be schent,</L>
<L>Sith all maner of Iustyce and pyte</L>
<L>Is banyscht out of &aacute; ladys entent.</L>
<L N="769">I can nat se but all is at o stent,<NOTE PLACE="foot">a stent T, oo stente H.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;e good, &thorn;e<NOTE PLACE="foot">and TH.</NOTE> yll, &thorn;e vyce, and eke vertu.</L>
<L>Sych as be good, schall haue the punyschment</L>
<L N="772">ffor the trespace of hem &thorn;at beth vntrewe."</L>
</LG>
<LG N="98" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(98) LA DAME.</HEAD>
<L N="773">"I haue no power, you to do<NOTE PLACE="foot">UH, to do you T.</NOTE> greuaunce,</L>
<L>Nor to punysch<NOTE PLACE="foot">UH, promyse T.</NOTE> non o&thorn;er cr&euml;ature;</L>
<L>But, to eschewe &thorn;e more encoumberaunce,</L>
<L>To kepe vs from you<NOTE PLACE="foot">you H, yow T, yois U.</NOTE> all, I holde hit sure.</L>
<L N="777">ffals semblant hath a vysage full demure,</L>
<L>lyghtly to cache &thorn;<SUP>e</SUP> ladyse in a-wayte;</L>
<L>wherfor we must, iffe &thorn;at<NOTE PLACE="foot">UH, <I>om.</I> T.</NOTE> we wyll endure,</L>
<L>Make ryght good wache: lo! &thorn;is is my conseyt."
<PB REF="00000159.tif" N="109"></L>
</LG>
<LG N="99" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(99) LAMANT.</HEAD>
<L N="781">"Sith &thorn;at, of grace, o goodly word allone</L>
<L>May noght be hade, but alway kept in store,</L>
<L>I pele<NOTE PLACE="foot">UH, speke T.</NOTE> to gode, (for he may her my mone,)</L>
<L>Of &thorn;e duresse which greuythe me so<NOTE PLACE="foot">which . . . so UH, that . . me T.</NOTE> sore.</L>
<L N="785">and of pyte I playne me fordermore,<NOTE PLACE="foot">furthermore T, furthere-more H.</NOTE></L>
<L>which he foryat, in all his ordynaunce,</L>
<L>Or elles my lyfe to h&aacute;ue endid by-fore,</L>
<L N="788">which he so sone put out of R&eacute;membraunce."</L>
</LG>
<LG N="100" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(100) LA DAME.</HEAD>
<L N="789">"Myn hert, nor I, haue done you no<NOTE PLACE="foot">noo H, <I>om.</I> T.</NOTE> forfait,<MILESTONE N="133b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>By which ye schuld complayne in any kynde.</L>
<L>Ther hurtyth you<NOTE PLACE="foot">UH, Then T.</NOTE> no thyng but your<NOTE PLACE="foot">your TH, ys U.</NOTE> conseyt:</L>
<L>Be Iuge your-selfe; for so ye schall hit fynde.</L>
<L N="793">Ons, for alwey, lat &thorn;is synke in your mynde:</L>
<L>Th&aacute;t ye desir, schall neuer Reioysed be.</L>
<L>ye noye me sore, in wastyng all &thorn;is<NOTE PLACE="foot">UH, of your T.</NOTE> wynde;</L>
<L N="796">ffor I haue sayd ynoghe, as semythe me."</L>
</LG>
<LG N="101" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(101)</HEAD>
<L N="797">This wofull man rose vp in all his payn,</L>
<L>And so partyd, with wepyng<NOTE PLACE="foot">UH, heuy T.</NOTE> countynaunce;</L>
<L>his wofull hert, all-most itt brast a<NOTE PLACE="foot">it brest in H, brast in T.</NOTE>-twayn</L>
<L>ffull lyke to dye, forth walkyng<NOTE PLACE="foot">H, walkyng forth UT.</NOTE> in a traunce,</L>
<L>And said, "now, deth, com forth!<NOTE PLACE="foot">UH, deth come forthe and T.</NOTE> thi-selfe avaunce,</L>
<L>Or &thorn;at my hart for-yet his propirte;</L>
<L>And make schortyr<NOTE PLACE="foot">UT, shorte H.</NOTE> all &thorn;is wofull penaunce</L>
<L N="804">Offe my pour lyfe, full of aduersyte!"</L>
</LG>
<LG N="102" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(102)</HEAD>
<L N="805">ffro thens he went, bot whidur wyst I noght,</L>
<L>Nor to what part he drow, in sothfastnese;</L>
<L>But he no mor wasse in his<NOTE PLACE="foot">his UH, <I>om.</I> T.</NOTE> ladyes thought,</L>
<L>ffor to the daunce anon sche gan her dresse.
<PB REF="00000160.tif" N="110"></L>
<L N="809">And afterward,&mdash;on<NOTE PLACE="foot">on UH, and T.</NOTE> told me &thorn;us expresse,&mdash;</L>
<L>He rent his here, for anguysch and for payn,</L>
<L>And In hym-selfe toke so gret hevynesse,</L>
<L N="812">That he wasse dede with-In a day or twayn.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="103" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(103) LENVOY.</HEAD>
<L N="813">ye trew louers, &thorn;is<NOTE PLACE="foot">UH, thus T.</NOTE> I be-seche you all,<MILESTONE N="134" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>Syche &aacute;vauntours, fle<NOTE PLACE="foot">UH, sle T.</NOTE> hem in euery wyse,</L>
<L>And as peple diffamyd, ye hem call,</L>
<L>ffor &thorn;ai, trewly, do you gret preiudyse.</L>
<L N="817">Refuse hath mad, for all sich flateryse,</L>
<L>Hys castels strong, stuffyd with ordynaunce;</L>
<L>ffor &thorn;ai haue hade long tyme, by &thorn;air offyce,</L>
<L N="820">The hole cuntre of loue in obbeisaunce.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="104" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(104)</HEAD>
<L N="821">And ye, ladyes, or<NOTE PLACE="foot">UH, of T.</NOTE> what a-state ye be,</L>
<L>In whome worschip hath chose his dwellyng place,</L>
<L>ffor goddes loue, do no sich cruelte,</L>
<L>Namly to hem &thorn;at haue<NOTE PLACE="foot">haue UT, <I>om.</I> H.</NOTE> deseruyd grace.</L>
<L N="825">Nore<NOTE PLACE="foot">Ner H, Nc T.</NOTE> in no wyse ne folow not<NOTE PLACE="foot">ye not HT.</NOTE> the trace</L>
<L>Of hyr, &thorn;at her is namyd<NOTE PLACE="foot">UH, is namyd her T.</NOTE> ryght-wysly,</L>
<L>Which by Reson, me semyth in &thorn;is case,</L>
<L N="828">May be called "la belle dame san&yogh; mercy."<NOTE PLACE="foot">UH, <I>om.</I> T.</NOTE></L>
<TRAILER>Explicit.</TRAILER>
</LG>
<LG N="105" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(105. Sir R. Ros's Envoy, in 4 Stanzas of sevens, <I>ababbcc.</I>)</HEAD>
<L N="829">Go, lytell boke! god send th&egrave; good pass&aacute;ge!</L>
<L>Chese well thy way; be<NOTE PLACE="foot">be TH, by U.</NOTE> symple of maner!</L>
<L>Loke thy clothyng be<NOTE PLACE="foot">be TH, by U.</NOTE> lyke thy pylgrymage,</L>
<L>And specyally, lete &thorn;is be<NOTE PLACE="foot">be H, be in T, by U.</NOTE> thi prayer</L>
<L N="833">Vn-to hem all<NOTE PLACE="foot">all UT, <I>om.</I> H.</NOTE> &thorn;at th&egrave; wull rede or her,</L>
<L>'Wher &thorn;ou art wronge, after &thorn;air helpe to call,</L>
<L N="835">Th&egrave; to corecte in any parte or all.'
<PB REF="00000161.tif" N="111"></L>
</LG>
<LG N="106" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(106)</HEAD>
<L N="836">Pray hem also, with thyn humble seruyse,<MILESTONE N="134b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>Thi bold&euml;nes<NOTE PLACE="foot">boldenesse H, boldnes U.</NOTE> to pardon in &thorn;is case;</L>
<L>ffor els &thorn;ou art not able, in no wyse,</L>
<L>To make thi selfe a-pere<NOTE PLACE="foot">appere TH.</NOTE> in any place.</L>
<L N="840">And for&thorn;ermor, by-seche hem, of &thorn;air grace,</L>
<L>By &thorn;air fauour and supportac&iuml;oun,</L>
<L N="842">To take in gre &thorn;is Rude translacioun.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="107" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(107)</HEAD>
<L N="843">The which, got wot, standith full destytute</L>
<L>Of eloquence, of metre, and of<NOTE PLACE="foot">of H, <I>om.</I> UT.</NOTE> colours,</L>
<L>Lyke as oo<NOTE PLACE="foot">a H. Wilde as a Harl. 372, Ff. I. 6, Camb. Univ.&mdash;Skeat.</NOTE> best, naked, with-out refute,</L>
<L>Vpon a playn tabyde<NOTE PLACE="foot">to abyde T, to bide H.</NOTE> all maner schours.</L>
<L N="847">I can no mor, but aske of hem socours,</L>
<L>At whos request you wer mad<NOTE PLACE="foot">made was H.</NOTE> in &thorn;is wyse,</L>
<L N="849">Comaundyng me with body and seruyse.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="108" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(108)</HEAD>
<L N="850">Ryght &thorn;us I make an end of &thorn;is processe,</L>
<L>By-sechyng hym &thorn;at all hath in bal&aacute;unce,</L>
<L>That no trew man be vexid, caus&euml;lesse,</L>
<L>As &thorn;is man wasse, which is of R&eacute;membraunce;</L>
<L N="854">And all &thorn;at do &thorn;air faithfull &oacute;bseruaunce,</L>
<L>And in &thorn;air trouth purp&oacute;se hem to endure,</L>
<L N="856">I pray god send<NOTE PLACE="foot">sende H, sun U.</NOTE> hem bettyr &aacute;venture.<NOTE PLACE="foot">T, <I>om.</I> U, Qui legit, emendat scriptorem, non reprehendat H.</NOTE></L>
<TRAILER>Explicit la bell dame saunce mercy.
</TRAILER>

</LG>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 TYPE="poem"><PB REF="00000162.tif" N="112">
<HEAD>A Hymn to the Virgin Mary to preserve King Henry.</HEAD>
<HEADNOTE><P>[<I>Lambeth MS.</I> 306, <I>leaf</I> 177, <I>back</I>.]</P></HEADNOTE>
<LG N="1" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(1)</HEAD>
<L N="1">O blessed mary,<NOTE PLACE="foot">'mayde,' alterd to 'mary.'</NOTE> the flowre of virgynite!</L>
<L>O quene of hevyn Imperyall!</L>
<L>O empres of hell, and lady of chastyte!</L>
<L>To th&egrave; obey all aungels celestyall!</L>
<L N="5">For the hevynly kyng enteryd thy close virgynall,</L>
<L>Man to redeme from dedely synne,</L>
<L N="7">That, by his deth, hevyn he myght wynne.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="2" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(2)</HEAD>
<L N="8">Hayle, bryght starre of Ierusalem!</L>
<L>Heyle, ruddy roose of Ierico!</L>
<L>Heyle, cler&euml;nes of bethlehem!</L>
<L>To th&egrave; all synners do go,</L>
<L N="12">Mercy callyng, and besechyng to &amp; fro,</L>
<L>Them to dyrect in this stormy se,</L>
<L N="14">As thou art parfyte rodde of Iesse.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="3" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(3)</HEAD>
<L N="15">O cler&egrave; porte of paradyse!</L>
<L>O spowse of Salamon so eloquent!</L>
<L>O quene of most precyous pryce!</L>
<L>Thou art a pyller of feyth excellent!</L>
<L N="19">My townge is not suffyc&iuml;ent</L>
<L>Thy cler&euml;nes to comprehende,</L>
<L N="21">Yf euery membre a tunge myght extende.
<PB REF="00000163.tif" N="113"></L>
</LG>
<LG N="4" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(4)</HEAD>
<L N="22">Heyle flece of gedion, with vertu decorate!</L>
<L>Heyle plesaunt lyly, most goodly in bewty!</L>
<L>Heyle towre of Dauid &amp; vyrgyn immaculat!</L>
<L>Redres mans sowle from all mysery,</L>
<L N="26">That he may enter the eternal glorye.</L>
<L>As thou art cyte of god, &amp; sempiternal throne,</L>
<L N="28">Here now, blessyd lady, my wofull mone.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="5" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(5)</HEAD>
<L N="29">O plesaunt olyue with grace circundate!</L>
<L>O lemyng lawmpe, in light passyng nature!</L>
<L>How greately is thy name glorificate!</L>
<L>To the geuyth praysynges euery creature!</L>
<L N="33">As thou art goddys modyr &amp; virgyn pure,</L>
<L>Graunt to man the blysse eternall</L>
<L N="35">When he passith thys lyfe terrestryall!</L>
</LG>
<LG N="6" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(6)</HEAD>
<L N="36">Heyle virgyn mary surmountyng clere tytan;<MILESTONE N="177b:2" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>Syttyng in hevyn most triumphantly!</L>
<L>Heyle blasyng starre withowte peere!</L>
<L>I beseche the as thou art moder of mercy,</L>
<L N="40">To preserue nobyl kyng herry</L>
<L>And all hys holy realme,</L>
<L N="42">As thou bare Iubyter In bethleem.<NOTE PLACE="end">[The Wright's Chaste Wife follows, though headed by "A medycine for the tothe ache."]</NOTE></L>
<TRAILER>EXPLICIT.
</TRAILER>

</LG>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 TYPE="poem"><PB REF="00000164.tif" N="114">
<HEAD>Crentale Sancti Gregorii.</HEAD>
<HEADNOTE><P>[<I>Brit. Mus. MS. Cott. Calig., A ii., leaf</I> 86, <I>back, col.</I> 2, <I>and MS. Lambeth</I> 306, <I>leaf</I> 110.] [The B. Mus. text is rather earlier than the Lambeth, and is therefore printed here, the chief variations of the Lambeth MS. being put in the notes. See an earlier version in <I>Minor Poems of the Vernon MS.</I>, E. E. T. Soc.]</P></HEADNOTE>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L><NOTE PLACE="foot"><Q><L>A Writt men ffynt, A fayre storye,</L><L>The Pope hit wrote, Seint gregorye</L></Q></NOTE>A nobull story wryte y fynde,</L>
<L>A pope hit wrote to haue yn mynde</L>
<L>Of his modur, (&amp; of her lyf)</L>
<L N="4">That holden was an holy wyfe,<NOTE PLACE="foot">That al men helden an holy housewyffe</NOTE></L>
<L>Of myrthes sadde, &amp;<NOTE PLACE="foot">So sade of maneres, so</NOTE> mylde of mode,</L>
<L>&THORN;at alle men held<NOTE PLACE="foot">Alle men helden</NOTE> her holy &amp; gode,</L>
<L>Bothe deuowte &amp;<NOTE PLACE="foot">Bonoure devoute so.</NOTE> mylde of steuen</L>
<L N="8">&THORN;at alle men helde her wordy<NOTE PLACE="foot">gesshed hire worthy to</NOTE> heuen;</L>
<L>So holy as she was holde of name,</L>
<L>Alle men were gladde of her fame,</L>
<L>But as holy as she holden was,<NOTE PLACE="foot">Also holy as she was</NOTE></L>
<L N="12">&THORN;e deuell brow&yogh;th her<NOTE PLACE="foot">The Fende it felde</NOTE> yn a foule cas,</L>
<L>He trifeled her so<NOTE PLACE="foot">And travailde hir</NOTE> with his trecherye</L>
<L>And ledde her yn lust<NOTE PLACE="foot">into synne</NOTE> of lecherye:</L>
<L>For with lust of lecherye he her<NOTE PLACE="foot">That luste of loue hir so</NOTE> begylde</L>
<L N="16">Tyll she hadde conceyued A chylde.<NOTE PLACE="foot">So ffer that she was with childe.</NOTE></L>
<L>And al so priuely she hit<NOTE PLACE="foot">So privily ner the lees she her</NOTE> bare</L>
<L>That &thorn;ere-of was no man ware.</L>
<L>And, for no mon shuld wyte of &thorn;at<NOTE PLACE="foot">witte her</NOTE> case,</L>
<L N="20">A-none as &thorn;e chylde born was,
<PB REF="00000165.tif" N="115"></L>
<L>The chylde she slow&yogh; &amp; wyryede,<NOTE PLACE="foot">Be the necke the child she wriede.</NOTE></L>
<L>And pryuely she hit<NOTE PLACE="foot">And a-none the childe she</NOTE> byryede.</L>
<L>&THORN;er<NOTE PLACE="foot">Thus</NOTE> was she combred yn a carefull case,</L>
<L N="24">And vnshryuen &thorn;er-of she was;<NOTE PLACE="foot">She shewed neuer shryfte &thorn;erof, alas!</NOTE></L>
<L>She ne tolde no<NOTE PLACE="foot">She tolde neuer</NOTE> preste her priuyte,</L>
<L>For she wolde holy holden be.<NOTE PLACE="foot">L. transposes this and the line above, and adds, <Q><L>Alle folke were fayne of hire name,</L><L>So holy she was holdene, and of gode fame.</L></Q> Twyes</NOTE></L>
<L>Efte sones she fell in<NOTE PLACE="foot">hir felle the</NOTE> &thorn;e same case</L>
<L N="28">Ry&yogh;th as beforn her be-tydde<NOTE PLACE="foot">as hit be-forne</NOTE> was.</L>
<L>For she was comen of hy&yogh; parage,<NOTE PLACE="foot">price</NOTE></L>
<L>Of gentyll<NOTE PLACE="foot">Riche</NOTE> kynne &amp; wor&thorn;y<NOTE PLACE="foot">gentille</NOTE> lynage;<NOTE PLACE="foot">L. adds, <Q><L>Hir sonne was Gregory the pope;</L><L>Men helden hir holy with alle her hope.</L></Q></NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;erfore she wolde not her synne<NOTE PLACE="foot">durste she no shryft</NOTE> shewe,</L>
<L N="32">Nor yn schryfte hit be<NOTE PLACE="foot">lest be schreft hir case were</NOTE> knowe,<NOTE PLACE="foot">L. adds, <Q><L>So shame maketh men to hide ther shryffte,</L><L>And lese the grace of god alle-myght,</L><L>And sethen to lyve synfully,</L><L>And fallen to dethe sodeynly.</L></Q></NOTE></L>
<L>And so here<NOTE PLACE="foot">This womans</NOTE> dedes were not a-spyed;</L>
<L>But afturwarde sodenly<NOTE PLACE="foot">And sothely afterward</NOTE> she dyed.</L>
<L>When she was seyn so sodenly<NOTE PLACE="foot">softly</NOTE> dye,</L>
<L N="36">Men hoped she was yn heuen hye;<NOTE PLACE="foot">fulle hie</NOTE></L>
<L>They helde her<NOTE PLACE="foot">helden hire</NOTE> so holy &amp; deuowte,</L>
<L>&THORN;at of here deth &thorn;ey made<NOTE PLACE="foot">men had</NOTE> no dowte,</L>
<L>But sykurly men wende y-wys<NOTE PLACE="foot">wenden witterly al to wysse</NOTE></L>
<L N="40">&THORN;at she was wor&thorn;y<NOTE PLACE="foot">sett in</NOTE> heuen blys.</L>
<L>Then aftur with-Inne a shorte<NOTE PLACE="foot">Ther after. . .litelle</NOTE> tyme,<MILESTONE N="87:1" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>Vpon a day soone aftyr pryme,</L>
<L>The pope, as he at his mass&euml;<NOTE PLACE="foot">Her Sonne the pope at the mas</NOTE> stode,</L>
<L N="44">Vpon his modur he hadde &thorn;ow&yogh;t<NOTE PLACE="foot">And of his moder hee trowed but</NOTE> goode,</L>
<L>Prayng to god with conciens clere
<PB REF="00000166.tif" N="116"></L>
<L>The so&thorn;e to know&euml; as hit were;<NOTE PLACE="foot">L. omits lines 45, 46.</NOTE></L>
<L>And sodenly, yn mydd&euml;s his<NOTE PLACE="foot">the myd</NOTE> masse,</L>
<L N="48">&THORN;er &thorn;row&yogh; to hym such a<NOTE PLACE="foot">drewe to him a grete</NOTE> derkenesse</L>
<L>&THORN;at he lakkede ner<NOTE PLACE="foot">That blacked alle</NOTE> &thorn;e day&euml;s ly&yogh;t,</L>
<L>For hit was<NOTE PLACE="foot">And was alse</NOTE> derk&euml; as mydny&yogh;t;</L>
<L>In &thorn;at derkenes was<NOTE PLACE="foot">And in the derknes a</NOTE> myste among.</L>
<L N="52">All a-stonyed he stode, so hit stongke;<NOTE PLACE="foot">L., <Q><L>Stonyed he was of a stynche fulle stronge.</L><L>Ther-of so gresely he was a-gaste</L><L>That in swonyng he was alle-moste.</L></Q></NOTE></L>
<L>Be-syde he loked vn&thorn;ur hys lere;</L>
<L>In &thorn;at derknes a &thorn;yng &thorn;rew hym<NOTE PLACE="foot">Amiddes the derknes that &thorn;at drewe on</NOTE> nere,</L>
<L>A won&thorn;urfull<NOTE PLACE="foot">wonder</NOTE> grysely creature,</L>
<L N="56">Aftur a fend fyred with all her feture,<NOTE PLACE="foot">But as a ffende was hir feture</NOTE></L>
<L>All ragged &amp; rente, bo&thorn;e elenge &amp;<NOTE PLACE="foot">So ragged so rent and also</NOTE> euell,</L>
<L>As orrybull<NOTE PLACE="foot">dredfulle</NOTE> to be-holde as any<NOTE PLACE="foot">helle</NOTE> deuell:</L>
<L>Mowth&euml;, fac&euml;,<NOTE PLACE="foot">and nose</NOTE> eres &amp; yes,</L>
<L N="60">Brennede all<NOTE PLACE="foot">Flammynge</NOTE> full of brennyng lyes.</L>
<L><SUP>16</SUP>He was so agast of &thorn;at grysyly goste,</L>
<L>That yn a swonyng he was almoste;</L>
<L>He halsed hit, &thorn;orow<SUP>16</SUP><NOTE PLACE="foot"><SUP>16_16</SUP> He asked fullyche bi</NOTE> goddes my&yogh;te,</L>
<L N="64">That &thorn;e fende he putte to fly&yogh;te,<NOTE PLACE="foot">That alle deuelis shulde drade by right</NOTE></L>
<L>And be &thorn;e vertu of hys blode</L>
<L>That for mankynde dyed on Rode,</L>
<L>"Sey me sykerly &thorn;e so&thorn;&euml;<NOTE PLACE="foot">Sey thou me the sothe wel</NOTE> soone</L>
<L N="68">What &thorn;ou hast<NOTE PLACE="foot">Whate hate thou</NOTE> yn &thorn;is place to done:</L>
<L>What ys &thorn;y cause &thorn;ou cursed<NOTE PLACE="foot">the cause that &thorn;u weked</NOTE> wreche,</L>
<L>Thus at masse me for to<NOTE PLACE="foot">Thus me at masse do der and</NOTE> drecche?"</L>
<L>&THORN;e gost answered with drury<NOTE PLACE="foot">drery</NOTE> chere</L>
<L N="72">"I am &thorn;y modur &thorn;at &thorn;e beere,</L>
<L>&THORN;at for vnschryuen dedes so<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>om</I>. so</NOTE> derne</L>
<L>In byttyr paynes &thorn;us y brenne."
<PB REF="00000167.tif" N="117"></L>
<L>Then sayde<NOTE PLACE="foot">Tho answerd</NOTE> &thorn;e pope, "alas! Alas!</L>
<L N="76">Modur, &thorn;is ys to me<NOTE PLACE="foot">My moder this is</NOTE> a wondur case.</L>
<L>A! leef<NOTE PLACE="foot">Alas</NOTE> modur! how may &thorn;is be</L>
<L>In such paynes<NOTE PLACE="foot">A-Raye</NOTE> &thorn;e for to se?</L>
<L>For alle men wende y-wys<NOTE PLACE="foot">Men wendyne witterlyche I-wis</NOTE><MILESTONE N="87:2" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="80">That &thorn;ou hadde bene wordy<NOTE PLACE="foot">were worthi to haue</NOTE> heuen blys,</L>
<L>And full good<NOTE PLACE="foot">fulle welle with god</NOTE> &thorn;at &thorn;ou were</L>
<L>To praye for vs &thorn;at ben<NOTE PLACE="foot">leven</NOTE> here.</L>
<L>Sey me, modyr, with-outen fayne</L>
<L N="84">Why art &thorn;ou put to all &thorn;is payne."</L>
<L>She sayde, "sone, sykerly<NOTE PLACE="foot">my sonne sothefastlye</NOTE></L>
<L>I shalle &thorn;e telle &thorn;e caus&euml; why:</L>
<L>For y was not such as y semed,</L>
<L N="88">But mych&euml;<NOTE PLACE="foot">Butt wecked and</NOTE> wors&euml; &thorn;en men wened;</L>
<L>I lyuede in lustes<NOTE PLACE="foot">I synned</NOTE> wykkydly in my lyfe,</L>
<L>Of &thorn;e whyche y wolde me not<NOTE PLACE="foot">durste me neuer</NOTE> shryfe;"</L>
<L>And<NOTE PLACE="foot">She</NOTE> tolde hym trewly all &thorn;e<NOTE PLACE="foot">her</NOTE> case</L>
<L N="92">Fro &thorn;e bygynnyng how &thorn;at<NOTE PLACE="foot">From one tille other as</NOTE> hit wase.</L>
<L><SUP>16</SUP>The pope lette teres a-down Renne,</L>
<L>And to his modyr he sayde &thorn;en,<SUP>16</SUP><NOTE PLACE="foot"><SUP>16_16</SUP> L. omits these lines.</NOTE></L>
<L>"Telle me now, modur, for<NOTE PLACE="foot">Sey me, moder, for</NOTE> loue of mary flour,</L>
<L N="96">If any &thorn;yng may &thorn;e help or<NOTE PLACE="foot">Yf oughte the may save and</NOTE> sokour?</L>
<L><SUP>19</SUP>Bedes, or masse, &thorn;y penaunce to bye,</L>
<L>Or ony fastyng &thorn;y sorowe to aleye;</L>
<L>What crafte,<NOTE PLACE="foot">?MS.; may be 'curste'</NOTE> or caste, or any o&thorn;ur &thorn;yng</L>
<L N="100">The may help, or be &thorn;y Releuyng."<SUP>19</SUP><NOTE PLACE="foot"><SUP>19_19</SUP> <Q><L>Whe&thorn;er fastynge or pennaunce may &thorn;ee alegge,</L><L>Bedis or masses thi peynes to brygge,</L><L>With cost, and crafte, and other thinge</L><L>To the be helpe of Any savynge.</L></Q></NOTE></L>
<L>"My<NOTE PLACE="foot">My dere</NOTE> blessed sone," sayde she,</L>
<L>"Full well y hope &thorn;at hit may<NOTE PLACE="foot">welle y-holpen y myght</NOTE> be;</L>
<L>Syker &amp; saf my&yogh;th y<NOTE PLACE="foot">Holpen and savide y myghte</NOTE> be well,
<PB REF="00000168.tif" N="118"></L>
<L N="104">Who-so trewly wolde take a<NOTE PLACE="foot">vnder-toke a trewe</NOTE> trentell</L>
<L>Of ten chef fest&euml;s of<NOTE PLACE="foot">of alle</NOTE> &thorn;e &yogh;ere,</L>
<L>To syng for me yn<NOTE PLACE="foot">on</NOTE> &thorn;is manere,</L>
<L>Thre masses of crystys natyuyte,</L>
<L N="108">And of &thorn;e xij day<NOTE PLACE="foot">Epuphanie. L. compresses the next eight lines into four long ones.</NOTE> o&thorn;ur &thorn;re,</L>
<L>Thre of our ladyes puryfycacioun,</L>
<L>And o&thorn;ur &thorn;re of her Annunciacioun,</L>
<L>Thre of crystes gloryous Resurreccioun,</L>
<L N="112">And o&thorn;er &thorn;re of his hy&yogh; Ascencioun,</L>
<L>And of pentecoste o&thorn;ur &thorn;re,</L>
<L>And &thorn;re of &thorn;e blessed trinite,</L>
<L>And of our ladyes Assumpcioun, o&thorn;ur &thorn;re,</L>
<L N="116">And of here Ioyfull natiuite &thorn;re;</L>
<L>These ben &thorn;e chef&euml;<NOTE PLACE="foot">tho ilke</NOTE> fest&euml;s ten</L>
<L>That sokour &thorn;e sowles &thorn;at ben fro heuenn.<NOTE PLACE="foot">That souerenly socouren synfulle men</NOTE></L>
<L>"Who so<NOTE PLACE="foot">Whate preeste</NOTE> sayth &thorn;ese masses with-out fayle,</L>
<L N="120">For synnfulle sowles &thorn;ey shalle<NOTE PLACE="foot">To . . . they shulden myche</NOTE> a-vayle;</L>
<L>Alle A<NOTE PLACE="foot">In one</NOTE> &yogh;ere, with-outen trayne,<MILESTONE N="87b:1" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>They delyuere a sowle<NOTE PLACE="foot">Delyuer sowles</NOTE> out of payne.</L>
<L>Lette say &thorn;ese masses be &yogh;our hestes</L>
<L N="124">With-Inne &thorn;e<NOTE PLACE="foot">euery</NOTE> vtas of &thorn;e<NOTE PLACE="foot">euery</NOTE> festes;</L>
<L>And he &thorn;at shall &thorn;ese masses do,</L>
<L>Sey<NOTE PLACE="foot">Shalle sey . . too. For the next four lines the Lambeth MS. (fol.112) reads: <Q><L>Trewly with-owtene ony were</L><L>Euery day thorowe-oute the yere;</L><L>Do hem it to saye euery daye,</L><L>Or he that dothe thes masses to saye,</L><L>Whoso wille knowe this orisoun clene,</L><L>Hit is in Englisshe this myche to mene:</L><L>Oracio, 'Deus qui es nostra Redempcio'</L><L>"God, that arte oure verray Redempcioun,</L><L>To owre Sowlis sothefast saluacioun:</L><L>That chesest, alle o&thorn;er londis be-forne,</L><L>The lond of hest, in to be borne,</L><L>And thi dethe suffrest in that same,</L><L>Delyuere the Soules from helle blame!</L><L>Brynge hem oute of the fendis bonde,</L><L>And that londe out of hethen men honde!</L><L>And that pepille that levith not on the,</L><L>Throwe thi vertue a-mendide may be,</L><L>And alle that trustyn on thi merce,</L><L>Lord, save hem alle for thi pite!"</L></Q></NOTE> he &thorn;er-with &thorn;is oryson also,
<PB REF="00000169.tif" N="119"></L>
<L>'Deus qui es nostra Redempcio'</L>
<L N="128">With alle &thorn;e o&thorn;ur &thorn;at longen &thorn;er-to."</L>
<L>The pope was gladde here-of in fay,</L>
<L>And to his modur &thorn;en gon he say,</L>
<L>"Modyr," he sayde, "&thorn;is shall be<NOTE PLACE="foot">wille y</NOTE> do,</L>
<L N="132">For y am most bounde<NOTE PLACE="foot">I am a man moste holdynge</NOTE> &thorn;erto;</L>
<L>Thou were<NOTE PLACE="foot">artte</NOTE> my modur, I was<NOTE PLACE="foot">am</NOTE> &thorn;y sone;</L>
<L>Thys same &yogh;ere hit shall be done;<NOTE PLACE="foot">To synge these masses y shalle not shonne</NOTE></L>
<L>God graunte me grace to<NOTE PLACE="foot">me moder the</NOTE> stonde in stede</L>
<L N="136">A&yogh;eyns alle &thorn;e synnus &thorn;at euur &thorn;ou dede;</L>
<L>I commaunde hooly, my<NOTE PLACE="foot">pray the holiche</NOTE> moder dere,</L>
<L>&thorn;at &thorn;is tyme twelfmone&thorn; &thorn;ou to me apere,</L>
<L>And hooly to me &thorn;y state &thorn;ou telle,<NOTE PLACE="foot">Holiche thi state to me thowe shewe</NOTE></L>
<L N="140">That how &thorn;ou fare y may wyte welle."<NOTE PLACE="foot">faryst I mowe it knowe</NOTE></L>
<L>"My sone," she sayde, "y woll yn fay;"</L>
<L>And with &thorn;at worde she wente her way.<NOTE PLACE="foot">she vansshede awaye</NOTE></L>
<L>Day by day<NOTE PLACE="foot">So day from day</NOTE> &thorn;e &yogh;ere gon passe,</L>
<L N="144">The pope for-&yogh;ate neuur<NOTE PLACE="foot">lete neuer to say</NOTE> his masse</L>
<L>The sam&euml; dayes &thorn;at were a-syned,</L>
<L>To helpe his modur &thorn;at was<NOTE PLACE="foot">was soo</NOTE> pyned;</L>
<L>And toke &thorn;e orysons all-way &thorn;er-to</L>
<L N="148">Ry&yogh;th as she bad hym for<NOTE PLACE="foot">As his moder praide him</NOTE> to do.</L>
<L>xij mone&thorn; aftur, as he at masse<NOTE PLACE="foot">That time a twelmothe at the masse he</NOTE> stode,</L>
<L>With gret deuocioun &amp; holynesse gode,<NOTE PLACE="foot">Holy in prayers, with devociouns gode</NOTE></L>
<L>At &thorn;at sam&euml; tyme full Ryght<NOTE PLACE="foot">And in the same tide a-plight</NOTE></L>
<L N="152">He sawe a full swet&euml;<NOTE PLACE="foot">wondere sely</NOTE> syght:</L>
<L>A comely lady dressed<NOTE PLACE="foot">so dressyd</NOTE> &amp; dyght,</L>
<L>That all &thorn;e worlde was not so<NOTE PLACE="foot">alle the place of hir shone</NOTE> bry&yogh;t,</L>
<L>Comely<NOTE PLACE="foot">Comly and</NOTE> crowned as a qwene,
<PB REF="00000170.tif" N="120"></L>
<L N="156">Twenty Angellys her ladde<NOTE PLACE="foot">Two Angilles helden hir hem</NOTE> betwene.</L>
<L>He was so Raueshed<NOTE PLACE="foot">was y-Ravesshede</NOTE> of &thorn;at syght</L>
<L>That ny&yogh;<NOTE PLACE="foot">Allemoste</NOTE> for Ioye he swoned<NOTE PLACE="foot">felle downe</NOTE> Ryght;</L>
<L>He fell down flatte by-fore<NOTE PLACE="foot">to-for</NOTE> her fete,</L>
<L N="160">&THORN;at deuowtly teres wepynge<NOTE PLACE="foot">Devoute teres ther</NOTE> he lete,</L>
<L>And<NOTE PLACE="foot">He</NOTE> grette here with a mylde steuen,</L>
<L>And sayde &thorn;ere,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>om</I>. &thorn;ere</NOTE> "lady, qwene of heuen,</L>
<L>Modyr of Ihesu, mayde<NOTE PLACE="foot">mylde</NOTE> marye,<MILESTONE N="87b:2" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="164">For my modyr, mercy I crye."</L>
<L><SUP>10</SUP>At &thorn;at worde, with myld&euml; chere</L>
<L>She hym answered on &thorn;is manere,</L>
<L>"Blessed sone,<SUP>10</SUP><NOTE PLACE="foot"><SUP>10_10</SUP> Do way, she saide</NOTE> I am not she</L>
<L N="168">Who wenest &thorn;ou<NOTE PLACE="foot">Ne whom &thorn;u wenest</NOTE> &thorn;at I be;</L>
<L>But certes,<NOTE PLACE="foot">sothe</NOTE> as &thorn;ou seest me here,</L>
<L>I am &thorn;y modyr &thorn;at &thorn;e bere,</L>
<L>That here by-fore,<NOTE PLACE="foot">Be-forne y ferde</NOTE> &thorn;ou wyst&euml; well,</L>
<L N="172">I was wordy payne yn hell,<NOTE PLACE="foot">Right foule as a deville of helle</NOTE></L>
<L>And now y am such<NOTE PLACE="foot">I Am nowe swiche</NOTE> as &thorn;ou seest here,</L>
<L>&THORN;orow help of &thorn;e<NOTE PLACE="foot">and</NOTE> vertu of &thorn;y prayere;</L>
<L>Fro derknesse I dresse to<NOTE PLACE="foot">derknesse in to</NOTE> blyss&euml; clere;</L>
<L N="176">&THORN;e tyme be blessed &thorn;at y &thorn;e bere!</L>
<L>And, for &thorn;e kyndenesse of<NOTE PLACE="foot">and, sonne, for</NOTE> &thorn;y good dede,</L>
<L>Heuen blysse<NOTE PLACE="foot">Sovereyn Ioye</NOTE> shall be &thorn;y mede.</L>
<L>And alle &thorn;o &thorn;at leten &thorn;ese masses be<NOTE PLACE="foot">this massys this</NOTE> do,</L>
<L N="180">Shall saue hem self &amp; o&thorn;ur<NOTE PLACE="foot">haue hem selfe and the soules. L. omits the next two lines.</NOTE> mo;</L>
<L>&THORN;us may &thorn;ey helpe her frendes alle</L>
<L>That Reche-lesly yn synn&euml; falle:</L>
<L>Therfore, sone, &thorn;is story &thorn;ou preche;</L>
<L N="184">And almy&yogh;ty<NOTE PLACE="foot">My dere sonne</NOTE> god y &thorn;e be-teche."</L>
<L><SUP>23</SUP>At &thorn;e endyng of her wordes euen
<PB REF="00000171.tif" N="121"></L>
<L>An Angell her ber yn to heuen:</L>
<L>In-to &thorn;at plac&euml; god vs sende,</L>
<L N="188">To dwelle with her with-outen ende!</L>
<L>&para; Thys ys &thorn;e vertu, y &thorn;e telle,<SUP>23</SUP><NOTE PLACE="foot"><SUP>23_23</SUP> <Q><L>When she hadde this saide A-none,</L><L>The Angelle to hevyn with her con gone;</L><L>To that place god vs sende</L><L>That wonneth in blysse with-owten ende!</L><L>Now haue we herd fayre and wele</L><L>The vertus (of Seint Gregories trentalle)</L></Q></NOTE></L>
<L>Of seynt gregory trentelle;</L>
<L>But who so wyll do hit trewely,<NOTE PLACE="foot">parfitely</NOTE></L>
<L N="192">He most&euml; do more sykurly:<NOTE PLACE="foot">therto trewly</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;e preste &thorn;at &thorn;e masse shall<NOTE PLACE="foot">shalle this trentalle</NOTE> synge,</L>
<L>At eche feste &thorn;at he do&thorn; hit mynge,<NOTE PLACE="foot">dothe mynde</NOTE></L>
<L>He moste say with good deuocioun,</L>
<L N="196">Ouer<NOTE PLACE="foot">Euery</NOTE> Euen &thorn;e commendacyoun,</L>
<L>Placebo &amp; dyryge<NOTE PLACE="foot">&amp; the direges he most sey</NOTE> also,</L>
<L>The sowle to brynge out of woo;</L>
<L>And also &thorn;e salmis<NOTE PLACE="foot">spalmes</NOTE> seuenne</L>
<L N="200">For<NOTE PLACE="foot">That helpeth</NOTE> to brynge &thorn;e sowle to<NOTE PLACE="foot">tille</NOTE> heuen;</L>
<L>Among o&thorn;ur prayeres &thorn;ey ben<NOTE PLACE="foot">For A-monge alle other they bethe</NOTE> good</L>
<L>To brynge sowles<NOTE PLACE="foot">the soule</NOTE> fro helle f[l]ode,<NOTE PLACE="foot">flode L. (<I>fode</I>, Cott., is offspring, person).</NOTE></L>
<L>For euery psalme qwencheth<NOTE PLACE="foot">dothe quynche</NOTE> a synne</L>
<L N="204">As ofte as a man &thorn;oth hem mynne.<NOTE PLACE="foot">Any man dothe them be-gynne. L. adds: <Q><L>And with gode Devocion seith &thorn;em to the ende,</L><L>Then may the soules to hevyn wende;</L><L>Therfore this Salme haue ye in thought;</L><L>The xv Salmes for-yete ye nought;</L><L>The letany also ye haue in mynde,</L><L>Loke thou leve hit not be-hynde.</L></Q></NOTE></L>
<L>Loke<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>om.</I> Look</NOTE> with good deuocyon &thorn;ou hem<NOTE PLACE="foot">hit</NOTE> say,<MILESTONE N="88:1" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>And to alle halewes &thorn;at &thorn;ou<NOTE PLACE="foot">hallowun ther-with to</NOTE> pray,</L>
<L>To<NOTE PLACE="foot">Pray hem to</NOTE> helpe &thorn;e with all her my&yogh;te</L>
<L N="208">The sowle<NOTE PLACE="foot">soules</NOTE> to brynge to heuen bryght</L>
<L>There euur ys day, and neuur nyght;</L>
<L>Cryst graunt vs parte of &thorn;at lyght!<NOTE PLACE="foot">vs grace to se that sight</NOTE></L>
<L>Loke &thorn;ese<NOTE PLACE="foot">&thorn;is</NOTE> ben sayde alle in fere
<PB REF="00000172.tif" N="122"></L>
<L N="212">Euery day yn<NOTE PLACE="foot">thorowe</NOTE> &thorn;e &yogh;ere;</L>
<L>Neuer a day &thorn;at &thorn;ou<NOTE PLACE="foot">And euery day loke thou not</NOTE> for-gete,</L>
<L>These to say &thorn;ou ne<NOTE PLACE="foot">This is to say loke thou not</NOTE> lette;</L>
<L>Also in &thorn;e Vtas<NOTE PLACE="foot">In the evtas</NOTE> of euery feste</L>
<L N="216">Al so longe as hit doth<NOTE PLACE="foot">they do</NOTE> leste&mdash;</L>
<L>Viij<SUP>te</SUP> dayis men callen &thorn;e Vtas&mdash;</L>
<L>&THORN;e preste moste say in his masse,</L>
<L>(A nobull orysoun hit ys holde,)</L>
<L N="220">&THORN;e colette &thorn;at fyrst y of tolde;</L>
<L>And aftur &thorn;e fyrste orysoun,</L>
<L>&THORN;er ys an-o&thorn;ur of gret Renoun</L>
<L>&THORN;at to &thorn;e sowle ys won&thorn;ur swete,</L>
<L N="224">Menne calle hit &thorn;e 'secrete.'<NOTE PLACE="foot">L. has the side note, <I>Secret</I>[<I>um.</I>] <I>Omnipotcns sempiterne deus.</I></NOTE></L>
<L>When &thorn;e preste hath don<NOTE PLACE="foot">sacred</NOTE> his masse,</L>
<L>Vsed,<NOTE PLACE="foot">And vsid</NOTE> &amp; his hondes wasche,</L>
<L>A-no&thorn;ur oryson he moste say</L>
<L N="228">&THORN;at yn &thorn;e boke fynde he may,</L>
<L>&THORN;e 'post comen'<NOTE PLACE="foot">L. side note, <I>post</I> communionem. <I>Deus cuius</I> nomine (?).</NOTE> men don hit calle,</L>
<L>That helpeth sowles out of &thorn;ralle;</L>
<L>And &thorn;at &thorn;is be don at eche a feste</L>
<L N="232">As &thorn;e trentall speketh<NOTE PLACE="foot">That . . . speketh of</NOTE> moste &amp; leste;</L>
<L>Then may &thorn;ou be sykur &amp; certayne<NOTE PLACE="foot">fulle serteyne</NOTE></L>
<L>To brynge &thorn;e sowle out of<NOTE PLACE="foot">sowles oute of her</NOTE> payne</L>
<L>To endeles Ioye, &thorn;at lasteth aye,</L>
<L N="236">&THORN;at god dyed fore on good fryday.<NOTE PLACE="foot">He vs graunte that for vs Dyed on gode Frydaye.</NOTE></L>
<L>To &thorn;at Ioye he<NOTE PLACE="foot">god</NOTE> vs brynge</L>
<L>&THORN;at ys in heuen with-oute endynge!</L>
<L>Pray we alle hit may so<NOTE PLACE="foot">that hit so</NOTE> be,</L>
<L N="240">And say Amen for<NOTE PLACE="foot">Amen, Amen per</NOTE> charyte!<NOTE PLACE="end">[HERE AFTER FOLOWETH MEDCYNES OF LECHECRAFTE, FOL. 114 L. 'Vrbanitatis' follows in Calig. A ii.: printed in <I>Babees Book</I>, E. E. T. Soc., Orig. Ser. No. 32.]</NOTE></L>
<TRAILER>EXPLICIT. [SENT GREGORYS TRENTALLE, L.]
</TRAILER>

</LG>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 TYPE="poem"><PB REF="00000173.tif" N="123">
<HEAD>The Adulterous Falmouth Squire.</HEAD>
<HEADNOTE><P>(A STORY OF TOO SKWYRYS THAT WERE BRETHERN, THE WYCHE DWELLYD HERE YN YNGLOND, YN THE TOUNE OF FAL|MOWTHT, YN DORSETSCHERE; THE TONE WAS DAMPNYD FOR BREKYNG OF HYS WEDLOK, THE TOTHER WAS SAUYD.&mdash;Lambeth MS. 306, leaf 110: in a 16th century hand.)</P></HEADNOTE>
<DIV3 TYPE="part">
<HEAD>PROLOGUE.</HEAD>
<HEADNOTE><P><I>From MS. Ashmole</I> 61, <I>fol</I>. 136.</P></HEADNOTE>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>SIR WILLIAM BASTERDFELD'S WARNING.</HEAD>
<L>All crysten men &thorn;at walke by me,</L>
<L>Be-hold and se &thorn;is dulfull sy&yogh;ht!</L>
<L>It helpys not to calle ne cry,</L>
<L N="4">For I ame dampned, a dollfole wy&yogh;ht.</L>
<L>Some tyme in Ingland duellynge&mdash;</L>
<L>Thys was trew with-outen lesynge&mdash;</L>
<L>I was callyd sir Wylliam Basterdfeld, kny&yogh;t;</L>
<L N="8">Be-were be me, both kynge and kny&yogh;ht,</L>
<L>And amend &yogh;ou whyle &yogh;e haue space,</L>
<L>Fore I haue lost euer-lastynge ly&yogh;ht,</L>
<L>And &thorn;us of mercy cane I gete no grace.</L>
<L N="12">When I was now as &yogh;e be,</L>
<L>I kepyd neuer o&thorn;er lyffe,</L>
<L>I spendyd my lyffe in vanyte,</L>
<L>I[n] veynglory, bate, and stryffe;</L>
<L N="16">Grete othes with me wer fulle ryffe;</L>
<L>I had no grace me to amend,</L>
<L>I sparyd no&thorn;er meyd ne wyffe,</L>
<L>And &thorn;at hath brou&yogh;t me to &thorn;is ende.</L>
<L N="20">I hade no hape whyll I was here
<PB REF="00000174.tif" N="124"></L>
<L>Forto a-ryse and me repent,</L>
<L>Tyll &thorn;at I was brou&yogh;t on bere;</L>
<L>Than was to late, ffore I was schente.</L>
<L N="24">All-wey with &thorn;em I ame aweyde,</L>
<L>In fyre of hell I schall euer be brente;</L>
<L>Alas! &thorn;is world hath me deseyuede,</L>
<L>Fore I had no grace me to amende.</L>
<L N="28">In lechery I lede my lyfe,</L>
<L>Fore I hade gode and gold at wylle;</L>
<L>I scleu&yogh;e my selue with-outene knyffe,</L>
<L>And of glotony I hade my fylle;</L>
<L N="32">In sleuth I ley, and slepyd stylle.</L>
<L>I was deseyued in a reyste,</L>
<L>A dolefulle deth &thorn;at dyde me kylle;</L>
<L>Than was to late off had-I-wyste.</L>
<L N="36">Thus ame I lappyd all a-boute;</L>
<L>With todys and snaks, as &yogh;e may se,</L>
<L>I ame gnawyne my body a-boute.</L>
<L>Alas, alas! full wo is me,</L>
<L N="40">It is to late, it will not be!</L>
<L>I knaw welle women, mor and mynne,</L>
<L>Fore hym &thorn;at dy&yogh;ed fore &yogh;ou and me,</L>
<L>Aryse, and rest not in &yogh;our synne!</L>
<L N="44">Fore when I was in my flowres,</L>
<L>Than was I ly&yogh;ht as byrd on brere;</L>
<L>There-fore I suffere scharpe schoures,</L>
<L>And by &thorn;at bergayne wonder dere,</L>
<L N="48">And byde in peynes many and sere;</L>
<L>There-fore &thorn;us I make my mone.</L>
<L>Now may helpe me no prayere,</L>
<L>I have no gode bot god alone.</L>
<L N="52">Wo be &thorn;ei, who so euer &thorn;ei be,</L>
<L>And haue &thorn;er v wyttes at wylle,</L>
<L>And wyll not be-wer be me,</L>
<L>And knaw gode thinge fro &thorn;<SUP>e</SUP> ylle.</L>
<L N="56">The pore, fore faute late &thorn;em not spylle!<MILESTONE N="136b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>And &yogh;e do, &yogh;our deth is dy&yogh;ht;
<PB REF="00000175.tif" N="125"></L>
<L>&YOGH;oure fals flessch &yogh;e not fullfylle,</L>
<L>Lost with lucyfere fro the ly&yogh;ht.</L>
<L N="60">In delycate metes I sette my delyte,</L>
<L>And my&yogh;hty wynes vn-to my pay;</L>
<L>That make &thorn;is wormys on me to byte,</L>
<L>Ther-fore my song is well-y-wey!</L>
<L N="64">I my&yogh;ht not fast, I wold not praye,</L>
<L>I thou&yogh;t to amend me in myn age,</L>
<L>I droffe euer forth fro dey to dey,</L>
<L>There-fore I byde here in &thorn;is cage.</L>
<L N="68">Thys cage is euer lastynge fyre;</L>
<L>I ame ordeynd &thorn;er-in to duelle;</L>
<L>It is me gyuen, fore myne hyre,</L>
<L>Euer to bryne in &thorn;e pytte of helle.</L>
<L N="72">I ame feteryd with &thorn;e fendes selle,</L>
<L>There I a-byde as best in stalle;</L>
<L>There is no tonge my care cane telle,</L>
<L>Be-were &yogh;e haue not sych a falle!</L>
<L N="76">Alas &thorn;at euer I borne was,</L>
<L>Or modere me bore! why dyde sche so?</L>
<L>For I ame lost fore my trespas,</L>
<L>And a-byde in euer-lastynge wo;</L>
<L N="80">I haue no frend, bot many a fo.</L>
<L>Be-hold me how &thorn;at I ame tourne,</L>
<L>Fore I ame rente fro tope to to;</L>
<L>Alas &thorn;at euer I was borne!</L>
<L N="84">Gode bro&thorn;er, haue me in mynd,</L>
<L>And thinke how &thorn;ou schall dy&yogh;e all wey,</L>
<L>And to &thorn;i soule be not vn-kynde,</L>
<L>Remenbyre it bo&thorn;e ny&yogh;t and dey!</L>
<L N="88">Besyly lok&euml; &thorn;at &thorn;ou praye,</L>
<L>And be-seke &thorn;ou heuen kynge</L>
<L>To saue &thorn;e on &thorn;at dredfull dey</L>
<L>That euery man schall gyffe rekenynge;</L>
<L N="92">Fore &thorn;er no lordes schall fore &thorn;e praye,</L>
<L>Ne Justys, no&thorn;er no mane of lawe;</L>
<L>There charter helpys &thorn;e not &thorn;at dey,
<PB REF="00000176.tif" N="126"></L>
<L>There pletyne is not worth an hawe.</L>
<L N="96">God gyue &thorn;e grace &thorn;i selue to know,</L>
<L>And euery mane in hys degre!</L>
<L>Fare wele! I here an horne blow,</L>
<L>I may no lenger byde with &thorn;e.</L>
</LG>
</DIV3>
<DIV3 TYPE="part">
<HEAD>The Story.</HEAD>
<HEADNOTE><P>(<I>From MS. Lambeth</I> 306, <I>fol.</I> 107-110 (<I>sign l.</I> 3-6, <I>which has no Prologue</I>).</P></HEADNOTE>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="100">MAn, Frome<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. Ashmole, fro</NOTE> myschefe thou &thorn;e A-mende,</L>
<L>And to my talkynge thou take gode hede,</L>
<L>Fro synnes vij thou the defende,</L>
<L>The leste of all is for to drede;</L>
<L N="104">For of the leste y will you speke,</L>
<L>And for to fabill I will you nought;<NOTE PLACE="foot">fro hell I wyll you tech</NOTE></L>
<L>Be war&euml;, man, god will him wreke</L>
<L>Off him that is cause, spowsode to breke.<NOTE PLACE="foot">his teching do breke</NOTE></L>
<L N="108">The first Sacrement that euer god made,</L>
<L>That was wedlok, in gode faye;</L>
<L>Kepe<NOTE PLACE="foot">Be-leue</NOTE> thou hit<NOTE PLACE="foot">&thorn;at</NOTE> with-out&euml; dred,</L>
<L>For hit lastith till<NOTE PLACE="foot">&thorn;at schall last to</NOTE> domes daye.</L>
<L N="112">For his bonde we may all breke,<NOTE PLACE="foot">This line omitted.</NOTE></L>
<L>His owne worde, and<NOTE PLACE="foot">if</NOTE> we will halde,</L>
<L>To<NOTE PLACE="foot">Tyll</NOTE> deth&euml; com&euml; that shall wreke,<NOTE PLACE="foot">all shall werke</NOTE></L>
<L>And be cast in claye full colde.<NOTE PLACE="foot">vs all in cley to fold</NOTE></L>
<L N="116">The gretter<NOTE PLACE="foot">gretyst</NOTE> kynge of all the worlde</L>
<L>By som cause his Crowne may for-gone,&mdash;</L>
<L>I take witnesse of olde and yenge,<NOTE PLACE="foot">kyng rycherd</NOTE></L>
<L>Off kynge Sacre and kynge Salamond,<NOTE PLACE="foot">And kynge fabere and Absalome</NOTE></L>
<L N="120">Off Davit<NOTE PLACE="foot">And kynge Dauyd</NOTE> that made the Sauter booke,<NOTE PLACE="foot">Add, "For synne &thorn;at he dyde with bersabe"</NOTE></L>
<L>Criste of<NOTE PLACE="foot">fro</NOTE> hym his crowne con<NOTE PLACE="foot">he</NOTE> take.<NOTE PLACE="foot">Add, "Thus holy wryte tellys me"</NOTE><MILESTONE N="107b" UNIT="folio">
<PB REF="00000177.tif" N="127"></L>
<L>The grettest Clerke that Euer thou seste,</L>
<L>To take hym vnder heuen cope,<NOTE PLACE="foot">This line (not in Lambeth MS.) is from MS. Ashmole.</NOTE></L>
<L N="124">He may neuer take order of preste,</L>
<L>But he haue licence<NOTE PLACE="foot">leue</NOTE> of the pope,</L>
<L>And he be getten in bawdre,<NOTE PLACE="foot">vowtry</NOTE></L>
<L>Or ellis a bastarde he be borne,&mdash;</L>
<L N="128">This cause I tell well for the,<NOTE PLACE="foot">Thus I canne well telle to ye</NOTE>&mdash;</L>
<L>The order of preest-hode<NOTE PLACE="foot">preste</NOTE> he has forlorne.</L>
<L>The<NOTE PLACE="foot">And the</NOTE> begger at the town&euml;s ende,</L>
<L>To hym wedlok is as fre</L>
<L N="132">As to the Ricchest kynge or quene,<NOTE PLACE="foot">&thorn;e ryall kyng of kyne</NOTE></L>
<L>For all is but one<NOTE PLACE="foot">a</NOTE> dignyte.</L>
<L>Man, yf thou wist whate it were</L>
<L>To take a-no&thorn;er then thi wyffe,</L>
<L N="136">Thou wolde<NOTE PLACE="foot">woldyst</NOTE> rather suffre here<NOTE PLACE="foot">it</NOTE></L>
<L>To be quycke<NOTE PLACE="foot">Omitted.</NOTE> slayne with a knyffe;</L>
<L>For yf thou take a-no&thorn;er manes wyffe,</L>
<L>A wronge aire<NOTE PLACE="foot">eyere</NOTE> thou moste nedis gett</L>
<L N="140">And this (<I>sic</I>) thou bringest iij sowles in stryfe,</L>
<L>In hell&euml; fyre to bren<NOTE PLACE="foot">ly</NOTE> and hete.</L>
<L>But write thes thing&euml;s in thine<NOTE PLACE="foot">wreches thinke in &thorn;er</NOTE> herte</L>
<L>That felis the<NOTE PLACE="foot">fele &thorn;em</NOTE> gilty in this case,</L>
<L N="144">With shryfte of mouthe and pennaunce smerte,</L>
<L>They wene ther blis for to vmbrace,<NOTE PLACE="foot">vn brace</NOTE></L>
<L>But and thei dye a sodeyne dethe</L>
<L>With-outen shrefte or penaunce,<NOTE PLACE="foot">repentans</NOTE></L>
<L N="148">To helle they gone<NOTE PLACE="foot">go</NOTE> with-outen lese,<NOTE PLACE="foot">lete</NOTE></L>
<L>For thay can chese none o&thorn;er chaunse.</L>
<L>A gode Ensampill<NOTE PLACE="foot">sampull</NOTE> y will<NOTE PLACE="foot">&thorn;ou inserted.</NOTE> tell;</L>
<L>To my talkynge ye<NOTE PLACE="foot">tale if &yogh;e</NOTE> take gode<NOTE PLACE="foot">Omitted.</NOTE> hede,</L>
<L N="152">In Falmowthe<NOTE PLACE="foot">felamownte</NOTE> this case be-fell.</L>
<L>Thirty wynter be-for<NOTE PLACE="foot">senne</NOTE> the dethe<MILESTONE N="108" UNIT="folio">
<PB REF="00000178.tif" N="128"></L>
<L>Ther dwellyd two bre&thorn;eren in a<NOTE PLACE="foot">&thorn;e</NOTE> towne,</L>
<L>By on Fadir and moder goten and borne,<NOTE PLACE="foot">getyne</NOTE></L>
<L N="156">Squiers thei were of gret Renowne,</L>
<L><NOTE PLACE="foot">This line follows line 154 in MS. Ashmole.</NOTE>As the story tell<NOTE PLACE="foot">tellys</NOTE> me by-forne.</L>
<L>The elder bro&thorn;er had a wyfe,</L>
<L>The fairest woman in any<NOTE PLACE="foot">all &thorn;at</NOTE> londe,</L>
<L N="160">And yett he<NOTE PLACE="foot">Omitted.</NOTE> vsid a cursid lyfe,</L>
<L>And brought his<NOTE PLACE="foot">hyre</NOTE> soule in bitter bonde;</L>
<L>He Rought not whate woman he toke,</L>
<L>So litell he sett by his spoushode,<NOTE PLACE="foot">wyffe</NOTE></L>
<L N="164">To<NOTE PLACE="foot">Omitted.</NOTE> the devill caught him in his<NOTE PLACE="foot">A</NOTE> croke,</L>
<L>And with grete myschefe marked his mede.<NOTE PLACE="foot">And marked his mede with, etc.</NOTE></L>
<L>Thes two bre&thorn;eren vpon a daye</L>
<L>With Enmyse were slayne in fight;</L>
<L N="168">The elder to hell&euml;<NOTE PLACE="foot">helle he</NOTE> toke the waye,</L>
<L>The yonger to paradic&euml; bright;<NOTE PLACE="foot">ry&yogh;ht</NOTE></L>
<L>And this was knowen in sothefastnes;<NOTE PLACE="foot">sothnes</NOTE></L>
<L>Herken,<NOTE PLACE="foot">Herkyns</NOTE> sires, whate y will<NOTE PLACE="foot">schall</NOTE> saye!</L>
<L N="172">Take gode hede bothe more and lasse,</L>
<L>For godis loue ber this<NOTE PLACE="foot">this tale</NOTE> a-waye!</L>
<L>The elder bro&thorn;er hade a Sonne to<NOTE PLACE="foot">a</NOTE> clerke,</L>
<L>Well of fyftene wynter of age;<NOTE PLACE="foot">fully xv &yogh;ere of Age</NOTE></L>
<L N="176">He was wyse &amp;<NOTE PLACE="foot">ry&yogh;ht</NOTE> holy in<NOTE PLACE="foot">in hys</NOTE> worke,</L>
<L>To<NOTE PLACE="foot">Tho</NOTE> hym shulde falle the Eritage.</L>
<L>For his Fader he made grete mone,</L>
<L>As fallis a gode childe euer<NOTE PLACE="foot">sone</NOTE> of kynde;</L>
<L N="180">Eiche<NOTE PLACE="foot">Euery</NOTE> nyght to his Fadir grave wolde he gone,</L>
<L>To<NOTE PLACE="foot">For to</NOTE> haue his soule in Speciall mynde.<NOTE PLACE="foot">in minde</NOTE></L>
<L>Thus he prayed bothe day and nyght</L>
<L>To god and to his modir dere,</L>
<L N="184">Off his Fadyr to haue a Sight,</L>
<L>To wytt<NOTE PLACE="foot">Omitted.</NOTE> in whate place that he<NOTE PLACE="foot">he in</NOTE> were.
<PB REF="00000179.tif" N="129"></L>
<L>The childe that was so nobill and wise<MILESTONE N="108b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>Stode at his Fadir graue at eve;<NOTE PLACE="foot">grauys graue</NOTE></L>
<L N="188">Ther come in<NOTE PLACE="foot">Omitted.</NOTE> oone in a white Surplice,</L>
<L>And priuely toke him by the sleve,</L>
<L>And sayd, "Childe, come on with me,<NOTE PLACE="foot">Come onne chyld and go with me</NOTE></L>
<L>God<NOTE PLACE="foot">For God</NOTE> hase herde thi prayer;</L>
<L N="192">Child, thi Fader thou shalt see,</L>
<L>Where he brenys<NOTE PLACE="foot">bryneth</NOTE> in hell&euml; fyre."</L>
<L>He led him to A comly hill,</L>
<L>The Erthe opened, and in thay yode;<NOTE PLACE="foot">he in &yogh;ede</NOTE></L>
<L N="196">Smoke and fire ther con<NOTE PLACE="foot">gan &thorn;er</NOTE> oute falle;<NOTE PLACE="foot">welle</NOTE></L>
<L>And many gostis glowinge on glede,<NOTE PLACE="foot">saules glo-wand in glede</NOTE></L>
<L>In peynes stronge, and troubill with-alle.<NOTE PLACE="foot">This line omitted.</NOTE></L>
<L>Ther he sawe many Sore turment,</L>
<L N="200">How saules were putt in grete pyne;<NOTE PLACE="foot">py[n]inge</NOTE></L>
<L>He sawe his Fa&thorn;er how he brentt,</L>
<L>And by the membrys how that<NOTE PLACE="foot">Omitted.</NOTE> he henge;<NOTE PLACE="foot">hynge</NOTE></L>
<L>Fendis black<NOTE PLACE="foot">bold</NOTE> with Crokis kene</L>
<L N="204">Rent his body fro lithe to lyth.<NOTE PLACE="foot">fader fro lyth to leme</NOTE></L>
<L>"Child, &thorn;u comyste<NOTE PLACE="foot">conets</NOTE> thi Fadir to sene,</L>
<L>Loke vp nowe, and speke him with."<NOTE PLACE="foot">with him</NOTE></L>
<L>"Alas, Fadyr, how standis<NOTE PLACE="foot">stand</NOTE> this case</L>
<L N="208">That ye bene in this peyn&euml;s stronge?"</L>
<L>"Sonne," he said, "y may sey alas</L>
<L>That euer y did thi moder wronge,</L>
<L>For she was both&euml; fayre and gode,</L>
<L N="212">And also bothe tresti and trewe.</L>
<L>Alas! y am<NOTE PLACE="foot">was</NOTE> worss&euml; than wode</L>
<L>Myn own&euml; bal&euml; for to<NOTE PLACE="foot">&thorn;er I dyde</NOTE> brewe."</L>
<L>"Fadir,<NOTE PLACE="foot">Whe&thorn;er</NOTE> is ther no<NOTE PLACE="foot">any</NOTE> Saint in hevyn</L>
<L N="216">That ye were wonte to haue in mynde,</L>
<L>That myght you helpe<NOTE PLACE="foot">lowse</NOTE> oute of this payne,<NOTE PLACE="foot">prison</NOTE>
<PB REF="00000180.tif" N="130"></L>
<L>Our lady mary, or some gode frende?"<MILESTONE N="109" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>"Sonne, all the saintes that bethe in hevyn,</L>
<L N="220">Nor all the Angilles vndir the trinite,<NOTE PLACE="foot">skye</NOTE></L>
<L>For to redde me<NOTE PLACE="foot">one oure space oute</NOTE> of this payne</L>
<L>They haue no power for to helpe<NOTE PLACE="foot">to lyst me</NOTE> me.</L>
<L>Sonne, and<NOTE PLACE="foot">if</NOTE> euery gresse were a preeste</L>
<L N="224">That growith vpon goddis grownde,</L>
<L>Off this paynes<NOTE PLACE="foot">peyne</NOTE> that thou me seste</L>
<L>Canne neuer mak&euml; me vnbounde.</L>
<L>Sonne, &thorn;u shalt be a preeste, y wote it wele;</L>
<L N="228">Onys or this day seven yere&mdash;</L>
<L>Att messe ne<NOTE PLACE="foot">At</NOTE> matynes, mett ne<NOTE PLACE="foot">ne At</NOTE> mele,&mdash;</L>
<L>Thou take me neuer in thi prayer:</L>
<L>Loke, Sonne, &thorn;u do as Y the saye!</L>
<L N="232">Therfor y warne the wele before,</L>
<L>For euer the lenger<NOTE PLACE="foot">more</NOTE> &thorn;u prayes for me</L>
<L>My paynes shall be more and more.</L>
<L>Fare wele," he saide, "my der&euml; Sonne,</L>
<L N="236">The Fadir of hevyn be-teche y the,</L>
<L>And warne euery man, where-so &thorn;u come,</L>
<L>Off wedlok to brek&euml;,<NOTE PLACE="foot">brekynge</NOTE> ware to be."</L>
<L>The Angill be-ganne &thorn;e child to lede</L>
<L N="240">Oute<NOTE PLACE="foot">Sone oute</NOTE> of that wrechidly<NOTE PLACE="foot">wrechyd</NOTE> wone</L>
<L>In-to a forest was longe in brede;</L>
<L>The sonne was vp, and bright it shone.</L>
<L>He led him to a fayre Erbere,<NOTE PLACE="foot">arbour</NOTE></L>
<L N="244">The yatis<NOTE PLACE="foot">pathys</NOTE> were of clene Cristalle</L>
<L>That to his sight were passyng fayre.</L>
<L>And as<NOTE PLACE="foot">als</NOTE> bright as any beralle;</L>
<L>The wallys semed of gold bright,</L>
<L N="248">With dorrys that were high and longe,<NOTE PLACE="foot">dores and with tourys strong</NOTE></L>
<L>Thay harde vpon the yatis on high,<NOTE PLACE="foot">hyht</NOTE></L>
<L>Mynstralsy and Angelle<NOTE PLACE="foot">with Angelles</NOTE> songe:&mdash;<MILESTONE N="109b" UNIT="folio">
<PB REF="00000181.tif" N="131"></L>
<L>The pellycan and the papynjaye,</L>
<L N="252">The tymor and the turtill trewe,</L>
<L>An hondered thousande in<NOTE PLACE="foot">on</NOTE> her laye,<NOTE PLACE="foot">rewe</NOTE></L>
<L>The nyghtyngale with notis newe.</L>
<L>On a grene hill he sawe a tre,<NOTE PLACE="foot">an hylle</NOTE></L>
<L N="256">The Savoure<NOTE PLACE="foot">fauour</NOTE> of hit was stronge &amp; store,</L>
<L>Pale it was, and wanne of ble,</L>
<L>Lost hit had bothe<NOTE PLACE="foot">hat &thorn;e</NOTE> frute and floure.</L>
<L>A Ruthefull<NOTE PLACE="foot">reufull</NOTE> sight that child con see,</L>
<L N="260">And of that sight he had grete drede,</L>
<L>"A! dere<NOTE PLACE="foot">god</NOTE> lady, howe may this bee,<NOTE PLACE="foot">le</NOTE></L>
<L>The blode of this tre bledis<NOTE PLACE="foot">lokys</NOTE> so rede?"</L>
<L>The Angill saide, "childe,<NOTE PLACE="foot">Omitted.</NOTE> this is the tree</L>
<L N="264">That God, Adam, the frute for-bede,</L>
<L>And therfor drevyn oute was hee,</L>
<L>And in the Erthe his lyfe to lede.</L>
<L>In the same place ther yn feste it blede,<NOTE PLACE="foot">For in the place ther thou seys it spred</NOTE></L>
<L N="268">Grewe<NOTE PLACE="foot">Grow</NOTE> the appill that Adam bote,</L>
<L>And that was thorough Evys rede</L>
<L>And the devill of hell, full well y wote.<NOTE PLACE="foot">it knewote</NOTE></L>
<L>Whan Any Synfull comys here in,</L>
<L N="272">As &thorn;u sest nowe here<NOTE PLACE="foot">chyld</NOTE> with me,</L>
<L>For vengeance of that cursyd Synne,</L>
<L>The blode will Ranne<NOTE PLACE="foot">rynneth</NOTE> oute of the tre."</L>
<L>He ladde him forthe vpon a<NOTE PLACE="foot">&thorn;e</NOTE> playne,</L>
<L N="276">He was ware of a pynacle pight,&mdash;</L>
<L>Suche on had<NOTE PLACE="foot">saw</NOTE> he neuer sayne,<NOTE PLACE="foot">none</NOTE>&mdash;</L>
<L>Off clothes of gold burneysshed bright;</L>
<L>Ther-vnder sate a cr&euml;ature</L>
<L N="280">As<NOTE PLACE="foot">Als</NOTE> bright as any Sonn&euml; beme,</L>
<L>Angillis<NOTE PLACE="foot">The angell</NOTE> did him grete honoure;</L>
<L>"Lo, childe,"<NOTE PLACE="foot">son</NOTE> he saide, "this is thy neme;</L>
<L>Ther, Fa&thorn;er<NOTE PLACE="foot">Thy feyr</NOTE> bro&thorn;er thou may senne in heuen,<NOTE PLACE="foot">Omitted.</NOTE>
<PB REF="00000182.tif" N="132"></L>
<L N="284">In heuen<NOTE PLACE="foot">heuens</NOTE> bliss&euml; with-oute Ende;</L>
<L>So myght thi Fa&thorn;er hau&euml;<NOTE PLACE="foot">well a</NOTE> bene</L>
<L>And he to wedlock had ben kynde,</L>
<L>But<NOTE PLACE="foot">Omitted.</NOTE> therfor he has getten him helle</L>
<L N="288">Endles in the<NOTE PLACE="foot">&thorn;at</NOTE> depe dongeon</L>
<L>Ther euer more for to dwelle;</L>
<L>Fro that place is &thorn;er no<NOTE PLACE="foot">in helle is no</NOTE> Redempcion."</L>
<L>Man, from myschefe thou<NOTE PLACE="foot">Omitted.</NOTE> &thorn;e a-mende,</L>
<L N="292">And &thorn;u may sitt full<NOTE PLACE="foot">all</NOTE> safe from care:</L>
<L>From dedely synne thou<NOTE PLACE="foot">god</NOTE> the defende,</L>
<L>And stryghte to<NOTE PLACE="foot">And vnto</NOTE> blisse thi soule shall fare.<NOTE PLACE="end"><SUP>10</SUP>A story of too skwyrys that were brethern, the whyche dwellyd here yn ynglond, yn the towne of Falmowtht, yn Dorsetschere; the tone was dampnyd for brekyng of hys wedlok, the tother was sauyd.<SUP>10</SUP></NOTE><NOTE PLACE="end">HERE FOLOWITH SENT GREGORIS TRENTALLE.<SUP>10</SUP><NOTE PLACE="foot"><SUP>10_10</SUP> These words are in a later hand.</NOTE></NOTE></L>
<TRAILER>EXPLICIT.
</TRAILER>

</LG>
</DIV3>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 TYPE="poem"><PB REF="00000183.tif" N="133">
<HEAD><B>Jhesu, Mercy for my Mysdede!</B> A DEUOYT MEDITACIONE.</HEAD>
<HEADNOTE><P>[<I>Trin. Coll. Cambridge, B.</I> 10, 12, <I>leaf</I> 53. <I>Date of MS. about</I> 1450.] [22 <I>stanzas of eights, abab, cdcd.</I>]</P></HEADNOTE>
<LG N="1" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(1)</HEAD>
<L>Ihesu, mercy! mercy, I cry:</L>
<L>myn vgly synnes &thorn;ou me forgyfe.</L>
<L>&thorn;<SUP>e</SUP> werlde, my flesch, &thorn;<SUP>e</SUP> fende, felly</L>
<L N="4">&thorn;ai me besale both strange &amp; styfe;</L>
<L>I hafe ful oft to &thorn;aim consent,</L>
<L>&amp; so to do it is gret drede;</L>
<L>I ask mercy with gud entent;</L>
<L N="8">Ihesu, mercy for my mysdede!</L>
</LG>
<LG N="2" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(2)</HEAD>
<L>&THORN;e werlde thurgh his fals couetyse,</L>
<L>&thorn;<SUP>e</SUP> fende with pryde, wreth, ire, envy,</L>
<L>I hafe, ihesu, bene fylde oft sythys,</L>
<L N="12">my flesche with slewth &amp; lychery,</L>
<L>And o&thorn;ere many ful gret synnes:</L>
<L>with repentance, ihesu, me fede,</L>
<L>for euere my tyme opon me rynnes:</L>
<L N="16">Ihesu, mercy for my myse-dede!</L>
</LG>
<LG N="3" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(3)</HEAD>
<L>Turne not &thorn;i face, ihesu, fro me,</L>
<L>&thorn;of I be werst in my lyfynge;</L>
<L>I ask mekely mercy of &thorn;e,</L>
<L N="20">for &thorn;i mercy passes al thynge.</L>
<L>In &thorn;i fyue woundes &thorn;ou sett my hert,</L>
<L>&thorn;at for mankynde on rode walde blede,</L>
<L>&amp; for &thorn;i dede vgly &amp; smert,</L>
<L N="24">Ihesu, mercy for [my<NOTE PLACE="foot">Omitted in MS.</NOTE>] myse-dede!
<PB REF="00000184.tif" N="134"></L>
</LG>
<LG N="4" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(4)</HEAD>
<L>To &thorn;i lyknes &thorn;ou has me made;</L>
<L>&thorn;e for to lufe &thorn;ou gyfe me grace!</L>
<L>&thorn;ou art &thorn;<SUP>e</SUP> lufe &thorn;at neuere <MILESTONE N="53b" UNIT="folio">sal fade;</L>
<L N="28">mercy I ask whils I hafe space.</L>
<L>I tryst ihesu of forgyfnes</L>
<L>of al my synnes, &thorn;at is my crede;</L>
<L>I me betake to &thorn;i gudnes;</L>
<L N="32">ihesu, mercy for my myse dede!</L>
</LG>
<LG N="5" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(5)</HEAD>
<L>Als touchande grace, bot ask &amp; hafe:</L>
<L>&thorn;us has &thorn;ou het in &thorn;i beheste,</L>
<L>&thorn;arfor sum grace on &thorn;e I crafe;</L>
<L N="36">with outen grace I am bot beste,</L>
<L>&amp; warre &thorn;an beste defyled with syne;</L>
<L>&thorn;ou graunt &thorn;at grace may in me brede,</L>
<L>&thorn;at y<NOTE PLACE="foot">Inserted in a different hand.</NOTE> &thorn;i lufe, ihesu, my&yogh;t wynn:</L>
<L N="40">Ihesu, mercy for my myse dede!</L>
</LG>
<LG N="6" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(6)</HEAD>
<L>Al worldely lufe is vanite;</L>
<L>bot lufe of &thorn;<SUP>e</SUP> passes al thynge.</L>
<L>&thorn;ar is no lufe with outen &thorn;e;</L>
<L N="44">&amp; &thorn;e to lufe I aske syghynge.</L>
<L>Ihesu, me graunt lufe &thorn;<SUP>e</SUP> forthy,</L>
<L>&amp; in &thorn;i law, ihesu, me lede.</L>
<L>&thorn;at I myslufede, I aske mercy:</L>
<L N="48">Ihesu, mercy for my mysdede!</L>
</LG>
<LG N="7" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(7)</HEAD>
<L>It is of &thorn;<SUP>e</SUP> for to forgyfe</L>
<L>alkyn tryspas both more &amp; mynn;</L>
<L>It is of me, whyls I here lyfe,</L>
<L N="52">or more or lesse ilke day to synne,</L>
<L>And of &thorn;<SUP>e</SUP> fende to duell &thorn;er in:</L>
<L>&thorn;ou gyfe me grace to take gud hede</L>
<L>&thorn;at I &thorn;i lufe, ihesu, myght wynne!</L>
<L N="56">Ihesu, mercy for my myse dede!
<PB REF="00000185.tif" N="135"></L>
</LG>
<LG N="8" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(8)</HEAD>
<L>Dispyce me no&yogh;t, swete lorde ihesu,</L>
<L>I am &thorn;<SUP>e</SUP> warke of &thorn;in aghen hende,</L>
<L>&thorn;of I hafe bene to &thorn;e vntrew;</L>
<L N="60">Ihesu, &thorn;ou kan me sone amende;</L>
<L>&thorn;ou has me made to &thorn;i lyknes,</L>
<L>thurgh synne I hafe loste heuenly mede;</L>
<L>Now, lorde, I aske of &thorn;i gudenes,</L>
<L N="64">Ihesu, mercy for my myse dede!</L>
</LG>
<LG N="9" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(9)</HEAD>
<L>&thorn;ow walde be borne for synful man,</L>
<L>for syn &thorn;ou take no wreke on <MILESTONE N="54" UNIT="folio">me.</L>
<L>. . . . .</L>
<L N="68">. . . . .<NOTE PLACE="inline"><I>no gap in MS.</I></NOTE></L>
<L>My comforth be &thorn;i harde passione;</L>
<L>Ihesu, &thorn;er of hafe I gret nede;</L>
<L>For synne &thorn;ou graunt me contrycione:</L>
<L N="72">Ihesu, mercy for mysdede!</L>
</LG>
<LG N="10" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(10)</HEAD>
<L>After my dedes &thorn;ou deme me no&yogh;t;</L>
<L>after mercy &thorn;ou do to me;</L>
<L>If &thorn;ou me deme als I hafe wroght,</L>
<L N="76">in bytter payns I drede to be.</L>
<L>My lyfe to mende, &amp; hafe mercy,</L>
<L>my lorde ihesu, &thorn;ou be my spede,</L>
<L>luf &thorn;<SUP>e</SUP>, &amp; drede, &thorn;at syttis on hy:</L>
<L N="80">Ihesu, mercy for my myse dede!</L>
</LG>
<LG N="11" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(11)</HEAD>
<L>If I had done ilke cursed warke,</L>
<L>&amp; alken synnes wer wro&yogh;t in me,</L>
<L>&thorn;ou may &thorn;aim sleke, als is a sparke</L>
<L N="84">when it is put in myddes &thorn;<SUP>e</SUP> see;</L>
<L>&amp; &thorn;ar may no man sleke my myse</L>
<L>bot &thorn;ou, ihesu, of &thorn;i godhede;</L>
<L>when &thorn;ou wouchesafe, &thorn;ou sone forgyfese:</L>
<L N="88">Ihesu, mercy for my mysdede!
<PB REF="00000186.tif" N="136"></L>
</LG>
<LG N="12" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(12)</HEAD>
<L>Who sal &thorn;e loue in fynyal blyse</L>
<L>bot trow mankynde &amp; angels fre?</L>
<L>Myne heretage forsoth &thorn;at is:</L>
<L N="92">thurgh gude lyfeynge &amp; grace of &thorn;e,</L>
<L>&thorn;ou me restore vnto &thorn;at blyse;</L>
<L>beholde frelete of my manhede</L>
<L>&thorn;at makes me oft to do of myse:</L>
<L N="96">Ihesu, mercy for my myse dede!</L>
</LG>
<LG N="13" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(13)</HEAD>
<L>&THORN;o[u] wil no dede of synful man:</L>
<L>&thorn;us says &thorn;ou, lorde, in haly wryt;</L>
<L>Ful wele wote &thorn;ou coueytis &thorn;an</L>
<L N="100">he turne his lyfe &amp; sone mende it:</L>
<L>&thorn;ou gyfe me grace my lyfe to mende,</L>
<L>beswylede in synn als wyckede wede;</L>
<L>graunt me &thorn;i lufe with outen ende:</L>
<L N="104">Ihesu, mercy for my myse dede!</L>
</LG>
<LG N="14" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(14)</HEAD>
<L>&THORN;ow art my god, I &thorn;<SUP>e</SUP> honour;</L>
<L>&thorn;ou art &thorn;<SUP>e</SUP> sone of maydyn &amp; moder,<MILESTONE N="54b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>In my dysese &thorn;ou me succure</L>
<L N="108">&thorn;ou art my lorde, &thorn;ou art my brother;</L>
<L>&thorn;ou sal me deme, my cryatour,</L>
<L>when vp sal ryse euere ilke a lede.</L>
<L>Mercy, ihesu, my sauyour!</L>
<L N="112">Ihesu, mercy for my myse dede!</L>
</LG>
<LG N="15" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(15)</HEAD>
<L>&THORN;ou helpe me, lorde, in my dysese,</L>
<L>&thorn;at walde susan helpe in hir tyme;</L>
<L>Ful gret clamour &thorn;an gon &thorn;ou pese</L>
<L N="116">when scho acusede was of crime.</L>
<L>&thorn;ou sett my saule, myn hert, in ese,</L>
<L>&thorn;<SUP>e</SUP> fende to flee &amp; his falshede,</L>
<L>&amp; soferandely &thorn;<SUP>e</SUP> for to plese:</L>
<L N="120">Ihesu, mercy for my mysedede!
<PB REF="00000187.tif" N="137"></L>
</LG>
<LG N="16" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(16)</HEAD>
<L>In my baptym I mayde beheste</L>
<L>&thorn;<SUP>e</SUP> for to serue lelely &amp; wele;</L>
<L>Of &thorn;i seruyse oft hafe I seste,</L>
<L N="124">with synnes thowsandes serued vnsele;</L>
<L>Bot &thorn;i mercy nedes moste be sene</L>
<L>&thorn;er moste synn is &amp; wyckededede;</L>
<L>&thorn;<SUP>e</SUP> moste synful I am, I wene;</L>
<L N="128">Ihesu, mercy for my myse dede!</L>
</LG>
<LG N="17" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(17)</HEAD>
<L>For synful man walde &thorn;ou be borne;</L>
<L>for ryghtwys not &thorn;ou wil recorde;</L>
<L>when man had synnede, he was forlorne,</L>
<L N="132">&amp; &thorn;an him kyndely &thorn;ou restorde;</L>
<L>&thorn;ou sufferde paynes cor&omacr;nde with thorne,</L>
<L>nakede with outen clath or schrede,</L>
<L>with mykel sorue &thorn;i body torne:</L>
<L N="136">Ihesu, mercy for my mysdede!</L>
</LG>
<LG N="18" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(18)</HEAD>
<L>&THORN;ou art my hope, my way ful sure,</L>
<L>ay lastande hele, both streng[t]h &amp; pese;</L>
<L>&thorn;ou art pyte &thorn;at ay sal dure;</L>
<L N="140">&thorn;ou art gudenes &thorn;at neuer sal sese;</L>
<L>&thorn;ou art clennes, both mylde &amp; mure;</L>
<L>me &thorn;<SUP>e</SUP> displese, ihesu, for bede,</L>
<L>Als &thorn;ou was borne of virgyne <MILESTONE N="55" UNIT="folio">pure:</L>
<L N="144">ihesu, mercy for my myse dede.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="19" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(19)</HEAD>
<L>&THORN;ou byddes ilke man &yogh;elde gud for ille,</L>
<L>not il for il to &yogh;elde agayne;</L>
<L>&thorn;an I beseke &thorn;e &thorn;at &thorn;ou wil</L>
<L N="148">graunt me mercy in stede of payne!</L>
<L>&thorn;ou me forgyfe, &amp; mercy graunt,</L>
<L>&amp; in my saule &thorn;ou sawe &thorn;i sede,</L>
<L>&thorn;at I may, lorde, make myne auaunt:</L>
<L N="152">Ihesu, mercy for my myse dede!
<PB REF="00000188.tif" N="138"></L>
</LG>
<LG N="20" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(20)</HEAD>
<L>Bot, worthy lorde, to &thorn;<SUP>e</SUP> I cry,</L>
<L>&amp; I in syne stande obstynate;</L>
<L>&thorn;arfore &thorn;ou heres no&yogh;t me forthy,</L>
<L N="156">&thorn;ou wil no&yogh;t here me in &thorn;at state.</L>
<L>&thorn;ou gyfe me grace lefe my foly,</L>
<L>&amp; fe[r]uently &thorn;<SUP>e</SUP> lufe &amp; drede,</L>
<L>&thorn;an wate I wele I get mercy:</L>
<L N="160">Ihesu, mercy for my myse dede!</L>
</LG>
<LG N="21" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(21)</HEAD>
<L>Noght euere-ilke man &thorn;at cales &thorn;<SUP>e</SUP> lorde</L>
<L>or mercy askes, sal hafe &thorn;i blise,</L>
<L>his conscienc&yogh; bot he remorde,</L>
<L N="164">&amp; wirke &thorn;i wil, &amp; mende his lyfe.</L>
<L>to blyse sal I sone be restorede</L>
<L>if I my saule &thorn;usgates wil fede;</L>
<L>Of &thorn;i mercy late me recorde:</L>
<L N="168">ihesu, mercy for my mysedede!</L>
</LG>
<LG N="22" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(22)</HEAD>
<L>I me betake to &thorn;i mercy</L>
<L>&thorn;at mercy gyffes to synful men;</L>
<L>&thorn;ou kepe me, lorde, for I sal dye,</L>
<L N="172">&amp; wot neuere whore, ne how, ne when.</L>
<L>In &thorn;i hote lufe me graunt to brene,</L>
<L>&amp; &thorn;at lesson trewly to rede;</L>
<L>Mercy &thorn;ou graunt! amen! amen!</L>
<L N="176">Ihesu, mercy for my myse dede! Amen!
</L>
</LG>

</DIV2>
<DIV2 TYPE="poem"><PB REF="00000189.tif" N="139">
<HEAD>Alya Cantica.</HEAD>
<HEADNOTE><P>[<I>Trin. Coll. Cambridge, B.</I> 10. 12, <I>leaf</I> 55. <I>Date of MS. about</I> 1450.] [5 <I>stanzas of eights, abab, abab</I>.]</P></HEADNOTE>
<LG N="1" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(1)</HEAD>
<L>Ihesu, &thorn;i name honourde my&yogh;t be</L>
<L>with al &thorn;at any lyfe is in.</L>
<L>Nou, swet ihesu, als &thorn;ou made me,</L>
<L N="4">&thorn;ou kepe me ay fro dedely synne!</L>
<L>Ihesu, &thorn;<SUP>e</SUP> sone of mary fre,</L>
<L>&thorn;e ioy of heuen &thorn;ou graunt me wynne;<MILESTONE N="55b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>My saule, ihesu, take I to &thorn;e</L>
<L N="8">when my body &amp; it sal twynne.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="2" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(2)</HEAD>
<L>Ihesu, &thorn;i name in me be sett</L>
<L>als &thorn;ou art kynnge &amp; lorde of lyght,</L>
<L>&amp; graunt me grace ai bett &amp; bett</L>
<L N="12">my lyfe to mende &amp; lyf ay ryght.</L>
<L>Ihesu, &thorn;i sydes with blode war wett,</L>
<L>&amp; dulefully for me war dyght;</L>
<L>&thorn;ou kepe me oute of syne &amp; dett,</L>
<L N="16">now, swete ihesu, ay moste of myght!</L>
</LG>
<LG N="3" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(3)</HEAD>
<L>Ihesu, &thorn;i name is hegh to neuen,</L>
<L>&amp; &yogh;it I, katyfe, cry &amp; kall,</L>
<L>Ihesu, me helpe &amp; brynge to heuen</L>
<L N="20">with &thorn;<SUP>e</SUP> to won my synful sall.</L>
<L>Myghty ihesu, &thorn;ou here my steuen</L>
<L>als &thorn;ou me boght when I was thrall,</L>
<L>&amp; forgyfe me &thorn;<SUP>e</SUP> synnes seuen,</L>
<L N="24">for I am gilty in &thorn;aim all.
<PB REF="00000190.tif" N="140"></L>
</LG>
<LG N="4" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(4)</HEAD>
<L>Ihesu, my lufe &amp; my lykynge,</L>
<L>for euere more blyste mot &thorn;ou be.</L>
<L>Mi lufely lorde, my dere darlynge,</L>
<L N="28">ful wer me [fayne<NOTE PLACE="foot">Omitted in the MS.</NOTE>] myght I &thorn;e se.</L>
<L>Ihesu, my lorde, &thorn;ou gar me synge</L>
<L>a lufely kynge is comen to me;</L>
<L>My swete swetnes of alkyn thynge,</L>
<L N="32">my hope &amp; tryste is al in &thorn;e.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="5" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(5)</HEAD>
<L>Ihesu, me helpe euere more at nede,</L>
<L>&amp; fro &thorn;<SUP>e</SUP> fende &thorn;ou me defende;</L>
<L>&thorn;ou sett my saule in lufe &amp; drede,</L>
<L N="36">&amp; al my myse &thorn;at I may mende.</L>
<L>Ihesu, &thorn;i blude &thorn;at &thorn;ou walde blede,</L>
<L>fro &thorn;is fals lyfe or &thorn;at I wende</L>
<L>&thorn;ou wesche a way al my mysdede,</L>
<L>&amp; graunt me blyse with outen ende. Amen.
</L>
</LG>

</DIV2>
<DIV2 TYPE="poem"><PB REF="00000191.tif" N="141">
<HEAD>Whi art thow froward sith I am Merciable.</HEAD>
<HEADNOTE><P>[5 <I>stanzas of eights, abab, bcbc</I>.]</P><P>[MS. Univ. Libr. Camb., Hh. iv. 12. leaf 85 <I>a</I>; handwriting of the 15th century. In every case a stroke is drawn over the final <I>on</I>. Sometimes the preceding <I>i</I> is omitted, in which case it is here inserted in italics.]</P></HEADNOTE>
<P>In cruce sum pro te, qui peccas; desine, pro me, Desine; do veniam; dic culpam, retraho penam.</P>
<LG N="1" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(1)</HEAD>
<L>&para; "Vpon a crosse naylyd I was for the,</L>
<L>Soffred deth to pay thy rawinson;<NOTE PLACE="foot">or, rawmson</NOTE></L>
<L>Forsake thy synn&euml; for the loffe of me,</L>
<L N="4">Be r&eacute;pentant, mak playne confess&iuml;on.</L>
<L>To contrite hertis I do remiss&iuml;on;</L>
<L>Be nat dispayryd, for I am not venge&aacute;ble;</L>
<L>Gayn gostly enmys thynk on my passion;</L>
<L N="8">Whi art thow froward, sith I am merci&aacute;ble?</L>
</LG>
<LG N="2" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(2)</HEAD>
<L>&para; "My blody woundis downe raylyng by thys tre,</L>
<L>loke on hem well, and haf compass&iuml;on;</L>
<L>The crowne of thorne, &thorn;<SUP>e</SUP> spere, and nailys thre</L>
<L N="12">Percyd hand and fote of indignacion,</L>
<L>Myn hert ryuen for thy redempc&iuml;on;</L>
<L>lat us tweyn in thys thyng be gre&aacute;ble,</L>
<L>loffe for loff, by iust conuenc&iuml;on;</L>
<L N="16">whi art thow froward, sith I am merci&aacute;ble?
<PB REF="00000192.tif" N="142"></L>
</LG>
<LG N="3" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(3)</HEAD>
<L>&para; "I had, on petyr and magdaleyne, pite</L>
<L>For the gret constrent of there contricion;<MILESTONE N="85b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>Gayne thomas Ind&egrave;s incredulite,</L>
<L N="20">he put hys [hand]<NOTE PLACE="foot">A word is here lost.</NOTE> depe in my side adowne;</L>
<L>Rolle up thys mater, graue it in thy reson;</L>
<L>Sith I am kynd, why art &thorn;ou so vnstable?</L>
<L>My blod, best triacle for thy tran[s]gression;</L>
<L N="24">Whi art thow froward, sith I am merci&aacute;ble?</L>
</LG>
<LG N="4" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(4)</HEAD>
<L>&para; "Thynk, a-gayne pride, on myn humilete;</L>
<L>Ren to scole, record well thys lesson;</L>
<L>Gayn fals enuy, thynk on my charite,</L>
<L N="28">My blode all spilt by distillac&iuml;on;</L>
<L>whi did I thys? to safe the fro prisoune;</L>
<L>afforne thyn hert, hang thys lityll table,</L>
<L>Swetter than bawme gayn all gostly poyson;</L>
<L N="32">Be &thorn;ow not froward, sith I am merci&aacute;ble."</L>
</LG>
<LG N="5" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(5)</HEAD>
<L>&para; "lord, on synfull knelyng on ther knee,</L>
<L>Thi deth remembryng of humble affeccion,</L>
<L>O ihesu, grant of thy benignite,</L>
<L N="36">That tho .v. wellys ple[n]teuose of fuyson,</L>
<L>Callyd thy .v. wowndis by computacion,</L>
<L>May wach in vs all surfetis r&eacute;proue&aacute;ble.</L>
<L>Now, for thy moders meke meditacion,</L>
<L N="40">At hyr request, be to us merci&aacute;ble."<NOTE PLACE="end">NOTES.&mdash;L. 11, <I>Nailys Thre</I>, because one was put through the two feet, and one through each hand. L. 19, <I>Thomas Indes:</I>&mdash; Thomas was said in old legends to have preached in India; see "The Complaynt of Criste" in this volume, l. 58, and <I>Piers Plowman</I> (vol. ii. p. 405, l. 13283), "Thaddee and ten mo: with <I>Thomas of Inde</I>."</NOTE></L>
<TRAILER>EXPLICIT.
</TRAILER>

</LG>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 TYPE="poem"><PB REF="00000193.tif" N="143">
<HEAD>Incypyt the Stacyons of Rome.</HEAD>
<HEADNOTE><P>[Cott. Calig. A. ii. leaf 83, and Lambeth 306, leaf 152, back. The text, to line 553, is that of the Cotton MS.: the readings of the Lambeth MS. are in the notes.]</P></HEADNOTE>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>He &thorn;at wyll hys sowl&euml;<NOTE PLACE="foot">wolle be his soullis</NOTE> leche,</L>
<L>Lysteneth to me, and y woll &yogh;ou teche.</L>
<L>Pardon ys &thorn;e sowl&euml;<NOTE PLACE="foot">sowelys</NOTE> bote,</L>
<L N="4">At gret&euml; Rome &thorn;er ys &thorn;e Rote:</L>
<L>Pardon, yn frensh a worde hit ys,<NOTE PLACE="foot">Pardon, A worde in trouthe is</NOTE></L>
<L>For&yogh;eu&euml;nesse of synnes y-wys.</L>
<L>The<NOTE PLACE="foot">A</NOTE> Duches of troye &thorn;at sum tyme<NOTE PLACE="foot">whilom there</NOTE> was,</L>
<L N="8">To Rome she come with grete pres;<NOTE PLACE="foot">moche solace.</NOTE></L>
<L>Of hyr came Romyrus<NOTE PLACE="foot">Remus</NOTE> &amp; Romulus</L>
<L>Of whom Rome ys cleped &yogh;yt y-wys:<NOTE PLACE="foot">clepyd thus</NOTE></L>
<L>Hethen hit was, &amp; cristened<NOTE PLACE="foot">Rome was hethene, and crystene</NOTE> now&yogh;t</L>
<L N="12">Tyll petyr and paule hadde hit bow&yogh;t,</L>
<L>Wyth golde, syluere, ne<NOTE PLACE="foot">Neydur with syluer, neydur</NOTE> with good,</L>
<L>But with her flesh &amp;<NOTE PLACE="foot">and with</NOTE> her blode,</L>
<L>For &thorn;er &thorn;ey suffrede both&euml; dethe,<NOTE PLACE="foot">to be dede</NOTE></L>
<L N="16">Here sowles to sav&euml; fro &thorn;e qwe&thorn;e.<NOTE PLACE="foot">to save her soule from the qweede. L. omits the next eight lines.</NOTE></L>
<L>In Rome Y shall &yogh;ou steuene</L>
<L>And hon&thorn;red kyrkes fowrty and seuen;</L>
<L>Chapelles &thorn;er ben many mo,</L>
<L N="20">Tenne &thorn;owsand &amp; fyfe; also</L>
<L>A-bowte &thorn;e wall, to &amp; fowrty,</L>
<L>Grete towres &thorn;re hondredde &amp; syxty,</L>
<L>Fowr &amp; twenty gret &yogh;ates &thorn;er be</L>
<L N="24">Pryncypall ouur o&thorn;ur, y tell &thorn;e.
<PB REF="00000194.tif" N="144"></L>
<L>&para; At seynt petur whe shall be-gynne</L>
<L>To telle of pardon &thorn;at slaketh<NOTE PLACE="foot">the pardon &thorn;at quenchithe</NOTE> synne:</L>
<L>A fayr mynstyr men may &thorn;er<NOTE PLACE="foot">there &thorn;ou myght</NOTE> se,</L>
<L N="28">Nyne and twenty grecys &thorn;er be;<NOTE PLACE="foot">xxxix Auters there be spesyally.</NOTE></L>
<L>And al so ofte<NOTE PLACE="foot">As ofte</NOTE> as &thorn;ou gost vp or downe,</L>
<L>Begynneth of gode<NOTE PLACE="foot">Be cause of</NOTE> deuocyoun</L>
<L>Thow sha[l]t haue at eche a gree,<NOTE PLACE="foot">shalt . . degree.</NOTE>&mdash;</L>
<L N="32">Man or wommon whe&thorn;ur &thorn;ou bee,&mdash;</L>
<L>Seuenne &yogh;ere of<NOTE PLACE="foot">to</NOTE> pardon,</L>
<L>And &thorn;er-to goddes benysoun;<NOTE PLACE="foot">And of thy synnes Remyssyon. The next two lines are, <Q><L>Pope Alysaundur grauntythe all and some</L><L>to all theyme that thyddur come;</L></Q> and the next eight lines are omitted.</NOTE></L>
<L>Pope Alyxandur hit graunted at Rome,</L>
<L N="36">To man or womman &thorn;at dedur come.</L>
<L>A-bouenne &thorn;e grece, as &thorn;ou shalt gone,</L>
<L>Stondeth a chapell hym self a-lone,</L>
<L>In &thorn;e whych song petur his fyrst masse,</L>
<L N="40">As &thorn;e Romaynis seyn, more &amp; lasse.</L>
<L>As often as &thorn;ou wylt &thorn;ydur come,<MILESTONE N="83b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>Seuenne &thorn;owsand &yogh;er &thorn;ou getest of pardon;</L>
<L>And as mony lentones mo</L>
<L N="44">Euery day &yogh;yf &thorn;ou wylt &thorn;edur go.</L>
<L>In &thorn;at mynster may &thorn;ou<NOTE PLACE="foot">&thorn;ou mayste</NOTE> fynde</L>
<L>An houn&thorn;red<NOTE PLACE="foot">fowre score</NOTE> Auters by-fore &amp; be-hynde;</L>
<L>And when &thorn;e<NOTE PLACE="foot">Alle the</NOTE> Auters halowed were,</L>
<L N="48">xxiiij<NOTE PLACE="foot">xviij</NOTE> &yogh;ere, &amp; so mony lentones more<NOTE PLACE="foot">lenttis by-foore</NOTE></L>
<L>He &yogh;af &amp; graunted to<NOTE PLACE="foot">of</NOTE> pardon,</L>
<L>And ther-to goddes<NOTE PLACE="foot">crystys</NOTE> benesoun.</L>
<L>A-mong &thorn;e auters vij &thorn;er be</L>
<L N="52">More of grace &amp;<NOTE PLACE="foot">moste of grace and of</NOTE> dyngnyte:</L>
<L>The Auter of &thorn;e Vernake ys &thorn;at on,<NOTE PLACE="foot">is one</NOTE></L>
<L>Vpon &thorn;e Ry&yogh;th hond as &thorn;ou shalt gon;
<PB REF="00000195.tif" N="145"></L>
<L><SUP>1</SUP>The secounde, yn honour of our lady ys;</L>
<L N="56">The &thorn;rydde, of seynt symon y-wys;</L>
<L>The iiij, of seynt Andrew &thorn;ou shalt haue;</L>
<L>&THORN;e .v. of seynt gregour, &thorn;er he lys yn graue;<SUP>1</SUP><NOTE PLACE="foot"><SUP>1_1</SUP> <Q><L>&thorn;e secunde is symonde &amp; Iude, &thorn;ou myght haue,</L><L>there of seynt gregorye there he is grave.</L><L>the iiij<SUP>te</SUP> of oure ladye I-wys,</L><L>of whome the covent syngithe messe;</L><L>the fyvithe of seynt Andrewe is.</L></Q></NOTE></L>
<L>The syxte, of seynt leon &thorn;e pope,<NOTE PLACE="foot">leo papa I-wys. L. omits the next seven lines, and transposes the eighth and ninth, reading <I>doo</I> for <I>done</I>, to ryme with <I>also</I>.</NOTE></L>
<L N="60">There he song masse yn his cope;</L>
<L>Of &thorn;e holy crosse &thorn;e seuenny&thorn; ys,</L>
<L>In &thorn;e whych no wommon cometh ywys.</L>
<L>At eche on of &thorn;ese Auteres &thorn;ere</L>
<L N="64">Is euery tyme, of pardon vij &yogh;ere,</L>
<L>And as mony lentones mo</L>
<L>To all &thorn;at wyll de&thorn;ur goo,</L>
<L>At &thorn;e hy&yogh; Auter &thorn;er petur ys done,</L>
<L N="68">Pope gregory graunteth a pardon</L>
<L>Of synnis for-gyffenne &amp; o&thorn;es<NOTE PLACE="foot">for-yeett and odur</NOTE> Also,</L>
<L>Seuenne &amp; twenty &yogh;ere<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. &yogh;ef; L and vij yere. Lambeth has, 'And vij &yogh;ere he grauntythe therto.'</NOTE> he &yogh;af &thorn;er-to,</L>
<L>Fro holy &thorn;orsday yn-to<NOTE PLACE="foot">vnto</NOTE> lammes</L>
<L N="72">Is<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>om</I>. Is</NOTE> euery day more &amp; lasse,</L>
<L>Fowrtene<NOTE PLACE="foot">there is xiiij</NOTE> &thorn;owsand &yogh;ere.</L>
<L>To all &thorn;at cometh to &thorn;at mynstere<NOTE PLACE="foot">to alle men that comys there</NOTE></L>
<L><SUP>9</SUP>On our lady day &thorn;e Assumpcioun</L>
<L N="76">Is a &thorn;owsand &yogh;er of pardon.</L>
<L>On seynt petur &amp; powle day</L>
<L>&THORN;at<SUP>9</SUP><NOTE PLACE="foot"><SUP>9_9</SUP> Of seynt Martyn the xviij daye this</NOTE> mynster was halowed, as<NOTE PLACE="foot">as <I>om</I>.</NOTE> y say,</L>
<L>&THORN;en ys &thorn;er xiiij<NOTE PLACE="foot">is vij</NOTE> &thorn;owsand &yogh;er &amp; le[n]tons<NOTE PLACE="foot">lenttis</NOTE> &thorn;er-to,</L>
<L N="80">&amp; &thorn;e &thorn;rydde part of &thorn;y<NOTE PLACE="foot">&thorn;y <I>om</I>.</NOTE> penauns vndo.</L>
<L>When &thorn;e vernacull shewed ys,<MILESTONE N="83b:2" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>Gret pardon for so&thorn;e &thorn;er ys,<NOTE PLACE="foot">is there I-wys</NOTE></L>
<L>Fowr &thorn;owsand &yogh;ere, as y &yogh;ou<NOTE PLACE="foot">thre thowesande yere the</NOTE> telle,
<PB REF="00000196.tif" N="146"></L>
<L N="84">To men &thorn;at yn &thorn;e cyte<NOTE PLACE="foot">to hem that in Rome</NOTE> dwelle;</L>
<L>And men &thorn;at dwellen be-sydwarde,<NOTE PLACE="foot">And they that were thyddyrwarde</NOTE></L>
<L>ix &thorn;owsand &yogh;er shall be here<NOTE PLACE="foot">is theyre</NOTE> part;</L>
<L>And &thorn;ou &thorn;at passen<NOTE PLACE="foot">yff thowe passe</NOTE> ouur &thorn;e see,</L>
<L N="88">xij &thorn;owsand &yogh;ere ys graunted &thorn;e;</L>
<L>And &thorn;er-to &thorn;ou shalt haue more,<NOTE PLACE="foot">shalt wynne</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;e &thorn;rydde parte for&yogh;euenesse of &thorn;y sore.<NOTE PLACE="foot">For-yevenes of all thy synne.</NOTE></L>
<L>In lenton ys more<NOTE PLACE="foot">lent that holy</NOTE> grace;</L>
<L N="92"><SUP>8</SUP>Eche pardoun ys dowbled yn &thorn;at<SUP>8</SUP><NOTE PLACE="foot"><SUP>8_8</SUP> is dowbylde in eche place beethe Idoone</NOTE> place.</L>
<L>In &thorn;at place &thorn;er be done</L>
<L>Holy bon&euml;s mony on,</L>
<L>Of petur, powle, &amp; saynt<NOTE PLACE="foot">Iude and</NOTE> symon,</L>
<L N="96">Seynt Iude,<NOTE PLACE="foot">and of sent</NOTE> gregour, and leon,</L>
<L><NOTE PLACE="foot">L. inserts, <Q><L>Seynt Iohn and seynt Boneface,</L><L>Proscesse and Martyn in that place.</L></Q> See 171/841.</NOTE>Seynt parnell &thorn;at holy vyrgyn,</L>
<L>And seynt Sythe<NOTE PLACE="foot">sythi L, sythe C.</NOTE> &thorn;at &thorn;oled<NOTE PLACE="foot">suffyrde</NOTE> pyne,</L>
<L>And mony mo &thorn;er are yn fere<NOTE PLACE="foot">bethe I fere</NOTE></L>
<L N="100">&THORN;at to Ihesu beth<NOTE PLACE="foot">been to cryst</NOTE> leue &amp; dere:</L>
<L><SUP>16</SUP>No mon kan &thorn;e so&thorn;&euml; say.</L>
<L>&THORN;erfore passe we forth an o&thorn;ur way<SUP>16</SUP><NOTE PLACE="foot"><SUP>16_16</SUP> <Q><L>Nowe passe we forthe in oure waye</L><L>that we mowe the sothe saye</L></Q></NOTE></L>
<L>To seynt powle, as y wene,</L>
<L N="104">Fowr myle ys holden<NOTE PLACE="foot">been</NOTE> be-twene;</L>
<L>In &thorn;at place<NOTE PLACE="foot">waye</NOTE> ys grette pardon,</L>
<L>And of many synnis<NOTE PLACE="foot">of synnes</NOTE> remyssyoun;</L>
<L>Sawle was his nome<NOTE PLACE="foot">name</NOTE> by-fore,</L>
<L N="108">Syth &thorn;e tyme &thorn;at he was bore;<NOTE PLACE="foot">frome that tyme he was I-boore</NOTE></L>
