<L>&sect;Relykes &thorn;er be mony &amp; fele:</L>
<L><SUP>9</SUP>The sponge of galle &amp; of eysell</L>
<L N="496">That &thorn;e Iewes profered cryst to<SUP>9</SUP><NOTE PLACE="foot"><SUP>9_9</SUP> <Q><L>that is there for sothe to telle</L><L>Whan . . . profyrde to drynk thoo</L></Q></NOTE></L>
<L>When<NOTE PLACE="foot">Whan that . . Sissio</NOTE> he sayde "scicio";</L>
<L>&Verbar;<SUP>11</SUP>And a nayle, when Ihesu criste was</L>
<L>Don on &thorn;e Rode for our trespas.<SUP>11</SUP><NOTE PLACE="foot"><SUP>11_11</SUP> <Q><L>And yeet moore I wole the telle:</L><L>there is A coorde In one chapelle,&mdash;</L><L>Ane highe in the Roofe hit is doo,<MILESTONE N="159" UNIT="folio"></L><L>for no man shoulde come &thorn;er-too.&mdash;</L><L>that ylke coorde, they sey hit is,</L><L>with whiche cryste was led to &thorn;e crosse I-wys;</L><L>&Verbar; And A nayle that smyte cryst Ihesus</L><L>whane he Suffyrde Dethe for us;</L><L>And the hede of seynt vynsent;</L><L>the clothe of bapetyse whan he was brent.</L></Q></NOTE>
<PB REF="00000211.tif" N="161"></L>
<L N="500">And yn &thorn;at cherche<NOTE PLACE="foot">the chirche hit</NOTE> ys also</L>
<L>Of &thorn;e crosse &thorn;at he was on<NOTE PLACE="foot">god was</NOTE> Ido,</L>
<L>And of &thorn;e tre &thorn;at &thorn;e &thorn;eues henge on<NOTE PLACE="foot">the crosse &thorn;at &thorn;e theefe hyng hym</NOTE> by</L>
<L>That of his synnis askede<NOTE PLACE="foot">whan he cryed, Lorde</NOTE> mercy;</L>
<L N="504"><NOTE PLACE="foot">L. inserts: the tethe Also there been of seynt blase, <Q><L>And odyr Relykys many oone,</L><L>I cannat telle hem everychone.</L></Q></NOTE> And a tityll of syr pylat,&mdash;</L>
<L>He may hit Rede &thorn;at ys<NOTE PLACE="foot">made hit Red &thorn;at was</NOTE> &thorn;er-at,&mdash;</L>
<L>"Thys ys Ihesu of na&yogh;areth,</L>
<L>Kyng of Iewes, &thorn;at &thorn;olede<NOTE PLACE="foot">suffyrde</NOTE> deth;"</L>
<L N="508">The tytyll ys honged, y wyll not<NOTE PLACE="foot">hyde with-owten</NOTE> lye,</L>
<L>By<NOTE PLACE="foot">In</NOTE> a crosse &thorn;at ys hym bye,<NOTE PLACE="foot">hangithe hye</NOTE></L>
<L>In &thorn;e maner of a bowe<NOTE PLACE="foot">In maner of A bowe for-soothe</NOTE></L>
<L>In &thorn;e myddes of &thorn;e kyrke, y trowe;<NOTE PLACE="foot">menystre Rooffe</NOTE></L>
<L N="512">In &thorn;at maner hit ys do<NOTE PLACE="foot">I-doo</NOTE></L>
<L>For no man shulde come &thorn;er-to.</L>
<L>&para; Of more pardon y wyll &yogh;ou<NOTE PLACE="foot">I yowe</NOTE> say</L>
<L>That at seynt laurence ys eche<NOTE PLACE="foot">of seynt lawerens &thorn;at ylk</NOTE> day;</L>
<L N="516">Seuen &thorn;owsand &yogh;er, &amp; lentones<NOTE PLACE="foot">with lenttis</NOTE> &thorn;er-to,</L>
<L>And &thorn;e &thorn;rydde parte of &thorn;y penauns vndo.<NOTE PLACE="foot">L. inserts: <Q><L>In tyme off the Emperoure</L><L>kynge constantyne of grete honoure</L></Q></NOTE></L>
<L>Pope pelagyus,<NOTE PLACE="foot">honorius</NOTE> &thorn;at holy man,<MILESTONE N="86b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>That chyrche to halowe fyrst<NOTE PLACE="foot">halowed and</NOTE> be-gan,</L>
<L N="520">And graunted &thorn;er-to hys pardon<NOTE PLACE="foot">the pardoone he grauntyd to alle Anoone</NOTE></L>
<L>And also goddes<NOTE PLACE="foot">there-to his</NOTE> benyson,</L>
<L>Thorow prayres of two martires<NOTE PLACE="foot">the holy marter</NOTE></L>
<L>Steuen &amp; laurence &thorn;at &thorn;er lyes.<NOTE PLACE="foot">Seynt st. and seynt l. &thorn;at be there</NOTE>
<PB REF="00000212.tif" N="162"></L>
<L N="524"><SUP>1</SUP>And vn&thorn;ur &thorn;e awter ys made a stone,</L>
<L>There a-bowte &thorn;ey may gone:</L>
<L>An hole on &thorn;is awter &thorn;ou may fynde;</L>
<L>Knele down &thorn;er with good mynde,</L>
<L N="528">Putte yn &thorn;y heed or &thorn;y honde,</L>
<L>And &thorn;ou shalt fele a swete gronde,</L>
<L>A swete smelle of bodyes &thorn;at &thorn;er be,<SUP>1</SUP><NOTE PLACE="foot"><SUP>1_1</SUP> <Q><L>A-bowte the Awter &thorn;ou shalt goone;<MILESTONE N="159b" UNIT="folio"></L><L>At every ende &thorn;ou shalt fynde&mdash;</L><L>knele there-to yf &thorn;ou be hende,&mdash;</L><L>A swete smelle, thoowe hit be derke,</L><L>(thorowe grace of crystis owne werke,)</L><L>of bodyes that there beryed be</L></Q></NOTE></L>
<L>Here sowles be with god in trinite.</L>
<L N="532"><SUP>2</SUP>And &yogh;yf &thorn;ou be &thorn;er all &thorn;e &yogh;ere,</L>
<L>Eche wednesday yn &thorn;at mynster,</L>
<L>Thow may haue, of cristes powere,</L>
<L>A sowle to drawe out of purgatory fyre.<SUP>2</SUP><NOTE PLACE="foot"><SUP>2_2</SUP> <Q><L>Who-so wole dwelle in halle,</L><L>And go eche Daye to seynt lawrence mynstyr,</L><L>he may there delyuer with orysone</L><L>A sowle owte of purgatory presone.</L></Q></NOTE></L>
<L N="536">&para; At seynt sympyll, fawstyne, &amp; betrys,<NOTE PLACE="foot">In the chirche of fastyine, simple, beatrice</NOTE></L>
<L>That ben all martyres of<NOTE PLACE="foot">be very Martyrs of Ihesu</NOTE> cryste.</L>
<L>Seynt sympull, pope of Rome he<NOTE PLACE="foot">in Roome</NOTE> was,</L>
<L>And god hym sente a fayr grace;</L>
<L N="540">Seuen hondred holy<NOTE PLACE="foot">vj M<SUP>l</SUP> [= 6000] holy mennys</NOTE> bones</L>
<L>He gedered, but not<NOTE PLACE="foot">gadyrde to gedur alle</NOTE> at ones,</L>
<L>And yn &thorn;at chyrche he dede hem graue,</L>
<L>For ho-so seke hem, his sowle he may saue;<NOTE PLACE="foot">Sykyr he was that they were savede. (<I>Sowle</I> is in a later hand.)</NOTE></L>
<L N="544">And he &yogh;af pardon to alle &thorn;o</L>
<L>That be shryuen &amp; &thorn;ydur wyll<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>om</I>. wylle</NOTE> go,</L>
<L>Fyfe &thorn;owsand &yogh;er<NOTE PLACE="foot">vij M<SUP>l</SUP> yere of pardoon</NOTE> &amp; more</L>
<L>Thorow prayeres of hem &thorn;at lyen<NOTE PLACE="foot">lygg</NOTE> &thorn;ore.
<PB REF="00000213.tif" N="163"></L>
<L N="548">&para;<NOTE PLACE="foot">Cott. MS. With-owte owte. L. inserts: <Q><L>Whane he was dede, &thorn;er was he grave;</L><L>Cryste his soule kepe and save!</L><L>A stoone do&thorn;e stande in &thorn;e weye</L><L>By-twyx the chyrche and martyrs twey,</L><L>Seynt Iulyan and seynt vrban,</L><L>there was men and women,</L><L>In that stoone wryttyn is</L><L>grete pardoone, soothe I-wys,</L><L>Euery daye in the yere</L><L>vij thowesande yere &thorn;ou myght have there.</L></Q></NOTE> With-owte &thorn;e kyrke of Iulyan<NOTE PLACE="foot">chirche of seynt vyuyen (lf. 160, bk.)</NOTE></L>
<L>Ther ys wryten yn a stone</L>
<L>That honoryus, &thorn;at holy pope,</L>
<L>That kyrke<NOTE PLACE="foot">this chirche</NOTE> halewede yn his<NOTE PLACE="foot">A</NOTE> cope;</L>
<L N="552">And six<NOTE PLACE="foot">thre</NOTE> &thorn;owsand &yogh;ere he &yogh;af to pardon</L>
<L>To all &thorn;o &thorn;at &thorn;ydur wyll come.<NOTE PLACE="foot"><Q><L>And there-to goddis benysone</L><L>lastynge for euer-more</L><L>to alle men that been there.</L></Q></NOTE><NOTE PLACE="end">[Here the Cotton MS. ends, but the Lambeth MS. (leaf 160) continues.]</NOTE></L>
<TRAILER>.;. EXPLICIT &thorn;E STACIONES OF ROME .;.</TRAILER>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>In the menyster of &thorn;at holy preste</L>
<L>that is dere to Ihesu cryste,</L>
<L N="556">Eusebius is there name,&mdash;</L>
<L>to tell of hym hit is goode game,&mdash;</L>
<L>hit is wryttyn in A stoone</L>
<L>'I wole the halowe or I goone,'</L>
<L N="560">that pope gregory with his hande</L>
<L>that chirche halowed, I vndyrstande,</L>
<L>and yave pardoun, I yowe saye,</L>
<L>A C yerys and fourty daye</L>
<L N="564">and there-to mo I wole yowe telle</L>
<L>to Abate the peyne off helle.</L>
<L>And In the chyrche of seynt Iulyan</L>
<L>there is his chykk, and tethe &thorn;er-one;</L>
<L N="568">A thorne thyrlyd in crystis hed,</L>
<L>when he suffyrde for us to be ded,</L>
<L>And odyr Relykys many and dere;
<PB REF="00000214.tif" N="164"></L>
<L>Go thyddyr and haue vij C yere.</L>
<L N="572">Anodyr chyrche for-so&thorn;e there is,</L>
<L>of seynt Mathewe worshupe I-wys,</L>
<L>In the Right hande as &thorn;ou shalt goone</L>
<L>to the chyrche of seynt Iohn:</L>
<L N="576">An hole Arme of seynt Christofre, goddis knyght,</L>
<L>[In a chiste right there is dyght,]</L>
<L>In that same chyrche hit is I-doo,</L>
<L>And grete pardone yeve thertoo,</L>
<L N="580">for cryste hym selffe there-on stoode,</L>
<L>whan he bare hym on the Floode.</L>
<L>In the chirche of uyght and modeste,<MILESTONE N="160b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>there men mowe have, moste &amp; leste,</L>
<L N="584">the iiij<SUP>te</SUP> parte of for-yevenes of syn,</L>
<L>what tyme he comythe &thorn;e chirche with-in.</L>
<L>vij M<SUP>l</SUP> martyrs lyggythe there,</L>
<L>As hit is wryttyn in that mynystre;</L>
<L N="588">In tyme of Emperoure Anthony[n]e</L>
<L>that tyrant was, and paynyme;</L>
<L>this is the vij parte of &thorn;y synne ondoone.</L>
<L>At seint mary maioure</L>
<L N="592">Is A chirche of grete honowre;</L>
<L>As the hye Auter, hit is seyde,</L>
<L>there is the body of mathewe leyde:</L>
<L>In the chyrche, Anodyr partye,</L>
<L N="596">lyethe seynt Ierome sykerlye;</L>
<L>frome the Cyte of Damase,</L>
<L><NOTE PLACE="foot">A long initial letter which looks like I, stands before <I>he</I>.</NOTE>he was brought in-to &thorn;at plase;</L>
<L>by-foore A plase he was pyght,</L>
<L N="600">'precepe' men clepe hit.</L>
<L>vppon his graue lyethe A stoone,</L>
<L>And A crosse is leyde there-one;</L>
<L>A-bowte that stoone A grate there is</L>
<L N="604">of Irne stronge made I-wys.</L>
<L>In that plase is A chapell</L>
<L>of seynt Agas, &thorn;ou wott hit wele;
<PB REF="00000215.tif" N="165"></L>
<L>x yere of pardone is grauntyd there,</L>
<L N="608">lygyng there-to evyr-more.</L>
<L>A lytyll clothe lyethe there too,</L>
<L>of whiche cryst was fyrste in do</L>
<L>of his modyr, whan he was bore</L>
<L N="612">to save man that was for-lore.</L>
<L>of his Flesche the Syrcumsyse,</L>
<L>Men hit holdythe of grete pryse;</L>
<L>And of the hey, more and lasse,<MILESTONE N="161" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="616">that cryste lay on by-fore &thorn;e asse.</L>
<L>An arme is also there</L>
<L>of seynt thom[a]s the marter,</L>
<L>and A party of the brayne of his hede</L>
<L N="620">At caunterbury there he was dede,</L>
<L>And Rochet that is goode,&mdash;</L>
<L>hit was sprongyn with his bloode&mdash;</L>
<L>which he had one whan he was take</L>
<L N="624">for alle holy chirche-is saake.</L>
<L>And An Image sykurly</L>
<L>wondyr fayre of oure ladye;</L>
<L>seynt luke, whyles he was in londe,</L>
<L N="628">woulde haue payntyd hit with his hande;</L>
<L>And whane he hade ordeyinyd hit soo,</L>
<L>alle his colourse there too,</L>
<L>he founde An Image alle Redy,</L>
<L N="632">Neuer noone syche in eorthe he sy,</L>
<L>with Angellis handis, &amp; nought with his:</L>
<L>the story in Roome wyttnessithe this,</L>
<L>that is wryttyn every dele</L>
<L N="636">At the hye awter in A tabyll.<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. In a tabylle at, etc.</NOTE></L>
<L>there is pardoone, men may see,</L>
<L>of many popys &thorn;at there hathe bee;</L>
<L>vppon the chyrch&euml; halydaye</L>
<L N="640">A M<SUP>l</SUP> yere of pardon &thorn;ou may,</L>
<L>And there-to, yff &thorn;ou wylt more,</L>
<L>the thyrde parte of alle &thorn;y lore,
<PB REF="00000216.tif" N="166"></L>
<L>And vii C yere there-too;</L>
<L N="644">wele is hym that thyddyr may goo.</L>
<L>In eche feste of oure ladye,</L>
<L>to &thorn;at graunttythe seynt gregorye;</L>
<L>he yaffe therto A C yere of pardone,</L>
<L N="648">And therto crystis benysone.</L>
<L>In owre ladijs day Assumpsione,</L>
<L>There is than grete pardone;<MILESTONE N="161b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>frome &thorn;at fest tyll Ihesu was bore,</L>
<L N="652">No daye shall be for-lore;</L>
<L>there is xv M<SUP>l</SUP> yere</L>
<L>of penaunce &thorn;ou shuldyst full-fyll here.</L>
<L>Anodur chyrche also there is,</L>
<L N="656">'Pudencyam' hit is clepyd I-wys;</L>
<L>An holy woman I fynde she was,</L>
<L>All full-fyllyd by goddis grace:</L>
<L>the thyrde parte of &thorn;y synne</L>
<L N="660">for-yevenes ther &thorn;ou myght wynne.</L>
<L>A chyrche-yerde is there too</L>
<L>of seynt presell, men clepe hit soo.</L>
<L>Seynt gregory tellythe [us]</L>
<L N="664">that in &thorn;at yarde &amp; in &thorn;at house</L>
<L>Ben beryed many of thoo,</L>
<L>thre thowesand with-owten moo;</L>
<L>for eche body &thorn;ou myght tell</L>
<L N="668">O yere and o lent &thorn;ou myght spell</L>
<L>of pardon is grauntyd to &thorn;e</L>
<L>By prayer of hem &thorn;at there bee;</L>
<L>for seynt petyr &amp; seynt poule, &thorn;at some tyme were,</L>
<L N="672">Bothe were harborowed there.</L>
<L>A lytyll chapell yeet there is,</L>
<L>I-clepyd 'titulus pastoris;'</L>
<L>As &thorn;ou comyst at the chyrche-is ende,</L>
<L N="676">that chapell &thorn;ou shalt fynde;</L>
<L>The pope of Rome &thorn;at was than,</L>
<L>seynt peius the holy man,</L>
<L>the bapetystore there he founde,
<PB REF="00000217.tif" N="167"></L>
<L N="680">and holowed [<I>sic</I>] hit with his honde;</L>
<L>And vppon An estyr daye&mdash;</L>
<L>As I tell yowe nowe I maye&mdash;</L>
<L>Syxty soules and xviij there-to,</L>
<L N="684">to Crystyn-dom he brought thoo.</L>
<L>Of praxed, the holy woman,<MILESTONE N="162" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>all the soth&euml; tell I can,</L>
<L>A thowesande bodyes with-owten moo,</L>
<L N="688">And iij hundyrde there-too,</L>
<L>In &thorn;at place buryed shee&mdash;</L>
<L>her sowelys bethe with cryst so Fre&mdash;</L>
<L>that suffyrde dethe in &thorn;at tyme</L>
<L N="692">Of the emperoure Anthony[n]e.</L>
<L>pope Innocent, for love of hem,</L>
<L>graunte[de] tho to all&euml; men</L>
<L>O yere, and xl dayes there-to,</L>
<L N="696">And the iiij parte of penaunce vndo.</L>
<L>And there is of the pyllur A party</L>
<L>that cryste was bounde to sykyrly;</L>
<L>And yff &thorn;ou come in lent to chyrche,</L>
<L N="700">Double pardoone &thorn;ou myght wyrche.</L>
<L>there lyethe bodyes of sylvester &amp; seynt martyn,</L>
<L>the story of Rome wytnessithe hit myne.</L>
<L>Anodur Day in the yere</L>
<L N="704">of seynt petre men clepythe there</L>
<L>Ad<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. And</NOTE> vincula in londe,</L>
<L>lammasse day &thorn;ou vndyrstonde,</L>
<L>whan petur was bounde with Irnys grete,</L>
<L N="708">As wee in oure bokis Reede,</L>
<L>that daye is grete pardoone,</L>
<L>of alle thy synnys remyssyoun;</L>
<L>And every day, yff &thorn;ou wolt crave,</L>
<L N="712">fyve hundyrd yere there &thorn;ou myght haue,</L>
<L>And so many lenttis moo</L>
<L>pope gelasius ha&thorn;e grauntyd &thorn;erto.</L>
<L>&para; there is a pese of the Roode
<PB REF="00000218.tif" N="168"></L>
<L N="716">that cryst was on do for oure goode,</L>
<L>And the bed<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. hed</NOTE> of seynt Martyne,</L>
<L>An holy man &thorn;at tholyd pyne;</L>
<L>In that bed shall no man lye,</L>
<L N="720">for he wole not &thorn;at hit be seye,<MILESTONE N="162b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>Ne touche-hit with no manis hande,<NOTE PLACE="foot">This line is repeated after the next.</NOTE></L>
<L>for hit is prevy, I vndyrstande.</L>
<L>Suche bed of penaunce I not no moo,</L>
<L N="724">to A plase of<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. of of</NOTE> the postyllis twoo&mdash;</L>
<L>cryste us kepe owte of woo!&mdash;<NOTE PLACE="foot">Seemingly l. 725 should follow 723, and be followed by a line like 'Now lat us forthe goo.'</NOTE></L>
<L>fyrste of constantyne hit was sett,</L>
<L>And sythen herytykis done hit bett;</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="728">Pelagius and pope Iohn,</L>
<L>they dede hit Rere vp Anone,</L>
<L>And yave there-to grete pardoone,</L>
<L>for there lyethe many A seynt of grete Renowne,</L>
<L N="732">phylype and Iacobe in shryne,</L>
<L>Sent eugenie &thorn;e holy vyrgyne,</L>
<L>Seint sabasabyne, wrote wee fynde,</L>
<L>And the tabarde of thomas of Inde:</L>
<L N="736">An arme of seynt blase is there,</L>
<L>And odyr relykys many and sere.</L>
<L>two thowesande yere, yf &thorn;ou wolt crave,</L>
<L>Eche day there myght &thorn;ou have,</L>
<L N="740">And on eche Apostyllis day</L>
<L>this pardoon is dowbyld, I the saye.</L>
<L>At seynt bartylmewe &thorn;ou my&yogh;te have</L>
<L>A thowesande yere yf &thorn;ou wolte crave;</L>
<L N="744">there lyethe his bodye on &thorn;e hye Auter:</L>
<L>wele is hym that comythe there.</L>
<L>at seynt mary Rotounde</L>
<L>there is A chyrche fayre I-founde;</L>
<L N="748">there is wryttyn, I yowe saye,</L>
<L>In o sonday that is in maye;
<PB REF="00000219.tif" N="169"></L>
<L>whan the soneday is I-come,</L>
<L>there is full Remyssyone,</L>
<L N="752">And eche daye in the yere</L>
<L>grete pardon &thorn;ou myght have there:</L>
<L>Agrypa ded hit make</L>
<L>for sabillis &amp; neptuno-is sake;</L>
<L N="756">Modyrs they were of cursyd men,<MILESTONE N="163" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>And false fendis folowed hem.<NOTE PLACE="marg">[really Mars and Jupiter],</NOTE></L>
<L>he yave hit name of pantheon;</L>
<L>In all Rom&euml; was syche noone;</L>
<L N="760">A fygur they made of golde Reede,</L>
<L>More than god they gan hit drede;</L>
<L>'Neptune' clepyd hit was I-wys;</L>
<L>to leve there-one they were nat wysse;</L>
<L N="764">An hye on the tempyll hit satt,</L>
<L>And lokyde forthe lyke A katt,</L>
<L>vppon the Rooffe in an holle</L>
<L>hit brent as hell&euml; cole:</L>
<L N="768">vppon his hed A covert of brasse;</L>
<L>to seynt petyr blowen hit was</L>
<L>with A wynde of hell, I trowe,</L>
<L>for no man myght hit thedur throwe;</L>
<L N="772">there standythe [hit,] I tell thee,</L>
<L>by-fore the mynyster dor &thorn;ou myght hit see;</L>
<L>the Rofe is opyn there he stoode;</L>
<L>there stondythe, and do&thorn;e no goode.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="776">And the pope boneface</L>
<L>was full-fyllyd with goddis grace;</L>
<L>In hym selffe he was dismayed</L>
<L>that mannys soule was so betrayed:</L>
<L N="780">to the emperoure Iulius sone he came,</L>
<L>that was forso&thorn;e A wele goode man;</L>
<L>"that tempyll," he sayde, "graunt hit me,<NOTE PLACE="marg">[Phocas, A.D. 609.]</NOTE></L>
<L>I the praye for seynt charyte,</L>
<L N="784">that men clepe pantheon, I leve,</L>
<L>that mannys soule hit do&thorn;e greve."</L>
<L>he seyde, "take hit euery dele;
<PB REF="00000220.tif" N="170"></L>
<L>that &thorn;ou hit have, me lykythe wele."</L>
<L N="788">And the fyrst day of novembur,</L>
<L>pope boneface with hart&euml; tendyr</L>
<L>the pepull of Rome ded calle,</L>
<L>And bade assemble in his halle,<MILESTONE N="163b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="792">In pantheon all in-same,</L>
<L>for to chaunge &thorn;at ylk&euml; name</L>
<L>In honowre of oure ladye,</L>
<L>and all halowen &thorn;at bethe &thorn;er-bye;</L>
<L N="796">this was noster dame la Rounde,</L>
<L>In pantheon fyrste I-founde;</L>
<L>And sange hys mase &thorn;at ylk&euml; daye,</L>
<L>And yave grete pardone, I yowe saye,</L>
<L N="800">And comawndyd all crystyn men</L>
<L>that daye to halowe, for love of hem</L>
<L>that bethe in hevyn with swete Ihesus,</L>
<L>Night and day to praye for us.</L>
<L N="804">And on the morowe he be-hett also</L>
<L>that men shoulde to chyrch&euml; goo</L>
<L>to praye for hem that ded bee,</L>
<L>that cryste on hem have pyte,</L>
<L N="808">And one us whan wee dye;</L>
<L>Amen, saythe all for charyte.</L>
<L>At seynt mary transpedian</L>
<L>there been ij pyllurs made of stoone,</L>
<L N="812">to whiche petyr and poule bounden were</L>
<L>when th&eacute; levyd in eorth&euml; there.</L>
<L>there they stonde, I tell&euml; thee;</L>
<L>whan &thorn;ou Art there, &thorn;ou mayste hem see;</L>
<L N="816">Eche day, yf &thorn;ou comyste there,</L>
<L>foure hundyrd yer&euml; &thorn;ou haste there.</L>
<L>At seynt Speryte hospytalle,</L>
<L>there men mowe haue, gret and smalle,</L>
<L N="820">vij yere of pardoune,</L>
<L>the vij<SUP>te</SUP> parte of penaunce ondone.</L>
<L>At seynt Iamys vppon the flome</L>
<L>Be thre hundyrde yere of pardonne,
<PB REF="00000221.tif" N="171"></L>
<L N="824">And so many Lenttis moore</L>
<L>for-sothe ben I-grauntyd there.</L>
<L>Att seynt mary tryst-iuere<MILESTONE N="164" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>thowe shalt have sevyn yere:</L>
<L N="828">two wellis there bethe, I tell thee,</L>
<L>that sprynggythe oyle, there men may see,</L>
<L>that ylk nyght &thorn;at cryst was boore</L>
<L>to save man that was for-loore.</L>
<L N="832">At sesyle, the holy marter,</L>
<L>thowe myght have A C yere.</L>
<L>At seynt petyr and poullys preson</L>
<L>thowe myght have grete pardonne,</L>
<L N="836">two thowesande yere, I tell thee,</L>
<L>Eche day yf thowe there bee.</L>
<L>thorowe the vertu of her orysune</L>
<L>A well spronge there in prisune,</L>
<L N="840">with whiche water, baptysyd were</L>
<L>processe and martuman, crystis dere.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>At seynt mary la noue &thorn;ou myght haue</L>
<L>an hundyrde yere if &thorn;ou wolt craue.</L>
<L N="844">at the chirche of seynt Alext</L>
<L>there wee mowe have, moste &amp; leste,</L>
<L>two thowesande and ij C yere,</L>
<L>eche day yf &thorn;ou comyst there.</L>
<L N="848">At seynt cosme and Demiave</L>
<L>iij hundyrd yere &thorn;ou myght have.</L>
<L>At the chyrche of seynt eustace</L>
<L>there men myght fynde A wele fayre place;</L>
<L N="852">there lyethe he and his wyffe,</L>
<L>and his ij sonnes, with-owttyn stryffe,</L>
<L>two thowesande yere &thorn;ou myght have</L>
<L>eche Daye yf &thorn;ou wolte crave.</L>
<L N="856">nowe passe wee to &thorn;e saluator</L>
<L>to whome men dothe grete honowre.</L>
<L>A fygur of god &thorn;ou myght see,</L>
<L>his face, his crowne, I tell thee;</L>
<L N="860">there myght &thorn;ou have A M<SUP>l</SUP> yere;
<PB REF="00000222.tif" N="172"></L>
<L>Eche day yff thowe be there,</L>
<L>Syx hundred and xxx<SUP>ty</SUP> mo, I the tell,<MILESTONE N="164b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>for to Abate the peynys of hell.</L>
<L N="864">at seynt Sysely the holy marter,</L>
<L>there thowe myght haue A C yere.</L>
<L>the Mawdlene there, I tell thee,</L>
<L>whan &thorn;ou Art there &thorn;ou myght see.</L>
<L N="868">Be-sydes petre-Ad-vincula A chapell is</L>
<L>of A Saluator worshupte Iwys,</L>
<L>where he delyd his tresoure</L>
<L>to save holy chyrchis honoure:</L>
<L N="872">of pardon ij thowesande yere</L>
<L>thowe myght have whan &thorn;ou art there</L>
<L>At the chyrche of iiij Doctours fyne,</L>
<L>Ierome, gregory, Ambrose, &amp; Austyne,</L>
<L N="876">At eche chyrche yff &thorn;ou wylt craue<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. haue</NOTE></L>
<L>A thowesande yere, &thorn;ou<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. yf &thorn;ou</NOTE> myght hit haue.</L>
<L>At seynt lawrence in Damace</L>
<L>there shalt &thorn;ou fynde A feyre place:</L>
<L N="880">Eche day, yf thowe come there,</L>
<L>thowe myght have v C yere.</L>
<L>At seynt mary Rochelle</L>
<L>there is many greses, I wete wele;</L>
<L N="884">there is ij thowesande yere &amp; more</L>
<L>to hem that wole thyddyr goo.<NOTE PLACE="foot">For <I>fore</I> or <I>fare</I>.</NOTE></L>
<L>there is An Image, I vndyrstonde,</L>
<L>of oure ladye &thorn;at Lewke wrought with his honde,</L>
<L N="888">I-closed alle withe syluer clere,</L>
<L>I-payntted Abowte withe colours dere;</L>
<L>there dwellythe Frere menowrse,</L>
<L>And servyn owre ladye with honowrse.</L>
<L N="892">At seynt Mary Merle bethe dwellynge<NOTE PLACE="marg">[de' Miracoli?]</NOTE></L>
<L>Frere prechourse to Rede and synge:</L>
<L>Sykyrly there &thorn;ou myght have</L>
<L>A M<SUP>l</SUP> yere, and &thorn;ou hit crave.</L>
<L N="896">At seynt Andrewys holy chyrche sykyrly
<PB REF="00000223.tif" N="173"></L>
<L>Been yeerys grauntyd full fourty,<MILESTONE N="165" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>And seynt gregory purchased syche grace,</L>
<L>what man or woman is buryed in &thorn;at plase,</L>
<L N="900">yf he beleve in god &amp; holy chyrche also,</L>
<L>he shall not be dampned for nought &thorn;at he hathe doo,</L>
<L>But be saved frome the payne of hell:</L>
<L>this is the sothe that I the tell.</L>
<L N="904">yf &thorn;ou tryste no &thorn;yng to me,</L>
<L>on the chyrche-dore &thorn;ou mayst hit see.</L>
<L>pardone is there myche moore</L>
<L>than I have Reseyned<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>resigno</I>, I reveal, disclose.</NOTE> here byfore,</L>
<L N="908">And that I shall with all my myght</L>
<L>there-off wryte bo&thorn;e day &amp; nyght,</L>
<L>By gode that was of mary boore</L>
<L>to save mankynde &thorn;at was for-loore,</L>
<L N="912">Graunt vs parte of this pardoone,</L>
<L>And there-withe gyve us his benysone!<NOTE PLACE="end">[Follow: A Medecyne for the Pestylens, etc., The maner to kepe haukes, etc.]</NOTE></L>
<TRAILER>EXPLICIT &THORN;E STACIONS OF ROOME.
</TRAILER>

</LG>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 TYPE="poem"><PB REF="00000224.tif" N="174">
<HEAD>Gaude, flore Virginali.</HEAD>
<HEADNOTE><P>(<I>Lambeth MS.</I> 306, <I>leaf</I> 133.)</P></HEADNOTE>
<LG N="1" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(1)</HEAD>
<L><B>Gaude</B>, the flowre of virginyte,</L>
<L>In hevyn thow hast a principalite</L>
<L>Off worship and honowre;</L>
<L N="4">Thi blys is more in dignite</L>
<L>Then alle the sayntis that euer may be</L>
<L>Or aungelis in hevyn towre!</L>
<L><B>Gaude, flore virginali!</B></L>
</LG>
<LG N="2" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(2)</HEAD>
<L N="8"><B>Gaude</B>, goddys spouse so deere!</L>
<L>Was there neuer sonnye day so cleere</L>
<L>Nor of so grete lyght!</L>
<L>There myght neuer son shyne heere</L>
<L N="12">As thow fyllist heuyn empere</L>
<L>With bemys that ar so bryght!</L>
<L><B>Gaude, sponsa cara dei!</B></L>
</LG>
<LG N="3" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(3)</HEAD>
<L><B>Gaude</B>, vessel of vertue &amp; grace,</L>
<L N="16">I-Crowned quene in that place</L>
<L>Where thy sonne is kynge!</L>
<L>Angels alle in his presence</L>
<L>Ar vndyr thyn obedyence,</L>
<L N="20">And do the worshippynge!</L>
<L><B>Gaude, splendens vas virtutum!</B></L>
</LG>
<LG N="4" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(4)</HEAD>
<L><B>Gaude</B>, modyr and mayden fre,</L>
<L>Throw the bonde of charyte</L>
<L N="24">To god so holy and knytte,</L>
<L>That what so euer thi askyng be,</L>
<L>Alle the holy trynite</L>
<L>Ful goodly grauntyth the hitte.</L>
<L N="28"><B>Gaude, nexu caritatis!</B>
<PB REF="00000225.tif" N="175"></L>
</LG>
<LG N="5" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(5)</HEAD>
<L><B>Gaude</B>, frute of all&euml; flowres!</L>
<L>For who so euer the honowryth</L>
<L>With preyour nyght or day,</L>
<L N="32">The fadyr of heuyn, of his godhed</L>
<L>He graunt them to ther mede</L>
<L>The blysse that lastyth aye!</L>
<L><B>Gaude, mater miserorum!</B></L>
</LG>
<LG N="6" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(6)</HEAD>
<L N="36"><B>Gaude</B>, the modyr of cryst iesu,</L>
<L>So gracyous and ful of vertu,</L>
<L>That, for thi holynesse,</L>
<L>So highe arte nowe in dignite!</L>
<L N="40">Thowe sitteste next the trinite</L>
<L>In grete honowre and blysse.</L>
<L><B>Gaude</B>, virgo, mater Christi!</L>
</LG>
<LG N="7" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(7)</HEAD>
<L><B>Gaude</B>, mayden clene and pure,</L>
<L N="44">Euyr beynge secure and suere</L>
<L>That these yoies seuyn</L>
<L>Shalle neuer swage nor sesse,</L>
<L>But euermore endure and encresse</L>
<L N="48">While god regnyth in heuyn. Amen.</L>
<L><B>Gaude, virgo, mater pura!</B><NOTE PLACE="end">Scriptus Anno Domini 1508 per D. T. Mylle.</NOTE>
</L>
</LG>

</DIV2>
<DIV2 TYPE="poem"><PB REF="00000226.tif" N="176">
<HEAD>Regina Celi Letare.</HEAD>
<HEADNOTE><P>[<I>Lambeth MS.</I> 306, <I>leaf</I> 132, <I>back.</I>] [The thick letters mark the red ones of the MS.]</P></HEADNOTE>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L><B>Regina celi letare</B>. alleluya.</L>
<L><B>quia</B> quem <B>meruisti portare</B>. alleluya.</L>
<L><B>resurrexit sicut dixit</B>. alleluya.</L>
<L N="4"><B>ora</B> pro <B>nobis</B> deum. alleluya.</L>
</LG>
<P>In ista antiphona <B>alleluya</B> accipitur iiij<SUP>or</SUP> diuersis modis. Primum alleluia. lauda deum creatura. <B>Secun|dum</B>. salus. vita. lux. Tercium. saluum me fac deus. Quartum idem est. quod pater, et filius, et spiritus sanctus.</P>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L><B>Regina celi le - ta - re!</B></L>
<L>Quene of hevyn, make thou myrth!</L>
<L N="12"><B>alleluya!</B> lauda deum cr[e]atura!</L>
<L>And prayse god wyth alle thy myght!</L>
<L>quia quem <B>meruisti portare.</B></L>
<L>For of the. he toke his byrth.</L>
<L N="16"><B>alleluya.</B> salus vita lux.</L>
<L>That is, heele, lyfe, and lyght.</L>
<L><B>resurrexit, sicut dixit;</B></L>
<L>he rose from deth; so sayde he.</L>
<L N="20"><B>alleluya!</B> Saluum me fac deus!</L>
<L>Saue vs, god, in ned&euml; moste!</L>
<L><B>ora pro nobis deum!</B></L>
<L>Pra for vs the trynyte!</L>
<L N="24"><B>alleluya!</B> pater et filius et spiritus sanctus,</L>
<L>Fader, and sonne, and holy goste.
</L>
</LG>

</DIV2>
<DIV2 TYPE="poem"><PB REF="00000227.tif" N="177">
<HEAD>Quia Amore Langueo. (PART I.)</HEAD>
<HEAD>(THE VIRGIN'S COMPLAINT BECAUSE MAN'S SOUL IS WRAPT IN SIN.)</HEAD>
<HEADNOTE><P>[<I>Lambeth MS.</I> 853, <I>ab.</I> 1430 A.D., <I>page</I> 4.] [8 stanzas in eights, <I>abab bcbc</I>, except st. 1, <I>abab bcbd.</I>]</P></HEADNOTE>
<LG N="1" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(1)</HEAD>
<L>IN a tabernacle of a tour,</L>
<L>As y stood musynge on &thorn;e moone,</L>
<L>A crowned queene, moost of honour,</L>
<L N="4">Me &thorn;ou&yogh;te y si&yogh; sittinge in trone.</L>
<L>Sche made hir c&oacute;mpleynt bi hir oone,</L>
<L>For mannis soule is wrappid in synne:<NOTE PLACE="foot">The ryme should be in -o, as in the other stanzas.</NOTE></L>
<L>"Y may not leeue mankynde a-loone,</L>
<L N="8">Quia amore langueo.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="2" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(2)</HEAD>
<L><B>I</B> loke for loue of man, my bro&thorn;ir,<MILESTONE N="5" UNIT="page"></L>
<L>I am his avoket<NOTE PLACE="foot">Alterd by a later hand to 'advoket.'</NOTE> on euery wise,</L>
<L>I am his moder, y can noon o&thorn;ir;</L>
<L N="12">Whi schulde y my dere child dispise?</L>
<L>&para; &THORN;ou&yogh; he me wra&thorn;&thorn;e in diuerse wise,</L>
<L>&THORN;oru&yogh; freelte of fleisch be falle me fro,</L>
<L>&YOGH;it muste y rue til &thorn;at he rise,</L>
<L N="16">Quia amore langueo.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="3" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(3)</HEAD>
<L><B>I</B> abood &amp; abide with greet longynge,</L>
<L>I loue &amp; loke whanne man wole craue,</L>
<L>I pleyne me for pitee of pinynge;</L>
<L N="20">Wolde he aske merci, he schulde it haue;</L>
<L>Seie to me, soule, y schal &thorn;ee saue;
<PB REF="00000228.tif" N="178"></L>
<L>Bid me, child, &amp; y wole goo;</L>
<L>Praiedist me neuere, but y forgaue,</L>
<L N="24">Quia amore langueo.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="4" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(4)</HEAD>
<L>Moder of mercy y was for &thorn;ee made:</L>
<L>Who nedi&thorn; mercy but &thorn;ou a-loone?</L>
<L>To &yogh;eue grace &amp; merci y am more glade</L>
<L N="28">&THORN;an &thorn;ou to aske; whi nyst &thorn;ou noon?</L>
<L>&para; Whanne seide y nay? tel me to whom!<MILESTONE N="6" UNIT="page"></L>
<L>Neuere &yogh;it to freend ne foo!</L>
<L>Whanne &thorn;ou askist not, &thorn;an make y moon,</L>
<L N="32">Quia amore langueo.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="5" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(5)</HEAD>
<L><B>O</B> wrecche, in &thorn;is world y loke on &thorn;ee</L>
<L>Whanne y se &thorn;ee trespase day bi daye,</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; leccheri a&yogh;en my chastite,</L>
<L N="36">With pride a&yogh;en my meeke a-ray.</L>
<L>&para; My loue abidi&thorn; &thorn;ee; yra is a-way;</L>
<L>Mi loue &thorn;ee calli&thorn;, &amp; &thorn;ou stelist me fro;</L>
<L>&YOGH;it sue to me, synner, y &thorn;ee pray,</L>
<L N="40">Quia amore langueo!</L>
</LG>
<LG N="6" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(6)</HEAD>
<L>My sone was outlawid for &thorn;i synne,</L>
<L>His body was beten for &thorn;i trespase,</L>
<L>&YOGH;it pricki&thorn; it myn herte &thorn;at so ny&yogh; my kynne</L>
<L N="44">&THORN;at so schulde be disesid, a sone, a-las!</L>
<L>&para; Mi sone is &thorn;i fader, his moder y was,</L>
<L>He soukide my pappis; he loued &thorn;ee so,</L>
<L>He is deed for &thorn;ee; myn herte &thorn;ou has,</L>
<L N="48">Quia amore langueo.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="7" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(7)</HEAD>
<L>&para; My son&euml; deed&euml; for &thorn;i loue,<MILESTONE N="7" UNIT="page"></L>
<L>His herte was persid with a spere</L>
<L>To bringe &thorn;i soule to heuene a-boue,</L>
<L N="52">For &thorn;i loue so diede he here.
<PB REF="00000229.tif" N="179"></L>
<L>&para; &THORN;erfor &thorn;ou must be to me moost dere,</L>
<L>Si&thorn;en my son&euml; loued &thorn;ee so;</L>
<L>&THORN;ou praiest to me neuere but y &thorn;ee here,</L>
<L N="56">Quia amore langueo.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="8" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(8)</HEAD>
<L>My sone ha&thorn; grauntide me, for &thorn;i sake,</L>
<L>Euery merciful praier &thorn;at y wole haue;</L>
<L>For, he wole no veniaunce take</L>
<L N="60">If y aske mercy for &thorn;ee, but &thorn;at y schal haue.</L>
<L>&para; &THORN;erfor axe &thorn;ou merci, &amp; y schal &thorn;ee saue,</L>
<L>With pitee y rue vpon &thorn;ee so,</L>
<L>I longe for mercy &thorn;at &thorn;ou schuldist craue,</L>
<L N="64">Quia amore langueo."</L>
</LG>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 TYPE="poem">


<DIV3 TYPE="version"><PB REF="00000230.tif" N="180">
<HEAD>Quia Amore Langueo. (PART II.)</HEAD>
<HEAD>(OR CHRIST'S COMPLAINT FOR HIS SISTER, MAN'S SOUL.) </HEAD>
<HEADNOTE><P>[16 stanzas of eights, <I>abab bcbc</I>.]</P></HEADNOTE>
<HEAD><I>Lambeth MS. 853</I>.</HEAD>
<HEADNOTE><P>[Follows the last poem, seemingly as a continuation.]</P></HEADNOTE>
<LG N="1" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(1)</HEAD>
<L>IN a valey of &thorn;is restles mynde</L>
<L>I sou&yogh;te in mounteyne &amp; in myde,</L>
<L>Trustynge a trewe loue for to fynde.</L>
<L N="4">Vpon an hil &thorn;an y took hede;</L>
<L>&para; A voice y herde&mdash;&amp; neer y &yogh;ede&mdash;<MILESTONE N="8" UNIT="page"></L>
<L>In huge dolour complaynynge &thorn;o,</L>
<L>"Se, dere soule, how my sidis blede,</L>
<L N="8">Quia amore langueo."</L>
</LG>
<LG N="2" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(2)</HEAD>
<L>Vpon &thorn;is hil y fond a tree;</L>
<L>Vndir &thorn;e tree a man sittynge,</L>
<L>From heed to foot woundid was he,</L>
<L N="12">His hert&euml; blood y si&yogh; bledinge:&mdash;</L>
<L>&para; A semeli man to ben a king,</L>
<L>A graciouse face to loken vnto;&mdash;</L>
<L>I askide whi he had peynynge,</L>
<L N="16">He seide "quia amore langueo."</L>
</LG>
<LG N="3" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(3)</HEAD>
<L><B>I</B> am true loue, &thorn;at fals was neuere;</L>
<L>Mi sistyr, mannis soule, y loued hir &thorn;us;</L>
<L>Bi-cause we wolde in no wise disceuere,</L>
<L N="20">I lefte my kyngdom glorious.</L>
<L>&para; I purueide for hir a paleis precious;</L>
<L>Sche fleyth, y flolowe, y sou&yogh;te hir so,</L>
<L>I suffride &thorn;is peyn&euml; piteuous</L>
<L N="24">Quia amore langueo.
<PB REF="00000232.tif" N="182"></L>
</LG>
<LG N="4" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(4)</HEAD>
<L>My fair spouse, &amp; my lou&euml; bri&yogh;t,<MILESTONE N="9" UNIT="page"></L>
<L>I saued hir fro betynge, &amp; sche ha&thorn; me bet;</L>
<L>I clo&thorn;id hir in grace &amp; heuenli li&yogh;t,</L>
<L N="28">&thorn;is bloodi scherte sche ha&thorn; on me sette,</L>
<L>&para; For longynge of loue &yogh;it wolde y not lett;</L>
<L>Swet&euml; strokis ax&euml; &thorn;ese; lo,</L>
<L>I haue loued hir euere as y hir het,</L>
<L N="32">Quia amore langueo.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="5" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(5)</HEAD>
<L><B>I</B> crowned hir wi&thorn; blis, &amp; sche me with &thorn;orn;</L>
<L>I ledde hir to chaumbir, &amp; sche me to die;</L>
<L>I brou&yogh;te hir to worschipe, &amp; sche me to scorn;</L>
<L N="36">I dide her reuerence, &amp; sche me vilonye.</L>
<L>&para; To loue &thorn;at loue&thorn;, is no maistrie;</L>
<L>Hir hate made neuere my loue hir foo,</L>
<L>Ax&euml; me no questioun whi,</L>
<L N="40">Quia amore langueo.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="6" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(6)</HEAD>
<L>Loke vnto myn hondis, man!</L>
<L>&thorn;ese gloues were &yogh;oue me whan y hir sou&yogh;te;</L>
<L>&thorn;ei ben not white, but rede &amp; wan,</L>
<L N="44">On broudrid with blood my spouse hem brou&yogh;te.</L>
<L>&para; &THORN;ei wole not of, y loose hem nou&yogh;te,<MILESTONE N="10" UNIT="page"></L>
<L>I wowe hir with hem where-euere sche go;</L>
<L>&THORN;ese hondis for hir so freendli fou&yogh;te,</L>
<L N="48">Quia amore langueo.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="7" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(7)</HEAD>
<L>Merueille nou&yogh;te, man, &thorn;ou&yogh; y sitte stille;</L>
<L>Se, loue ha&thorn; sched me wondir streite,</L>
<L>Boclid my feet, as was hir wille,</L>
<L N="52">With scharp naile, lo, &thorn;ou maiste waite.</L>
<L>&para; In my loue was neuere desaite,</L>
<L>Alle myn humours y haue opened hir to,</L>
<L>&THORN;ere my bodi ha&thorn; maad hir hertis baite,</L>
<L N="56">Quia amore langueo.
<PB REF="00000234.tif" N="184"></L>
</LG>
<LG N="8" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(8)</HEAD>
<L>In my side y haue made hir neste;</L>
<L>Loke in! how weet a wounde is heere,</L>
<L>&THORN;is is hir chaumbir, heere schal sche reste,</L>
<L N="60">&THORN;at sche &amp; y may slepe in fere.</L>
<L>&para; Heere may sche waische, if ony fil&thorn;e were,</L>
<L>Heere is sete for al hir woo;</L>
<L>Come whanne sche wole, sche schal haue chere,</L>
<L N="64">Quia amore langueo.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="9" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(9)</HEAD>
<L><B>I</B> wole abide til sche be redy,<MILESTONE N="11" UNIT="page"></L>
<L>I wole hir sue if sche seie nay;</L>
<L>If sche be richilees, y wole be gredi,</L>
<L N="68">And if sche be daungerus, y wole hir praie.</L>
<L>&para; If she wepe, &thorn;at hide y ne may,</L>
<L>Myn armes her hired to clippe hir me to;</L>
<L>Crie oonys; y come: now, soule, asay,</L>
<L N="72">Quia amore langueo.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="10" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(10)</HEAD>
<L><B>I</B> sitte on &thorn;is hil, for to se fer,</L>
<L>I loke into &thorn;e valey, my spouse to se;</L>
<L>Now renne&thorn; sche a-wayward, &yogh;it come sche me neer,</L>
<L N="76">For out of my si&yogh;te may sche not flee.</L>
<L>&para; Summe wayte hir prai to make hir to flee,</L>
<L>I renne bifore, and fleme hir foo;</L>
<L>Returne my spouse a&yogh;en to me,</L>
<L N="80">Quia amore langueo.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="11" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(11)</HEAD>
<L>Fair loue, lete us go pleye!</L>
<L>Applis ben ripe in my gardayne,</L>
<L>I schal &thorn;ee clo&thorn;e in a newe aray,</L>
<L N="84">&THORN;i mete schal be mylk, hony, &amp; wiyn.</L>
<L>&para; Fair loue, lete us go digne,<MILESTONE N="12" UNIT="page"></L>
<L>&THORN;i sustynaunce is in my crippe, lo!</L>
<L>Tarie &thorn;ou not, my faire spouse myne,</L>
<L N="88">Quia amore langueo.
<PB REF="00000236.tif" N="186"></L>
</LG>
<LG N="12" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(12)</HEAD>
<L>Iff &thorn;ou be foul, y schal &thorn;ee make clene;</L>
<L>If &thorn;ou be sijk, y schal &thorn;ee hele;</L>
<L>If &thorn;ou moorne ou&yogh;t, y schal &thorn;ee meene;</L>
<L N="92">Whi wolt &thorn;ou not, faire loue, with me dele?</L>
<L>&para; Foundist &thorn;ou euere loue so leel?</L>
<L>What woldist &thorn;ou, spouse, &thorn;at y schulde do?</L>
<L>I may not vnkyndeli &thorn;ee appele,</L>
<L N="96">Quia amore langueo.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="13" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(13)</HEAD>
<L>What schal y do with my fair spouse,</L>
<L>But a-bide hir of my gentilnes</L>
<L>Til &thorn;at sche loke out of hir house</L>
<L N="100">Of fleischli affeccioun? loue myn sche is.</L>
<L>&para; Hir bed is maade, hir bolstir is blis,</L>
<L>Hir chaumbir is chosen; is &thorn;er non moo.</L>
<L>Loke out on me at &thorn;e wyndow of kyndenes,</L>
<L N="104">Quia amore langueo.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="14" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(14)</HEAD>
<L>My loue is in hir chaumbir: holde &yogh;oure pees,<MILESTONE N="13" UNIT="page"></L>
<L>Make &yogh;e no noise, but lete hir slepe:</L>
<L>My babe, y wolde not were in disese,</L>
<L N="108">I may not heere my dere child wepe.</L>
<L>&para; With my pap y schal hir kepe.</L>
<L>Ne merueille &yogh;e not &thorn;ou&yogh; y tende hir to;</L>
<L>&THORN;is hole in my side had neuere be so depe,</L>
<L N="112">But quia amore langueo.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="15" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(15)</HEAD>
<L>Longe &thorn;ou for loue neuere so hi&yogh;,</L>
<L>My loue is more &thorn;an &thorn;in may be;</L>
<L>&THORN;ou wepist, &thorn;ou gladist, y sitte &thorn;ee bi,</L>
<L N="116">&YOGH;it woldist &thorn;ou oonys, leef, loke vn-to me!</L>
<L>&para; Schulde y alwey fed&euml; &thorn;ee</L>
<L>With children mete? nay, loue, not so!</L>
<L>I wole preue &thorn;i loue wi&thorn; aduersite,</L>
<L N="120">Quia amore langueo.
<PB REF="00000238.tif" N="188"></L>
</LG>
<LG N="16" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(16)</HEAD>
<L>Wexe not wery, myn own&euml; wijf!</L>
<L>What mede is it to lyue euere in coumfort?</L>
<L>In tribulacioun y regne moore rijf</L>
<L N="124">Ofttymes &thorn;an in disport.</L>
<L>&para; In wele &amp; in woo y am ay to supporte;<MILESTONE N="14" UNIT="page"></L>
<L>Myn own&euml; wijf, go not me fro!</L>
<L>&THORN;i meede is markid whan &thorn;ou art mort,</L>
<L N="128">Quia amore langueo.</L>
</LG>
</DIV3>
<DIV3 TYPE="version">

<PB REF="00000231.tif" N="181">
<HEAD>Quia Amore Langueo.</HEAD>
<HEAD>(<I>From the Song of Solomon.</I>)</HEAD>
<HEADNOTE><P> [16 stanzas of eights, <I>abab bcbc.</I>]</P></HEADNOTE>
<HEAD>[MS. Univ. Lib. Camb. Hh. 4. 12, leaf 41<I>b.</I> Handwriting of the latter half of the 15th century.]</HEAD>
<LG N="1" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(1)</HEAD>
<L>IN the vaile of restles mynd</L>
<L>I sowght in mownteyn &amp; in mede,</L>
<L>trustyng a treulofe for to fynd:</L>
<L N="4">vpon an hyll / than toke I hede;</L>
<L>a voise I herd / (and nere I yede)</L>
<L>in gret dolour complaynyng tho,</L>
<L>"see, der&euml; soule, my syd&euml;s blede</L>
<L N="8"><I>Quia amore langueo.</I>"<NOTE PLACE="foot">Solomon's Song, ii. 5 and v. 8 (Vulgate).</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG N="2" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(2)</HEAD>
<L>&para; Vpon thys mownt I fand a tree;</L>
<L>vndir thys tree / a man sittyng;</L>
<L>from hede to fote / wowndyd was he,</L>
<L N="12">hys hert blode I saw bledyng;</L>
<L>A semely man / to be a kyng,</L>
<L>A graciose face / to loke vnto.</L>
<L>I askyd hym / how he had paynyng,</L>
<L N="16">he said, "<I>Quia amore langueo.</I>"</L>
</LG>
<LG N="3" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(3)</HEAD>
<L>&para; I am treulove / that fals was neuer:</L>
<L>my sistur, mannys soule, I loued hyr thus;<NOTE PLACE="foot">Sol. Song, iv. 9.</NOTE></L>
<L>By-cause I wold on no wyse disseuere,</L>
<L N="20">I left my kyngdome gloriouse;</L>
<L>I purueyd hyr a place full preciouse;</L>
<L>she flytt / I folowyd / I luffed her soo;</L>
<L>that I suffred thes payn&egrave;s piteuouse</L>
<L N="24"><I>Quia amore langueo.</I>
<PB REF="00000233.tif" N="183"></L>
</LG>
<LG N="4" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(4)</HEAD>
<L>&para; My faire love and my spous&euml; bryght,<MILESTONE N="42" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>I saued hyr fro betyng / and she hath me bett;</L>
<L>I clothed hyr in grace / and heuenly lyght,</L>
<L N="28">this blody surcote she hath on me sett;</L>
<L>for langyng love, I will not lett,</L>
<L>swet&euml; strokys be thes, loo;</L>
<L>I haf loued euer<NOTE PLACE="marg">[MS. ouer]</NOTE> als I hett,</L>
<L N="32"><I>Quia amore langueo.</I></L>
</LG>
<LG N="5" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(5)</HEAD>
<L>&para; I crownyd hyr with blysse / and she me with thorne,</L>
<L>I led hyr to chambre / and she me to dye;</L>
<L>I browght hyr to worship / and she me to skorne,</L>
<L N="36">I dyd hyr reuerence / and she me velanye.</L>
<L>to love that loueth / is no maistrye,</L>
<L>hyr hate made neuer my love hyr foo;</L>
<L>ask than no moo questions whye,</L>
<L N="40">but <I>Quia amore langueo.</I></L>
</LG>
<LG N="6" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(6)</HEAD>
<L>&para; loke vnto myn handys, man!</L>
<L>thes gloues were geuen me / whan I hyr sowght;</L>
<L>they be nat white / but rede and wan,</L>
<L N="44">embrodred with blode / my spouse them bowght;</L>
<L>they wyll not of / I lefe them nowght,</L>
<L>I wowe hyr / with them / where euer she goo;</L>
<L>thes handes full frendly for hyr fowght,</L>
<L N="48"><I>Quia amore langueo.</I></L>
</LG>
<LG N="7" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(7)</HEAD>
<L>&para; Maruell not, man, / thof I sitt styll,<MILESTONE N="42b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>my love hath shod me / wondyr strayte;</L>
<L>she boklyd my fete / as was hyr wyll</L>
<L N="52">with sharp nailes / well thow maist waite!</L>
<L>in my love was neuer dissaite,</L>
<L>for all my membres I haf opynd hyr to;</L>
<L>my body I made hyr hertys baite,</L>
<L N="56"><I>Quia amore langueo.</I>
<PB REF="00000235.tif" N="185"></L>
</LG>
<LG N="8" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(8)</HEAD>
<L>&para; In my syde / I haf made hyr nest,</L>
<L>loke in me / how wyde a wound is here!</L>
<L>this is hyr chambre / here shall she rest,</L>
<L N="60">that she and I may slepe in fere.</L>
<L>here may she wasshe / if any filth were;</L>
<L>here is socour for all hyr woo;</L>
<L>cum if she will / she shall haf chere,</L>
<L N="64"><I>Quia amore langueo.</I></L>
</LG>
<LG N="9" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(9)</HEAD>
<L>&para; I will abide / till she be redy,</L>
<L>I will to hyr send / or she sey nay;</L>
<L>If she be rechelesse / I will be redy,</L>
<L N="68">If she be dawngerouse / I will hyr pray.</L>
<L>If she do wepe / than byd I nay;</L>
<L>myn armes ben spred to clypp hyr to;</L>
<L>crye onys, "I cum!" / now, soule, assaye!</L>
<L N="72"><I>Qui amore langueo.</I></L>
</LG>
<LG N="10" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(10)</HEAD>
<L>&para; I sitt on an hille / for to se farre,<MILESTONE N="43" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>I loke to the vayle / my spouse I see;</L>
<L>now rynne she awayward, now cummyth she narre,</L>
<L N="76">yet fro myn eye syght she may nat be;</L>
<L>sum waite<NOTE PLACE="marg">[MS. "make," corrected in margin to "waite."]</NOTE> ther pray / to make hyr flee,</L>
<L>I rynne tofore / to chastise hyr foo;<NOTE PLACE="marg">[Satan]</NOTE></L>
<L>recouer my soule / agayne to me,</L>
<L N="80"><I>Quia amore langueo.</I></L>
</LG>
<LG N="11" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(11)</HEAD>
<L>&para; My swete spouse / will we goo play;</L>
<L>apples ben rype in my gardine;<NOTE PLACE="marg">[Sol. Song, iv. 16.]</NOTE></L>
<L>I shall clothe the in new array,</L>
<L N="84">thy mete shall be / mylk / honye / &amp; wyne;<NOTE PLACE="marg">[Sol. Song, v. 1.]</NOTE></L>
<L>now, dere soule, latt us go dyne,</L>
<L>thy sustenance is in my skrypp, loo!</L>
<L>tary not now / fayre spous&euml; myne,</L>
<L N="88"><I>Quia amore langueo.</I>
<PB REF="00000237.tif" N="187"></L>
</LG>
<LG N="12" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(12)</HEAD>
<L>&para; yf thow be fowle / I shall make [thee] clene,</L>
<L>if thow be seke, I shall the hele;</L>
<L>yf thow owght morne / I shall be-mene,</L>
<L N="92">spouse, why will thow nowght with me dele?</L>
<L>thow fowndyst neuer / love so lele;</L>
<L>what wilt thow, sowle / that I shall do?</L>
<L>I may / of vnkyndnes the appele,</L>
<L N="96"><I>Quia amore langueo.</I></L>
</LG>
<LG N="13" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(13)</HEAD>
<L>What shall I do now with my spouse?<MILESTONE N="43b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>abyde I will hyre iantilnesse,</L>
<L>wold she loke onys / owt of hyr howse</L>
<L N="100">of flesshely affeccions / and vnclennesse;</L>
<L>hyr bed is made / hyr bolstar is in blysse,</L>
<L>hyr chambre is chosen, / suche ar no moo;</L>
<L>loke owt / at the wyndows of kyndnesse,<NOTE PLACE="marg">[Sol. Song, ii. 9.]</NOTE></L>
<L N="104"><I>Quia amore langueo.</I></L>
</LG>
<LG N="14" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(14)</HEAD>
<L>&para; Long and love thow neuer so hygh,</L>
<L>yit is my love more / than thyn may be;</L>
<L>thow gladdyst / thou wepist / I sitt the bygh,</L>
<L N="108">yit myght thow, spouse / loke onys at me!</L>
<L>spouse, shuld I alway fed&euml; the</L>
<L>with childys mete? / nay, love, / nat so!</L>
<L>I pray the, love, with aduersite,</L>
<L N="112"><I>Quia amore langueo.</I></L>
</LG>
<LG N="15" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(15)</HEAD>
<L>&para; My spouse is in chambre, hald &yogh;owre pease!<NOTE PLACE="marg">[Sol. Song, ii. 7 and viii. 4.]</NOTE></L>
<L>make no noyse / but lat hyr slepe;</L>
<L>my babe shall sofre noo disease,</L>
<L N="116">I may not here my dere childe wepe,</L>
<L>for with my pappe I shall hyr kepe;</L>
<L>no wondyr / thowgh I tend hyr to,</L>
<L>thys hoole in my side had neuer ben so depe,</L>
<L N="120">but <I>Quia amore langueo.</I></L>
</LG>
<LG N="16" TYPE="stanza">

<PB REF="00000239.tif" N="189">
<HEAD>(16)</HEAD>
<L>&para; Wax not wery, myn owne dere wyfe,<MILESTONE N="44" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>what mede is aye to lyffe in comfort?</L>
<L>for in tribulacion, I ryn more ryfe</L>
<L N="124">ofter tymes / than in disport;</L>
<L>In welth, in woo, euer I support;</L>
<L>than, der&euml; soule, go neuer me fro!</L>
<L>thy mede is markyd, whan thow art mort,</L>
<L N="128">in blysse; <I>Quia amore langueo</I>.</L>
<TRAILER>FINIT.</TRAILER>
</LG>
</DIV3>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 TYPE="poem">


<DIV3 TYPE="version"><PB REF="00000240.tif" N="190">
<HEAD>The Complaynt of Criste.</HEAD>
<HEAD>[<I>Lambeth MS.</I> 306, <I>ab.</I> 1460-70 A.D., <I>leaf</I> 145, <I>written in</I> 8-<I>line stanzas, though to l.</I> 135 <I>it is in</I> 12-<I>line ones.</I>]</HEAD>
<HEAD>(<I>Christ's First Complaint against Man.</I>)</HEAD>
<LG N="1" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(1)</HEAD>
<L>This is the comepleynt off god</L>
<L>Fro man to man that he ha&thorn;e bou&yogh;te,</L>
<L>And thus<NOTE PLACE="marg">[MS. thus thus]</NOTE> he seyethe to here Ateynt,</L>
<L N="4">"Myne owne pepull, what haue yee wrought</L>
<L>that thowe to me Art so feynt,</L>
<L>And I thy love so sore have sought?</L>
<L>In thyn Answer no thyng &thorn;ou peynte</L>
<L N="8">to me, By-cause I knewe &thorn;y &thorn;ought.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="2" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(2)</HEAD>
<L>"Haue I nat Do alle that me oughte?</L>
<L>have I lefft ony thynge be-hynde?</L>
<L>why wrathyst &thorn;ou me? I greve &thorn;e nought;</L>
<L N="12">why arte thowe to thy Frende onkynde?</L>
<L>I shewed th&egrave; Love; and that was seene</L>
<L>whane I made th&egrave; lyke to me;</L>
<L>On erthe my werkis bothe quyk &amp; grene,</L>
<L N="16">I put hem vndyr in thy poweste.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="3" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(3)</HEAD>
<L>"And frome pharos (that was so keene)</L>
<L>Of egypt I delyuerd thee,</L>
<L>I kyllyd hym and his by-deene.</L>
<L N="20">the Red see for the in to flye,</L>
<L>I bad that hit drye should&euml; bee;</L>
<L>I seassid the water and the wynde,<MILESTONE N="145b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>I lede the ouer, and made &thorn;e Free:</L>
<L N="24">why art thowe to thy freende onkynde?
<PB REF="00000242.tif" N="192"></L>
</LG>
<LG N="4" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(4)</HEAD>
<L>"And xl yere in wyldurnesse,</L>
<L>with angels food&euml; I th&egrave; Feed;</L>
<L>Into the londe of grete Ryches,</L>
<L N="28">to schewe th&egrave; love, there I th&egrave; led.</L>
<L>to do th&egrave; more of kyndenes,</L>
<L>I toke &thorn;&egrave; kyndely, and nothyng dred,</L>
<L>I lefft my<NOTE PLACE="marg">[MS. my my]</NOTE> myght, ant toke mekenes,</L>
<L N="32">And my harte bloode for th&egrave; I bled.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="5" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(5)</HEAD>
<L>"Thy soule to save, this lyffe I led,</L>
<L>I bounde my selffe, &thorn;e to onbynde,</L>
<L>thus with my woo thy nedis I spede;</L>
<L N="36">why art thowe to thy frende onkynde?</L>
<L>for the in paradyse I ordeynnyd A plase;</L>
<L>full Rych&euml; was thyn &eacute;nfeftment;</L>
<L>howe myght &thorn;ou me &thorn;us dispyse ony more,</L>
<L N="40">than to breke my comaundement,</L>
</LG>
<LG N="6" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(6)</HEAD>
<L>"And to synne In vij Maner wyse,</L>
<L>and to myne Enemy so soone Assent?</L>
<L>he put the Downe, thowe myghttyst nat Ryse;</L>
<L N="44">thy strenkythe, thy wytt, A-way is went!</L>
<L>poore, naked, shamed, and shent,</L>
<L>that Frendeshype myghttest &thorn;ou nat fynde,</L>
<L>But me that on the Roode was Rent;</L>
<L N="48">why art &thorn;ou to thy freende onkynde?</L>
</LG>
<LG N="7" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(7)</HEAD>
<L>"Man, I love the! whome Lovyst thowe?</L>
<L>I am &thorn;y frende; why wolt &thorn;ou feyne?</L>
<L>I for-yave, and &thorn;u me slewe:</L>
<L N="52">ho hath departyd oure lowe A tweyne?</L>
<L>Turne to me! by-thenke the howe</L>
<L>thowe haste go mys! come home Agayne!</L>
<L>And thowe shalt be as welcome nowe</L>
<L N="56">As he that synne neuer ded fayne.
<PB REF="00000244.tif" N="194"></L>
</LG>
<LG N="8" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(8)</HEAD>
<L>"Wayte what ded Mary Mawdeleyne,<MILESTONE N="146" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>And what I seyd to thomas of Inde;</L>
<L>I graunte the blysse, why lovys &thorn;ou peyne?</L>
<L N="60">why art &thorn;ou to thy Frende onkynde?</L>
<L>of A Frende the fyrst&euml; preffe</L>
<L>Is love, &amp; drede, &amp; nought displease.</L>
<L>there was neuer thyng to me so leffe</L>
<L N="64">As mankynde that nought may peasse.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="9" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(9)</HEAD>
<L>"For the I suffyrde grete repreffe:</L>
<L>In hyghe hevyn thy soule to easse</L>
<L>I was on-hanged as A theeffe;</L>
<L N="68">thowe dedest the deede, I had &thorn;e disease.</L>
<L>thowe canst me neydur thank nor pleasse,</L>
<L>Ne do goode deede, ne haue me in mynde;</L>
<L>I am thy leche in thy Disease,</L>
<L N="72">thowe cannyst me nowdur thanke nor pleasse,<NOTE PLACE="marg">[These lines are repeated by mis|take.]</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG N="10" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(10)</HEAD>
<L>"Ne do goode deede, we have in mynde,<NOTE PLACE="marg">[These lines are repeated by mis|take.]</NOTE></L>
<L>I am thy leche in thy diseasse,<NOTE PLACE="marg">[These lines are repeated by mis|take.]</NOTE></L>
<L>Why art thowe to &thorn;y Frende on-kynde?</L>
<L N="76">vnkynde,&mdash;for thowe kyllyd thy lorde,</L>
<L>And euery day &thorn;ou wounedyst hym newe,</L>
<L>for thowghe wee ben brought to oone Acorde,</L>
<L>In couunaunt, wreche, &thorn;ou art one-trewe,</L>
<L N="80">And Redy also to Resorte,</L>
</LG>
<LG N="11" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(11)</HEAD>
<L>"To folowe vyces and sle vertu;</L>
<L>All Rybawdry thowe canste reporte,</L>
<L>And Day by daye hit to Renewe;</L>
<L N="84"><NOTE PLACE="inline">[<I>No gap in MS.</I>]</NOTE></L>
<L>And redy also to pursewe</L>
<L>the poore peepull with sleyghttis blynde;</L>
<L>thowe shalt owte of this worlde remeve;</L>
<L N="88">why art thowe to thy Frende onkynde?
<PB REF="00000246.tif" N="196"></L>
</LG>
<LG N="12" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(12)</HEAD>
<L>"The devyll me tempttyd neuer but thrye,</L>
<L>But &thorn;ou me temptyst frome day to daye</L>
<L>whythe cursyng affter vengeaunce to crye,</L>
<L N="92">to styr my wrathe &thorn;ou wylt assaye,</L>
<L>thowe woledyst, and ony woulde me by,</L>
<L>Wele worsse than Iudas me be-traye;<MILESTONE N="146b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>at my werke &thorn;ou haste e[n]vye;</L>
<L N="96">that wele ne woo is to &thorn;y paye.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="13" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(13)</HEAD>
<L>"And thowe me myghttyst, as I &thorn;e maye,</L>
<L>wele byttyrly thowe woldyst me bynde;</L>
<L>I for-yave, and &thorn;ou seyest nay,</L>
<L N="100">why arte thowe to &thorn;e frende onkynde?</L>
<L>I have bought thy love full dere:</L>
<L>Onekynde! why for-sakis &thorn;ou myne?</L>
<L>I yave the myn hart &amp; bloode in Fere</L>
<L N="104">Onkynde! why wolt &thorn;ou nat yeve me &thorn;yne?</L>
</LG>
<LG N="14" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(14)</HEAD>
<L>"Thowe art on-kynd&euml; homagere,</L>
<L>for with my Fo &thorn;ou makest me fyne;</L>
<L>thowe servyst me with febull chere;</L>
<L N="108">to hym thyn hart wolte fully enclyne.</L>
<L>And I am lorde of blysse and pyne,</L>
<L>and alle thyng may I lousse &amp; bynde,</L>
<L>Ayenst the wole I my yatis tynde</L>
<L N="112">All whyle &thorn;ou arte to &thorn;y frende onkynde.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="15" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(15)</HEAD>
<L>"Man! by-thenk the what &thorn;ou Arte,</L>
<L>fro whens &thorn;ou come, &amp; wheder &thorn;ou mone,</L>
<L>for thow&yogh;e &thorn;ou to-day be in hele &amp; quarte,</L>
<L N="116">to-morowe I may put &thorn;e A-doune.</L>
<L>lett mylde mekenes melt in &thorn;yn hart,</L>
<L>that &thorn;ou Rewe on my passyone,</L>
<L>with my woundis depe and smarte,</L>
<L N="120">with crosse, naylys, spere, &amp; crowne.
<PB REF="00000248.tif" N="198"></L>
</LG>
<LG N="16" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(16)</HEAD>
<L>"Let god and discressione</L>
<L>thy wyll holy vp to me sende:</L>
<L>thowe hast wyttys &amp; Reasone,</L>
<L N="124">And yff &thorn;ou wylt, &thorn;ou mayst be kynde."</L>
<L><STAGE>(<I>Man's First Answer.</I>)</STAGE> &para; "A! lorde, A-yeenst the wee wole nat plette,</L>
<L>for as &thorn;ou wouledyst, hit is, and was,</L>
<L>And wee have deservyd hell&euml; hete,</L>
<L N="128">But nowe wee yelde us to thy grace.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="17" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(17)</HEAD>
<L>"Wee wole boowe, and thowe shalt bete,<MILESTONE N="147" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>And Chastice us, lorde, for oure trespase,</L>
<L>And lett mercy for vs entrete</L>
<L N="132">that neuer no feondis oure soweles chase.</L>
<L>A! blysfull lady, fayre of face,</L>
<L>helpe! for wee been fer be-hynde;</L>
<L>that wee nowe with weepyng crye 'alas,</L>
<L N="136">for that wee were to oure frende onkynde.' "</L>
<TRAILER>EXPLICIT [in a later hand. The Manuscript goes right on with the continuation, really a separate Poem.]</TRAILER>
</LG>
<LG N="18" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(18)(<I>Christ's Second Complaint.</I>)</HEAD>
<L>Thus oure gracius god, prince of pyte,</L>
<L>whos myght, whose goodenes, neuer by-gan,</L>
<L>at whose wyll all by-hovythe to bee,</L>
<L N="140">Compleynnyng hym thus to synfull man:</L>
<L>"Myne owne pepull, Answer me,</L>
<L>Excuse thy selffe yf &thorn;ou can:</L>
<L>what haue I trespassyd vnto the?</L>
<L N="144">thowe for-sakyst me, &thorn;ou servyst Sathan.
<PB REF="00000250.tif" N="200"></L>
</LG>
<LG N="19" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(19)</HEAD>
<L>"Mane! suche A loue to the I hade!</L>
<L>this worllde in vj dayes whan I wrought,</L>
<L>thau was the last thyng that I made</L>
<L N="148">By-cause I woulde &thorn;ou wantyd nought.</L>
<L>what thyng the myght helpe or glade,</L>
<L><NOTE PLACE="inline">2 <I>lines wanting in MS</I>. . . . .</NOTE></L>
<L>. . . . .</L>
<L N="152">to thy be-hoffe alle forthe is brought.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="20" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(20)</HEAD>
<L>"More-ouer I yave the suffraunt[e]</L>
<L>that alle Bestis shoulde bowe &thorn;e vntyll;</L>
<L>I made the also lyke to me,</L>
<L>And yaffe the connyng<NOTE PLACE="marg">[MS. <I>comyng</I>]</NOTE> of Fre wyll,</L>
<L N="157">me to serve, that thowe myght see,</L>
<L>god chese the goode, and leve the yll.</L>
<L>I ax no thyng Agayne of the</L>
<L N="160">But be my<NOTE PLACE="marg">[MS. <I>thy</I>]</NOTE> servaunt, as hit is skyll.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="21" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(21)</HEAD>
<L>"But vnto this, takys thowe no tent</L>
<L>thowe wyrchyst A-waye full onkyndely,</L>
<L>Aloone one-lefully that love is lent;</L>
<L N="164">thy hart be-holdythe nat hevyn one hye,</L>
<L>For alle the goodenesse I have the sente,</L>
<L>The lyst nat onys to saye gramercye.<MILESTONE N="147b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>In tyme comyng lest &thorn;ou Repent,</L>
<L N="168">Man! make Amendis or &thorn;ou dye."</L>
</LG>
<LG N="22" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(22)(<I>Man's Second Answer.</I>)</HEAD>
<L><B>A</B> crysten soule conseyvyd with synne</L>
<L>Resceyvyd in consyence &thorn;is compleynt;</L>
<L>he fyll downe flatt with dulfull synne,</L>
<L N="172">And seyd, "lorde, mercy, souerayne seynt!</L>
<L>I, moste vnkynde wreche of mankynne,</L>
<L>I knowelege I am thy traytur atteynt;</L>
<L>this wykkyd lyffe that I lyve in,</L>
<L N="176">I may hit nat frome &thorn;y knowyng glent:
<PB REF="00000252.tif" N="202"></L>
</LG>
<LG N="23" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(23)</HEAD>
<L>"I want wordis and Also wytte,</L>
<L>of thy kyndenes to carpe A clawse;</L>
<L>All that I haue, &thorn;ou gave me hytt</L>
<L N="180">Of thy goodenesse with-owten cause;</L>
<L>thowe I have grevyd the, and do yeett,</L>
<L>thowe thy benefittis nought with-drawes;</L>
<L>I haue deserved to haue hell pytt,</L>
<L N="184">So haue I levyd Ayenst thy lawes.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="24" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(24)</HEAD>
<L>"but, lorde, &thorn;ou knowest mannys febullnes,</L>
<L>howe Frell he is, and ha&thorn;e been aye,</L>
<L>for thow&yogh;e the sowle have thy lyknesse,</L>
<L N="188">Man is but lothesum eorthe and claye,</L>
<L>In synne conseyued, and wrechchydnes,</L>
<L>And to the soule Rebell Alleweye.</L>
<L>furst A man growys As A gras,</L>
<L N="192">And Afftyr-warde welkythe as flowre or hay</L>
</LG>
<LG N="25" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(25)</HEAD>
<L>"sithe man is than so frell A thyng,</L>
<L>And thy power so grete in kynde,</L>
<L>this worlde, man, aye twynkelynge</L>
<L N="196">thowe maye distroye, noone may defende,</L>
<L>with that god mercy wole meenge,</L>
<L>and to my soule gostely &thorn;ou sende;</L>
<L>Sore me Repentythe my mys-levyng;</L>
<L N="200">Mercy! lorde! I wole A-mende."</L>
</LG>
<LG N="26" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(26)(<I>Christ's Third Complaint.</I>)</HEAD>
<L>"Man, I sende the bodyly helthe<MILESTONE N="148" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>that thowe shouldyst spend hit in my servyce,</L>
<L>fayrenes and Also feturs fele:</L>
<L N="204">But, man, what doste &thorn;ou with all this?</L>
<L>thowe doest the delytys of &thorn;e devyll;</L>
<L>thy delyte is to me to dispyse;</L>
<L>thowe levyst A lecherous lyfe one-lelle;</L>
<L N="208">frome yere to yere &thorn;at lyst nat to A-Ryse.
<PB REF="00000254.tif" N="204"></L>
</LG>
<LG N="27" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(27)</HEAD>
<L>"Thowe stodyest affter more Araye,</L>
<L>And makest gret cost on clothyng,</L>
<L>to make the semely, as who shoulde saye</L>
<L N="212">thowe cowdest Amend[e] thy makyng.</L>
<L>thowe cannyst Dyght the Rychely day by day</L>
<L>to steere the peopull to synnyng,</L>
<L>thy wrechchyd wyll &thorn;ou folowyst alle daye;</L>
<L N="216">what ende syn hathe, thowe thenkyst nowght.<NOTE PLACE="marg">[The rhyme requires <I>no thyng.</I>]</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG N="28" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(28)</HEAD>
<L>"In noyes tyme, by-cause of synne&mdash;</L>
<L>for lechery In Especyall&mdash;</L>
<L>what vengeaunce cam &thorn;an to mankyn!</L>
<L N="220">Save viij persowenys they were drowenyd alle.</L>
<L>Of sodome and gomer the ought to meene,</L>
<L>howe I made fyre and brymston falle</L>
<L>frome heven on men that bade there-in;</L>
<L N="224">for synne were distroyed bo&thorn;e grete &amp; smalle.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="29" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(29)</HEAD>
<L>"Man, wenyst thowe my myght be lesse</L>
<L>than hit was than, or ellis I</L>
<L>hathe nat as mych&euml; wykkydnesse</L>
<L N="228">As whan I smote so spiteousely?</L>
<L>But yett I wyll thy fawtes Redresse,</L>
<L>thoowe I nowe spar&euml; for my mercy;</L>
<L>Man, thenke vppon my Ryghtwysnes,</L>
<L N="232">And make A-mendis or that &thorn;ou dye."</L>
</LG>
<LG N="30" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(30)</HEAD>
<HEAD>(<I>Man's Third Answer.</I>)</HEAD>
<L>"<B>I</B> wott wele, lorde, &thorn;ou Ryghtfull arte,</L>
<L>And &thorn;at synne mut be ponysshed need;</L>
<L>But o thyng holdythe hope in myn harte,</L>
<L N="236">that mercye passithe my mysdede;</L>
<L>I know&euml; wele I may nat with-starte,<MILESTONE N="148b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>I have so doone, I ought to dreede.</L>
<L>With beaute and with bodyly quarte</L>
<L N="240">to serv&euml; the I toke noone heede.
<PB REF="00000256.tif" N="206"></L>
</LG>
<LG N="31" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(31)</HEAD>
<L>"I haue mysspendyd my yonge age</L>
<L>In synne, and wantonnehed also,</L>
<L>I have been slowe and lovyd outerage;</L>
<L N="244">A gloton, A lechur, I was bothe to.</L>
<L>I am worthy noon odyr wage</L>
<L>But for to dwell in eendeles woo;</L>
<L>Alas! why haue I been so outerage,</L>
<L N="248">And servyd the fende &thorn;at was my Foo?</L>
</LG>
<LG N="32" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(32)</HEAD>
<L>&para; "But, lorde, in holy wrytt Rede wee</L>
<L>that &thorn;ou for-sakyst no wrechchyd wyght</L>
<L>that leuythe his syn and turnythe to the,</L>
<L N="252">And I to the turne have tyght.</L>
<L>ffull prowde and Rebell haue I been,</L>
<L>But I wele meke me to my myght,</L>
<L>frome hens forwarde I purpose me</L>
<L N="256">A-yenst myn own&euml; flesche to fyght.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="33" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(33)</HEAD>
<L>"My Flesche to fell&euml; I wole faste,</L>
<L>My louys to travell I wole sende,</L>
<L>And thorowe thy grace I am nat A-gast,</L>
<L N="260">what sorowe or sykenes to me &thorn;ou sende,</L>
<L>to suffyr whyle my lyffe wole laste;</L>
<L>for vttyrly to this Entent,</L>
<L>to ponysche &thorn;at I haue trespassed,</L>
<L N="264">Mercy, Ihesu, I wole Amende."</L>
</LG>
<LG N="34" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(34)</HEAD>
<HEAD>(<I>Christ's Fourth Complaint.</I>)</HEAD>
<L>"Man, I haue sende &thorn;e syluer &amp; gollde,</L>
<L>And alle the welthe within &thorn;y woone,</L>
<L>to susteyne the and thyn houssolde,</L>
<L N="268">And with the Resedewe many one</L>
<L>tho myghttyst &thorn;ou haue yonge and olde</L>
<L>that been diseassyd and woo-by-goone;</L>
<L>My servauntis suffyr hunger and colde,<MILESTONE N="149" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="272">Releffe of the yeet haue I noone.
<PB REF="00000258.tif" N="208"></L>
</LG>
<LG N="35" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(35)</HEAD>
<L>"yff &thorn;ou yeve for my love A ferthyng,</L>
<L>thowe doest hit with An hevy harte;</L>
<L>In almys dar &thorn;ou Do nothyng</L>
<L N="276">for Drede &thorn;ou fall&euml; in pouerte,</L>
<L>In wordis and in vayne spekyng,</L>
<L>what-euer &thorn;ou wastyst, mery &thorn;ou arte;</L>
<L>Of suche I wole haue Rekenyng;</L>
<L N="280">A Domys day &thorn;ou shalt not starte.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="36" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(36)</HEAD>
<L>"than shalt &thorn;ou yeve A-counte full strayte,</L>
<L>howe thowe come by thy goode, eche dele,</L>
<L>whedur with trouth&euml; or Dyssayte,</L>
<L N="284">And howe &thorn;ou spendyst hit, evyll or wele.</L>
<L>Noone odyr grace than afftyr wayte:</L>
<L>As &thorn;ou haste wrought, so shalt &thorn;ou fele.</L>
<L>what shall than prophyte &thorn;i gowne purfylled?</L>
<L N="288">Poundes and markes of the I peele.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="37" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(37)</HEAD>
<L>"A clene conscyence shall &thorn;at daye</L>
<L>More prophyte be, &amp; more sett bye,</L>
<L>than all thy muke and alle &thorn;y moneye</L>
<L N="292">that euer was, or shall be vndyr &thorn;e skye.</L>
<L>than wole nat help&euml; plete nor playe,</L>
<L>for ar Right-wole than Deme shall I;</L>
<L>And there-for, whyl&euml; &thorn;at &thorn;ou may,</L>
<L N="296">Make Amendis or &thorn;ou dye."</L>
</LG>
<LG N="38" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(38)</HEAD>
<HEAD>(<I>Man's Fourth Answer.</I>)</HEAD>
<L>"I wote wele, lorde, frome yere to yere</L>
<L>full gretely grevyd the, I have;</L>
<L>that I wete wele; nor, &thorn;y mercy were,</L>
<L N="300">My modyrs wombe hade be my grave.</L>
<L>for what profyttythe my levyng here</L>
<L>But &thorn;ou wolt affter-warde me save?</L>
<L>But Ihesu, as &thorn;ou boughttest me dere,</L>
<L N="304">Leve nat my soul&euml; in hell&euml; Cave!
<PB REF="00000260.tif" N="210"></L>
</LG>
<LG N="39" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(39)</HEAD>
<L>"My waste expensis I wyll with-drawe,<MILESTONE N="149b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>Nowe, sertayne, 'waste,' wele colyd &thorn;ei be,</L>
<L>for &thorn;ou were spent my boste to blowe,</L>
<L N="308">My name to bere by londe and ssee.</L>
<L>wele I wott me thought nat trewe</L>
<L>with many A man of my cuntre;</L>
<L>yff they me mett, they me nat knewe,</L>
<L N="312">Ne neuer yett harden speke of me.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="40" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(40)</HEAD>
<L>"fondely haue I wrought &amp; wyrchyd on wyse;</L>
<L>I myght haue goton mych&euml; meede</L>
<L>had I spent hit in goddis seruyce,</L>
<L N="316">On men diseisyd and almys deede.</L>
<L>But thorowe thy grace I wyll A-Ryse,</L>
<L>for, haue I and myne, oure bare mede,</L>
<L>with the Remnaunt, lorde, at &thorn;y devyse,</L>
<L N="320">the poore, the nakyd, to clo&thorn;e &amp; ffeede.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="41" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(41)</HEAD>
<L>"Syk men that lyen in goddis bondis,</L>
<L>they haue no syluer for to spende,</L>
<L>And prisonners bounden with fete and hondis,</L>
<L N="324">Offt for to vesyte I wyll hem Amende:</L>
<L>what I see howe hit with hem stondis,</L>
<L>Suche as I haue, I shall hem fynde;</L>
<L>But, lorde, lett &thorn;y worke be &thorn;y bondis;</L>
<L N="328">A, mercy, Ihesu, I wyll Amende!"</L>
</LG>
<LG N="42" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(42)</HEAD>
<HEAD>(<I>Christ's Fifth Complaint.</I>)</HEAD>
<L>"Man, yff thowe wylt Amendis make,</L>
<L>Do thyn Almes with thyne owne goode,</L>
<L>And wayte &thorn;ou wyrk&euml; no man wrake,</L>
<L N="332">to venge Anodyr manys goode.</L>
<L>yff thowe ontrewly frome one take,</L>
<L>And there-with fynde xl. her goode;</L>
<L>Suche sacrefysis I for-saake,</L>
<L N="336">they been to me as sowre as soote.
<PB REF="00000262.tif" N="212"></L>
</LG>
<LG N="43" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(43)</HEAD>
<L>"the poore peopull &thorn;ou doest opresse</L>
<L>with flyghttis &amp; wylys many also:</L>
<L>thowe makyst chyrches, and syng messes,<MILESTONE N="150" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="340">thowe Amendyst wayes, men on to go;</L>
<L>and some men ban the, &amp; some men blesse:</L>
<L>Whedur shall I here of theese twoo?</L>
<L>yff &thorn;ou wolt haue grace as &thorn;ou thenkis,</L>
<L N="344">lett falsnes be Flemyd the froo.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="44" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(44)</HEAD>
<L>"the mothes that thy clothys etys,</L>
<L>and &thorn;ou lettest poore men go bare,</L>
<L>thy drynkis soweren, &thorn;ou mouledest metis</L>
<L N="348">where-with the febull myght wele fare.</L>
<L>thy Rustes &thorn;at thy syluer ffreete,</L>
<L>thy goodis that evyll goton are,</L>
<L>they cryen vppon the vengeaunce grete,</L>
<L N="352">there for to spyll, yeet I &thorn;e spare.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="45" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(45)</HEAD>
<L>"with-holdyn hem A-yenst the Ryght,</L>
<L>thoow&yogh;e thy servaunttis vppon &thorn;e crye;</L>
<L>And, man, offtymes &thorn;ou hast me hyght</L>
<L N="356">thowe woulde Amende, &amp; leve folye.</L>
<L>thowe spekyst soore by day and nyght,</L>
<L>thowe brekyst couinaunt contenually;</L>
<L N="359">yett is me lothe with the to fyght;</L>
<L>yett make Amendis, man, or &thorn;ou dye."<NOTE PLACE="marg">[See note on p. 214]</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG N="46" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(46)</HEAD>
<HEAD>(<I>Man's Fifth Answer.</I>)</HEAD>
<L>"Swete lorde, I may nat Ayenst &thorn;e saye,<NOTE PLACE="marg">[on leaf 152]</NOTE></L>
<L>I have nat holden &thorn;at I the heete:</L>
<L>I greve the gretely every daye,</L>
<L N="364">I do nat as I am in dett,</L>
<L>I woulde do wele, but wele-A-waye,</L>
<L>With Enemyes I am euer by-sett;</L>
<L>whan my soule woulde faynest &thorn;e paye,</L>
<L N="368">My flesche is the fyrst &thorn;at wole it lett.
<PB REF="00000264.tif" N="214"></L>
</LG>
<LG N="47" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(47)</HEAD>
<L>"Euer the fatter that I [hit] Feede,</L>
<L>Euer the Fressher hit is my foo,</L>
<L>yett must wee bere hit Abowt&euml; nede,</L>
<L N="372">But febull hit is, hit wole me sloo.</L>
<L>the worlde, the fende, my batayle byde</L>
<L>Some tyme with wele, some tyme with woo;</L>
<L>whate may I do with a wykkyd weede,</L>
<L N="376">to fy&yogh;te A-yeen my enemyes soo?</L>
</LG>
<LG N="48" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(48)</HEAD>
<L>"whan I in-force me wother wyles,</L>
<L>And thynke I woulde lyve a trewe lyffe</L>
<L>and for-sooke all batayllis &amp; gylys,</L>
<L N="380">the worlde byddythe me batell blyve,</L>
<L>And, but I wole vse wrenchis wylys,</L>
<L N="382">to comyn wyse as I shall nat stryve,"<NOTE PLACE="end">[MS. ends, and is incomplete.] ["The Stacyons of Rome" follows on leaf 152, back.] [After line 360 the MS. runs on with line 383, p. 216, and transposes Man's Fifth Answer, ll. 361-382, to the end, p. 224. I fetch it back to its right place above.&mdash;F. J. F.]</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG N="49" TYPE="stanza">
<PB REF="00000266.tif" N="216">
<HEAD>(49)</HEAD>
<HEAD>(<I>Man's Sixth Answer.</I>)</HEAD>
<L N="383">"Swete Ihesu, answer I [ne] can,</L>
<L>But oft I crye mercy with hart stable;</L>
<L>Alas for woo! why is man</L>
<L N="386">wele woorse than beste onreson&aacute;ble?</L>
<L>All bestis, sithe this worllde by-gan,</L>
<L>In kyndely wyrchyng be dur&aacute;ble,</L>
<L>Save onely I, off wyttys wanne,</L>
<L N="390">that wofull many dedis dampn&aacute;ble.
<PB REF="00000268.tif" N="218"></L>
</LG>
<LG N="50" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(50)</HEAD>
<L>"I, man, was made to knowe my maker,</L>
<L>And to love hym ouer alle thyng;</L>
<L>And I, A wreche, was neuer maker</L>
<L N="394">to cache kynde knowyng of my kynge;<MILESTONE N="150b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>to tryfyllis have I be tent-taker.</L>
<L>A songe for sorowe wele may I synge,</L>
<L>for hade I of syn be for-saker,</L>
<L N="398">of cryst shoulde I have hade knowynge.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="51" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(51)</HEAD>
<L>"My gostely than blysefull off duste,</L>
<L>Curssyd covetyse hathe so blyndedyd me,</L>
<L>they been shotyn with ffleschely luste,</L>
<L N="402">than hevenly thyngis may I noone see.</L>
<L>But, lorde, thow&yogh;e I have been on[i]est,</L>
<L>thorowe helpe of thy Benyngnyte</L>
<L>I hope to Rube A-waye the Ruste,</L>
<L N="406">with penaunce, frome my gostely syhte.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="52" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(52)</HEAD>
<L>"And where that I haue A-fore this</L>
<L>My worledly synnys spente,</L>
<L>frome hens forwarde my purpose is</L>
<L N="410">to lerne thy lawe to my lyvys ende.</L>
<L>thy x comaund&euml;mentis I-wys,</L>
<L>hem for to kepe I wyll me bende,</L>
<L>And there as I haue doone A-mys,</L>
<L N="414">Mercy, Ihesu! I wyll Amende."</L>
</LG>
<LG N="53" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(53)</HEAD>
<HEAD>(<I>Christ's Seventh Complaint.</I>)</HEAD>
<L>"Man, my mercy, yf &thorn;ou it mende,</L>
<L>I have the hit shewed in many wyse</L>
<L>Sythen the tyme that &thorn;ou fyrst synned</L>
<L N="418">Ayenst myne hest in paradyse.</L>
<L>In hell preson when &thorn;ou were pynyd</L>
<L>for doyng of the develys devyse,</L>
<L>owte of thy teene for to be tenyd,</L>
<L N="422">Mercy and love &thorn;e holpe or this.
<PB REF="00000270.tif" N="220"></L>
</LG>
<LG N="54" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(54)</HEAD>
<L>"Mercy was thyn advocate cheffe</L>
<L>that I for the tooke Flesche &amp; bloode;</L>
<L>loue made the to me so leffe,</L>
<L N="426">that I for the was Rente on Roode;</L>
<L>I suffyrde dethe to chaunge &thorn;y greffe,</L>
<L>And In-to hell than doune I yeede;</L>
<L>I brought &thorn;e to preeffe to the blysse:</L>
<L N="430">Man! I haue been thy frende full goode.<MILESTONE N="151" UNIT="folio"></L>
</LG>
<LG N="55" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(55)</HEAD>
<L>"I be-gan poore, th&eacute; Ryche to make;</L>
<L>to make th&eacute; whyte, I was made Rede;</L>
<L>my sorowe, my syknes, made th&eacute; to slake,</L>
<L N="434">My hunger booke the blysfull brede.</L>
<L>I bonde my selffe, &thorn;y bondis I braake;</L>
<L>to gett thy lyffe, I suffyrd dede;</L>
<L>what shoulde I do more for thy saake?</L>
<L N="438">to hele thy foote, hurt was my hede.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="56" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(56)</HEAD>
<L>"yff &thorn;ou thynk I myght more do</L>
<L>for thy saake, saye, I am Redy</L>
<L>to dye A-yeen, yff neede were there-too:</L>
<L N="442">Suche loue, man, to the haue I.</L>
<L>I hyght the myrthe &amp; Ioy&euml;s moo,</L>
<L>But &thorn;ou Art thy moste Enemy,</L>
<L>for nought that I do but &thorn;ou wylt so;</L>
<L N="446">Man! make Amendis or thowe dye."</L>
</LG>
<LG N="57" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(57)</HEAD>
<HEAD>(<I>Man's Seventh Answer.</I>)</HEAD>
<L>"Lorde, whan I thynke on &thorn;y pouerte,</L>
<L>and how wylfull &thorn;ou were and fayne;<NOTE PLACE="marg">[Lines 449 and 448 are transposed, and 450a repeated wrongly.]</NOTE>&mdash;</L>
<L>to sle my syn, &thorn;ou were slayne<NOTE PLACE="marg">[Lines 449 and 448 are transposed, and 450a repeated wrongly.]</NOTE>&mdash;</L>
<L N="450">to suffyr for me woundis smarte;</L>
<L N="450a">And howe wylfull &thorn;ou were and fayne;</L>
<L>harder than Iren is my harte</L>
<L>that hathe no pyte of thy payne!</L>
<L>Euer the kynder to me &thorn;ou arte,</L>
<L N="454">the more vnkynder I am A-gayne.
<PB REF="00000272.tif" N="222"></L>
</LG>
<LG N="58" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(58)</HEAD>
<L>"Why wouledyst &thorn;ou, lorde, be slayne for me?</L>
<L>than Am I thyne Enemye moste vnhende,</L>
<L>Sithen no man hathe more charyte</L>
<L N="458">than deethe to suffyr for his Frende?</L>
<L>what skyll is &thorn;ou shouledyst slayne bee,</L>
<L>Sythen I made &thorn;e thrall to &thorn;e Fende?</L>
<L>I trespassyd, lorde, why smottis &thorn;ou nat me?</L>
<L N="462">Nowe, blessyd be &thorn;ou with-owttyn eende!</L>
</LG>
<LG N="59" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(59)</HEAD>
<L>"I see wele, lorde, that &thorn;ou lovest us<MILESTONE N="151b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>for oure profyte, &amp; nought for yeve;<NOTE PLACE="marg">[pyne]</NOTE></L>
<L>for what were &thorn;ou, ne were Ihesus,</L>
<L N="466">thoughe all wee were in eendeles payne.</L>
<L>Alas, wee been so vysyous,</L>
<L>And so onkyndely frome hyr declyne,</L>
<L>that is oure god so grac&iuml;us,</L>
<L N="470">And is so lothe, mannys soule to tyne.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="60" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(60)</HEAD>
<L>"But, swete lorde, as &thorn;ou haste bygoone,</L>
<L>so lett thy mercy forthe extende;</L>
<L>Put thy crosse and thy passyon</L>
<L N="474">By-twene my werkis, they ought to be brent,</L>
<L>And thy dome that I may nat shoone,</L>
<L>that bondis of hell can me nat hende.</L>
<L>Who but the fadur shoulde helpe &thorn;e soone?</L>
<L N="478">Mercy, Ihesus! I wyll Amende."</L>
</LG>
<LG N="61" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(61)</HEAD>
<HEAD>(<I>Christ's Eighth Complaint.</I>)</HEAD>
<L>"Man, yff &thorn;ou wolte my mercy gete,</L>
<L>thorowe my passyon of grete vertu,</L>
<L N="481">why lovyst nat &thorn;ou me for to bete?</L>
<L>Eche day on crosse &thorn;ou doest me newe</L>
<L>with deedly syn, at morne, at mete,</L>
<L>thowe turmentis me on-trewe,</L>
<L>And namely, with thyne othis grete,</L>
<L N="486">to swere &thorn;ou wolte nat me eschewe
<PB REF="00000274.tif" N="224"></L>
</LG>
<LG N="62" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(62)</HEAD>
<L>"No lym on me, man, &thorn;ou for-beryste:</L>
<L>why doyst &thorn;ou evyll Ayenst goode?</L>
<L>By my soule thowe offt-tyme sweryst,</L>
<L N="490">by my body, and by my bloode;</L>
<L>with thy tunge me all to-teryst,</L>
<L>whan &thorn;ou arte wro&thorn;e &amp; wel ny woode;</L>
<L>Man, with thy onkyndnes more me derest</L>
<L N="494">than they that rent me on &thorn;e Roode.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="63" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(63)</HEAD>
<L>"thowe haste more pyte vppon &thorn;y too</L>
<L>yff hit be hurt, and lytyll bleede,</L>
<L>than euer &thorn;ou haddyst for all &thorn;e woo</L>
<L N="498">that euer I Suffyrde for &thorn;y mysdeede.</L>
<L>Whan &thorn;ou arte tought, than &thorn;ou shalt woo<MILESTONE N="152" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>of sweryng, but yff hit were neede:</L>
<L>thowe scorenest hem than seyne &thorn;e soo,</L>
<L N="502">thowe takest to my heste no kepe.<NOTE PLACE="marg">[heede]</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG N="64" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(64)</HEAD>
<L>"Lowde lesyngis on me &thorn;ou makyst,</L>
<L>Some tyme to wynne An halpenye,</L>
<L>what tyme to wytnes &thorn;ou me takyste,</L>
<L N="506">And yeet the for-sweryst &thorn;e wyttyngly.</L>
<L>Byyng and syllyng, &thorn;ou nat for-sakyst;</L>
<L>bothe veyne &amp; wronge &thorn;ou sweryst wronge;</L>
<L>whan &thorn;ou doest thus, there bale &thorn;ou bakeste;</L>
<L N="510">Man! make Amendis or thowe dye."<NOTE PLACE="end">[<I>See note on p. 214.</I>]</NOTE></L>
</LG>
</DIV3>
<DIV3 TYPE="version">

<PB REF="00000241.tif" N="191">
<HEAD>Goddis owne complaynt.</HEAD>
<HEAD>"WHI ART THOU TO THI FREEND VNKINDE?"</HEAD>
<HEADNOTE><P>[<I>Lambeth MS.</I> 853, <I>ab.</I> 1430 A.D., <I>page</I> 81, <I>written without breaks.</I>] </P></HEADNOTE>
<LG N="1" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(1)</HEAD>
<HEAD>(<I>Christ's First Complaint against Man.</I>)</HEAD>
<L>This is goddis owne complaynt</L>
<L>To euery man &thorn;at he ha&thorn; bou&yogh;t,</L>
<L>And &thorn;us he sei&thorn; to hem ataynt,</L>
<L N="4">"Myne own&euml; peple, what han &yogh;e wrou&yogh;t,</L>
<L>&para; &THORN;ou &thorn;at to me art so faynt,</L>
<L>And y &thorn;i loue so fer haue sou&yogh;t?</L>
<L>In &thorn;ine answere no &thorn;ing &thorn;ou paynt</L>
<L N="8">To me; for whi, y knowe &thorn;i &thorn;ou&yogh;t.</L>
<L>&para; Haue y not doon al &thorn;at me ou&yogh;t?</L>
<L>Haue y left ony &thorn;yng bihynde?</L>
<L>Whi wra&thorn;&thorn;ist &thorn;ou me? y greue &thorn;ee nou&yogh;t;</L>
<L N="12">Whi art &thorn;ou to &thorn;i freend vnkinde?</L>
</LG>
<LG N="2" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(2)</HEAD>
<L>I schewid &thorn;ee loue, &amp; &thorn;at was sene</L>
<L>Whanne y made &thorn;ee lijk to me;</L>
<L>On er&thorn;e my werkis <MILESTONE N="82" UNIT="page">bo&thorn;e quycke &amp; grene,</L>
<L N="16">I putte hem vndir in &thorn;i poste.</L>
<L>And fro farao&mdash;&thorn;at was so kene&mdash;</L>
<L>Of egipt y delyuered &thorn;ee,</L>
<L>I killid him &amp; hise bidene.</L>
<L N="20">&THORN;e reed see atwo to flee</L>
<L>&para; I bad, &thorn;at drie it schuld&euml; be;</L>
<L>I ceessid &thorn;e watir &amp; &thorn;e wynde,</L>
<L>I ledde &thorn;e ouer, &amp; made &thorn;ee free:</L>
<L N="24">Whi art &thorn;ou to &thorn;i freend vnkinde?
<PB REF="00000243.tif" N="193"></L>
</LG>
<LG N="3" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(3)</HEAD>
<L>And fourti &yogh;eer in wildirnes</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; aungelis fod&euml; y &thorn;ee fedde;</L>
<L>Into &thorn;e lond of greet richesse,</L>
<L N="28">To schewe &thorn;e lou&euml;, y &thorn;ee ledde.</L>
<L>&para; To do &thorn;e more of kynd&euml;nes</L>
<L>I took &thorn;i kinde, and no&thorn;ing dredde,</L>
<L>I lefte my my&yogh;t, &amp; tooke meekenes;</L>
<L N="32">Myn hert&euml; blood for &thorn;ee y bleed.</L>
<L>&para; Thi soule to saue, &thorn;is lijf y ledde;</L>
<L>I boond my silf, &thorn;ee to vnbinde;</L>
<L>&THORN;us with my wo &thorn;i nedis I spedde;</L>
<L N="36">Whi art &thorn;ou to &thorn;i freend vnkinde?<MILESTONE N="83" UNIT="page"></L>
</LG>
<LG N="4" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(4)</HEAD>
<L>For &thorn;ee y ordeyned paradijs;</L>
<L>Ful riche was &thorn;in enfeffement;</L>
<L>How my&yogh;tist &thorn;ou me ony more dispise,</L>
<L N="40">&THORN;an to breke my c&oacute;maundement,</L>
<L>&para; And synne in seuene maner of wise,</L>
<L>And to myn enemy so soone assent?</L>
<L>He putte &thorn;ee doun, &thorn;ou my&yogh;tist not rise;</L>
<L N="44">&THORN;i streng&thorn;e, &thorn;i witt, awei is went!</L>
<L>&para; Pore, nakid, schamed, &amp; schent,</L>
<L>&THORN;at frendschip my&yogh;tist &thorn;ou noon fynde</L>
<L>But me, &thorn;at on &thorn;e roode was rent;</L>
<L N="48">Whi art &thorn;ou to &thorn;i freend vnkynde?</L>
</LG>
<LG N="5" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(5)</HEAD>
<L>O Man, y loue &thorn;ee! whom louest &thorn;ou?</L>
<L>I am &thorn;i freend; whi wolt &thorn;ou feyne?</L>
<L>I for-&yogh;af, &amp; &thorn;ou me slou&yogh;:</L>
<L N="52">Who ha&thorn; departide oure loue a tweyne?</L>
<L>&para; Turne<MILESTONE N="84" UNIT="page">to me! bi&thorn;inke &thorn;ee how</L>
<L>&THORN;ou hast goon mys! come hoom ageyne!</L>
<L>And &thorn;ou schalt be as weel-come now</L>
<L N="56">As he that synne neuere dide steyne.
<PB REF="00000245.tif" N="195"></L>
<L>&para; Waite what y dide to marie maudeleyne,</L>
<L>And what y seide to thomas of ynde;</L>
<L>I graunte &thorn;ee blis, whi lovest &thorn;ou peyne?</L>
<L N="60">Whi art &thorn;ou to &thorn;i freend vnkinde?</L>
</LG>
<LG N="6" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(6)</HEAD>
<L>Of a freend the first[&euml;] preef</L>
<L>Is loue wi&thorn; drede, &amp; nou&yogh;t displese.</L>
<L>&THORN;ere was neuere &thorn;ing to me so leef</L>
<L N="64">As mankinde &thorn;at nou&yogh;t may pese.</L>
<L>&para; For &thorn;ee y suffride greet repreef:</L>
<L>In hi&yogh; heuene, &thorn;i soule to ceese,</L>
<L>Y was an-hangid as a &thorn;eef;</L>
<L N="68">&THORN;ou dedist &thorn;e dede, y hadde &thorn;e disese.</L>
<L>&para; &THORN;ou canst me neuere &thorn;anke ne please,</L>
<L>Ne do no good dede to haue me in mynde;</L>
<L>Y am &thorn;i leche<MILESTONE N="85" UNIT="page"> in &thorn;i disese,</L>
<L N="72">Whi art &thorn;ou to &thorn;i freend vnkinde?</L>
</LG>
<LG N="7" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(7)</HEAD>
<L><B>O</B> vnkinde! for &thorn;ou haste slayn &thorn;i lord,</L>
<L>And euery day &thorn;ou woundist me newe,</L>
<L>For &thorn;ou&yogh; we ben brou&yogh;t to oon acoord,</L>
<L N="76">In couenaunt, wrecche, &thorn;ou art vntrewe,</L>
<L>&para; And redy also to resorte</L>
<L>To folewe vicis &amp; flee vertu;</L>
<L>Al ribaudie &thorn;ou canst reporte,&mdash;</L>
<L N="80">Woo is him &thorn;at &thorn;i wra&thorn;&thorn;e may not eschewe!&mdash;</L>
<L>&para; And redi also to pursue</L>
<L>&THORN;e poore peple with slei&yogh;tis blynde.</L>
<L>&THORN;ou schalt out of &thorn;is world remewe,</L>
<L N="84">Bi-cause &thorn;ou art to &thorn;i freend vnkinde.
<PB REF="00000247.tif" N="197"></L>
</LG>
<LG N="8" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(8)</HEAD>
<L>&THORN;e deuel me temptide neuere but &thorn;rie;</L>
<L>But &thorn;ou me temptist from day to day</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; cursynge, aftir venieaunce doo&thorn; crie;</L>
<L N="88">To stire mi wra&thorn;&thorn;e &thorn;ou wolt a-saye;</L>
<L>&para; &THORN;ou woldist, &amp; ony wolde me bie,<MILESTONE N="86" UNIT="page"></L>
<L>Weel worse &thorn;an iudas me bitraie;</L>
<L>At my werk &thorn;ou hast enuye,</L>
<L N="92">&THORN;at weel ne woo may &thorn;ee noon paye.</L>
<L>&para; For &amp; &thorn;ou ouer me my&yogh;tist, as y ouer &thorn;ee may,</L>
<L>Weel bittirli &thorn;ou woldist me bynde:</L>
<L>I for&yogh;af, &amp; &thorn;ou seiest naye;</L>
<L N="96">&THORN;us y am freend, &amp; &thorn;ou vnkynde.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="9" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(9)</HEAD>
<L><B>I</B> haue bou&yogh;t &thorn;i loue ful dere:</L>
<L>Vnkinde! whi forsakist &thorn;ou myn?</L>
<L>I &yogh;af &thorn;ee myn herte &amp; blood in fere;</L>
<L N="100">Vnkinde! whi nyl &thorn;ou &yogh;eue me &thorn;in?</L>
<L>&para; &THORN;ou art an vnkynde omagere,</L>
<L>For with my foo &thorn;ou makist &thorn;i fyn;</L>
<L>&THORN;ou seruest me with febil chere;</L>
<L N="104">To him &thorn;in herte wolt hooli enclyne.</L>
<L>&para; And y am lord of blis &amp; pyne,</L>
<L>And al &thorn;ing may y lose<MILESTONE N="87" UNIT="page"> &amp; bynde,</L>
<L>A&yogh;en &thorn;ee wole y my &yogh;atis tyne,</L>
<L N="108">Al &thorn;e while &thorn;ou art to &thorn;i freend vnkynde.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="10" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(10)</HEAD>
<L>Man! bi&thorn;inke &thorn;ee what &thorn;ou art,</L>
<L>From whens &thorn;ou come, and whidir &thorn;ou art boun!</L>
<L>For &thorn;ou&yogh; &thorn;ou to-day be in hele &amp; qwart,</L>
<L N="112">To-morewe y may putte &thorn;ee doun.</L>
<L>&para; Lete mylde &amp; meckenes melte in &thorn;in herte,</L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;ou rue on my pass&iuml;oun,</L>
<L>With wid&euml; woundis depe &amp; smerte,</L>
<L N="116">Wi&thorn; cross&euml;, nailis, spere, &amp; crowne.
<PB REF="00000249.tif" N="199"></L>
<L>&para; Lete drede &amp; good discres&iuml;oun</L>
<L>&THORN;i wil holli up to me send:</L>
<L>&THORN;ou hast fyue wittis &amp; reasoun,</L>
<L N="120">And if &thorn;ou wolt, &thorn;ou maist be kynde."</L>
</LG>
<LG N="11" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(11)</HEAD>
<HEAD>(<I>Man's First Answer.</I>)</HEAD>
<L>A! lord, a&yogh;ens &thorn;ee wole we not plete,</L>
<L>For as &thorn;ou wolt, it is, &amp; was;</L>
<L>We han deserued hell&euml; hete,</L>
<L N="124">But now<MILESTONE N="88" UNIT="page"> we &yogh;eelde us to &thorn;i grace.</L>
<L>&para; We wolen bowe, &amp; &thorn;ou schalt bete,</L>
<L>And chastice us, lord, for oure trespace,</L>
<L>And lete merci for us entrete,</L>
<L N="128">&THORN;at neuere no feendis oure soulis chase.</L>
<L>&para; A! blissid lady, fair of face,</L>
<L>help! for wee be fer bihynde;</L>
<L>&THORN;at wee wi&thorn; weepynge moun crie, alas!</L>
<L N="132">For that we were to oure freend vnkinde."<NOTE PLACE="end">["Iff &thorn;ou wole be wul with god" follows.]</NOTE></L>
<TRAILER>A-M-E-N.</TRAILER>
</LG>
</DIV3>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 TYPE="poem">
<HEAD>Christ's own Complaint,</HEAD>
<DIV3 TYPE="part">
<HEAD>"MAN, MAKE AMENDIS OR &thorn;OU DIE." (otherwise called the Remorse of Conscience.)</HEAD>
<LG N="12" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(12)(<I>Christ's Second Complaint.</I>)</HEAD>
<L>Thus oure gracious god, prince of pitee,<MILESTONE N="193" UNIT="page"><NOTE PLACE="marg">God</NOTE></L>
<L>whos mi&yogh;t, whos goodnes, neuere bigan,</L>
<L>At whos wil al bihoue&thorn; to be,</L>
<L N="136">Compleyneth him &thorn;us to synful man:</L>
<L>"Myn owne peple, answere &yogh;e me,</L>
<L>Excuse &thorn;i silf if &thorn;at &thorn;ou can:</L>
<L>what haue y trespasid vnto &thorn;ee</L>
<L N="140">&thorn;at &thorn;ou forsakist me, &amp; seruest sathan?
<PB REF="00000251.tif" N="201"></L>
</LG>
<LG N="13" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(13)</HEAD>
<L>&para; "Man! such a loue to &thorn;ee y hadde!<MILESTONE N="194" UNIT="page"></L>
<L>&THORN;e world in sixe daies whanne y it wrou&yogh;t,</L>
<L>&THORN;ou were &thorn;e laste &thorn;ing &thorn;at y maad,</L>
<L N="144">By-cause y wolde &thorn;ee wantid nou&yogh;t.</L>
<L>Wh&aacute;t &thorn;ing my&yogh;te &thorn;ee helpe or glade,</L>
<L>What &thorn;at &thorn;ou nedidist durst nou&yogh;t be sou&yogh;t;</L>
<L>Foul, fische, al &thorn;ing, &thorn;ee to glade,</L>
<L N="148">To &thorn;i bihoue al was for&thorn; brou&yogh;t.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="14" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(14)</HEAD>
<L>&para; "More-ouer y &yogh;afe &thorn;ee souereynte</L>
<L>&THORN;at alle beestis schulde bowe &thorn;ee vntille;</L>
<L>I made &thorn;ee also lijk to me,</L>
<L N="152">And &yogh;af &thorn;ee kunnynge and free wille,</L>
<L>Me to serue &thorn;at &thorn;ou my&yogh;tist se,</L>
<L>To chese &thorn;e good, and leue &thorn;e ille.</L>
<L>Y aske no &thorn;ing a&yogh;en of &thorn;ee</L>
<L N="156">But be &thorn;i souereyn, as it is skille.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="15" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(15)</HEAD>
<L>&para; "But vnto &thorn;is, takist &thorn;ou no tent,</L>
<L>But wri&thorn;ist awey ful vnkindely,</L>
<L>On loue onleefful &thorn;i loue is lent;</L>
<L N="160">&THORN;in herte biholdi&thorn; not heuen an hi&yogh;,</L>
<L>For of al &thorn;ee good y haue &thorn;ee sent,<MILESTONE N="195" UNIT="page"></L>
<L>&THORN;ou list not to seie oonys 'gramercy.'</L>
<L>In tyme comynge lest &thorn;ou repente,</L>
<L N="164"><B>Man! make Amendis or &thorn;ou dye."</B></L>
</LG>
<LG N="16" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(16)</HEAD>
<HEAD>(<I>Man's Second Answer.</I>)</HEAD>
<L><B>A</B> Cristen soule conceyued with synne<NOTE PLACE="marg">Man.</NOTE></L>
<L>Receyued in conscience &thorn;is compleynt;</L>
<L N="167">Fallyng doun flat with doolful dynne,</L>
<L>And seide, "lord, mercy, moost souereyne seynt!</L>
<L>I, moost vnkynde wretche of mankynne,</L>
<L>Y knouliche y am &thorn;i traitour atent;</L>
<L>&THORN;is wickid lijf &thorn;at y lyue ynne,</L>
<L N="172">Y may it not from &thorn;i knowynge gleynt:
<PB REF="00000253.tif" N="203"></L>
</LG>
<LG N="17" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(17)</HEAD>
<L>&para; "I want wordis and also witt;</L>
<L>Of &thorn;in kindenes to carpe oon clause;</L>
<L>Al &thorn;at y haue, &thorn;ou &yogh;aue me it</L>
<L N="176">Of &thorn;i goodnesse, wi&thorn;-outen cause;</L>
<L>&THORN;ou&yogh; y haue greued &thorn;ee, &amp; do &yogh;itt,</L>
<L>&THORN;ou &thorn;i benefetis not wi&thorn;drawis;</L>
<L>I haue deserued hell&euml; pitt,</L>
<L N="180">So haue y lyued a&yogh;ens &thorn;i lawis.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="18" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(18)</HEAD>
<L>&para; "But, lord, &thorn;ou knowist mannis febilnes,<MILESTONE N="196" UNIT="page"></L>
<L>How freel he is, &amp; ha&thorn; ben ay,</L>
<L>For &thorn;ou&yogh; &thorn;e soule haue &thorn;i lijknes,</L>
<L N="184">Man is but wlatsum er&thorn;e and clay,</L>
<L>In synne conceyued &amp; wretchidnesse,</L>
<L>And to &thorn;e soule, rebel alwey.</L>
<L>First a man growith as doo&thorn; a gras,</L>
<L N="188">And anoon after welewith as flouris of hay.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="19" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(19)</HEAD>
<L>&para; "Si&thorn;en man is &thorn;an so freel a &thorn;ing,</L>
<L>And &thorn;i power, lord, is so fer ykend,</L>
<L>&THORN;is world, is an i&yogh;&euml;s twynkeling</L>
<L N="192">&THORN;ou maist distroie, noon may defende.</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; &thorn;i ri&yogh;t, lord, mercy mynge,</L>
<L>And to my soule goosteli salue &thorn;ou sende!</L>
<L>Sore me repenti&thorn; my mys-lyuynge,</L>
<L N="196"><B>For, merciful lord! y schal amende."</B></L>
</LG>
<LG N="20" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(20)</HEAD>
<HEAD>(<I>Christ's Third Complaint.</I>)</HEAD>
<L>"<B>A</B>, Man, y &yogh;af &thorn;ee bodili hele</L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;ou schuldist it spende in my seruice,</L>
<L>Fairnesse also, and feturis fele:</L>
<L N="200">But, man, what doist &thorn;ou with alle &thorn;eise?</L>
<L>&THORN;ou doist &thorn;e delicis of &thorn;e deuel:<MILESTONE N="197" UNIT="page"></L>
<L>&THORN;i delite is me to dispise;</L>
<L>&THORN;ou lyuest a letcherouse lijf vnleel;</L>
<L N="204">From &yogh;eer to &yogh;eer &thorn;ou list not rise.
<PB REF="00000255.tif" N="205"></L>
</LG>
<LG N="21" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(21)</HEAD>
<L>&para; "&THORN;ou studiest aftir nyce aray,</L>
<L>And makist greet cost in clo&thorn;ing</L>
<L>To make &thorn;ee semeli, as who schulde say</L>
<L N="208">&THORN;ou cowdist ameend&euml; my making.</L>
<L>&THORN;ou atirist &thorn;ee richeli day bi day,</L>
<L>To stire &thorn;e peple to synnynge;</L>
<L>&THORN;i wrecchid wil &thorn;ou folewist alway;</L>
<L N="212">What eende synne ha&thorn;, &thorn;ou &thorn;inkist no &thorn;ing.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="22" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(22)</HEAD>
<L>&para; "In noes tyme, by-cause of synne&mdash;</L>
<L>And for letcherie moost in special&mdash;</L>
<L>What veniaunce came &thorn;anne to mankynne!</L>
<L N="216">Saue .viij. persoones, drowned were al.</L>
<L>On sodom and gommor &thorn;ou ou&yogh;te to mynne,</L>
<L>How y made fier &amp; brymstoone falle</L>
<L>From heuene on men &thorn;at abood &thorn;erynne;</L>
<L N="220">In synne were distroied bo&thorn;e greet &amp; smal.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="23" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(23)</HEAD>
<L>&para; "Man, wenest &thorn;ou now my my&yogh;t be lesse<MILESTONE N="198" UNIT="page"></L>
<L>&THORN;an it was &thorn;anne? or ellis y</L>
<L>Hate not so mych&euml; wickidnesse</L>
<L N="224">As whanne y smoot so spiteuoseli?</L>
<L>But &yogh;it y wole &thorn;i fautis redresse,</L>
<L>&THORN;ou&yogh; y now spare for my mercy;</L>
<L>Man, &thorn;inke vpon my ri&yogh;twijsnesse,</L>
<L N="228"><B>And, man, make amendis or &thorn;ou die."</B></L>
</LG>
<LG N="24" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(24)</HEAD>
<HEAD>(<I>Man's Third Answer.</I>)</HEAD>
<L>"<B>I</B> Woot weel, lord, &thorn;ou ri&yogh;tful art,</L>
<L>And &thorn;at synne mote be ponyschid neede;</L>
<L>But oon &thorn;ing holdi&thorn; in hope myn hart,</L>
<L N="232">&THORN;i merci passi&thorn; my mysdeede;</L>
<L>I knowe weel y may nat with-start;</L>
<L>I haue so doon, me ou&yogh;te to drede.</L>
<L>With bewte &amp; with bodily qwart</L>
<L N="236">To seru&euml; &thorn;ee, y took noon hede.
<PB REF="00000257.tif" N="207"></L>
</LG>
<LG N="25" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(25)</HEAD>
<L>&para; "I haue myspendid my &yogh;ong age</L>
<L>In synne, &amp; wantownesse also;</L>
<L>Y haue be slow, and loued to rage;</L>
<L N="240">A glotoun, a letchour, y was bo&thorn;e two.</L>
<L>I am wor&thorn;i to haue noon o&thorn;ir wage<MILESTONE N="199" UNIT="page"></L>
<L>But for to dwelle in eendelees woo;</L>
<L>Alas! whi haue y ben outrage,</L>
<L N="244">And serued &thorn;e feend &thorn;at was &thorn;i foo?</L>
</LG>
<LG N="26" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(26)</HEAD>
<L>&para; But, lord, in hooli writt rede we,</L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;ou forsakist no wretchid wi&yogh;t</L>
<L>&THORN;at leue&thorn; his synne &amp; turne&thorn; to &thorn;ee;</L>
<L N="248">And y to turne to &thorn;ee have ti&yogh;t.</L>
<L>Full proud and rebel haue y bee;</L>
<L>But y wole meeke me in my si&yogh;t;</L>
<L>From hens forward, y purpose me,</L>
<L N="252">A&yogh;en myn own&euml; fleisch to fi&yogh;t.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="27" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(27)</HEAD>
<L>&para; "My fleisch to feble, y wole faste;</L>
<L>Mi boonis to traueile y wole bende;</L>
<L>And &thorn;oru&yogh; &thorn;i grace, y am not agast,</L>
<L N="256">What sorewe or sijknes to me &thorn;ou sende,</L>
<L>To suffre whilis my lijf may laste;</L>
<L>For vttirli to &thorn;is y wole entende,</L>
<L>To ponysche &thorn;at y haue trespast;</L>
<L N="260"><B>Mercy, ihesu! y wole amende."</B></L>
</LG>
<LG N="28" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(28)</HEAD>
<HEAD>(<I>Christ's Fourth Complaint.</I>)</HEAD>
<L>"MAn, y haue sente &thorn;ee siluer and golde,<MILESTONE N="200" UNIT="page"></L>
<L>And al &thorn;e wel&thorn;e withinne &thorn;i woon,</L>
<L>To susteine &thorn;ee and &thorn;in householde;</L>
<L N="264">And with &thorn;e residue, manye oon</L>
<L>&THORN;ou my&yogh;tist han holpe, &yogh;ong &amp; oolde</L>
<L>&THORN;at ben disesid and woo-bigoon;</L>
<L>My seruauntis suffren hungir &amp; coolde,</L>
<L N="268">Releef of &thorn;ee &yogh;it haue &thorn;ei noon.
<PB REF="00000259.tif" N="209"></L>
</LG>
<LG N="29" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(29)</HEAD>
<L>&para; "If &thorn;ou &yogh;eue for my love a fer&thorn;inge,</L>
<L>&THORN;ou doist it with an heuy harte;</L>
<L>In almesse &thorn;ou darist &yogh;eue no &thorn;ing</L>
<L N="272">For drede &thorn;ou schuldist falle in pouerte.</L>
<L>In wordis and in veyn spekynge,</L>
<L>what euere &thorn;ou waastist, &thorn;ou myrie art;</L>
<L>Of such y wole haue rekenynge;</L>
<L N="276">On doomysday &thorn;ou schalt not starte.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="30" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(30)</HEAD>
<L>&para; "&THORN;anne schalt &thorn;ou &yogh;eue acountis ful streite,</L>
<L>How &thorn;ou come to &thorn;i good, euery deel,</L>
<L>Whe&thorn;ir &thorn;ou it wan with trou&thorn;e or with disceite,</L>
<L N="280">And how &thorn;ou spendist it, yuel or weel.</L>
<L>Noon o&thorn;er grace &thorn;anne aftir waite;<MILESTONE N="201" UNIT="page"></L>
<L>For, as &thorn;ou hast wrou&yogh;te, so schalt &thorn;ou feele.</L>
<L>What schal &thorn;anne profite &thorn;i gowne y-pleite,</L>
<L N="284">Poundis or markis &thorn;at &yogh;e of &thorn;e peple peele?</L>
</LG>
<LG N="31" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(31)</HEAD>
<L>&para; "A clene conscience schal in &thorn;at day</L>
<L>More profite, &amp; be more sett by,</L>
<L>&THORN;an al &thorn;e muk &amp; &thorn;e money</L>
<L N="288">&thorn;at euere was or schal be, vndir &thorn;e sky.</L>
<L>&THORN;anne wole not helpe to plete ne pray;</L>
<L>&thorn;erfore, as ri&yogh;t wole, &thorn;anne deme schal y:</L>
<L>And &thorn;er-fore, man, whilis &thorn;ou may,</L>
<L N="292"><B>Man, make amendis or &thorn;ou die."</B></L>
</LG>
<LG N="32" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(32)</HEAD>
<HEAD>(<I>Man's Fourth Answer.</I>)</HEAD>
<L>"I Woot weel, lord, from &yogh;eer to &yogh;eer<NOTE PLACE="marg">Man.</NOTE></L>
<L>Ful greetli greeued &thorn;ee y haue;</L>
<L>&THORN;at y wolde neer &thorn;i mercy were,</L>
<L N="296">My modirs wombe had be my graue.</L>
<L>For what profiti&thorn; my lyuynge heere,</L>
<L>But y my&yogh;te aftirward be saaf?</L>
<L>But ihesu, as &thorn;ou bou&yogh;tist me deere,</L>
<L N="300">Lete not my soule come in helle caaf!
<PB REF="00000261.tif" N="211"></L>
</LG>
<LG N="33" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(33)</HEAD>
<L>&para; "My waast expensis y wole with-drawe;<MILESTONE N="202" UNIT="page"></L>
<L>Now, certis, 'waast' weel callid &thorn;ei be,</L>
<L>for &thorn;ei were spent, my boost to blowe,</L>
<L N="304">My name to bere bo&thorn;e on londe &amp; see.</L>
<L>Weel y woot me dare not trowe,</L>
<L>&THORN;ou&yogh; many a man of my countree,</L>
<L>If &thorn;ei me mette, &thorn;ei me not knowe,</L>
<L N="308">Ne neuere &yogh;it herde speke of me.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="34" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(34)</HEAD>
<L>&para; "Fonnedli haue y wrou&yogh;t, as a wretche vnwijs,</L>
<L>Where y my&yogh;te haue gete me myche meede</L>
<L>Had y it spend in god-is seruyce,</L>
<L N="312">On men diseesid, and almesdeede.</L>
<L>But &thorn;oru&yogh; &thorn;i grace, lord, y wole rise;</L>
<L>For, haue y or myne, oure bar&euml; neede,</L>
<L>with the remenaunt, lord, at &thorn;i dyuyse,</L>
<L N="316">&thorn;e poore &amp; nakid y wole clo&thorn;e &amp; fede.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="35" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(35)</HEAD>
<L>&para; "Sijke men &thorn;at liggen in god-is boondis,</L>
<L>&THORN;at han noo siluer for to spende,</L>
<L>And prisoners bounden feet and hondis,</L>
<L N="320">Ofte for to visite y wole to hem tende:</L>
<L>Whanne y se how it with hem stoondis,<MILESTONE N="203" UNIT="page"></L>
<L>Such as y haue, y schal hem sende;</L>
<L>But, lord, lete &thorn;ese werkis be &thorn;i sondis;</L>
<L N="324"><B>For, merciful lord, I wole amende!"</B></L>
</LG>
<LG N="36" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(36)</HEAD>
<HEAD>(<I>Christ's Fifth Complaint.</I>)</HEAD>
<L>"MAn, if &thorn;ou wolt amendis make,<NOTE PLACE="marg">God.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;an do &thorn;in almes of &thorn;in owne good,</L>
<L>And waite &thorn;ou worch&euml; no man wrake,</L>
<L N="328">to venge anothir man-is mood.</L>
<L>And &thorn;ou vntruli from oon take,</L>
<L>And &thorn;erwith fynde fourty her foode,</L>
<L>Al suche sacrificis y forsake,</L>
<L N="332">For &thorn;ei ben to me as sour as sood.
<PB REF="00000263.tif" N="213"></L>
</LG>
<LG N="37" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(37)</HEAD>
<L>&para;"&THORN;e poore peple &thorn;ou doist oppresse</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; sleitis and wilis ful manye also;</L>
<L>&THORN;ou makist chirchis, and doist singe messe,</L>
<L N="336">And mendist weies, men on to go;</L>
<L>And sum men &thorn;ee banne, &amp; summ&euml; blesse:</L>
<L>Which schal y heere of &thorn;eis&euml; two?</L>
<L>If &thorn;ou wolt haue grace as &thorn;ou doist gesse,</L>
<L N="340">Lete al falsnes be fleemyd &thorn;ee fro.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="38" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(38)</HEAD>
<L>&para;"&THORN;e mo&thorn;&thorn;is &thorn;at &thorn;i clo&thorn;is ete,<MILESTONE N="204" UNIT="page"></L>
<L>And &thorn;ou letist poore men go bare,</L>
<L>&THORN;i drinkis &thorn;at sowren, &amp; &thorn;i mowlid mete</L>
<L N="344">Wherwith &thorn;e febil my&yogh;te weel fare,</L>
<L>&THORN;e rust &thorn;at &thorn;i siluer doi&thorn; freete,</L>
<L>&THORN;i goodis &thorn;at yuel gote[n] are,</L>
<L>&THORN;ei crien vpon &thorn;ee veniaunce greete</L>
<L N="348">&THORN;ee for to spille; but &yogh;it y spare.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="39" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(39)</HEAD>
<L>&para;"With-holden hire, a&yogh;en &thorn;e ri&yogh;t</L>
<L>Of &thorn;i seruanntis, vpon &thorn;ee crye;</L>
<L>And, man, ofte tyme &thorn;ou hast me hi&yogh;t</L>
<L N="352">&THORN;ou woldist amende, &amp; leue folie;</L>
<L>&THORN;ou spekist faire bo&thorn;e day &amp; nyght,</L>
<L>&THORN;ou brekist couenaunt contynuely;</L>
<L>Me is ful loo&thorn; wi&thorn;e &thorn;ee to fight;</L>
<L N="356"><B>&THORN;erfore make amendis, man, or</B> &thorn;ou <B>die!</B>"</L>
</LG>
<LG N="40" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(40)</HEAD>
<HEAD>(<I>Man's Fifth Answer.</I>)</HEAD>
<L>"Sweete lord, y may not a&yogh;en say,<NOTE PLACE="marg">Man.</NOTE></L>
<L>Y haue not holden &thorn;at me hette:</L>
<L>Y greeued &thorn;ee greetli euery day,</L>
<L N="360">Y do not as y am in dette;</L>
<L>I wolde do weel; but, welle-away!<MILESTONE N="205" UNIT="page"></L>
<L>Wi&thorn; enemyes y am euere bisette!</L>
<L>Whanne y wolde &thorn;ee faynest pay,</L>
<L N="364">My fleisch is &thorn;e first &thorn;at wole me lette.
<PB REF="00000265.tif" N="215"></L>
</LG>
<LG N="41" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(41)</HEAD>
<L>&para;"Euere &thorn;e fattir &thorn;at y it feede,</L>
<L>Euere &thorn;e freischer it is my foo,</L>
<L>&YOGH;it y muste bere it a-bout&euml; nede:</L>
<L N="368">Ful febil it is, it wole me sloo.</L>
<L>&THORN;e world, &thorn;e feend, me [bataile] beede,</L>
<L>Sumtyme with weele, sumtyme with woo;</L>
<L>What may y do with a wekkid<NOTE PLACE="marg">[MS. welkid]</NOTE> wede,</L>
<L N="372">To fi&yogh;te a&yogh;en &thorn;ree enemyes soo?</L>
</LG>
<LG N="42" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(42)</HEAD>
<L>&para;"Whanne y enforso&thorn;e me o&thorn;ir whilis,</L>
<L>And &thorn;inke y wolde lyue a trew&euml; lijf</L>
<L>And forsake all batailis &amp; gilis,</L>
<L N="376">&THORN;e world biddi&thorn; me bataile blijf;</L>
<L>And, but y wole vse wrenchis &amp; wilis,</L>
<L>&THORN;e comoun uoice is, y schal not &thorn;rijf.</L>
<L>Summe at me mowis, summe at me smylis,</L>
<L N="380">And counten me but a kynde caitif.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="43" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(43)</HEAD>
<L>&para;"But y &thorn;inke, not-withstonding &thorn;is,<MILESTONE N="206" UNIT="page"></L>
<L>To forsake falsnes wi&thorn;-outen eende,</L>
<L>To restore a&yogh;en &thorn;at y took mys,</L>
<L N="384">And to paie my dettis fair and hende;</L>
<L>And whanne y haue &yogh;euen eche man his,</L>
<L>As resoun is, &thorn;anne wole y spende,</L>
<L>And &yogh;eue myn alm&euml;s &thorn;ere nede is;</L>
<L N="388"><B>Mercy</B>, ihesu! <B>y wole amende.</B>"</L>
</LG>
<LG N="44" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(44)</HEAD>
<HEAD>(<I>Christ's Sixth Complaint.</I>)</HEAD>
<L>"MAn, y sente &thorn;ee kindeli in-si&yogh;te<NOTE PLACE="marg">God.</NOTE></L>
<L>Of vndir-stondyng, skil, &amp; witt,</L>
<L>To rewle &thorn;i silf bi resoun ri&yogh;t;</L>
<L N="392">More-ouer &thorn;ou hast holi writt,</L>
<L>&THORN;at cleerli schewi&thorn; &thorn;ee goostli li&yogh;t,</L>
<L>How &thorn;ou schuldist deedli synne with-sett,</L>
<L>And, how &thorn;ou me pleas&euml; myght:</L>
<L N="396">What eili&thorn; &thorn;ee, man, &thorn;in i&yogh;e to schett?
<PB REF="00000267.tif" N="217"></L>
</LG>
<LG N="45" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(45)</HEAD>
<L>&para;"Wordli richesse, &amp; rial repaire,</L>
<L>Iewels, and &thorn;ingis, and myr&thorn;e of iolite,</L>
<L>Fischis, beestis, briddis of &thorn;e eir,</L>
<L N="400">&THORN;ese &thorn;inki&thorn; &thorn;ee semeli for to se.</L>
<L>If &thorn;o &thorn;ingis &thorn;at schulen perische &amp; paire,<MILESTONE N="207" UNIT="page"></L>
<L>Vnto &thorn;i sighte &thorn;us semeli bee,</L>
<L>Weel maist &thorn;ou wite, y am weel faire,</L>
<L N="404">Of whom ech &thorn;ing ha&thorn; his bewte.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="46" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(46)</HEAD>
<L>&para;"But, man, as &thorn;ou wittlees were,</L>
<L>&THORN;ou lokist euere dounwarde as a beest;</L>
<L>It heeuyeth &thorn;ee of me to heere,</L>
<L N="408">Foule speche is to &thorn;ee a feeste.</L>
<L>I coumforte &thorn;ee and make &thorn;e cheere,</L>
<L>And &thorn;ou a&yogh;enward louest me leest;</L>
<L>I calle &thorn;ee to me &yogh;eer and &yogh;eer,</L>
<L N="412">&YOGH;it wolt &thorn;ou not come at my request.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="47" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(47)</HEAD>
<L>&para;"As from &thorn;i foo, &thorn;ou from me flees,</L>
<L>Y folewe feste, and on &thorn;ee crye,</L>
<L>&THORN;ou wrappist &thorn;ee wi&thorn; vanytees,</L>
<L N="416">And &thorn;inkist my speche is but folie:</L>
<L>For &thorn;ing &thorn;at nou&yogh;t is, &thorn;ou wolt leese<NOTE PLACE="marg">[MS. leesee]</NOTE></L>
<L>My ioie &thorn;at lasti&thorn; euere eendeleesly.</L>
<L>Man, &yogh;it leue vice, and vertu chese,</L>
<L N="420"><B>And amendis make, or &thorn;ou die."</B></L>
</LG>
<LG N="48" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(48)</HEAD>
<HEAD>(<I>Man's Sixth Answer.</I>)</HEAD>
<L>"SWeete ihesu, answere noon y can,<MILESTONE N="208" UNIT="page"><NOTE PLACE="marg">Man.</NOTE></L>
<L>But ofte cry mercy with herte stable:</L>
<L>Alas for woo! whi is a man</L>
<L N="424">weel worse &thorn;an a beeste vnreson&aacute;ble?</L>
<L>Alle bestis, si&thorn;en &thorn;is world bigan,</L>
<L>In kindeli worchinge ben dur&aacute;ble,</L>
<L>Saaf oonly I, of wittis wan,</L>
<L N="428">&THORN;at haue doon manye dedis ful dampn&aacute;ble.
<PB REF="00000269.tif" N="219"></L>
</LG>
<LG N="49" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(49)</HEAD>
<L>&para; "I, man, was made to knowe my maker,</L>
<L>And to loue him aboue al o&thorn;ir &thorn;ing;</L>
<L>And y, a wrecche, was neuere waker</L>
<L N="432">To catche kinde knowing of my kyng;</L>
<L>To triflis y haue be a greet tent-taker;</L>
<L>A song of sorewe weel may I synge,</L>
<L>For hadde y of synne ben a verri forsaker,</L>
<L N="436">Of crist schulde y haue had knowyng.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="50" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(50)</HEAD>
<L>&para; "Mi goostli i&yogh;en ben ful of dust,</L>
<L>Cursid coueitise ha&thorn; so blyndid me,</L>
<L>&THORN;ei ben blood-schoten with fleischli lust,</L>
<L N="440">&THORN;at heuenly &thorn;ingis may y noon se.</L>
<L>But, lord, &thorn;ou&yogh; y haue ben vniust,<MILESTONE N="209" UNIT="page"></L>
<L>&YOGH;it &thorn;oru&yogh; &thorn;e help of &thorn;i benignite</L>
<L>I hope to rubbe aweye &thorn;e rust,</L>
<L N="444">With penaunce, from my goostli y&yogh;e;</L>
</LG>
<LG N="51" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(51)</HEAD>
<L>&para; "And where &thorn;at y haue to-for&euml; &thorn;is</L>
<L>My witt in wordli &thorn;ingis spende,</L>
<L>From hens for&thorn;ward my purpos ys</L>
<L N="448">To leerne &thorn;i lawe to my lyu&euml;s eende.</L>
<L>&THORN;i ten comaundementis, so haue y blis,</L>
<L>Them for to kepe, y wole me bende;</L>
<L>And &thorn;ere as y haue a-fore doon mys,</L>
<L N="452"><B>Now, merci, God! y wole amende.</B>"</L>
</LG>
<LG N="52" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(52)</HEAD>
<HEAD>(<I>Christ's Seventh Complaint.</I>)</HEAD>
<L>"MAn, my merci, if &thorn;ou it mynned,<NOTE PLACE="marg">God.</NOTE></L>
<L>Y haue schewid it &thorn;ee on many wise</L>
<L>Si&thorn;en &thorn;at tyme was &thorn;at &thorn;ou first synned</L>
<L N="456">A&yogh;ens my precept in paradijs.</L>
<L>In helle prisoun whane &thorn;ou were pynned</L>
<L>For doinge of &thorn;e deuelis deuyce,</L>
<L>Out of &thorn;at prisoun for to be twynned,</L>
<L N="460">Mercy and loue &thorn;ee halp; &thorn;inke on &thorn;ese.
<PB REF="00000271.tif" N="221"></L>
</LG>
<LG N="53" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(53)</HEAD>
<L>&para; "Mercy was &thorn;in aduoket cheef<MILESTONE N="210" UNIT="page"></L>
<L>&THORN;at y for &thorn;ee took fleisch &amp; blood;</L>
<L>Loue mad&euml; &thorn;ee to me so leef,</L>
<L N="464">&THORN;at y for &thorn;ee was rent on roode;</L>
<L>I suffride dee&thorn; to chaunge &thorn;i greef,</L>
<L>And vnto helle &thorn;an doun y &yogh;oode;</L>
<L>Y brou&yogh;te &thorn;ee to blis from repreef:</L>
<L N="468">&THORN;us haue y be, man, &thorn;i freend ful good.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="54" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(54)</HEAD>
<L>&para; "I bicame poore, &thorn;ee riche to make;</L>
<L>To make &thorn;ee whi&yogh;t, y was made reed;</L>
<L>Mi sorewe, my sijknesse, made &thorn;in to slake,</L>
<L N="472">Myn hungir book &thorn;i blisful breed.</L>
<L>I boond my silf, &thorn;i boondis y brake;</L>
<L>To gete &thorn;ee lijf, y suffride &thorn;e deede;</L>
<L>What schulde y more do for &thorn;i sake?</L>
<L N="476">To hele &thorn;i foot, hurt was myn heed.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="55" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(55)</HEAD>
<L>&para; "What woldist &thorn;ou, man, &thorn;at y schuld do?</L>
<L>My mercy to &thorn;ee is ful redy</L>
<L>Yf &thorn;ou wolt dispose &thorn;ee &thorn;erto;</L>
<L N="480">Such loue t&oacute; &thorn;ee, man, haue y,</L>
<L>I hi&yogh;te &thorn;ee myr&thorn;e and ioi&euml;s moo,<MILESTONE N="211" UNIT="page"></L>
<L>But &thorn;ou art &thorn;in owne moost enemy;</L>
<L>for ou&yogh;t &thorn;at y &thorn;ee bidde, &thorn;ou wolt so;</L>
<L N="484"><B>Man! make amendis or &thorn;ou die."</B></L>
</LG>
<LG N="56" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(56)</HEAD>
<HEAD>(<I>Man's Seventh Answer.</I>)</HEAD>
<L>"LOrd, whanne y &thorn;inke on &thorn;i pouert,<NOTE PLACE="marg">Man.</NOTE></L>
<L>And how wilful &thorn;ou were, &amp; fayn,</L>
<L>To suffre for me woundis smert;&mdash;</L>
<L N="488">To slee my synn&euml;s &thorn;ou were slayn,&mdash;</L>
<L>Hardir than iren is myn hert,</L>
<L>Which ha&thorn; no pitee of &thorn;i payn!</L>
<L>Euere &thorn;e kyndir to me &thorn;ou art,</L>
<L N="492">&THORN;e more vnkyndir am y agayn.
<PB REF="00000273.tif" N="223"></L>
</LG>
<LG N="57" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(57)</HEAD>
<L>&para; "Whi woldist &thorn;ou, lord, be slayn for me,</L>
<L>&THORN;at am &thorn;in enemy moost vnhende?</L>
<L>Si&thorn;en no man ha&thorn; more charite,</L>
<L N="496">&THORN;an dee&thorn; to suffre for his freende,</L>
<L>What skile is &thorn;ou schuldist s&oacute; slayn be,</L>
<L>Si&thorn;en y made &thorn;ee &thorn;ral to &thorn;e feend?</L>
<L>I trespaside, lord; whi smoot &thorn;ou not me?</L>
<L N="500">Now, blessid be &thorn;ou wi&thorn;-outen eende!</L>
</LG>
<LG N="58" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(58)</HEAD>
<L>&para; "I se weel, lord, &thorn;at &thorn;ou louest us<MILESTONE N="212" UNIT="page"></L>
<L>For oure profite, &amp; not for &thorn;ine;</L>
<L>For what were &thorn;ou &thorn;ee werse, ihesus,</L>
<L N="504">&thorn;ou&yogh; alle we weren in eendelees peyne.</L>
<L>Alas, whi ben we so vi[ci]ouse,</L>
<L>And so vnkyndeli from &thorn;ee declynne</L>
<L>&thorn;at oure god art so grac&iuml;ous,</L>
<L N="508">And so loo&thorn; art, mannis soule to tyne?</L>
</LG>
<LG N="59" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(59)</HEAD>
<L>&para; "But, sweete lord, as &thorn;ou hast bigunne,</L>
<L>So lete &thorn;i mercy for&thorn; extende:</L>
<L>Putte &thorn;i crosse &amp; &thorn;i passioun</L>
<L N="512">Bitweene my werkis wor&thorn;i to be brende,</L>
<L>And &thorn;i doom &thorn;at y may not schounne,</L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;e boondis of helle come me not hende.</L>
<L>Who but &thorn;e fadir schoulde helpe &thorn;e sonne?</L>
<L N="516"><B>Merciful</B> ihesu, <B>y wole amende."</B></L>
</LG>
<LG N="60" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(60)</HEAD>
<HEAD>(<I>Christ's Eighth Complaint.</I>)</HEAD>
<L>"MAn, if &thorn;ou wolt my mercy gete<NOTE PLACE="marg">God.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;oru&yogh; my passioun of myche vertu,</L>
<L>Whi leuest &thorn;ou not of me to bete?</L>
<L N="520">Eche day on crosse &thorn;ou doist me newe</L>
<L>With deedli synne, at morn, at meete,<MILESTONE N="213" UNIT="page"></L>
<L>As a turmentour to me vntrewe,</L>
<L>And nameli, with &thorn;in o&thorn;is greete,</L>
<L N="524">To swer&euml; &thorn;ou wolt not eschewe.
<PB REF="00000275.tif" N="225"></L>
</LG>
<LG N="61" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(61)</HEAD>
<L>&para; No lyme on me, man, &thorn;ou forbeerist:</L>
<L>Whi doist &thorn;ou yuel a&yogh;ens good?</L>
<L>By my soule &thorn;ou ofte tyme sweerist,</L>
<L N="528">Bi my body, and bi my blood.</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; &thorn;i tunge &thorn;ou me al to-teerist</L>
<L>Whanne &thorn;ou art wroo&thorn;, as wi&yogh;t moost wood.</L>
<L>Man, with &thorn;in vnkindenes &thorn;ou more me deerist</L>
<L N="532">&THORN;an &thorn;ei &thorn;at diden me on &thorn;e roode.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="62" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(62)</HEAD>
<L>&para; &THORN;ou hast more pitee on &thorn;i too</L>
<L>If it be hurt, and a litil bleede,</L>
<L>&THORN;an euere &thorn;ou haddist for al &thorn;e woo</L>
<L N="536">&THORN;at euere y suffride for &thorn;i mys-deede.</L>
<L>Whanne &thorn;ou art tau&yogh;t &thorn;at &thorn;ou schuldist hoo</L>
<L>Of sweering, but whanne it were neede,</L>
<L>&THORN;ou scornest hem &thorn;at sayn &thorn;ee soo;</L>
<L N="540">To myn heestis takist &thorn;ou noon hede.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="63" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(63)</HEAD>
<L>"Lowd&euml; lesyngis on me &thorn;ou makist,<MILESTONE N="214" UNIT="page"></L>
<L>Sum tyme to wynne an halpeny,</L>
<L>What tyme to witnes &thorn;ou me takist,</L>
<L N="544">And &yogh;it &thorn;ou forsweerist &thorn;ee wityngly.</L>
<L>Biynge &amp; sillynge &thorn;ou not forsakist,</L>
<L>Bo&thorn;e veyn &amp; wrong to sweere me by;</L>
<L>Whanne &thorn;ou &thorn;us doist, &thorn;i bale &thorn;ou bakist;</L>
<L N="548">Man! make &thorn;ou amendis or &thorn;ou die."</L>
</LG>
<LG N="64" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(64)</HEAD>
<HEAD>(<I>Man's Eighth Answer.</I>)</HEAD>
<L>"Sweete ihesu, how schulde y a&yogh;en say,<NOTE PLACE="marg">Man.</NOTE></L>
<L>But &thorn;at y caitife am, more curst</L>
<L>&THORN;an &thorn;o &thorn;at doon &thorn;ee on &thorn;e crosse eche day</L>
<L N="552">With greet oo&thorn;is &amp; werkis wurst,</L>
<L>And myche more &thorn;ee greeue&thorn; &thorn;an &thorn;ei</L>
<L>&THORN;at on calueri slowen &thorn;ee firste;</L>
<L>For hadde &thorn;ei knowe &thorn;ee for god verray,</L>
<L N="556">&THORN;ee to dee&thorn; &thorn;ei hadde not durst.
<PB REF="00000276.tif" N="226"></L>
</LG>
<LG N="65" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(65)</HEAD>
<L>&para; But y knowe, aftir my bileeue,</L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;ou art god omnipotent,</L>
<L>And &yogh;it y ceesse not &thorn;ee to greue!</L>
<L N="560">Weel wor&thorn;i am y to be schent!</L>
<L>How maist &thorn;ou, lord, suffre me to meeue?<MILESTONE N="215" UNIT="page"></L>
<L>Alle creaturis owen me to turment;</L>
<L>Merueile it is &thorn;at y not myscheeue,</L>
<L N="564">&THORN;at y neere kild, drowned, or brent.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="66" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(66)</HEAD>
<L>&para; The er&thorn;e opened and swelewid al quicke,</L>
<L>Daton &amp; abiron for her synne;</L>
<L>And y weene &thorn;ei were neuere so wick</L>
<L N="568">As y, moost caitife of mankynne!</L>
<L>In deedly synne men dien now &thorn;icke;</L>
<L>Disese ful greet now doo&thorn; bigynne,</L>
<L>And &yogh;it in my synne y stonde and sticke;</L>
<L N="572">Yuel custum ys ful hard to blynne</L>
</LG>
<LG N="67" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(67)</HEAD>
<L>&para; I wolde be wantowne, and do ille,</L>
<L>But y wolde noon me reprehende,</L>
<L>But lete me lyue aftir my wille:</L>
<L N="576">&THORN;is was leefful, sumtyme y wende,</L>
<L>But now y se &thorn;at it is skille,</L>
<L>&THORN;at such light to me &thorn;ou sende,</L>
<L>But if y leue synne, it wole me spille.</L>
<L N="580"><B>Merciful lord</B> ihesu, <B>y wole amende!"</B></L>
</LG>
<LG N="68" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(68)</HEAD>
<HEAD>(<I>Christ's Ninth Complaint.</I>)</HEAD>
<L>"Man, of &thorn;i silf it schal be-long<MILESTONE N="216" UNIT="page"></L>
<L>If so be &thorn;i soule be spilt;</L>
<L>For&yogh;eue &thorn;ou hem &thorn;at worchen &thorn;ee wrong,</L>
<L N="584">And y schal for&yogh;eue &thorn;ee &thorn;i gilt;</L>
<L>And if &thorn;ou be of herte so strong,</L>
<L>And on no wise for&yogh;eue &thorn;ou wilt,</L>
<L>But venge &thorn;i silf with herte &amp; tunge,</L>
<L N="588">As a traitour &thorn;ou schalt be ouer tilt.
<PB REF="00000277.tif" N="227"></L>
</LG>
<LG N="69" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(69)</HEAD>
<L>&para; &THORN;ou getist no merci, &thorn;i silf to saue,</L>
<L>&THORN;at no mercy on o&thorn;ir has:</L>
<L>How may &thorn;ou me of merci craue,</L>
<L N="592">And &thorn;ou wolt graunt&euml; no man grace?</L>
<L>Merciful men schulen mercy haue;</L>
<L>Fel folk, schal y fleeme fro my face;</L>
<L>What ensaumple &thorn;at y &thorn;ee &yogh;aue,</L>
<L N="596">Whanne y dee&thorn; suffride, no tent &thorn;ou taas.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="70" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(70)</HEAD>
<L>&para; I praied for hem &thorn;at me disesid,</L>
<L>&THORN;ou&yogh; y my&yogh;te hem haue dampned for ay;</L>
<L>For, and &thorn;ou be a litil displeside,</L>
<L N="600">&THORN;ou bannest &amp; cursist nyght and day;</L>
<L>For no preching wolt &thorn;ou be pleside,<MILESTONE N="217" UNIT="page"></L>
<L>But for to venge &thorn;ee is &thorn;i wil alway;</L>
<L>Ful foul&euml; schulde &thorn;i foos be fesid</L>
<L N="604">If &thorn;ou my&yogh;te ouer hem, as y ouer &thorn;ee may.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="71" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(71)</HEAD>
<L>&para; Without&euml; cause ofte art &thorn;ou wroo&thorn;</L>
<L>Vnto &thorn;i freendis vnskilfully;</L>
<L>Whanne &thorn;ei &thorn;ee techen &amp; councelle bo&thorn;e</L>
<L N="608">To leue &thorn;i wra&thorn;&thorn;e and &thorn;in enuye,</L>
<L>With wordis greete and spiteful oo&thorn;</L>
<L>&THORN;ou defendist &thorn;ee of &thorn;i foule folie;</L>
<L>But &thorn;ee to leese, y am ful loo&thorn;;</L>
<L N="612"><B>Man, make amendis or &thorn;ou die.</B>"</L>
</LG>
<LG N="72" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(72)</HEAD>
<HEAD>(<I>Man's Ninth Answer.</I>)</HEAD>
<L>"Sweete lord, &thorn;inke &thorn;ou madist us alle,</L>
<L>And how kinde and propir it is to &thorn;ee,</L>
<L>On synful men &thorn;at to &thorn;ee calle,</L>
<L N="616">On hem to haue mercy and pitee.</L>
<L>&THORN;ou&yogh; y haue be as bettir as galle,</L>
<L>For &thorn;i greet merci, haue mercy on me,</L>
<L>And fro &thorn;i loue &thorn;at y no more falle!</L>
<L N="620">But kindele &thorn;ou me in charitee.
<PB REF="00000278.tif" N="228"></L>
</LG>
<LG N="73" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(73)</HEAD>
<L>&para; For &thorn;ou&yogh; y cow&thorn;e al kunnynge ken,<MILESTONE N="218" UNIT="page"></L>
<L>And speke with aungils tung&euml; cleer,</L>
<L>And &thorn;ou&yogh; y delide among poore men</L>
<L N="624">My wordli goodis alle in feer,</L>
<L>And &yogh;af my bodi for to brenne</L>
<L>For loue of &thorn;ee &thorn;at bou&yogh;tist me dere,</L>
<L>&YOGH;it al &thorn;is profiti&thorn; me not &thorn;en,</L>
<L N="628">In loue and charite but if y weere.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="74" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(74)</HEAD>
<L>&para; And y woot it is more plesyng</L>
<L>To &thorn;ee, ihesu, my souereyne lord,</L>
<L>&THORN;at y loue &thorn;ee ouer al &thorn;ing,</L>
<L N="632">And be in charite and acoorde</L>
<L>With alle my nei&yogh;boris, oolde &amp; &yogh;yng,</L>
<L>&THORN;an for to faste &amp; goo wollewarde,</L>
<L>And heere alle &thorn;e massis &thorn;at preestis syng;</L>
<L N="636">But if y loue, y gete no coumfort.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="75" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(75)</HEAD>
<L>&para; Alas! whi haue y so wra&thorn;ful ben,</L>
<L>&THORN;at loue myn herte my&yogh;te not come hende?</L>
<L>I hatide hem &thorn;at me neuere dide teen,</L>
<L N="640">Y loued not hem &thorn;at me good kende,</L>
<L>I castide me no &thorn;ing to be in &thorn;at meen;<MILESTONE N="219" UNIT="page"></L>
<L>To loue myn enemyes, y wolde not entende;</L>
<L>But &yogh;it schal y hem neuere curse, y weene;</L>
<L N="644"><B>Merciful</B> ihesu! <B>y wole amende.</B>"</L>
</LG>
<LG N="76" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(76)</HEAD>
<HEAD>(<I>Christ's Tenth Complaint.</I>)</HEAD>
<L>"MAn, if &thorn;ou wolt of bataile blynne,</L>
<L>And charite kepe in ech&euml; chaunce,</L>
<L>My merci soon&euml; schalt &thorn;ou wynne,</L>
<L N="648">So &thorn;at &thorn;ou do fruytis of penaunce.</L>
<L>Loke &thorn;in herte be contrite with-ynne,</L>
<L>And sory for &thorn;i mys-gouernaunce:</L>
<L>What profi&yogh;ti&thorn; &thorn;ee to schryue &thorn;ee of &thorn;i synne</L>
<L N="652">But &thorn;ou in herte haue r&eacute;pentaunce?
<PB REF="00000279.tif" N="229"></L>
</LG>
<LG N="77" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(77)</HEAD>
<L>&para; &THORN;ou scornest, and penaunce doist &thorn;ou noon</L>
<L>For &thorn;i synne, but &thorn;in herte be soor;</L>
<L>For wordli losse &thorn;ou makist moone,</L>
<L N="656">&THORN;ou si&yogh;est and sorewist myche &thorn;erfore.</L>
<L>And if &thorn;i body were woo bigoon,</L>
<L>What bittir medecyn &yogh;euen &thorn;ee wore,</L>
<L>Ioiyngly &thorn;ou woldist it take anoon,</L>
<L N="660">Thi bodily hel&euml; &thorn;ee to restore.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="78" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(78)</HEAD>
<L>&para; &THORN;i soule with synne is goostly slayn,<MILESTONE N="220" UNIT="page"></L>
<L>And &thorn;ou withoute sorewe &thorn;i synn&euml; tellis,</L>
<L>To do such penaunce, &thorn;ou art not fayn,</L>
<L N="664">As &thorn;i schrift-fadir &thorn;ee councellis.</L>
<L>Thou wolt neuere restore agayn</L>
<L>Fals-goten good &thorn;at &thorn;ou wi&thorn; mellis:</L>
<L>Man, &thorn;ou must &thorn;erfore suffre payn</L>
<L N="668">For &thorn;i synnes, heere or sumwhere ellis.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="79" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(79)</HEAD>
<L>&para; It is impossible, and may not be,</L>
<L>To passe fro ioie to ioie: for thi,</L>
<L>Take &thorn;i crosse to &thorn;ee, and folewe me,</L>
<L N="672">If &thorn;ou wolt to my blis up sti&yogh;e.</L>
<L>Greet sijknesse and al aduersite,</L>
<L>What-so-euere come&thorn;, suffre paciently;</L>
<L>Hate alway synne, and euere it flee,</L>
<L N="676"><B>And, man, make amendis or &thorn;ou die.</B>"</L>
</LG>
<LG N="80" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(80)</HEAD>
<HEAD>(<I>Man's Tenth Answer.</I>)</HEAD>
<L>"LOrd, &yogh;eue me grace amendis to make,</L>
<L>For of my silf me faili&thorn; poweer:</L>
<L>Synne &thorn;at is deedli y wole forsake,</L>
<L N="680">And to do deedis &thorn;at wor&thorn;i merite weere.</L>
<L>In &thorn;is world sende me woo &amp; wrake</L>
<L>For synnis &thorn;at y haue doon ful seere:<MILESTONE N="221" UNIT="page"></L>
<L>Who ha&thorn; no desese, heere he may quake;</L>
<L N="684">Hem &thorn;at &thorn;ou louest, &thorn;ou chastisist heere.
<PB REF="00000280.tif" N="230"></L>
</LG>
<LG N="81" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(81)</HEAD>
<L>For my sake, &thorn;ritti &yogh;eeris &amp; moo,</L>
<L>greet traueile for me in er&thorn;e &thorn;ou hadde;</L>
<L>&thorn;i modir, wi&thorn; &thorn;in apostolis also,</L>
<L N="688">In greet disese her lijf &thorn;ei ledde:</L>
<L>In aduersite and mych&euml; woo</L>
<L>martris &amp; confessouris weren clad:</L>
<L>in such a companye to goo</L>
<L N="692">in &thorn;i leuerey, y schulde be glad.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="82" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(82)</HEAD>
<L>Si&thorn;en &thorn;i derlingis &thorn;at with &thorn;ee dwelle</L>
<L>hadden such aduersitee in &thorn;is lijf,</L>
<L>what herte may &thorn;inke, or tung&euml; telle,</L>
<L N="696">&thorn;e payne, &thorn;e anguische, &amp; &thorn;e strijf</L>
<L>&thorn;at dampned men schulen haue in helle,</L>
<L>&thorn;ere eendelees woo &amp; sorewis ben riyf?</L>
<L>Y wole forsake my synnes so felle,</L>
<L N="700">&amp; to a discreet preeste y wole me schryue.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="83" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(83)</HEAD>
<L>&para; In trewe penaunce is myn entent,<MILESTONE N="222" UNIT="page"></L>
<L>Fro hens forward my tyme to spende,</L>
<L>And kepe y wole &thorn;i comaund&euml;ment,</L>
<L N="704">Ellis in helle fier y schal be brende.</L>
<L>Rial repeire, riche roobis, and rent,</L>
<L>What mowe &thorn;ei helpe me at myn eende?</L>
<L>But y &thorn;ee serue, y schal be schende;</L>
<L N="708"><B>Mercy, lord ihesu, y schal amende."</B></L>
</LG>
<LG N="84" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(84)</HEAD>
<HEAD>(<I>Christ's Eleventh and last Complaint.</I>)</HEAD>
<L>"MAn, do penaunce whilis &thorn;ou may,</L>
<L>Lest sudeynli y take veniaunce:</L>
<L>Do y not abide &thorn;ee day bi day</L>
<L N="712">Bicause y wolde &thorn;ou dide penaunce?</L>
<L>Man, y am more redy alway</L>
<L>To for&yogh;eue &thorn;ee &thorn;i mys-gouernaunce</L>
<L>&THORN;an &thorn;ou art mercy for to pray,</L>
<L N="716">For my wille were &thorn;ee to enhaunce.
<PB REF="00000281.tif" N="231"></L>
</LG>
<LG N="85" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(85)</HEAD>
<L>&para; Whanne &thorn;ou alle &thorn;i freendis hast asaied,</L>
<L>&THORN;ou schalt fynde no freend lijk me;</L>
<L>'&THORN;ou wolt amende,' &thorn;us ofte &thorn;ou seide,</L>
<L N="720">And a&yogh;en amendis wole y not be;</L>
<L>Do trewe penaunce, &amp; y am payed,<MILESTONE N="223" UNIT="page"></L>
<L>From eendelees peine y wole make &thorn;ee free;</L>
<L>For whi? for &thorn;i loue my lijf y laied:</L>
<L N="724">What freend wolde haue so doon for &thorn;ee?</L>
</LG>
<LG N="86" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(86)</HEAD>
<L>&para; With soruful herte &thorn;i synne &thorn;ou schryfe,</L>
<L>Make amendis with &thorn;i my&yogh;t &amp; mayn,</L>
<L>And if &thorn;ou &thorn;us leeue &thorn;i wickid lijf,</L>
<L N="728">Myn aungils wolen be &thorn;erof fayn.</L>
<L>&THORN;inke &thorn;ou ofte on lottis wijf,</L>
<L>And turne not to &thorn;i synne agayn;</L>
<L>Lete not dispeir&euml; &thorn;ee doun drijf;</L>
<L N="732">&THORN;inke on petir &amp; on mawdeleyn.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="87" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(87)</HEAD>
<L>&para; Man, &thorn;us wipe awey &thorn;i wickidnes,</L>
<L>And kepe my biddynge bi and by,</L>
<L>And &thorn;ou schalt haue in my blis,</L>
<L N="736">Worschip wi&thorn;oute ony velonye,</L>
<L>No pouert, but al richesse,</L>
<L>Hele, stren&thorn;e, &amp; wijsdom eendeleesly;</L>
<L>&THORN;ou schalt be ful of al swetnesse</L>
<L N="740"><B>Where &thorn;ou schalt lyue &amp; neuere die.</B>"</L>
</LG>
<LG N="88" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(88)</HEAD>
<HEAD>(<I>Man's Eleventh and last Answer.</I>)</HEAD>
<L>"GRaunte mercy, ihesu, crop &amp; roote<MILESTONE N="224" UNIT="page"></L>
<L>Of al frenschip, for &thorn;ou neuere failis;</L>
<L>A&yogh;ens &thorn;ee nyle y not moote,</L>
<L N="744">But, as ofte as me yue[l] aylis,</L>
<L>I wole fall&euml; flat to thi foote,</L>
<L>To help&euml; me in goostli batailis.</L>
<L>A&yogh;ens al bale, lord, &thorn;ou be my boote,</L>
<L N="748">Whanne synne &amp; sorowe me sore asailis.
<PB REF="00000282.tif" N="232"></L>
</LG>
<LG N="89" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(89)</HEAD>
<L>&para; Now woot y where y schal me hide</L>
<L>Whanne y am stirid to ony synne;</L>
<L>In &thorn;e greet wounde of &thorn;i right side;</L>
<L N="752">And, be y veryli hid &thorn;er-ynne,</L>
<L>As in a tour &thorn;ere may y a-bide</L>
<L>For au&yogh;t &thorn;at &thorn;e feend can ymagyne,</L>
<L>For al &thorn;is world &thorn;at is so wiyde,</L>
<L N="756">&THORN;ere is for man moost souereyn medicyn.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="90" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(90)</HEAD>
<L>&para; &THORN;ere may no wanhope make me care,</L>
<L>&THORN;at ha&thorn; oon of &thorn;in aungils so good</L>
<L>To kepe me &thorn;at y not mys fare,</L>
<L N="760">And &thorn;i modir, myldest of mood,</L>
<L>&THORN;at schewi&thorn; to &thorn;ee hir pappis<NOTE PLACE="foot">Compare Hoccleve's <I>Mother of God</I>, p. 47, l. 112; p. 54, l. 72. Are these paps referd to in English poetry before the 15th century?</NOTE> bare<MILESTONE N="225" UNIT="page"></L>
<L>(For me) of which &thorn;ou soukedist foode;</L>
<L>And to-fore &thorn;i fadir, [&amp;] mere<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. not clear.?mere = mother.</NOTE> maree,</L>
<L N="764">&THORN;ou schewist &thorn;i woundis rent on roode.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="91" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(91)</HEAD>
<L>&para; How my&yogh;te y of &thorn;i mercy mys,</L>
<L>Si&thorn;en to helpe man &thorn;ou art so hende?</L>
<L>Now, ihesu, lord, &thorn;ou weel us wisse,</L>
<L N="768">And, whilis we lyue, such grace us sende</L>
<L>&THORN;at we may bide wi&thorn; &thorn;ee in blis,</L>
<L>And wi&thorn; aungils, world withouten eende,</L>
<L>&THORN;at to be chosen, ordeyned ys</L>
<L N="772">To leeue al synne, &amp; hem amende.<NOTE PLACE="end">["In my &yogh;onge age" follows in the MS., p. 226.]</NOTE></L>
<TRAILER><B>Amen:</B> Amen <B>:Amen</B> Amen."
</TRAILER>

</LG>
</DIV3>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 TYPE="poem"><PB REF="00000283.tif" N="233">
<HEAD>The Virgin's Complaint.<NOTE PLACE="foot">In the first edition, this and the following poem from Harl. 3954, having the same first two stanzas, were printed opposite one another, for the contrast of their later stanzas. But as in this second edition the parallel arrangement would have left p. 233 blank, the Resurrection poem is now put after the Death one.</NOTE> filius Regis Mortuus est.</HEAD>
<HEADNOTE><P>[<I>Lambeth MS.</I> 853, <I>ab.</I> 1430 A.D., <I>page</I> 74, <I>written without breaks</I>.] [12 stanzas of 12 lines each, <I>abab abab bcbc</I>.]</P></HEADNOTE>
<LG N="1" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(1)</HEAD>
<L>AS resoun rewlid my richelees mynde,</L>
<L>Bi wielde waies as y hadde went,</L>
<L>A solempne citee me fortuned to fynde;</L>
<L N="4">To turne &thorn;erto was myne entent.</L>
<L>&para; A maiden y mette, a modir hynde,</L>
<L>Sobbinge &amp; si&yogh;ynge, sche was neer schent;</L>
<L>Sche wepte, sche wailid, so sore sche pined;</L>
<L N="8">Hir heer, hir face, sche tuggid &amp; rent,</L>
<L>&para; Sche tuggid, sche taar with greet turment,</L>
<L>Sche racide hir skyn, bothe body &amp; brest;</L>
<L>Sche seide &thorn;eise wordis euere as sche went,</L>
<L N="12">"Filius regis mortuus est."</L>
</LG>
<LG N="2" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(2)</HEAD>
<L>"The kingis sone," sche seide, "is deed,</L>
<L>&THORN;e ioie, &thorn;e substaunce of my lijfe:</L>
<L>&THORN;e modir to se hir sone so blede,</L>
<L N="16">It kitti&thorn; myn herte as with a knyf.</L>
<L>&para; My sone &thorn;at y was woont to fede,</L>
<L>To lulle, to lappe, with songis rijf;</L>
<L>Out of his herte his blood to schede,</L>
<L N="20">Maki&thorn; me, his modir, in myche strijfe.</L>
<L>&para; I am bo&thorn;e maiden, modir, &amp; wijf,<MILESTONE N="75" UNIT="page"></L>
<L>And sones haue y no mo to souke my brest;</L>
<L>I may make sorewe without relijf,</L>
<L N="24">For 'filius regis mortuus est.'
<PB REF="00000284.tif" N="234"></L>
</LG>
<LG N="3" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(3)</HEAD>
<L>Thus filius regis, myn owne dere child,</L>
<L>Hangi&thorn; on &thorn;e croos: y stoonde and se</L>
<L>How he is woundid &amp; defilid</L>
<L N="28">With spittinge &amp; speeris so piteuousli.</L>
<L>&para; I cried upon him as y were wielde,</L>
<L>'Mi swete dere sone, seest &thorn;ou not me,</L>
<L>&THORN;ine owne dere modir?' &thorn;o he me biheld,</L>
<L N="32">And seide, 'moorne not, modir, &thorn;i sorowe lete be;</L>
<L>&para; I schal be &thorn;in &amp; come to &thorn;ee.'</L>
<L>He spak; y swowned, y neuere ceest;</L>
<L>A! sone myn, sone myn, upon a tree!</L>
<L N="36">Filius regis mortuus est.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="4" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(4)</HEAD>
<L>He die&thorn;, he die&thorn;, &thorn;at is my blis;</L>
<L>He swelte, y swowned, y cried a-las!</L>
<L>No wondir is of my greet heuynes!</L>
<L N="40">Mi fadir, my bro&thorn;ir, my spouse, he was,</L>
<L>&para; My modir, my socour, &amp; al &thorn;at ys!</L>
<L>Now fadirlees &amp; modirlees y mai for&thorn; passe,<MILESTONE N="76" UNIT="page"></L>
<L>Bro&thorn;erlees, spouselees, ful wrecchid y-wis,</L>
<L N="44">As a &thorn;ing forsaken &thorn;at no &thorn;ing has!</L>
<L>&para; A! gabriel, &thorn;ou clepidist me ful of grace.</L>
<L>Nay! ful of sorowe &thorn;ou now me seest;</L>
<L>&THORN;e teeris trikilen dowun on my face,</L>
<L N="48">For 'filius regis mortuus est.'</L>
</LG>
<LG N="5" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(5)</HEAD>
<L>I lokide up," sche seid, "vn-to my child,</L>
<L>I cried on &thorn;e iewis, &amp; bad hem hang</L>
<L>&THORN;e modir bi &thorn;e sone &thorn;at neuere was filid:</L>
<L N="52">O dee&thorn;, dee&thorn;, &thorn;ou doost me wrong!</L>
<L>&para; Mi babe &thorn;ou sleest, &thorn;at neuere was wielde;</L>
<L>Come, sle &thorn;e modir! whi tariest &thorn;ou so long?</L>
<L>&THORN;ou mor&thorn;er man, whi art &thorn;ou now myelde
<PB REF="00000285.tif" N="235"></L>
<L N="56">Vn-to &thorn;e modir &thorn;at wolde dee&thorn; fong?</L>
<L>&para; &THORN;ou pynest my sone with peyn&euml;s strong;</L>
<L>Pyne &thorn;an &thorn;e modir at hir reqwest!</L>
<L>Alas, y may synge a soruful song,</L>
<L N="60">&THORN;at<MILESTONE N="77" UNIT="page"> 'filius regis mortuus est.'</L>
</LG>
<LG N="6" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(6)</HEAD>
<L>A! &thorn;ou er&thorn;e! on &thorn;ee y clayme apeel</L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;ou receyuedist his giltlees blood.</L>
<L>&THORN;ou stoon! whi woldist &thorn;ou be so freel</L>
<L N="64">To be &thorn;e morteis &thorn;ere &thorn;e crosse stood?</L>
<L>&para; He made &thorn;e er&thorn;e and stoonis feele,</L>
<L>And &yogh;e ben instrumentis now to &thorn;e roode</L>
<L>To sle &yogh;oure maker! &yogh;e wite ful weel</L>
<L N="68">He dide neuere yuel, but euermore good.</L>
<L>&para; He was euere meeke &amp; mylde of mood;</L>
<L>Now is he stikid as it were a beest!</L>
<L>Alas my babe, my lyu&euml;s foode,</L>
<L N="72">Filius regis mortuus est!</L>
</LG>
<LG N="7" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(7)</HEAD>
<L>Thou tree, &thorn;ou crosse, how durst &thorn;ou be</L>
<L>A galow to hang thi maker so?</L>
<L>Vnto his fadir y may apeele &thorn;ee</L>
<L N="76">&THORN;at woldist be cause of &thorn;e son&euml;s woo;</L>
<L>&para; Not cause, but help &thorn;at he deed be!</L>
<L>&YOGH;e trees! crie mercy, &yogh;e be my foo;</L>
<L>Hadde &yogh;e be ordeyned<MILESTONE N="78" UNIT="page"> a roode for me,</L>
<L N="80">To hang me bi him, it hadde ben weel doo.</L>
<L>&para; But what may y seie? whidir schal y do? [go]</L>
<L>&THORN;e tree ha&thorn; hangid a king, a preest;</L>
<L>Of all&euml; kingis suche ben no mo</L>
<L N="84">As 'filius regis mortuus est.'</L>
</LG>
<LG N="8" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(8)</HEAD>
<L>O &yogh;e creaturis vnkynde! &thorn;ou iren, &thorn;ou steel,</L>
<L>&thorn;ou scharp &thorn;orn!</L>
<L>How durst &yogh;e slee &yogh;oure best frend,
<PB REF="00000286.tif" N="236"></L>
<L N="88">&THORN;e holiest child &thorn;at euere was born?</L>
<L>&para; &YOGH;e haue him woundid, ye haue him pyned;</L>
<L>Spere &amp; nail his bodi ha&thorn; schorn!</L>
<L>&THORN;ou spere! whi suffridist &thorn;ou &thorn;e smyth &thorn;e grynde</L>
<L N="92">So scharpe, &thorn;at al his herte &thorn;ou hast to-torn?</L>
<L>&para; I may crie out on &thorn;ee bo&thorn;e euen &amp; morn;</L>
<L>A wemlees maydens sone &thorn;ou sleest!</L>
<L>I wringe &amp; wepe as &thorn;ing for-lorn!</L>
<L N="96">Filius regis mortuus est.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="9" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(9)</HEAD>
<L>Thou scourg&euml; maad of ful tou&yogh; skyn,</L>
<L>Knottid &amp; gnaggid, y crie on &thorn;ee!</L>
<L>&THORN;ou <MILESTONE N="79" UNIT="page">beet my barn &thorn;at neuere dide synne:</L>
<L N="100">Whi beet &thorn;ou him, &amp; f&oacute;rbare me?</L>
<L>&para; Made he &thorn;ee nou&yogh;t? my&yogh;te &thorn;ou not blynne?</L>
<L>For ouermyche &thorn;ou fraiedist &thorn;at free;</L>
<L>&THORN;oru&yogh;-out his bodi no place was inne,</L>
<L N="104">Bo&thorn;e fleisch &amp; blood &thorn;ou pullidist with &thorn;ee:</L>
<L>&para; &THORN;ou madist ful blac &thorn;at was bri&yogh;t of blee,</L>
<L>&THORN;ou schalt oonis come to oure conquest.</L>
<L>O fadir of heuene! now haue pitee</L>
<L N="108">&THORN;at 'filius regis mortuus est.'</L>
</LG>
<LG N="10" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(10)</HEAD>
<L>Also &thorn;ou beest must bere &thorn;e galle</L>
<L>&THORN;at he schulde drinke; &thorn;ou pynest him more!</L>
<L>Vpon my knees here dowun y falle,</L>
<L N="112">And axe iuggement of heuen &thorn;erfore;</L>
<L>&para; And moost y crie on &yogh;ou iewis alle,</L>
<L>For &yogh;it my&yogh;te noon of hem so him haue to-tore,</L>
<L>Of alle &thorn;ese &thorn;e instrumentis &thorn;at y on calle,</L>
<L N="116">But &yogh;e hem made to greue him so sore.</L>
<L>&para; He made &yogh;ou iewis: &yogh;ou to restore</L>
<L>He come to &yogh;e er&thorn;e; &amp; now &yogh;e encreest</L>
<L>His pyne: <MILESTONE N="80" UNIT="page">alas, &thorn;at euere &yogh;e were bore!</L>
<L N="120">For 'filius regis mortuus est.'
<PB REF="00000287.tif" N="237"></L>
</LG>
<LG N="11" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(11)</HEAD>
<L><B>O</B> &yogh;e fals iewis! whi dide &yogh;e &thorn;us,</L>
<L>Him &thorn;us to slee, &yogh;oure sauyour?</L>
<L>Whanne he sitti&thorn; for iuge, whidir wole &yogh;e trus?</L>
<L N="124">&YOGH;e moun not hide &yogh;ou from his reddour.</L>
<L>&para; Alle o&thorn;ere creaturis ben peteuose;</L>
<L>&THORN;e sunne, &thorn;e cloudis, for his dolour,</L>
<L>Schewith her moornynge; but &yogh;e viciose,</L>
<L N="128">&YOGH;oure lau&yogh;inge doo&thorn; him dishonour.</L>
<L>&para; &THORN;e er&thorn;e qwakid temple &amp; tour</L>
<L>To bere &yogh;ou synnful, proud, &amp; prest;</L>
<L>&THORN;e sunne &yogh;eue &yogh;ou no li&yogh;t &thorn;is hour,</L>
<L N="132">For 'filius regis mortuus est.'</L>
</LG>
<LG N="12" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(12)</HEAD>
<L>Now 'mortuus est' my fair lord!</L>
<L>Now deed is my dere child, alas!</L>
<L>Now y may walke in &thorn;is world</L>
<L N="136">As a wrecche &thorn;at wanti&thorn; grace!</L>
<L>&para; Al &thorn;is y seie to bere recorde;</L>
<L>Noo lengir my&yogh;te y loke in his face;</L>
<L>&THORN;us y come fro calueriward,</L>
<L N="140">Weping &amp; wailing &thorn;at y born was.</L>
<L>&para; If ony man loue me, lene me a plase</L>
<L>Where y may <MILESTONE N="81" UNIT="page">wepe my fille &amp; reste,</L>
<L>And my sone wole graunte him sum &thorn;at he has</L>
<L N="144">Filius regis mortuus est."
</L>
</LG>

</DIV2>
<DIV2 TYPE="poem"><PB REF="00000288.tif" N="238">
<HEAD>The Virgin's Complaint and Comfort. Filius Regis Mortuus est. Resurrexit: Regis Mortuus est.</HEAD>
<HEADNOTE><P>[<I>Harl. MS.</I> 3954, <I>ab.</I> 1420 A.D.; <I>leaf</I> 90 <I>a.</I>] [12 stanzas of 12 lines each, <I>abab abab bcbc.</I>]</P></HEADNOTE>
<LG N="1" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(1)</HEAD>
<L>as reson hathe rulyd my recles mynde,</L>
<L>Be a wey wandryng as I went,</L>
<L>A solom cite me fortunyd to fynde.</L>
<L N="4">To turne &thorn;er-to was myne entent;</L>
<L>A louely lady, a maydyn hende,</L>
<L>I met here mornyng; but wath sche ment</L>
<L>I kowde no&yogh;t knowyn; but fast sche pynyd,</L>
<L N="8">Sche swonnyde, sche seyd, &amp; was nere schent.</L>
<L>&THORN;at blissid beerde fro grownd I hent,</L>
<L>Wyth water I wesche here face &amp; brest;</L>
<L>Her here, her skyn, sche raside &amp; rent,</L>
<L N="12">And seyd "<B>filius regis mortuus est.</B></L>
</LG>
<LG N="2" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(2)</HEAD>
<L>&THORN;e kynges sone," sche seyd, "is dede!</L>
<L>Hyest in heuene his fader is;</L>
<L>I am his moder &thorn;orowe his manhede,</L>
<L N="16">In bedlem I bare &yogh;our alderes blisse,</L>
<L>In circumsicion I saw hym blede,</L>
<L>&THORN;at prince present I-wys.</L>
<L>In a tempille, as lawe gan lede,</L>
<L N="20">Tirtildovys I offerid a-bouyn al &thorn;is;</L>
<L>In-to egipt I fled, as m[o]der his,</L>
<L>And lost hym, &amp; fond hym at a fest</L>
<L>&THORN;er he tornyd water in-to wyn I-wis;</L>
<L N="24">And nowe: <B>filius regis mortuus est.</B>
<PB REF="00000289.tif" N="239"></L>
</LG>
<LG N="3" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(3)</HEAD>
<L>"Whan he was ded &amp; hang on a tre,</L>
<L>iiij flodes of paradice fro hym ran;</L>
<L>I cried, 'dere sone, seist &thorn;u no&yogh;t me,</L>
<L N="28">Thi karefulle moder blo &amp; wanne?'<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. wanme.</NOTE></L>
<L>A doleful loke &thorn;an lokede he,</L>
<L>That percyd myn hert, bo&thorn;e blode &amp; bon;</L>
<L>I criede on deth, 'why wilt &thorn;u fle?</L>
<L N="32">Cum, sle his moder, &thorn;u morder man!</L>
<L>Why slest &thorn;ou my sone? cum, sle me &thorn;an!</L>
<L>Why comst &thorn;u no&yogh;t at my request?</L>
<L>&THORN;ou takist fro me alle &thorn;at I wan,</L>
<L N="36">Nowe <B>filius</B> regis <B>mortuus est</B>.'</L>
</LG>
<LG N="4" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(4)</HEAD>
<L>"What wonder is it &thorn;owe I be wo,</L>
<L>For he is dede &thorn;at soke my pappe?</L>
<L>His cors-is graue I come nowe fro,</L>
<L N="40">&THORN;at sumtyme lay quyke on my lappe.</L>
<L>A-las! for sorwe I haue no mo;</L>
<L>I, ka[r]fulle moder, where is myn happe?<MILESTONE N="90b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>Nowe ligi&yogh;t he ded, bo&thorn;e blok &amp; blo!</L>
<L N="44">&THORN;e sonne lost his lith, &thorn;e clowdes gan clappe,</L>
<L>The elementes gonne to rusche &amp; rappe,</L>
<L>And smet downe chirches &amp; templis with crak,</L>
<L>Dede men out of here graue gan skappe,</L>
<L N="48">And seyd <B>filius regis mortuus est</B>."</L>
</LG>
<LG N="5" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(5)</HEAD>
<L>Why deyed &thorn;i sone, &thorn;ou maydyn cha[s]t?</L>
<L>&THORN;e secund persone, &amp; &thorn;e godhede nowt,</L>
<L>Nore &thorn;e thirde persone, &thorn;e holigost,</L>
<L N="52">&THORN;is merueli&yogh;t me meche in my thowt.</L>
<L>For wysdome to &thorn;o sone was be-tawte<NOTE PLACE="foot">These lines do not rhyme with 1 and 3 of this stanza, as the others in the poem do.</NOTE></L>
<L>Whan Adam to synne was browt,</L>
<L>iij for iij &thorn;at we xulde trespace nowt;<NOTE PLACE="foot">These lines do not rhyme with 1 and 3 of this stanza, as the others in the poem do.</NOTE>
<PB REF="00000290.tif" N="240"></L>
<L N="56">But maker of redempcion was or we were wrowt.</L>
<L>Adam to a tre his hand&euml;s cawt;</L>
<L>Cristis handis to a tre were fest;</L>
<L>To felle our fon our frendis fawt,</L>
<L N="60">And &thorn;er <B>filius regis mortuus est.</B></L>
</LG>
<LG N="6" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(6)</HEAD>
<L>Seynt poule seythe he deyed for alle;</L>
<L>Why were not alle men sauyd &thorn;an?</L>
<L>Sent austyn answerid in generalle,</L>
<L N="64">He deyid for euery leuyng man.</L>
<L>Hym self&euml; &thorn;at wille not god calle,</L>
<L>He wylle not leue &thorn;at he hym whan;<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>for</I> wan.</NOTE></L>
<L>What wonder is it, &thorn;owe he be thralle</L>
<L N="68">That byndi&yogh;t hym selfe, &amp; not vn-lose can?</L>
<L>&THORN;e blod &thorn;at fro his syd&euml;s ran</L>
<L>Whan alle &thorn;is werlde was derke, est &amp; west,</L>
<L>Ther-for I syng as I be-gan,</L>
<L N="72"><B>Filius regis mortuus est.</B></L>
</LG>
<LG N="7" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(7)</HEAD>
<L>"Go, loke," sche seyid, "whille &thorn;ou mayst se,</L>
<L>I may no lenger taryon out of towne."</L>
<L>I toke my gate up to &thorn;e tre</L>
<L N="76">&THORN;&eacute;r &thorn;e blod was rennyng downe:</L>
<L>iij dayis I dithe me &thorn;er to be,</L>
<L>For pete of his pass&iuml;on,</L>
<L>Sithen to his graue he went a-lone fro me.</L>
<L N="80">iij women I met with precess&iuml;on,</L>
<L>I askyd hem whedir &thorn;at &thorn;ei were bone;</L>
<L>Fulle sone &thorn;ei toke sorowe with-outyn rest,</L>
<L>&YOGH;et &thorn;ei answerid with dollefulle sone,<MILESTONE N="91" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="84">And seyd, <B>Filius regis mortuus est.</B></L>
</LG>
<LG N="8" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(8)</HEAD>
<L>So to his graue I went ful rythe,</L>
<L>And pursuyd after to wetyn an ende;
<PB REF="00000291.tif" N="241"></L>
<L>I sawe angelis with gret lithe</L>
<L N="88">Of seraphynnys order adowne gan sende.</L>
<L>&THORN;e women, &thorn;ei sobbid, &amp; mornyd sore in sithe;</L>
<L>&THORN;ei seyd, "we leyd hym here with oure hande."</L>
<L>&THORN;e angelis answeryd with wordis rythe,</L>
<L N="92">And seyd, "is not here &thorn;at &yogh;e wende;</L>
<L>He is resyn, as he &yogh;owe kennyd,</L>
<L>And in to galalye forthe is prest."</L>
<L>Here chere &amp; comfort gan a-mende,</L>
<L N="96">For <B>resurrexit! non</B> mortuus <B>est!</B></L>
</LG>
<LG N="9" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(9)</HEAD>
<L>To telle &thorn;is tale I hied me fast,</L>
<L>That <B>filius regis.</B> was resyn a-geyn;</L>
<L>B&eacute; a tempille as I forthe past,</L>
<L N="100">I herd wepyng with mech&euml; peyn;</L>
<L>A woman I sawe &thorn;ere at &thorn;e last</L>
<L>That I first met, with-outyn layn,</L>
<L>Ful doofully on me here eyn sche cast;</L>
<L N="104">But howe sche ferd, fast I gan frayn:</L>
<L>"A-las," sche sayd, "I am vn-fayn</L>
<L>To se my sone in &thorn;is dissesse."</L>
<L>&THORN;an to &thorn;at ladi I answerid a-gayn,</L>
<L N="108">And seyd, "<B>filius regis</B> non mortuus <B>est."</B></L>
</LG>
<LG N="10" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(10)</HEAD>
<L>Seynt thomes seythe, &amp; oder doctours an heppe,</L>
<L>&THORN;at first he apperid to our ladi dere;</L>
<L>His dethe to here hert sanke most depe</L>
<L N="112">For sche was most of his chere;</L>
<L>So bryth, so gloriouce, &thorn;e sonne increppe,</L>
<L>His schynyng merkes here bodi bare,</L>
<L>He salutyd his moder with gret worchepe,</L>
<L N="116">&THORN;at salutacion I herd neuere are,</L>
<L>"<B>Salue</B>, sancta <B>parens!"</B> I trowe it ware,&mdash;</L>
<L>In latyne is wretyn fulle honest,&mdash;</L>
<L>"My blissid moder for euer-mare!</L>
<L N="120">For <B>resurrexit!</B> non mortuus <B>est!</B>"
<PB REF="00000292.tif" N="242"></L>
</LG>
<LG N="11" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(11)</HEAD>
<L>"&THORN;is was gret mervayle for to se,</L>
<L>&THORN;e ertdly moder &thorn;at kyng to susteyne;</L>
<L>Sweche ioy and solemp[ni]te,</L>
<L N="124">Be-forn ne after was neuer seyn;</L>
<L>The erde is glad, &thorn;e sunne is fre,<MILESTONE N="91b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>&THORN;e sunne is glad &thorn;at it brythe xalle bene,</L>
<L>And neuer after so blac to sene.</L>
<L N="128">&THORN;e werlde<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. welrde</NOTE> is glad, &amp; hath grace sene,</L>
<L>Alle cristen pepill glad xal bene</L>
<L>&THORN;at crist is bo&thorn;&euml; k[i]ng and prest;</L>
<L>Nowe is seyd <B>hec dies</B> for ioye, I wene,</L>
<L N="132">That <B>resurrexit!</B> non mortuus <B>est!</B>"</L>
</LG>
<LG N="12" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(12)</HEAD>
<L>Syn he was lord &amp; k[i]ng ouer alle,</L>
<L>Had mythe &amp; powere of good &amp; ille,</L>
<L>Whi wolde he not at oo word calle</L>
<L N="136">&THORN;e soulis fro heuene at his owyn wille,</L>
<L>But &thorn;us to be ded &amp; thralle?</L>
<L>To &thorn;is oure gloce wylle answere tylle:</L>
<L>He leet his mythe at &thorn;at tyme falle,</L>
<L N="140">And wrowt wisdomys folle sotylle,</L>
<L>To bie our soulis &thorn;at were hese with skille.</L>
<L>&THORN;e fende of mankende had gret tryste;</L>
<L>There lost he his cause; &thorn;at lekid hym ille,</L>
<L N="144">Whan <B>filius regis mortuus est</B>.</L>
<TRAILER>Explicit Filius Regis . &middot; .</TRAILER>
</LG>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 TYPE="poem">

<PB REF="00000293.tif" N="243">
<HEAD>Part of a Meditation of St. Augustine.</HEAD>
<HEADNOTE><P>IN the 1866 issue of the stereotyped edition of Mr. Craik's <I>Compendious History of the English Language</I>, v. 1, p. 193, is the following passage quoted from Sir Frederic Madden's Preface to <I>Havelok:</I> "Between the years 1244 and 1258, we know, was written the versification of part of a meditation of St. Augustine, as proved by the age of the prior who gave the MS. to the Durham Library, MS. Eccl. Dun. A. iii. 12, and Bodl. 42." On my applying to the Librarian at Durham for further information about this piece of verse, the Rev. W. Greenwell answered, "It is upon a small piece of vellum, inserted, and forms no part of the original volume. I send you a correct copy." The Rev. H. O. Coxe, Bodleian Librarian, has also kindly sent me a copy of the Bodleian version, which I print side by side with the Durham one. Mr. Coxe dates the Oxford copy at from 1300 to 1320 A.D.</P></HEADNOTE>
<DIV3 TYPE="version">
<HEAD><I>MS. Eccl. Dun. A</I>. III. 12.</HEAD>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Wyth was his halude brest</L>
<L>and red of blod his syde</L>
<L>Bleye was his fair handled</L>
<L>his wund dop ant wide</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>And his arms ystreith</L>
<L>hey up-hon &thorn;e rode</L>
<L>On fif studes on his body</L>
<L>&thorn;e stremes ran o blode.<NOTE PLACE="end">(P.S.&mdash;See Sir F. Madden's print of the Oxford copy, with the original Latin, in <I>Warton</I>, v. 1, p. 24, note, ed. 1840.)</NOTE></L>
</LG>
</DIV3>
<DIV3 TYPE="version">
<HEAD><I>MS. Bodl</I>. 42, <I>fol</I>. 250.</HEAD>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Wit was his nakede brest</L>
<L>and red of blod his side</L>
<L>Blod was his faire neb</L>
<L>his wnden depe an uide</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Starke waren his armes</L>
<L>Hi-spred opon &thorn;e rode</L>
<L>In fif steden in his bodi</L>
<L>Stremes hurne of blode.<NOTE PLACE="end">(P.S.&mdash;See Sir F. Madden's print of the Oxford copy, with the original Latin, in <I>Warton</I>, v. 1, p. 24, note, ed. 1840.)</NOTE>
</L>
</LG>

</DIV3>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 TYPE="poem"><PB REF="00000294.tif" N="244">
<HEAD TYPE="main">The Seven Deadly Sins, OR "GYF ME LYSENS TO LYVE IN EASE."</HEAD>
<HEADNOTE><P>[MS. Univ. Lib. Camb. Ff. 1. 6. fol. 56 <I>b</I>. Handwriting of the 15th century. Every <I>ll</I> has a stroke through it, and most of the final <I>n</I>'s have a stroke over them as here indicated.]</P></HEADNOTE>
<LG N="1" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(1)</HEAD>
<L>As I walkyd apon a day</L>
<L>To take the eyre of fylde &amp; floure,</L>
<L>Apon a mylde mornyng of may,</L>
<L N="4">when floures ben full of swete savoure,</L>
<L>I harde on say, "o god! for ay?</L>
<L>hough long shall I leve in my doloure?"</L>
<L>Apon hys kn&euml;ys he gan pray,</L>
<L N="8">"Swete Ihesu, sende me sum socoure,</L>
<L>Maryes son, most of honoure,</L>
<L>That ryche &amp; pore may ponyche &amp; please,</L>
<L>lys me now in my longoure,</L>
<L N="12">And gyf me lysens to lyve in ease.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="2" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(2)</HEAD>
<L>To lyve in ease, thy lawes to kepe,</L>
<L>Graunt me grace, lorde in blys soo bryght,</L>
<L>That I neuer in that caban crepe</L>
<L N="16">Ther lusifer ys lokyn with-outyn lyght.</L>
<L>My myddell woundys, they ben derne &amp; depe,</L>
<L>Ther ys no plaster that persyth aryght,</L>
<L>her smertyng wyll nat suffre me to slepe,</L>
<L N="20">Tyll a leche with dewte have th&emacr;m dyght.</L>
<L>hit most be a cnect, a crouned wyght,</L>
<L>That knowth that quaysy from ben &amp; pese,</L>
<L>Or ellys theyre medsyns they haue no myght</L>
<L N="24">To geve a man lysens to lyve in ease.
<PB REF="00000295.tif" N="245"></L>
</LG>
<LG N="3" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(3)</HEAD>
<L>This wound norysshyth woundes sevyn;</L>
<L>'Superbia' ys the most prinsipall,</L>
<L>'pryde pertly' in englysshe steven,</L>
<L N="28">For he ys more bytter then euer was gall.</L>
<L>I haue had ther-to lechys aleven,<MILESTONE N="57" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>and they gave me medysins all.</L>
<L>The souereynyst medysyn that ys vnder heven,</L>
<L N="32">hyt growes nother in ground nother wall;</L>
<L>'vmylitas' I hard a clerke it call;</L>
<L>had I hit, I were at ease.</L>
<L>larde! sende it vnto the syke thralle,<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. tharlle.</NOTE></L>
<L N="36">and gyff me lysens to lyve in ease.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="4" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(4)</HEAD>
<L>A wycked wound hath me walled,</L>
<L>And traveyld me from topp to too;</L>
<L>This wracched worlde hit may be called,</L>
<L N="40">hit hath many a blayne black and bloo.</L>
<L>hit hurtys my soule, it makes me to halt,</L>
<L>In hed, in hond, in hart al-soo.</L>
<L>Nad I ben babtyzyd in water and salt,</L>
<L N="44">This ferdly fester wolde neuer me froo.</L>
<L>This leche lyssyd me, lazars, &amp; moo,</L>
<L>Davith and danyell, of her dysease.</L>
<L>Amend my wound that doth me woo,</L>
<L N="48">And gyff me lysens to lyve in ease.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="5" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(5)</HEAD>
<L>'Invidia' the therd wound ys,</L>
<L>A wyckkyd gnawer, or venym, or gowt;</L>
<L>he ys a wyckyd wound, I gess,</L>
<L N="52">Ther he hath power to Reyne or Rought.</L>
<L>The condyssion of the wound ys this,</L>
<L>To bren my brest with-in and with-oute.</L>
<L>I asked a lech what myght me lyss,</L>
<L N="56">he toke me 'carytas,' and put it in a clout,
<PB REF="00000296.tif" N="246"></L>
<L>And bade me bame me well aboute,<MILESTONE N="57b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>when hit wolde other water or wese;</L>
<L>And sone after, with-outyn doute,</L>
<L N="60">Than shold I have lysens to lyve in ease.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="6" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(6)</HEAD>
<L>'Ira' ys a wyckyd wound;</L>
<L>he ravesshith me, both raw and rede;</L>
<L>And all my cors he woll confound,</L>
<L N="64">so sore he swellyth in hart and hede;</L>
<L>There ys non erbe that growyth on grounde,</L>
<L>Nor no coresy may queth that qued,</L>
<L>Set 'amor cum paciencia,' in a littyll stound;</L>
<L N="68">For he wyll drey ham and make ham ded.</L>
<L>Lord! sende me sum 'amor' sede,</L>
<L>In my gardyn to rote and ryse;</L>
<L>Or ellys, as seker as men ete bred,</L>
<L N="72">I shall neuer have lysens to lyve in ease.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="7" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(7)</HEAD>
<L>'Auaryssia' ys a [balefull bane,]<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. "a souking sore," copied from l. 85.</NOTE></L>
<L>he bladdyrth and byldeth all in my boure;</L>
<L>he makyth me to swell, both flesh and veyne,</L>
<L N="76">And kepith me low lyke a cochoure.</L>
<L>I have herde of an erbe to lyss that peyne,</L>
<L>Men seyth it bereth a doubyll floure;</L>
<L>'vigilate, et orate:' vse well they tweyne,</L>
<L N="80">That shall help the of thy doloure,</L>
<L>As sekere as bred ys made of floure,</L>
<L>Smell them in sesyn with thy nese;</L>
<L>The swetness of that savoure</L>
<L N="84">Shall geve the lysens to lyve in ease.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="8" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(8)</HEAD>
<L>'Accidia' ys a souking sore,<MILESTONE N="58" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>he traveylyth me from day to day,</L>
<L>And euer he wyll have more and more</L>
<L N="88">Plasters than he purvey may.
<PB REF="00000297.tif" N="247"></L>
<L>I axst a mayster of fysyke lore,</L>
<L>what wold hym drye and dryve away?</L>
<L>'Elymosina' ys an erbe ther-fore,</L>
<L N="92">Oon of the best that euer I say;</L>
<L>Noynt hem ther-wyth ay when thow may,</L>
<L>Thingk that Requiem shall in the rent &amp; sese,</L>
<L>And sone after, with-in a nyght &amp; a day,</L>
<L N="96">Thou shalt haue lysens to lyve in ease.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="9" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(9)</HEAD>
<L>'Gula' ys a grevous gall;</L>
<L>he bereueth my rest all in my bed;</L>
<L>So sore I streyne my stomake with-all,</L>
<L N="100">wyth many festys when I am full fed;</L>
<L>I walow as worme doth in wall,</L>
<L>I may nat trest tyll a schamely sched.</L>
<L>Mercy! lorde! to the I call,</L>
<L N="104">For vs thou lettest thy brest be bled.</L>
<L>A leche hath layd hys hed to wed</L>
<L>To make a plaster that wolde me please,</L>
<L>Off abstinaunce; and I it had,</L>
<L N="108">Then sholde I haue lysens to lyve in ease.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="10" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(10)</HEAD>
<L>'Luxiria' ys a lyther mormale;</L>
<L>Mercy! lorde! full of pite;</L>
<L>Thou bringest my body in bitter bale,</L>
<L N="112">And fraill my sowle with thy frailte.</L>
<L>Sumtyme a surioune tolde me a tale;<MILESTONE N="58b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>This was the lessyn that he lerned me;</L>
<L>The rote of an erbe I sholde vp hale,</L>
<L N="116">Men call it 'chastite';<NOTE PLACE="foot">This line and the next are written as one; cf. l. 128.</NOTE></L>
<L>and pounde it with penytencie;</L>
<L>When the ryb wode wyll on the rese,</L>
<L>Drayne it and dringke it with confescion&egrave;,</L>
<L N="120">Then shalt thow haue lysens to lyve in ease.
<PB REF="00000298.tif" N="248"></L>
</LG>
<LG N="11" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(11)</HEAD>
<L>other Erbys ther ben alsoo,</L>
<L>That suffer the sores they may nat swell;</L>
<L>'Orys confescio' ys on of thoo,</L>
<L N="124">he wyll nat suffre no ded flessche for to dwell;</L>
<L>'Cordys contrycio' ys the too,</L>
<L>A wasshyth the woundes as doth a well;</L>
<L>'Operys satisfaccio' the souereyne sauetyff,<NOTE PLACE="foot">Or 'sanetyff,' sanative.</NOTE></L>
<L N="128">For soth as I yow tell."</L>
<L>God, that made both hevyn and hell,</L>
<L>geve vs grace to serue and please,</L>
<L>In that worthy blys that we may dwell,</L>
<L N="132">And gyff vs all lysens to lyve in ease!</L>
<TRAILER>Explicit in veritate Da michi quod merui Quod leweston.
</TRAILER>

</LG>
</DIV2>
</DIV1>
<DIV1 TYPE="section"><PB REF="00000299.tif" N="249">
<HEAD>SHORT RELIGIOUS POEMS</HEAD>
<HEADNOTE><P>FROM MS. HARL. 7322 (FIRST TREATISE, OF THE END OF THE 14TH CENTURY, WHICH HAS ENGLISH VERSES MIXED IN THE LATIN PROSE). [The full stops are mostly those of the MS.]</P></HEADNOTE>
<DIV2 TYPE="poem">
<HEAD>Christ on the Cross.</HEAD>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Ho &thorn;at si&thorn; him one &thorn;e Rode.<MILESTONE N="7" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>iesus his lemmon.</L>
<L>And his moder bi him stonde</L>
<L N="4">Sor&euml; wepinde, and seynt iohan.</L>
<L>And his syden istong&euml; sore.</L>
<L>For &thorn;e loue of &thorn;e, man.</L>
<L>Wel shulde he his sunne forsake.</L>
<L N="8">Wet&euml; ter&euml;s and eke leten.</L>
<L>&THORN;at of loue can.</L>
</LG>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 TYPE="poem">
<HEAD>All is Lost on Death.</HEAD>
<HEADNOTE><P>[See p. 253.]</P></HEADNOTE>
<DIV3 TYPE="part">
<HEAD>Memento nouissima tua, quia hec sunt signa mortis, videlicet:&mdash;</HEAD>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Whanne &thorn;e ffet coldet&yogh;.<MILESTONE N="7b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>and &thorn;e tunge ffoldet&yogh;.</L>
<L>And &thorn;e shyne sharpet&yogh;.</L>
<L N="4">And &thorn;e &thorn;rote Rotelet&yogh;.</L>
<L>And &thorn;e hew ffalewet&yogh;.</L>
<L>And &thorn;e Ey&yogh;en dasewet&yogh;
<PB REF="00000300.tif" N="250"></L>
<L>And him atroket&yogh; his bret&yogh;.</L>
<L N="8">And &thorn;e soule a-wey get&yogh;.</L>
<L>And on flore me him strecchet&yogh;.</L>
<L>And litel of him &thorn;anne me recchet&yogh;</L>
<L>And he &thorn;as er so proud.</L>
<L N="12">Ne shal he haue bote a cloud.</L>
<L>And of &thorn;at erer was his</L>
<L>Nou shal he hauen mys.</L>
<L><B>Et nichil de mundo portabit.</B></L>
</LG>
</DIV3>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 TYPE="poem">
<HEAD>All too Late.</HEAD>
<HEADNOTE><P>[See p. 253.]</P></HEADNOTE>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Wonne &thorn;in eren dinet: and &thorn;i nese scharpet.<MILESTONE N="169b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>And &thorn;in hew dunnet: and &thorn;i sennewess starket.</L>
<L>And &thorn;in eyen synket: and &thorn;i tunge foldet.</L>
<L N="4">And &thorn;in honde stinket: and &thorn;in fet coldet&yogh;.</L>
<L>And &thorn;in lippes blaket: and &thorn;in teth ratilet.</L>
<L>And &thorn;in hond quaket: and &thorn;i &thorn;rote rutelet&yogh;.</L>
<L>&mdash;Al to late. al to late. &thorn;en is te wayn atte yate.</L>
<L N="8">For may &thorn;or no man &thorn;enne: penaunce make.</L>
</LG>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 TYPE="poem">
<HEAD>Three Certainties of the Day of Death.</HEAD>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Hit beo&thorn; &thorn;reo tymes on &thorn;o day<MILESTONE N="8" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>&THORN;at so&thorn;e to witen me mai:</L>
<L>&THORN;at on ys, &thorn;at i shal henne;</L>
<L N="4">&THORN;at o&thorn;er, &thorn;at y not whenne;</L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;ridde is my moste care,</L>
<L>&THORN;at y not whider i shal fare.</L>
</LG>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 TYPE="poem">
<HEAD>Marriage.</HEAD>
<P>&para; Nupcie moriar, quia nubere dulce est.</P>
<P><B>For hit is mury to beon a</B> wife.</P>
<P>Anglice sic:</P>
<P><B>ich wolle leose my</B> life.
</P>

</DIV2>
<DIV2 TYPE="poem"><PB REF="00000301.tif" N="251">
<HEAD>Sins of our Time.</HEAD>
<HEADNOTE><P>[<I>Written as prose</I>.]</P></HEADNOTE>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; &YOGH;issinge and glosinge and felsship beon riue.<MILESTONE N="64" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>lu&thorn;er lustes ouer floten. with fals gile and strife</L>
<L>hardnesse and bakbiting wi&thorn; scornes out bersten;</L>
<L N="4">Bote almus dede and trou&thorn;e, wi&thorn; semli plei &thorn;ei resten.</L>
<L>vnkundenesse, vnkunninge, vnclannesse, beon arerd</L>
<L>so &thorn;at harmes &thorn;ei boden, as ich am aferd.</L>
</LG>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 TYPE="poem">
<HEAD>Some go up, and some go down, in this World.</HEAD>
<HEADNOTE><P>[<I>Printed in Rel. Ant.</I>, v. 1, p. 64.]</P></HEADNOTE>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>"Kinge i sitte, and loke aboute,<MILESTONE N="79" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>to morwen y mai beon wi&thorn;oute."</L>
<L>"Wo is me, a kinge ich was;</L>
<L N="4">&THORN;is world, ich louede bote &thorn;at, ilas!</L>
<L>Nouth longe gon i was ful riche;</L>
<L>Now is riche and poure iliche."</L>
<L>"Ich shal beo kinge, &thorn;at men shulle seo,</L>
<L N="8">When &thorn;ou, wrecch&euml;, ded shalt beo."<MILESTONE N="79b" UNIT="folio"></L>
</LG>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 TYPE="poem">
<HEAD>Four Proverbs.</HEAD>
<HEADNOTE><P>[<I>See Wright's Political Songs</I> (<I>Camden Soc.</I>, 1839), p. 386-7.]</P></HEADNOTE>
<P>&para; primus dixit Mith&yogh; is Rith&yogh;;<MILESTONE N="91b" UNIT="folio"> lith&yogh; is nith&yogh;; Fith&yogh; is flith&yogh;.</P>
<P>&para; secundus dixit On is two; frend is foo; wil is wo.</P>
<P>&para; tercius dixit lust hath leue; &yogh;ist is Reue; prude hath sleue.
<PB REF="00000302.tif" N="252"></P>
<P>&para; quartus dixit wil is Red wit is qued God is ded</P>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 TYPE="poem">
<P>nota <B>de</B> mirabilibus mundi.</P>
<P>Narrat solinus de mirabilibus mundi de quadam<MILESTONE N="103" UNIT="folio"> aue, que in nido suo facit duo foramina, vnum versus orientem, et aliud versus occidentem, vt per primum cicius videat solem de mane, &amp; per 2<SUP>m</SUP> diucius de sero. Et per primum exit de mane, &amp; per secundum intrat sero. Spiritualiter auis iste est quili|bet fidelis qui sibi facit duo foramina in nido, 1. in corde suo, &amp; in prima porta orientali, per quam ingre|ditur mundum, inuenient tres 'welcomeres' horribiles, videlicet.</P>
<P>Welcomers: nuditas; Fletus; debilitas;</P>
<P>Anglice: nakednesse; Reminge; feblesse;</P>
<P>Vel aliter sic quilibet intrat per portas, scilicet, nasty; sory; vnmi&yogh;ty; Et certe clamat .A. quod est primum nominis Ade; in qua litera sunt Anguli ad designandum tria incomoda, que quilibet nostrum incurrit quando noscitur; vnde quilibet nostrum quando flet &amp; clamat, .A. quasi dolens, diceret in Anglico sic, videlicet,</P>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Wi&thorn; wo &amp; drede i am born;<MILESTONE N="103b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>Al for adam y am lorn;</L>
<L>To wo and sorwe brou&yogh;t y am,</L>
<L>&THORN;at ha&thorn; mad &thorn;i sinne, Adam.</L>
<L>Teone and trauail shal beo my lif.</L>
<L>&YOGH;eru&thorn;e, Adam, haue &thorn;e sti&thorn;.</L>
</LG>
<P>Vt pro isto dici potest istud psalmi: "In peccatis concepit me mater mea." iob., etc.</P>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 TYPE="poem">

<PB REF="00000303.tif" N="253">
<HEAD>Signs of Death.</HEAD>
<HEADNOTE><P>[<I>Printed in Rel. Ant.</I>, v. 1, p. 64-5. <I>See</I> p. 249-50 <I>of this Text</I>.]</P></HEADNOTE>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Alle his frendes he shal beo lo&thorn;,<MILESTONE N="121" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>And helud shal ben wi&thorn; a clo&thorn;,</L>
<L>Hyse eres shullen dewen,</L>
<L N="4">&amp; his eyen shullen dymmen,</L>
<L>&amp; his nese shal sharpen,</L>
<L>&amp; his skyn shal starken,</L>
<L>&amp; his hew shal falewen,</L>
<L N="8">&amp; his tonge shal stameren, o&thorn;er famelen,</L>
<L>&amp; his lippes shulle bliken,</L>
<L>&amp; his hondes shulle quaken,</L>
<L>&amp; his te&thorn; shulle Ratelen,</L>
<L N="12">&amp; his &thorn;rote shal Rotelen,</L>
<L>&amp; his feet shullen streken,</L>
<L>&amp; his herte shal breken;</L>
<L>&amp; of al &thorn;is wordles b[l]isse,</L>
<L N="16">ne woldy &yogh;eue a pese iwis.</L>
<L>&thorn;ou &thorn;at art so proud,</L>
<L>Ne shalt &thorn;ou haue bote a clout.</L>
</LG>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 TYPE="poem">
<HEAD>The Covetous Man.</HEAD>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>On hit is, and ne haue&thorn; no&thorn;er<MILESTONE N="121b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>sone, ne suster, ne nou&thorn;er bro&thorn;er;</L>
<L>Ne he nere blynne&thorn; of trauaillinge,</L>
<L N="4">he nis no child of god halewinge,</L>
<L>for one him self he ne &thorn;enke&thorn;,</L>
<L>for wham he wake&thorn; and harde swinke&thorn;,</L>
<L>he wakke&thorn; bo&thorn;e dai and ni&yogh;t,</L>
<L N="8">&amp; lete&thorn; his soule ben vuel di&yogh;t.
</L>
</LG>

</DIV2>
<DIV2 TYPE="poem"><PB REF="00000304.tif" N="254">
<HEAD>Death.</HEAD>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="4">Est enim mors: mendacissima;<MILESTONE N="124b" UNIT="folio"> Occultissima; repacissima; seuerissima;</L>
<L>&thorn;o dedtur so is fals and falende,</L>
<L>Stille and eke stalkinge,</L>
<L>Gredy and Crepynge,</L>
<L N="8">steorne and eke stellende</L>
</LG>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 TYPE="poem">
<HEAD>Christ announces his Coming.</HEAD>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>"Nou &yogh;e alle beo glad and bli&thorn;e,<MILESTONE N="133b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>For i come to leden ou swi&thorn;e."</L>
<L>In quibus verbis quatuor proponam questiones. . .<NOTE PLACE="inter">quatuor questiones sunt:</NOTE></L>
<L N="4">"Ho art &thorn;ou &thorn;at comest so litel and so mithful?</L>
<L>Ho art &thorn;ou &thorn;at comest so dredful And so Rithful?</L>
<L>Ho art &thorn;ou &thorn;at comest so &yogh;onge And so connynge?</L>
<L>Ho art &thorn;ou &thorn;at comest so pore And al weldynge?"</L>
<L N="8">&para; Ad primam reponem, &amp; ad omnes alias:&mdash;</L>
<L>"ich am a knyth for ou to fithten;</L>
<L>ich am a pledour ou lede to Rithte;</L>
<L>ich am a maister to teche &thorn;e lawe;</L>
<L N="12">ich am an emperour, a god felawe."</L>
</LG>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 TYPE="poem">
<HEAD>Learn Love from Christ's Sufferings.</HEAD>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Biholt, &thorn;ou man wi&thorn; Routhful herte,<MILESTONE N="134" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>&THORN;e sharp&euml; scourge wi&thorn; knott&euml;s smerte!</L>
<L>Mi blodi bak wi&thorn; hit his beten:</L>
<L N="4">Leorn&euml;, mon, &thorn;i lust to leten;</L>
<L>For, wi&thorn; &thorn;is sper &thorn;at is so gril,</L>
<L>Min herte was stoungen, so was my uel,</L>
<L>For loue of &thorn;e &thorn;at was so dere;</L>
<L N="8">Wel au&yogh;test &thorn;ou of loue to lere.
</L>
</LG>

</DIV2>
<DIV2 TYPE="poem"><PB REF="00000305.tif" N="255">
<HEAD>Love Christ who Loves Thee.</HEAD>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Leorne to loue, as ich loue &thorn;e;<MILESTONE N="135b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>On alle my lym&euml;s &thorn;ou mith seo</L>
<L N="3">Hou sore ich quake for colde;</L>
<L>For &thorn;e ich soffre muche colde &amp; wo;</L>
<L>Loue me wel, and nomo;</L>
<L N="6">To &thorn;e i take and holde.</L>
</LG>
<P>Et Regina mater sua nichil habuit vnde posset eum induere; ideo dixit sibi:&mdash;</P>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 TYPE="poem">
<HEAD>(The Virgin's Song to her Baby Christ.)</HEAD>
<LG N="1" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(1)</HEAD>
<L>Iesu, swet&euml; son&euml; dere!<MILESTONE N="135b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>On porful bed, list &thorn;ou here,</L>
<L N="3">And &thorn;at me greue&thorn; sore;</L>
<L>For &thorn;i cradel is ase a bere,</L>
<L>Oxe and ass&euml; be&thorn; &thorn;i fere;</L>
<L N="6">Weope ich mai &thorn;ar-fore.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="2" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(2)</HEAD>
<L>Iesu, swete, beo noth wro&thorn;</L>
<L>&THORN;ou ich nabb&euml; clout ne clo&thorn;</L>
<L N="9">&THORN;e on for to folde,</L>
<L>&THORN;e on to fold&euml; ne to wrappe;</L>
<L>For ich nabb&euml; clout ne lappe;</L>
<L>Bote ley &thorn;ou &thorn;i fet to my pappe,</L>
<L N="13">And wite &thorn;e from &thorn;e colde.</L>
</LG>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 TYPE="poem">
<HEAD>The Vanity of this Life.</HEAD>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN;e lif of &thorn;is world<MILESTONE N="136b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>Ys Reuled wi&thorn; wynd.</L>
<L>Wepinge, derknesse,<NOTE PLACE="foot">'derknesse' probably for 'drednesse.' The Latin has Flatum, Fletum, Motum, Metum.</NOTE> a[n]d steriynge;</L>
<L N="4">Wi&thorn; wind we blowen,</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; wind we lassun.
<PB REF="00000306.tif" N="256"></L>
<L>Wi&thorn; weopinge we comen,</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; weopinge we passun.</L>
<L N="8">Wi&thorn; steriinge we byginnen,</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; steriinge we enden;</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; drede we dwellen,</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; drede we wenden.</L>
</LG>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 TYPE="poem">
<HEAD>Man made God's Brother.</HEAD>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN;is tim&euml; man ha&thorn; ouercome<MILESTONE N="138b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>&THORN;e fend, and Robbed helle;</L>
<L>Lok&euml; &thorn;at, on his seruise,</L>
<L N="4">Lenge &thorn;at &thorn;ou ne dwelle;</L>
<L>&THORN;is time man is mad kni&yogh;th</L>
<L>And shuppare ouer alle &thorn;inge;</L>
<L>Loke, on non erliche &thorn;inge</L>
<L N="8">&THORN;ou sett&euml; &thorn;yn endinge;</L>
<L>For now is erlich man bicome</L>
<L>God&euml;s owene bro&thorn;er;</L>
<L>Loke, man, on non&euml; wyse</L>
<L N="12">&THORN;ou chaunge for non o&thorn;er.</L>
</LG>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 TYPE="poem">
<HEAD>In Weal think of Woe.</HEAD>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>In die bonorum non inmemor sis malorum.<MILESTONE N="139b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>yn time of wele &thorn;enke on &thorn;i wo.</L>
<L>for &thorn;e wele of &thorn;is world wole sone go.</L>
</LG>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 TYPE="poem">
<HEAD>Four Evils.</HEAD>
<P>. . &amp; facit quatuor mala vbi regnant secundum quod<MILESTONE N="140b" UNIT="folio"> componitur ex quatuor literis. P. R. E. D. Vnde Anglice:</P>
<P>Anglice:</P>
<P>Hey Priuet&yogh; gritliche;</P>
<P>Hey Robbet&yogh; holliche:</P>
<P>Hey Endet&yogh; shameliche:</P>
<P>Hey Drawe&thorn; dredfulliche.
</P>

</DIV2>
<DIV2 TYPE="poem"><PB REF="00000307.tif" N="257">
<HEAD>Humility.</HEAD>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>A tokne of godes louiinge,<MILESTONE N="141b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>A sheld of mithful wynninge,</L>
<L>A Celer of siker kepinge,</L>
<L N="4">A keye of Redi vndoinge.</L>
</LG>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 TYPE="poem">
<HEAD>Eve, Mary, and Paradise.</HEAD>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN;e &yogh;ates of Parais<MILESTONE N="143" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>&THORN;oruth eue weren iloken;</L>
<L>and &thorn;oruth oure swete ladi,</L>
<L N="4">A&yogh;ein hui beo&thorn; nou&thorn;e open.</L>
</LG>
<P>Ideo ista humilitas dici potest 'clauis Dauid,' de quo habetur Apocalypsi 3, que claudit, &amp; nemo aperit.</P>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 TYPE="poem">
<HEAD>Envy.</HEAD>
<P>De isto malo dicit Angustinus, quod est aliene<MILESTONE N="143b" UNIT="folio"> felicitatis tristicia, et aduersitatis leticia: ista est mala condicio, &amp; summe cauenda propter quatuor: videlicet:</P>
<P>quia hit Rote&thorn; and brenne&thorn;, Hit frete&thorn; and twynne&thorn;.</P>
<P>&amp; ideo est sicut anglice dicitur, videlicet:</P>
<P>Ase:</P>
<P>&thorn;e worm on &thorn;e treo,</P>
<P>and &thorn;e hul on &thorn;e see,</P>
<P>and roust on &thorn;e knife,</P>
<P>and ase de&thorn; to &thorn;e life.</P>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 TYPE="poem">
<HEAD>The Evils of this Time.</HEAD>
<P>Set heu . . . raro inuenitur amor siue caritas! ideo<MILESTONE N="145" UNIT="folio"> dolorose potest dici modo istud Anglice:</P>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Loue is out of lond iwent;</L>
<L N="4">Defaute of loue &thorn;is lond ha&thorn; shent.<MILESTONE N="145b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>Reuth&thorn;e and treuth&thorn;e and charite</L>
<L>Be&thorn; out of lond, alle &thorn;reo:
<PB REF="00000308.tif" N="258"></L>
<L>Prude, enuye, and lecherie,</L>
<L N="8">Couetise, and tricherie,</L>
<L>Habbe&thorn; &thorn;is lond one here baillye.</L>
</LG>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 TYPE="poem">
<HEAD>Cupidity.</HEAD>
<P>Cupiditas.:</P>
<P>hit false&thorn;<MILESTONE N="145b" UNIT="folio"></P>
<P>hit reyme&thorn;</P>
<P>hit falle&thorn;</P>
<P>hit shende&thorn;</P>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 TYPE="poem">
<HEAD>A Triad.</HEAD>
<P>Frendsship &thorn;at is worsshipful<MILESTONE N="150" UNIT="folio"></P>
<P>serte &thorn;at is blisful</P>
<P>wonyinge &thorn;at is ioyeful</P>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 TYPE="poem">
<HEAD>Inscriptions. (<I>See page</I> 260-1.)</HEAD>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN;i wyckede dedis &thorn;e broutte to care. bot is &thorn;e for&yogh;oin,<NOTE PLACE="foot">for&yogh;ouin, p. 264, near the foot.</NOTE> &thorn;ou sinne no mare.<MILESTONE N="153" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>&THORN;e wickede dedis &thorn;e made syke sore. bot al i for-&yogh;iue &thorn;e, &amp; sinne no more.</L>
</LG>
<P>Alius rex s<SUP>i</SUP> dedit coronam auream memoratiuam in qua sic sculpebatur:</P>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN;eng wat &thorn;ou art, &amp; wat &thorn;ou was, &amp; &thorn;at al &thorn;i worssepe of me has.</L>
<L>&THORN;ou &thorn;eng wel on &thorn;ese &thorn;inges &thorn;re; wat tou art, &amp; wat tou were, &amp; al &thorn;e worsse[pe has of me.]</L>
</LG>
<P>Propugnator dedit anulum in quo sic scribebatur per girum.</P>
<P>Sicut te dilexi disce me diligere / nam in toto corpore poteris illud cernere.</P>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Lere to loue as Ic loue &thorn;e; on al my lemes &thorn;ou mait it se. [<I>Repeated, p.</I> 262.]</L>
<L>For &thorn;e I suffrede mikel wo. &thorn;ou loue [me] treuli ant no mo
<PB REF="00000309.tif" N="259"></L>
</LG>
<P>Anulum in quo sic insertum erat:</P>
<L>Noble &thorn;ou art &thorn;at were a-file. be war be onis &thorn;at nout &thorn;e gile. [<I>See p.</I> 261.]</L>
<P>Mediator dedit ei tercium anulum in quo sic scribe|batur:</P>
<L>Wou michel, ant wat, &amp; werfore. wat I haue &thorn;oled for loue of &thorn;e.</L>
<P>Germanus proprius sibi dedit quartum anulum in quo sic erat scriptum:</P>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>I am &thorn;i bro&thorn;er, be nout in wer; be nout agast to come me ner;</L>
<L>I am &thorn;i bro&thorn;er, be nout agast; be hende, &amp; trewe, &amp; sted&euml;fast.</L>
</LG>
<P>A sponso proprio dabatur sibi sigillum vnum per quod hereditas sibi assecurabatur in quo sic:</P>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Here I take &thorn;e to my liue; tac &thorn;ou non o&thorn;er to terme of liue.</L>
<L>Here I take &thorn;e to my spouse; &amp; &yogh;iue &thorn;e bo&thorn;&euml; land &amp; house.</L>
</LG>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 TYPE="poem">
<HEAD>The Signs of Faithful Love.</HEAD>
<P>Nam quatuor sunt signa fidelis Amoris, que ostendit<MILESTONE N="144b" UNIT="folio"> <I>Christus</I>, in quibus nobis exemplum reliquit, videlicet,</P>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>On word [and] &yogh;iuinge,</L>
<L>On werke and soffringe.</L>
</LG>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 TYPE="poem">
<HEAD>Christ Comes.</HEAD>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Wat is he &thorn;is &thorn;at comet so brith<MILESTONE N="153b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>Wit blodi clo&thorn;es al be-dith?</L>
<L>respondentes superiores dixerunt:</L>
<L N="4">"He is bo&thorn;e god and man:</L>
<L>swilc ne sawe neuere nan.</L>
<L>for adamis sinne he suffrede ded.</L>
<L>&amp; &thorn;erfore is his robe so red."
</L>
</LG>

</DIV2>
<DIV2 TYPE="poem"><PB REF="00000310.tif" N="260">
<HEAD>Love.</HEAD>
<P>Bene debent ista exempla nos mouere ad opera<MILESTONE N="145" UNIT="folio"> caritatis, &amp; eciam valor ipsius amoris qui habet con|diciones secundum quod ibi sunt quatuor litere, scilicet, L. O. V. E.</P>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Hit is Lawe &thorn;at saille&thorn; noth,</L>
<L>Hit is Ouer al &thorn;at mai beo wrou&yogh;th,</L>
<L>Hit Werke&thorn; wonderliche,</L>
<L N="4">And Ernes &yogh;eue&thorn; sikerliche.</L>
</LG>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 TYPE="poem">
<HEAD>Poverty.</HEAD>
<P>Nota. non habuit ubi capud potuit reclinare, Mori|endo<MILESTONE N="147b" UNIT="folio"> ubi capud potuit tegere. Inde, bene potuit dicere 'pauper sum ego.' Istud exemplum debemus sequi propter quatuor que faciunt in possessore:</P>
<P>hit reste&thorn; and hit queme&thorn;</P>
<P>hit riche&thorn; and hit deme&thorn;</P>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 TYPE="poem">
<HEAD>Lechery.</HEAD>
<P>Luxuria facit hec primo:</P>
<P>hit waste&thorn;<MILESTONE N="148" UNIT="folio"></P>
<P>hit File&thorn;.</P>
<P>hit wra&thorn;&thorn;e&thorn;</P>
<P>hit bigile&thorn;.</P>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 TYPE="poem">
<HEAD>Chastity.</HEAD>
<P>Castitas est:</P>
<P>A tresour of gret Richesse.<MILESTONE N="149" UNIT="folio"></P>
<P>A vertue of douthtynesse,</P>
<P>And is a worsshipful Clo&thorn;inge</P>
<P>And an help of gret wynn[i]nge.</P>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 TYPE="poem">
<HEAD>Inscriptions, p. 258-9, repeated.</HEAD>
<HEADNOTE><P>(y <I>and</I> &thorn; <I>are the same</I>.)</P></HEADNOTE>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN;i wyckede dedis &thorn;e broute to care; bot is &thorn;e for-&yogh;oui; &thorn;ou sinne no mare.<MILESTONE N="152" UNIT="folio">
<PB REF="00000311.tif" N="261"></L>
<L>&THORN;e wickede dedis &thorn;e made syke sore; bot al i for-&yogh;iue &thorn;e; &amp; sinne no more</L>
<L>&THORN;eng wat &thorn;ou art &amp; wat &thorn;ou was; &amp; &thorn;at al &thorn;i worssepe of me [&thorn;ou] has.</L>
<L N="4">&THORN;ou &thorn;eng wel on &thorn;ese &thorn;inges yie, wat tou art, &amp; wat tou were, &amp; al &thorn;e woisse.</L>
<L>Lere to loue as Ic loue &thorn;e: on al my lemes &thorn;ou mait it se;</L>
<L>For &thorn;e I suffrede mikel wo; &thorn;ou loue [me] trueli, ant no mo.</L>
<L>Noble &thorn;ou art, &thorn;at were afile; be war be onis &thorn;at none &thorn;e gile,</L>
<L N="8">Wou michel, at wat, &amp; werfore, wat I haue &thorn;oled for loue of &thorn;e.</L>
<L>I am &thorn;i bro&thorn;er, be nout in wer; be nout agast to come me nere;</L>
<L>I am &thorn;i bro&thorn;er, be nout agast; be hende &amp; trewe, &amp; sted&euml;fast.</L>
<L>Here I take &thorn;e to my liue, tac &thorn;ou non o&thorn;er to terme of liue;</L>
<L N="12">Here I take &thorn;e to my spouse, &amp; &yogh;iue &thorn;e bo&thorn;&euml; land &amp; house.</L>
</LG>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 TYPE="poem">
<HEAD>The Sinners' Lament.</HEAD>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>al &thorn;e io&yogh;e of oure herte nou is went a-wey:<MILESTONE N="153b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>for into serwe &amp; into wo, tornid is al oure pley.</L>
<L>&thorn;e croune of oure heued is felle to gronde:</L>
<L N="4">&thorn;at euere we sennede, weylawey &thorn;e stonde!</L>
</LG>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 TYPE="poem">
<HEAD>Christ's Woe.</HEAD>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&yogh;e &thorn;at be &thorn;is wey pace,<MILESTONE N="154" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>abidid &amp; behaldit my face;</L>
<L>&amp; loket wer ani wo or pine</L>
<L N="4">may be licnit nou to mine!
</L>
</LG>

</DIV2>
<DIV2 TYPE="poem"><PB REF="00000312.tif" N="262">
<HEAD>A Lover's Complaint.</HEAD>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Loue, &thorn;ou art of mikel mit;</L>
<L>Mi day &thorn;ou tornis into nit,</L>
<L N="3">&amp; dos me sik&euml; sore;</L>
<L>and al for on so swete a wit</L>
<L>&thorn;at onis &thorn;orw loue me trou&thorn;&euml; plit,</L>
<L N="6">to ben myn euere more.</L>
</LG>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 TYPE="poem">
<HEAD>Christ's Call to Love.</HEAD>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Lere to loue as .i. loue &thorn;e,</L>
<L>for on al mi lemes &thorn;ou mait it se.<NOTE PLACE="marg">[<I>See</I> p. 258.]</NOTE></L>
</LG>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 TYPE="poem">
<HEAD>True Love.</HEAD>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&thorn;ey loue be stro[n]g &amp; mikel of mith,<MILESTONE N="155b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>for wele, for wo, trewloue mat lith.</L>
<L>treuloue is larg&euml;, fre &amp; hende,</L>
<L N="4">&amp; loue &yogh;if alle&thorn;ing ble&thorn;eli to his frende.</L>
<L>in wele &amp; wo, loue sto[n]dit faste,</L>
<L>for lif, for det, trewloue wil laste.</L>
<L>fer &amp; frey loue hat on heu,</L>
<L N="8">for trewloue is fress &amp; euere neu.</L>
</LG>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 TYPE="poem">
<HEAD>Four Inscriptions.</HEAD>
<LG N="1" TYPE="stanza">
<L>fir &amp; watir, wind &amp; lond.</L>
<L>i desire bo haue vnder myn hond vel bond.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="2" TYPE="stanza">
<L>bede faste, for i come sone.</L>
<L>yif &thorn;ou serwe onli for me,</L>
<L N="5">sikerly &thorn;ou tit &thorn;i bone.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="3" TYPE="stanza">
<L>wil &yogh;e biddin, redi i am;</L>
<L>&yogh;if &yogh;e leuin, i go you fram.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="4" TYPE="stanza">
<L>smertlike i helpe, &amp; noman forsake;<MILESTONE N="156" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="9">ble&thorn;eli i fitte, &thorn;e maistri forto take.
</L>
</LG>

</DIV2>
<DIV2 TYPE="poem"><PB REF="00000313.tif" N="263">
<HEAD>Trust not the World.</HEAD>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>worldis bliss&euml;, strif hat wrout,<MILESTONE N="157" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>for it is wit serwe to end&euml; brout.</L>
<L>worldes catel<MILESTONE N="157b" UNIT="folio"> passet sone.</L>
<L N="4">&thorn;at wacset &amp; wansit rit as te mone.</L>
<L>trist nout to &thorn;[i]s wonder world &thorn;at lastit bot a wile;</L>
<L>for it is not bot wiles of wo a hasardour &thorn;at wil &thorn;e gile.</L>
</LG>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 TYPE="poem">
<HEAD>Purity.</HEAD>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>He is wel siker &thorn;at hat clennesse;</L>
<L>for al &thorn;at o&thorn;er renenant<NOTE PLACE="foot">remenant?</NOTE> is not bot wrechedenesse.</L>
</LG>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 TYPE="poem">
<HEAD>Mortality.</HEAD>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>allas! in gret sinne, alle be&yogh;ete we were:<MILESTONE N="158" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>stronge pines &thorn;oleden &thorn;e moderis &thorn;at vs bere.</L>
<L>here we liue bisiliche wit strong serwe &amp; care:</L>
<L N="4">de&yogh;e we ssulin sikerliche; bot god wot wanne &amp; were.</L>
</LG>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 TYPE="poem">
<HEAD>Pride.</HEAD>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>in alle maner &thorn;rifte,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>or</I> &thorn;riste</NOTE> y passe all&euml; &thorn;ingge;</L>
<L>&yogh;if oni &thorn;ing be lic me, to det i ssal him bringe.</L>
</LG>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 TYPE="poem">
<HEAD>Mercy.</HEAD>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&yogh;if sinne nere, merci nere non;</L>
<L>wan Merci is cald, he comet anon.</L>
<L>&thorn;er merci is rediest wer sinne is mest.</L>
<L N="4">&thorn;er merci is lattest were sinne is lest.</L>
<L>Merci abidet &amp; loket aldai,</L>
<L>wan mon fro sinne wil torne away.
</L>
</LG>

</DIV2>
<DIV2 TYPE="poem"><PB REF="00000314.tif" N="264">
<HEAD>Christ, Man's Help.</HEAD>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>god help hastou, man &amp; prest;</L>
<L>&thorn;e moder here sone sewet here brest;</L>
<L>&thorn;e sone his fadir ssewet his side,</L>
<L N="4">hise wondir wondis depe &amp; wide;</L>
<L>&thorn;anne mai &thorn;er be no maner werning,</L>
<L>&thorn;er of so gret loue is so gret tocning.</L>
</LG>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 TYPE="poem">
<HEAD>The King's Letters to his Son.</HEAD>
<P>Fulgencius in gestis romanorum: quidam rex duos habuit filios, quorum senior cum patre in pallacio fuit; Iunior vero in castro pernoctauit periculoso. cui pater litteras 5. transcripsit. prima erat ista, sic:</P>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>sinne &amp; folye<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. may be 'ful&thorn;e.'</NOTE> only for-sake;</L>
<L>to clennesse of lif, for mi loue tac.</L>
</LG>
<P>2<SUP>a</SUP> fuit ista, sic:</P>
<LG>
<L>loue god bo&thorn;e wit herte &amp; &thorn;out.</L>
<L N="4">for to his licnesse &thorn;ou art wrout.</L></LG>
<P>3<SUP>a</SUP> erat ista, sic:</P>
<LG>
<L>wit-outin lou&euml; &thorn;ou art lorn;<MILESTONE N="158b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>wose hat nout loue, were bettre on-born.</L>
</LG>
<P>4<SUP>ta</SUP> erat ista sic:</P>
<LG>
<L>of al &thorn;i wele i bidde non o&thorn;er,</L>
<L>bot loue me wel, as dot &thorn;i bro&thorn;er.</L>
</LG>
<P>vel sic:</P>
<LG>
<L>of al &thorn;i richesse i bidde no more,</L>
<L>bot loue me wel for euere more.</L></LG>
<P>5<SUP>ta</SUP> erat ista.</P>
<LG>
<L>Come nou, my swete chilt, wan &thorn;ou come wilt,</L>
<L>for redi is &thorn;in heritage, &amp; for&yogh;ouin is &thorn;i gilt.</L>
</LG>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 TYPE="poem">
<HEAD>The Ills of our Time.</HEAD>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Charite, chaste, pite, arn waxin al colde;</L>
<L>Couetise, Lust, &amp; maistrie, arn be-comin al bolde;<MILESTONE N="162" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="3">Consel, god acord, &amp; wedloc ben nou no&thorn;ing of tolde.
<PB REF="00000315.tif" N="265"></L>
<L>Stronge, trewe, &amp; corteis, kepte &thorn;e land;</L>
<L>Bot now feynte, false, folis, it han vndir hand;</L>
<L N="6">&THORN;eues, liers &amp; fowlwimmen boldeli ferth stand.</L>
<L>Vnder dercnesse, darket lit of stedefastnesse.<MILESTONE N="162b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>vnder sleu&thorn;e, darkit &thorn;e loue of holinesse.</L>
<L N="9">For faute of rit domusman, &thorn;e lauwe slepit of ritwisnesse.</L>
<L>wif, wille, and richesse, han &thorn;e maistrie ta[ke];</L>
<L N="11">vertu, godede, &amp; almisdede, arn al for-sake;</L>
<L>Oker, lieyng, &amp; wantonesse, mickel serwe make.</L>
</LG>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 TYPE="poem">
<HEAD>Look to the End.</HEAD>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN;is is a wondir merie pley, &amp; longe ssal laste:</L>
<L>bot, for &thorn;i sete is perilous, war &thorn;e ate laste.</L>
</LG>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 TYPE="poem">
<HEAD>A Lover's Saying.</HEAD>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>me &thorn;ing Rit &thorn;ou art so loueli, so fair, &amp; so swete,</L>
<L>&thorn;at sikerli it were mi det, &thorn;i companie to lete.</L>
</LG>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 TYPE="poem">
<HEAD>Ware the Wheel!</HEAD>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&thorn;is wondir wel vndir &thorn;is trone,</L>
<L>it changit ofte as dot &thorn;e mone;</L>
<L>al &thorn;at euere come &thorn;er-on,</L>
<L N="4">it fondit forto gile:</L>
<L>&amp; bot &thorn;ey<MILESTONE N="163" UNIT="folio"> be war be-forn,</L>
<L>it &yogh;elt hem euele her wile.</L>
</LG>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 TYPE="poem">
<HEAD>The Lion.</HEAD>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&thorn;e lion is wondirliche strong,</L>
<L>&amp; ful of wiles of wo;</L>
<L>&amp; we&thorn;er he pleye</L>
<L>o&thorn;er take his pre&yogh;e,</L>
<L N="5">he can not do bot slo.
</L>
</LG>

</DIV2>
<DIV2 TYPE="poem"><PB REF="00000316.tif" N="266">
<HEAD>Ware Bear's Play!</HEAD>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>war &thorn;e from &thorn;e bere plei auantir / last he bite;</L>
<L>for selde he stintit of his pley, bot yif he bite or smite.</L>
</LG>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 TYPE="poem">
<HEAD>The Dragon.</HEAD>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>I wile &yogh;ou alle swelewe wit-outin oni both:</L>
<L>dot<NOTE PLACE="foot">bot?</NOTE> some wile y saue, &amp; some wile y noth.</L>
</LG>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 TYPE="poem">
<HEAD>Fortune's Wheel.</HEAD>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&thorn;ou most fort, wit wele or wo,</L>
<L>be &thorn;ou lef, o&thorn;er be<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. bo</NOTE> &thorn;ou lot,</L>
<L>forto gon vp on &thorn;is wel</L>
<L N="4">&thorn;at eueremore about&euml; got.</L>
<L>&yogh;if &thorn;ou be coint&euml;, &thorn;ou ssalt liue:</L>
<L>&amp; ellis dedis dint i ssal &thorn;e &yogh;iue.</L>
<L>vel sic</L>
<L N="8">&yogh;if &thorn;ou go cointeli on &thorn;is wel,</L>
<L>&thorn;ou ssalt liue eueremore:</L>
<L>bot &yogh;if &thorn;ou falle, &amp; go amis,</L>
<L>wit dulful det i wonde &thorn;e sore.</L>
</LG>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 TYPE="poem">
<HEAD>Foolish Love.</HEAD>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>I am a fol, i can no god:</L>
<L>ho &thorn;at me louit, hi halde him wod;</L>
<L>.I. brenn&euml; hote, I smit&euml; sore,<MILESTONE N="163b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="4">ho &thorn;at me louit ssal &thorn;e no more.</L>
<L>dredful det out of me sprong,</L>
<L>fo[r] i am welle of wo:</L>
<L>I slou a wis king, fair &amp; strong;</L>
<L N="8">&amp; &yogh;it .i. ssal sle mo.
</L>
</LG>

</DIV2>
<DIV2 TYPE="poem"><PB REF="00000317.tif" N="267">
<HEAD>The Ten Stages of Man's Life.</HEAD>
<P>Vita hominis decurrit in:</P>
<P>10. horis; 10 dictis; 10 radiis</P>
<P>In:</P>
<P>ten times of &thorn;e day</P>
<P>ten stappes of oure way</P>
<P>ten spokes &thorn;at tornen ay</P>
<LG N="1" TYPE="stanza">
<L>waich &amp; wreschede &thorn;ou art in sith;</L>
<L>of alle maner beste, lest is ti mith.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="2" TYPE="stanza">
<L>Al &thorn;is world &thorn;e tornit to play;</L>
<L>&thorn;e more &thorn;ou playst, &thorn;e more &thorn;ou may.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="3" TYPE="stanza">
<L>Richesse makes man beholden aboute;</L>
<L>for to &thorn;e riche, men bowe &amp; louthe.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="4" TYPE="stanza">
<L>Nou hastou fondin &thorn;at tou hast sout:</L>
<L>be wel war; it lastit nout.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="5" TYPE="stanza">
<L>strong &thorn;ou was, nou failit &thorn;i mith;</L>
<L>&thorn;ou waxist heui, &thorn;at was wel lit.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="6" TYPE="stanza">
<L>Al mi lif ic sorwe &amp; care,</L>
<L>for det comit sone, &thorn;at noman wil spare.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="7" TYPE="stanza">
<L>Lore &thorn;ou hast, bo&thorn;e tonge &amp; minde:</L>
<L>as tou hast liuid, &thorn;ou ssalt sone finde.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="8" TYPE="stanza">
<L>al &thorn;is wo[r]ld &thorn;ou ssal forsake,</L>
<L>for det is comun, &thorn;at wil &thorn;e take.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="9" TYPE="stanza">
<L>man &amp; wimman han on ende;</L>
<L>for, esye he comun al; esye ho<NOTE PLACE="marg">[<I>or</I> he]</NOTE> ssuln wende.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="10" TYPE="stanza">
<L>Of &thorn;i lif nou litel lete,</L>
<L>for &thorn;ou art tornid to wormis mete.</L>
</LG>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 TYPE="poem">
<HEAD>Four Inducements to Repentance.<MILESTONE N="166b" UNIT="folio"></HEAD>
<P>[Q]Vatuor monent ad penitentiam. videlicet:</P>
<P>benignitas diuina, Christi doctrina, horrendum dei iudi|cium, in impeniten|tibus inferendum, &amp; premium eternum, vere penitentibus re|promissum.</P>
<P>anglice:</P>
<P>Godes hore,<MILESTONE N="167" UNIT="folio"> Cristes lore, Godes grisliche dom,</P>
<P>And the blisse &thorn;at ner nis don.
</P>

</DIV2>
<DIV2 TYPE="poem"><PB REF="00000318.tif" N="268">
<HEAD>God's Goodness.</HEAD>
<P>expectat pacienter, parcit faciliter, suscipit liberaliter, &amp; obliuiscitur totali|ter.</P>
<P>anglice:</P>
<P>he abit &thorn;olemodliche,</P>
<P>he fur-geft litliche,</P>
<P>he vnder-fenget freliche,</P>
<P>and he fur-&thorn;et holliche.</P>
<P><I>Written at the foot of the page in pale ink.</I><MILESTONE N="168b" UNIT="folio"></P>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Hou &thorn;i fairnisse is bi-spit,</L>
<L>Hou &thorn;i swetnisse is i-betin and ipit,</L>
<L>Hou &thorn;i lotleschipe to scharp det&yogh; is of set.</L>
</LG>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 TYPE="poem">
<HEAD>Against Temptation.</HEAD>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>of vr vife wittes, a wel witiynge;<MILESTONE N="172" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>of &thorn;ing &thorn;at vs egget, a vast vleynge;</L>
<L>and of &thorn;e laste ende, a bisi bi&thorn;enkynge.</L>
</LG>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 TYPE="poem">
<HEAD>Alas, that we ever Sinned!</HEAD>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Strong it hus to flitte<MILESTONE N="172b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>Fro worldes blisse to pitte;</L>
<L>Strengore is to misse</L>
<L N="4">Heuene-rich&euml; blisse;</L>
<L>Strengest is to wende</L>
<L>To pine wit-outen ende.</L>
<L>&THORN;e blisse of oure herte, al it is ago;</L>
<L N="8">Al vre wel&euml; torned is to wo;</L>
<L>&THORN;e croune of vre heued</L>
<L>Fallen is to grounde:</L>
<L>&THORN;at we euer syngeden,</L>
<L N="12">Weylawey &thorn;e stounde!</L>
</LG>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 TYPE="poem">
<HEAD>Job said:</HEAD>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&thorn;at ylke day be out of Muinde<MILESTONE N="181" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>&thorn;at y was bron to<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>do</I> alterd to <I>to</I>.</NOTE> Monnes kuynde!
</L>
</LG>

</DIV2>
<DIV2 TYPE="poem"><PB REF="00000319.tif" N="269">
<HEAD>The Saved says:</HEAD>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>For foul&euml; lust&euml;s .I. witstod,</L>
<L>In blisse .I. wer&euml;<NOTE PLACE="foot">This scribe uses &yogh; for &thorn;; and &thorn; for &yogh; in 'fur-&thorn;et,' forgets, 268/4.</NOTE> &yogh;ys garlond.</L>
</LG>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 TYPE="poem">
<HEAD>The Lost says:</HEAD>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Alas! worldes yissyng Me haueth scehent,<MILESTONE N="182" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L><NOTE PLACE="foot">This scribe uses &yogh; for &thorn;; and &thorn; for &yogh; in 'fur-&thorn;et,' forgets, 268/4.</NOTE>&yogh;at euere My soule in helle beth brent.</L>
</LG>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 TYPE="poem">
<HEAD>The Saved says:</HEAD>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>In heuene blisse .I. am in hele,</L>
<L>For I forsok<NOTE PLACE="foot">This scribe uses &yogh; for &thorn;; and &thorn; for &yogh; in 'fur-&thorn;et,' forgets, 268/4.</NOTE>&yogh;ys worldes wele.</L>
</LG>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 TYPE="poem">
<HEAD>The Lost says:</HEAD>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Alas! helle me hath in<NOTE PLACE="marg">[<I>or</I> an.? MS.]</NOTE> holt in ruyde;<MILESTONE N="183" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L><NOTE PLACE="foot">This scribe uses &yogh; for &thorn;; and &thorn; for &yogh; in 'fur-&thorn;et,' forgets, 268/4.</NOTE>&yogh;e deuel in pine for worldes pride.</L>
</LG>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 TYPE="poem">
<HEAD>The Reward of the Meek.</HEAD>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>For &thorn;ou were Meke, an laftuste pruyde,<MILESTONE N="183b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>Wite blisse in heuene I schal &thorn;e scruyde.</L>
</LG>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 TYPE="poem">
<HEAD>Matthew's feast.</HEAD>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Matheu hat mad a grete gesteny[n]g</L>
<L>te Ihesu at home in his whonyy[n]g.</L>
</LG>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 TYPE="poem">
<HEAD>The Virtues serve us.</HEAD>
<P>Inuitant <I>igitur</I> fides, pietas &amp; beneuolencia;</P>
<P>Recipiunt spes, humilitas &amp; continencia;</P>
<P>Recumbunt pauperes cari|tate &amp; paciencia;</P>
<P>Ministrant sanctitas, zelus &amp; modestia.</P>
<P>vs preyen, bileue, god wille,<MILESTONE N="184" UNIT="folio"> &amp; pite;</P>
<P>vs kepen, god hope, Meke|nes &amp; kastite;</P>
<P>vus sit by, pouert, wisdom, &amp; god leuy[n]g;</P>
<P>vus seruen clannesse, rych &amp; feyr bery[n]g.
</P>

</DIV2>
<DIV2 TYPE="poem"><PB REF="00000320.tif" N="270">
<HEAD>Lord, come to my feast.</HEAD>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Lord .I. bidde bo&yogh;e day &amp; nyth,</L>
<L>cum to my feste<NOTE PLACE="foot">This scribe uses &yogh; for &thorn;.</NOTE>&yogh;at .I. haue dyth.</L>
<L>&yogh;if hit queme Mi lord &yogh;e ky[n]g, &yogh;y[n]g<NOTE PLACE="foot">thing</NOTE> &yogh;at I him preye.<MILESTONE N="184b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>I bidde he come to My gesteni[n]g, wit vus to gomen &amp; pleye.</L>
<L>&yogh;if in &thorn;i sith i grace haue fonde,</L>
<L>&yogh;if me Mi wille at<NOTE PLACE="foot">This scribe uses &yogh; for &thorn;.</NOTE>&yogh;is stonde.</L>
</LG>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 TYPE="poem">
<HEAD>Hindrances of the Devil.</HEAD>
<P>promissio fallax.; promocio mendax.; prolacio Mordax.</P>
<P>anglice:</P>
<P>A fals by-hety[n]g.<MILESTONE N="185" UNIT="folio"></P>
<P>A lyeres auansyng.</P>
<P>A bitynde fondi[n]g.
</P>

</DIV2>
<DIV2 TYPE="poem"><PB REF="00000321.tif" N="271">
<HEAD>An A B C Poem on the Passion of Christ.</HEAD>
<HEADNOTE><P>[Harl. MS. 3954, leaf 87. The A B C, etc., are not rubri|cated in the MS., but are made black here to catch the eye. The initial &thorn; and y are the same.]</P></HEADNOTE>
<LG N="1" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(1)</HEAD>
<L>IN place as man may se,</L>
<L>Quan a chyld to scole xal set be,</L>
<L N="3">A bok hym is browt,</L>
<L>Naylyd on a brede of tre,</L>
<L>&THORN;at men callyt an abece,</L>
<L N="6">Pratylych I-wrout.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="2" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(2)</HEAD>
<L>Wrout is on &thorn;e bok with-oute,</L>
<L>.V. paraffys grete &amp; stoute</L>
<L N="9">Bolyd in rose red;</L>
<L>&THORN;at is set with-outyn doute,</L>
<L><NOTE PLACE="inline">[<I>No gap in the MS.</I>]</NOTE></L>
<L N="12">In tokenyng of cristis ded.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="3" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(3)</HEAD>
<L>Red letter in parchemyn</L>
<L>Makyth a chyld good &amp; fyn</L>
<L N="15">Lettrys to loke &amp; se.</L>
<L>Be &thorn;is bok men may dyuyne</L>
<L>&THORN;at cristis body was ful of pyne</L>
<L N="18">&THORN;at deyid on rod&euml; tre.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="4" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(4)</HEAD>
<L>On tre he was don ful blythe</L>
<L>With grete paraffys, &thorn;at be wondis .v.</L>
<L N="21">As &yogh;e mou vnder-stonde.</L>
<L>Loke in hys body, mayde &amp; wyfe,</L>
<L>Qwon hee gun naylys dryue</L>
<L N="24">In fot &amp; in honde.
<PB REF="00000322.tif" N="272"></L>
</LG>
<LG N="5" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(5)</HEAD>
<L>Hond &amp; fout &thorn;er was ful woo,</L>
<L>And &thorn;er were lettrys many moo</L>
<L N="27">With-in &amp; with-oute,</L>
<L>With rede wondis &amp; strokis blo</L>
<L>He was dryue fro top to &thorn;e too,</L>
<L N="30">Hys fayre body aboute.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="6" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(6)</HEAD>
<L>About &thorn;is, a pece I wyl spede,</L>
<L>&THORN;at I myth &thorn;is lettrys rede</L>
<L N="33">With-outyn ony dystaunce;</L>
<L>But god &thorn;at let hys body sprede</L>
<L>Vp-on &thorn;e rode for manys nede,</L>
<L N="36">In heuene vs alle avaunce!</L>
</LG>
<LG N="7" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(7)</HEAD>
<L>God with spere was wondyd for vs;</L>
<L>Fals iudas, to mendyn hys purs,</L>
<L N="39">To ded hath hym sold:</L>
<L>On goodfryday, clerkys seyn &thorn;us,</L>
<L>"Mortuus est, ded is Ihesus,</L>
<L N="42">In ston is ded &amp; cold."</L>
</LG>
<LG N="8" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(8)</HEAD>
<L><B>A</B> madful mone may men make<MILESTONE N="87:2" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>Quan &thorn;at suete Ihesu was take!</L>
<L N="45">Lystyn a lytyl pas:</L>
<L>&THORN;e iewys wroutyn hym wo &amp; wrake;<NOTE PLACE="marg">[MS. warke]</NOTE></L>
<L>Hee ledyn hym forth a gret shake</L>
<L N="48">Aforn busshop Cayfas.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="9" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(9)</HEAD>
<L>Bondyn he was for our bounte,</L>
<L>And suffryd strokis gret plente</L>
<L N="51">Be-forn cayfas &thorn;at nyth.</L>
<L>On &thorn;e morn, I tel &thorn;e,</L>
<L>Eft was he betyn at &thorn;e tre</L>
<L N="54">Be-forn pylatis syth;
<PB REF="00000323.tif" N="273"></L>
</LG>
<LG N="10" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(10)</HEAD>
<L>Cananis hym crodyn to heroudis kyng,</L>
<L>&THORN;er had he gret scornyng,</L>
<L N="57">&THORN;ei bodyn hym turne &thorn;e gate.</L>
<L>Hee leddyn &thorn;at maydynus sone &yogh;yng</L>
<L>For to takyn hys damnyng</L>
<L N="60">Be-forn iustice pylate.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="11" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(11)</HEAD>
<L>Dempt he was on a stounde,</L>
<L>Sethen betyn with many wonde.</L>
<L>He tokyn a clout, as it is founde,</L>
<L N="64">And wondyn hus body &thorn;er-inne.</L>
<L>With dry blod quan was he bounde,</L>
<L>Tho iewys, egre as ony hounde,</L>
<L>Threwyn hus body to &thorn;e grounde,</L>
<L N="68">And rentyn of cloth &amp; scynne:</L>
</LG>
<LG N="12" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(12)</HEAD>
<L>Euene in hus eyne greye</L>
<L>Hee spyttyd on hym, &thorn;e so&thorn;e to seye:</L>
<L N="71">He lokyd on hem ful mylde.</L>
<L>Mary hys moder went &thorn;e weye</L>
<L>To caluery &thorn;er he xuld deye,</L>
<L N="74">And waytyd &thorn;er here chylde.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="13" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(13)</HEAD>
<L>For feyntyce <B>fel</B> &thorn;at fayre fode,</L>
<L>Nakyd he bar &thorn;at hard rode</L>
<L N="77">To-ward caluery,</L>
<L>Al be-ronne with red blod;</L>
<L>Among &thorn;e iewys wylde &amp; wod,</L>
<L N="80">He suonnyd cekerly.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="14" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(14)</HEAD>
<L>God! with iewys gret was &thorn;i pyne,</L>
<L>Naylyd on rode, soth for to seyne.</L>
<L N="83">Hee leydyn &thorn;e on &thorn;e gronnde
<PB REF="00000324.tif" N="274"></L>
<L>And ryuyn &thorn;i body holy &amp; dygne,&mdash;<MILESTONE N="87b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>On &thorn;e he madyn a gret sygne,&mdash;</L>
<L N="86">Hee naylyd &thorn;e fot &amp; honnde;</L>
</LG>
<LG N="15" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(15)</HEAD>
<L>Harde &thorn;ei bondyn &thorn;at heuy rode;</L>
<L>&THORN;er-on hys body heng al on blode,</L>
<L N="89">As beryt wytnesse sen Ion.</L>
<L>&THORN;e wyckyd iewys, wyld &amp; wode,</L>
<L>Hard &thorn;ei dryuyn &thorn;at heuy rode</L>
<L N="92">In-to a morteys of ston.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="16" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(16)</HEAD>
<L>Ihesu, with iewys gret was &thorn;i pyne!</L>
<L>Hand &amp; fot, for so&thorn;e to seyne,</L>
<L N="95">Al to-toryn in &thorn;at tyde,</L>
<L>Al to-broste synwe &amp; veyne,</L>
<L>As beryt wytnesse Maudeleyne;</L>
<L N="98">She sau &thorn;e wondis wyde.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="17" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(17)</HEAD>
<L>Kyng crist was klad in poure wede:</L>
<L>Al &thorn;e syn of manys dede</L>
<L N="101">He hath bout wol dere;</L>
<L>To by&yogh;yn vs heuene, &thorn;at mery mede,</L>
<L>Al hys blod he gan blede,</L>
<L N="104">And sythyn water clere.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="18" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(18)</HEAD>
<L>Loue made crist fro heuene to comyn,</L>
<L>Loue made hym with man to wonyn,&mdash;</L>
<L N="107">As clerkys in bokys rede,&mdash;</L>
<L>Loue made hus hert to bledyn,</L>
<L>With hus blod oure soulys to fedyn,</L>
<L N="110">To bryngyn vs to oure mede.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="19" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(19)</HEAD>
<L>Man, for &thorn;i mekel mercy,</L>
<L>Maydynnus sone Mary,</L>
<L N="113">On godfryday &thorn;us deyide!
<PB REF="00000325.tif" N="275"></L>
<L>&THORN;us he heng on caluery</L>
<L>With wondis weyde cekerly,</L>
<L N="116">A thef on ey&thorn;er<NOTE PLACE="marg">[MS. eyeryer]</NOTE> syde.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="20" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(20)</HEAD>
<L>Nout he hadde at hys nede</L>
<L>To restyn hus hed, as clerkys rede,</L>
<L N="119">But al was hym be-reuyd.</L>
<L>Fox &amp; foul may reste &amp; hede,</L>
<L>But crist, &thorn;at deyid for manus nede,</L>
<L N="122">Hat nout to reste in hus had.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="21" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(21)</HEAD>
<L>Out ran hus blod &thorn;at was so bryth;</L>
<L>&THORN;an seyde our lord god almyth</L>
<L N="125">A word of gret pete,<MILESTONE N="87b:2" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>"Al &thorn;us with iewys I am dyth,</L>
<L>I seme a wyrm to manus syth."</L>
<L N="128">Man! for loue of &thorn;e,</L>
</LG>
<LG N="22" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(22)</HEAD>
<L>Pryckis hym peynyd, &yogh;e may here;</L>
<L>Hys hed was broydyn on a brere,</L>
<L N="131">&THORN;is is &thorn;e so&thorn;e to seyne;</L>
<L>With red blod was wet hus lere;</L>
<L>&THORN;o pryckis, &thorn;oru hus panne so dere,</L>
<L N="134">Wentyn in-to &thorn;e brayn!</L>
</LG>
<LG N="23" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(23)</HEAD>
<L>Qwen of heuene, wo was she</L>
<L>To sen hangyn on rode tre</L>
<L N="137">Ihesu, here sone so suete;</L>
<L>Here tendre hert myth breste on iij</L>
<L>Quan she sau here son&euml; fre</L>
<L N="140">On rode hys lyf lete.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="24" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(24)</HEAD>
<L>Ragyd &amp; rent, in red blod,</L>
<L>&THORN;us heng he vp-on &thorn;e rod</L>
<L N="143">A&yogh;en &thorn;e son&euml; glem.
<PB REF="00000326.tif" N="276"></L>
<L>For so&thorn;e he weryn werse &thorn;an wod</L>
<L>To slon Ihesu so good,</L>
<L N="146">&THORN;e iewys of ierusalem.<NOTE PLACE="marg">[MS. <ABBR>ielrm</ABBR>]</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG N="25" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(25)</HEAD>
<L>Slyt was hus flech, &amp; slawe;</L>
<L>&THORN;e iewys in here falc&euml; lawe,</L>
<L N="149">&THORN;ei dedyn hym mekel peyne:</L>
<L>As seyt &thorn;e gospel in hus sawe,</L>
<L>Euery lyth fro o&thorn;er was drawe;</L>
<L N="152">&THORN;at is nout to layne.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="26" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(26)</HEAD>
<L>Togyd with tene was god of prys;</L>
<L>To don hym sorwe was here delys:</L>
<L N="155">He seyd&euml; no word loth.</L>
<L>Quan he was naylyd at here a-vys,</L>
<L>&THORN;o iewys kestyn at &thorn;e dys</L>
<L N="158">Qwe&thorn;er xuld han hys cloth.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="27" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(27)</HEAD>
<L>Wyde weryn hus wondis wete,</L>
<L>Fro &thorn;e hond[es] to &thorn;e fete</L>
<L N="161">With deth he was [i]slawe.</L>
<L>Hys lomeber blod our bale may bete,</L>
<L>Of qwom spac Moyses &thorn;e prophete,</L>
<L N="164">Ryth in &thorn;e held lawe.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="28" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(28)</HEAD>
<L>Xpc crist on croys was sleynt;</L>
<L>To hys fader he made a pleynt,<MILESTONE N="88" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="167">Hys cry was, "hely!</L>
<L>Fader god in trynite!</L>
<L>Qwy hast &thorn;ou forsak&euml; me?"</L>
<L N="170">Cryst seyde on caluery.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="29" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(29)</HEAD>
<L>Y for I, in wryt is set.</L>
<L>Cryst for vs on croys was knet,</L>
<L N="173">Nalyd on &thorn;e rode:
<PB REF="00000327.tif" N="277"></L>
<L>Out of thraldam he vs fet,</L>
<L>&THORN;at we &thorn;oru syn hadde get,</L>
<L N="176">And bout vs with hys blode.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="30" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(30)</HEAD>
<L>&YOGH;et he was in suffryng</L>
<L>Of trokys &amp; naylis clynkyng,</L>
<L N="179">Tyl it was pacyd non;</L>
<L>Ne blenchyd he neuer for betyng;</L>
<L>To dede hee dedyn heuene kyng;</L>
<L N="182">&THORN;is was a ruful mon.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="31" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(31)</HEAD>
<L>&amp; is to seyn, god is ded,</L>
<L>Of hys blod hys body is red.</L>
<L N="185">He ros on estryn morwe;</L>
<L>To helle he &yogh;ede with-outyn abod,</L>
<L>For to stroyn &thorn;e fendys wod,</L>
<L N="188">To sauyn vs fro sorwe.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="32" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(32)</HEAD>
<L>Loke &thorn;at we ben seker &amp; kende,</L>
<L>And kepe &thorn;is apece<NOTE PLACE="marg">[<I>for</I> above]</NOTE> in oure mende,</L>
<L>&THORN;an sekere be we of blys with-outyn ende</L>
<L N="192">In tyme quan we xul dey;</L>
<L>Afterward men xal vp-ryce,</L>
<L>And wende for, bo&thorn;e fol &amp; wyce,</L>
<L N="195">To Iosaphat sekerly;</L>
</LG>
<LG N="33" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(33)</HEAD>
<L>And west, nort, &amp; south,</L>
<L>Euery man, bo&thorn;e fremyd &amp; kouth,</L>
<L N="198">Xul comyn with-outyn ly.</L>
<L>&THORN;er xal be gret asyce</L>
<L>Be-forn ihesu, &thorn;at hey Iustyce,</L>
<L N="201">With woundis al blody.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="34" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(34)</HEAD>
<L>Quan mannus soule hat in mynde</L>
<L>&THORN;e blod &thorn;at cryst let for mankende</L>
<L N="204">With terys &amp; woundis smerte,
<PB REF="00000328.tif" N="278"></L>
<L>Man fynde &thorn;ou non vnkyndnesse</L>
<L>Quan &thorn;e wey of suetnesse</L>
<L N="207">Wyl entryn in-to &thorn;in herte;<MILESTONE N="88:2" UNIT="folio"></L>
</LG>
<LG N="35" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(35)</HEAD>
<L>Sey, "a, ihesu! quat hast &thorn;ou gylt?</L>
<L>Qwy art &thorn;ou for my syn spylt,</L>
<L N="210">Flour of low&euml;nesse?</L>
<L>I am a thef, &thorn;ou for me deyist,</L>
<L>I am gylty, &amp; &thorn;ou abeyst</L>
<L N="213">For my wykydnesse;</L>
</LG>
<LG N="36" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(36)</HEAD>
<L>So gret raunsom for so wyl thyng!</L>
<L>Quat hast &thorn;ou wonne with &thorn;i peynyng,</L>
<L N="216">&THORN;ou hey in blysce aboue?</L>
<L>Gret godnesse hat &thorn;e makyd</L>
<L>For to hangyn on rode nakyd</L>
<L N="219">For mannus soul&euml; loue!</L>
</LG>
<LG N="37" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(37)</HEAD>
<L>But, lord ihesu, I kan no more</L>
<L>But &thorn;e besekyn with al my myth,</L>
<L N="222">&THORN;at I mot&euml; wepyn sore</L>
<L>Thyn hard&euml; peynus day &amp; nyth,</L>
<L>And &thorn;at loue mote also faste</L>
<L>In-to myn hert&euml; stykyd be,</L>
<L>As was &thorn;e spere in-to &thorn;in herte</L>
<L N="226">Quan &thorn;ou suffrydyst ded for me. Amen.
</L>
</LG>

</DIV2>
<DIV2 TYPE="poem"><PB REF="00000329.tif" N="279">
<HEAD>The fifty-first Psalm.</HEAD>
<HEADNOTE><P>[<I>Additional MS., No.</I> 10,036, <I>Brit. Mus., leaf</I> 96, <I>bk.</I><NOTE PLACE="foot">There is another copy of this Poem in Harl. MS. 3810, Part I.</NOTE>] (Twenty 4-measure stanzas of 8, <I>abab abab.</I>)</P></HEADNOTE>
<LG N="1" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(1) MIserere mei deus, secundum magnam misericordiam tuam!</HEAD>
<L>Mercy, god, of my mysdede!</L>
<L>For &thorn;i mercy &thorn;at mychel ys,</L>
<L>Late &thorn;i pite sprynge &amp; sprede,</L>
<L N="4">Off &thorn;i mercy &thorn;at I ne mys.</L>
<L>Aftur gostliche grace I grede;</L>
<L>Good god! &thorn;ou graunt me &thorn;is,</L>
<L>That I may lyue in loue &amp; drede,</L>
<L N="8">And neuer efter to do more amys.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="2" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(2) Et secundum multitudinem miseracionum tuarum, dele iniquitatem meam.</HEAD>
<L>And after &thorn;i mercies &thorn;at ben fele,</L>
<L>Lord, fordo my wickydnesse.</L>
<L>&YOGH;yue me grace to hyde &amp; hele</L>
<L N="12">The blam&euml; of my bruchelnesse.</L>
<L>&YOGH;if any sterynge on me stele,</L>
<L>Out of &thorn;e clos of &thorn;i clennesse</L>
<L>Wysse me, lord, in wo &amp; wele,</L>
<L N="16">And kep&euml; me fram vnkyndnesse.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="3" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(3) Amplius laua me ab iniquitate mea: &amp; a peccato meo munda me.
</HEAD>
<PB REF="00000330.tif" N="280">
<L>More-ouer, wasche me of my synne,<MILESTONE N="97" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>And of my gult&euml;s clanse &thorn;ow me;</L>
<L>And serche my soule with out &amp; Inne,</L>
<L N="20">That I no more defowlid be.</L>
<L>And as &thorn;yn hert aclef atwynne</L>
<L>With doleful deth on &thorn;e rod&euml; tre,</L>
<L>Late me neuer no werke bigynne,</L>
<L N="24">Lord, but &yogh;if it lyk&euml; &thorn;ee.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="4" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(4) Qoniam iniquitatem meam ego cognosco: &amp; peccatum meum contra me est semper.</HEAD>
<L>For al my wickidnesse I knowe,</L>
<L>And my synne is euer me a&yogh;eyn;</L>
<L>Ther-fore late &thorn;i grac&euml; growe,</L>
<L N="28">Ihesu, &thorn;at was with iewis sleyn.</L>
<L>Ryche &amp; por&euml;, hye &amp; lowe,</L>
<L>Smale &amp; gret[&euml;], in certeyn,</L>
<L>Atte domesdaie, when &thorn;ou schalt blowe,</L>
<L N="32">Of &thorn;i mercy schul be ful feyn.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="5" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(5) Tibi soli peccaui, &amp; malum coram te feci: ut iustificeris in sermonibus tuis, &amp;c.</HEAD>
<L>To &thorn;ee only trespassed haue I,</L>
<L>Wrou&yogh;t wickidly a&yogh;ens &thorn;i glorie</L>
<L>With wordes &amp; eke with trecherie.</L>
<L N="36">Thou demyst ri&yogh;t, &amp; hast &thorn;e vict&oacute;rie;</L>
<L>Ther-fore, &thorn;ee biseche now I,&mdash;<MILESTONE N="97b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>For tolde hit is in many story,&mdash;</L>
<L>That who so truste&thorn; to &thorn;i mercy,</L>
<L N="40">Is end&euml;les in &thorn;i mem&oacute;rie.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="6" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(6) Ecce enim in iniquitatibus conceptus sum: &amp; in peccatis concepit me mater mea.</HEAD>
<L>Biholde, in synne I was conceyued</L>
<L>Of my modre, as we ben alle:
<PB REF="00000331.tif" N="281"></L>
<L>Off my fadre I nou&yogh;t conceyued</L>
<L N="44">But flesche ful frel, &amp; fayn to falle.</L>
<L>And sithe &thorn;i flesche, lord, was furst perceyued,</L>
<L>And for oure sake laide strei&yogh;t in stalle,</L>
<L>Was neuer synful man deceyued,</L>
<L N="48">That to &thorn;i mercy wold&euml; calle.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="7" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(7) Ecce enim ueritatem dilexisti: incerta &amp; occulta sapiencie tue manifestasti michi.</HEAD>
<L>Lo! &thorn;ou hast louyd ry&yogh;t,</L>
<L>And schewid me counceil of &thorn;i wyt,</L>
<L>How, &thorn;orw mercy &amp; &thorn;orw my&yogh;t,</L>
<L N="52">Two kynd&euml;s ben to-gidre knyt:</L>
<L>Thral ys fre, &amp; knaue is kny&yogh;t,</L>
<L>And god is man, as gospel wryt;</L>
<L>And &yogh;it my soule in perel be py&yogh;t,</L>
<L N="56">Mercyful god, help &thorn;ou yt!</L>
</LG>
<LG N="8" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(8) Asperges me ysopo, &amp; mundabor: lauabis me, &amp; super niuem dealbabor.<MILESTONE N="98" UNIT="folio"></HEAD>
<L>With holi water &thorn;ou schalt me springe,</L>
<L>And as &thorn;e snowe I schal be whyt;</L>
<L>And &yogh;if my soule in synn&euml; stynke,</L>
<L N="60">With wepinge water I may it quyt.</L>
<L>Dedly drau&yogh;tes al-&thorn;ou&yogh; I drynke,</L>
<L>Of r&eacute;pentaunce &yogh;yue me respit;</L>
<L>For who-so on &thorn;i &thorn;row&euml;s &thorn;ynke,</L>
<L N="64">In world&euml;s wel&thorn;e is no delit.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="9" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(9) Auditui meo gaudium &amp; leticiam: et exultabunt ossa humiliata.</HEAD>
<L>To myn heryng &thorn;ou schalt &yogh;yue</L>
<L>Gladnesse, to glad&euml; bon&euml;s meke.</L>
<L>In lownesse lern&euml; me to lyue,</L>
<L N="68">Leu&euml; lord, I &thorn;ee by-seke!
<PB REF="00000332.tif" N="282"></L>
<L>The &thorn;eu&euml;s gult, hit was for&yogh;yue</L>
<L>On rod&euml; wher his bon&euml;s breke.</L>
<L>A contryt hert, &amp; clene yschryue,</L>
<L N="72">Saue&thorn; soule &amp; body eke.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="10" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(10) Auerte faciem tuam a peccatis meis: et omnes iniquitates meas dele.</HEAD>
<L>Fro my synn&euml;s turne &thorn;i face,</L>
<L>Do al my wickidnesse a-way!</L>
<L>Grete is my gult, gretter is &thorn;i<NOTE PLACE="foot">my <I>alterd to</I> &thorn;i.</NOTE> grace,<MILESTONE N="98b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="76">And ellis, faile&thorn; al oure fay.</L>
<L>And fawt&euml;s fele &thorn;at me do&thorn; face,</L>
<L>Make&thorn; &thorn;at I may no&yogh;t say,</L>
<L>But crie mercy when I trespace;</L>
<L N="80">I-wis I wote no better way.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="11" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(11) Cor mundum crea in me deus: &amp; spiritum rectum innoua in uisceribus meis.</HEAD>
<L>God! make &thorn;ou myn hert[&euml;] clene,</L>
<L>And a ri&yogh;tful spirit in me newe;</L>
<L>Fro seuene synnes &thorn;ou make me schene,</L>
<L N="84">That where &thorn;ou go, I may &thorn;ee seewe.</L>
<L>Al &thorn;i turment and &thorn;i tene,</L>
<L>Thi bodi blacke, &thorn;i bon&euml;s blewe,&mdash;</L>
<L>Now, graunt, cryst, &thorn;at it be sene</L>
<L N="88">In myn hert, &thorn;at hidowes hewe.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="12" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(12) NE proicias me a facie tua: &amp; spiritum sanctum tuum ne auferas a me.</HEAD>
<L>Cast me nou&yogh;t fro &thorn;i visage,</L>
<L>Take no&yogh;t fro me &thorn;ine holigost!</L>
<L>To byholde &thorn;i faire ymage,</L>
<L N="92">Of all&euml; mur&thorn;&euml;s hit is most.</L>
<L>A blisful bryd was born in cage,</L>
<L>Cow&thorn;e ykid in euery cost,
<PB REF="00000333.tif" N="283"></L>
<L>When he were drawe in tendre age,<MILESTONE N="99" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="96">To dryue adoun &thorn;e deueles bost.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="13" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(13) REdde michi leticiam salutaris tui: &amp; spiritu principali confirma me.</HEAD>
<L>Of &thorn;ine hel&thorn;e &yogh;yue me &thorn;e blisse,</L>
<L>And streng&thorn;e me with &thorn;i spirit cheef;</L>
<L>And alle my fyu&euml; wittes &thorn;ou wisse,</L>
<L N="100">That I may lyue as &thorn;ee is leef,</L>
<L>And &thorn;ou maist my langor lysse,</L>
<L>That brou&yogh;test man to gret boncheef;</L>
<L>So late me neuer &thorn;i mercy mysse,</L>
<L N="104">When I am gurt with gostly greef.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="14" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(14) DOcebo iniquos uias tuas: &amp; impij ad te co[n]uertentur.</HEAD>
<L>To &thorn;e wickid I schal &thorn;e<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>for</I> &thorn;i</NOTE> waies teche,</L>
<L>The synneful schulle to &thorn;ee conuerte.</L>
<L>Synful man, be war of wreche,</L>
<L N="108">And &thorn;enke on cryst&euml;s hede &amp; herte!</L>
<L>Brest &amp; hert was bete to bleche,</L>
<L>On bar&euml; bodi, with-out&euml; sherte;</L>
<L>To rewe on him I wol &thorn;ee preche,</L>
<L N="112">But alas! &thorn;er wolde no teer oute sterte.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="15" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(15) LIbera me de sanguinibus, deus meus salutis mee: &amp; exaltabit lingua mea iusticiam tuam.</HEAD>
<L>Delyuere me fram blameful<NOTE PLACE="foot">m, n, <I>alterd</I>.</NOTE> blode,<MILESTONE N="99b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>My lord, god of myn<NOTE PLACE="foot">m, n, <I>alterd</I>.</NOTE> hel&thorn;e;</L>
<L>And my mou&thorn;e schal with myld&euml; mode</L>
<L N="116">Apertely schewe &thorn;i sely sel&thorn;e.</L>
<L>Thi ri&yogh;tful blode ran doun on rode</L>
<L>To waschen vs fram oure fleschly fel&thorn;e;</L>
<L>Agayn many a storme &thorn;ou stode</L>
<L N="120">To wyssen vs fro &thorn;e world&euml;s wel&thorn;e.
<PB REF="00000334.tif" N="284"></L>
</LG>
<LG N="16" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(16) Domine, labia mea aperies: &amp; os meum annunciabit laudem tuam.</HEAD>
<L>Lord, my lippes &thorn;ou schalt vndo,</L>
<L>And my mou&thorn;e schal &thorn;i prechinge<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>for</I> preisinge</NOTE> spelle;</L>
<L>Thi mercy &amp; &thorn;i my&yogh;t also,</L>
<L N="124">So&thorn;fastly no tunge may telle;</L>
<L>For when we dedly synn&euml; do,</L>
<L>Thi ri&yogh;t vs deme&thorn; doun to helle;</L>
<L>But when we ceesen &amp; wol saie 'ho!'</L>
<L N="128">Thi mercy is oure waschynge welle.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="17" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(17) Quoniam si voluisses sacrificium dedissem utique: holocaustis non dilectaberis.</HEAD>
<L>&YOGH;if sacrifice hadde ben offrynge,</L>
<L>I hadde to &thorn;ee &yogh;yuen with hert fre;</L>
<L>But certeynly hit is none suche &thorn;inge,</L>
<L N="132">That, to &thorn;i, plesaunt may be.</L>
<L>Thi self was offrid a child ful &yogh;ynge,<MILESTONE N="100" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>And afterwarde on &thorn;e rod&euml; tre</L>
<L>Oute of &thorn;in herte &thorn;at blode gan sprynge,</L>
<L N="136">And &thorn;er-fore myn hert I offre to &thorn;ee.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="18" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(18) SAcrificium deo spiritus contribulatus: cor contritum &amp; humiliatum, deus, non despicies.</HEAD>
<L>To god hit is a sacryfice,</L>
<L>A synful spirit to sorwe sore;</L>
<L>A meke hert [&thorn;ou] schal no&yogh;t despice,</L>
<L N="140">Whan r&eacute;pentaunce hit wol restore.</L>
<L>I haue for sleu&thorn;e [left] &thorn;i seruyce,</L>
<L>And litel lyued aftur &thorn;i lore;</L>
<L>But I repente, &amp; wille now aryse;</L>
<L N="144">Mercy, god! I wolle no more.
<PB REF="00000335.tif" N="285"></L>
</LG>
<LG N="19" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(19) Benigne fac domine in bona uoluntate tua syon: &amp; edificentur muri ierusalem.</HEAD>
<L>With benygne wil, do to syon,</L>
<L>That ierusalem walles were wrou&yogh;t.</L>
<L>Ierusalem, as telle&thorn; seynt Ion,</L>
<L N="148">Is holy churche &thorn;at erre&thorn; nou&yogh;t:</L>
<L>Tho testamentis cordi&thorn; in on.</L>
<L>The wall&euml;s were to-gidre brou&yogh;t,</L>
<L>When cryst hym self was corner ston,</L>
<L N="152">That mann&euml;s synne ha&thorn; dere ybou&yogh;t.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="20" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(20) Tunc acceptabis sacrificium iusticie oblaciones &amp; holocausta: tunc im|ponent super altare tuum [vitulos]<NOTE PLACE="foot">vitulos <I>omitted</I>.</NOTE> domine.<MILESTONE N="100b" UNIT="folio"></HEAD>
<L>Than schalt &thorn;ou sacrifice accepte</L>
<L>Of ri&yogh;twisnesse &amp; treu&thorn;e entere;</L>
<L>And calu&euml;s, aftur &thorn;i precepte,</L>
<L N="156">Schulle be leide on &thorn;ine autere;</L>
<L>On caluarie a calf &thorn;er crepte.</L>
<L>Cryst on crosse, bo&thorn;e clene &amp; clere!</L>
<L>For &thorn;o teeris &thorn;at &thorn;i modre wepte,</L>
<L N="160">Thow schelde [us] fro &thorn;e fendes fere! Amen!</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>[<I>In a later hand:</I>]</HEAD>
<L>now, lord, be thou our helpe &amp; guide,</L>
<L>and pardon things that cause vs slide!
</L>
</LG>

</DIV2>
<DIV2 TYPE="poem"><PB REF="00000336.tif" N="286">
<HEAD>Verse Prolog and Epilog to a Book on Medicine.</HEAD>
<HEADNOTE><P><I>Verses written as a Preface to an English Treatise on Medicine.</I> (From Dr. J. F. Payne's vellum MS. of the first half of the 15th century.)<NOTE PLACE="foot">(S. is Sloane 1314; Sl. is Sloane 2584, of the same type as P.</NOTE></P></HEADNOTE>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>The man &thorn;at wol of lechecraft lere,</L>
<L>Red ovyr this book, and he may here</L>
<L>Many medycinis both<NOTE PLACE="foot">Many a medicyn S. Sl.</NOTE> good and trewe<NOTE PLACE="foot">trewe S. Sl., newe P.</NOTE></L>
<L N="4">To hel&euml;<NOTE PLACE="foot">To alle S., To leche Sl.</NOTE> sores both oolde and newe,</L>
<L><NOTE PLACE="foot">S. and Sl. leave out lines 5-10.</NOTE>And preciouse medycinis, &thorn;orw goddis grace,</L>
<L>To save men lyves in diverse place.</L>
<L>Cryst, &thorn;at made bothe Est and West,</L>
<L N="8">Geve grace her sowl&euml;s have god rest,</L>
<L>Evere more in hevene for to be,</L>
<L>In hevene wyt &thorn;<SUP>e</SUP> Trinite.</L>
<L>Her-inne be medycinis, wythout-yn fable,</L>
<L N="12">To hele alle sores &thorn;at ben cur&aacute;ble,</L>
<L>Of swerd, of knyf, and of arwe,&mdash;</L>
<L>Be &thorn;e wounde wyde or narwe,&mdash;</L>
<L>Of sper, of quarel, of dagger, of<NOTE PLACE="foot">of dagger of PS., or . . . or Sl.</NOTE> dart,</L>
<L N="16">To make him hool in ylk&euml;<NOTE PLACE="foot">in ilka S., on eche Sl.</NOTE> part,</L>
<L>So<NOTE PLACE="foot">&yogh;yf S., So &thorn;at Sl.</NOTE> &thorn;e seek wol do wysely,</L>
<L>And kepe him-self fro surfety.<NOTE PLACE="foot">from queysy S., fro serfetrie Sl.</NOTE></L>
<L>Be &thorn;e wounde nevere so deep,</L>
<L N="20">&THORN;er-of dar<NOTE PLACE="foot">thar S., &thorn;ar hem (<I>om.</I> no kepe) Sl.</NOTE> him take no kep,
<PB REF="00000337.tif" N="287"></L>
<L>So &thorn;at he drynke save<NOTE PLACE="foot">&yogh;yf he drynk antioche or saue S., So &thorn;at &thorn;ei drynke saue or antioche Sl., So . . save or anteocke P.</NOTE> or anteoche,</L>
<L>Him dar not drede of &thorn;at outrage:<NOTE PLACE="foot">Hem . . of non outrage Sl., &amp; Drede of hys wondes thar hym non haue S.</NOTE></L>
<L>Be &thorn;at on and twenti days be goon,<NOTE PLACE="foot">Be on &amp; twenti dayes gone S., Be . . be comyn and goon P., Be &thorn;at .21. daies be come &amp; gon Sl.</NOTE></L>
<L N="24">He schal be hol, both<NOTE PLACE="foot">both <I>om.</I> S., bo&thorn;e Sl.</NOTE> flesch and bon,</L>
<L>To ride and go in ylk[o]n<NOTE PLACE="foot">ilka S., eche Sl.</NOTE> place,</L>
<L>Thorw &thorn;e verteu<NOTE PLACE="foot">myht S., my&yogh;ht Sl.</NOTE> of goddys grace;</L>
<L>Thus seyth Ypocras, &thorn;e good surgien,</L>
<L N="28">And socrates and Galyen,</L>
<L>&THORN;at weren<NOTE PLACE="foot">wore Sl.</NOTE> philisophres alle thre,</L>
<L>&THORN;at tyme &thorn;e best<NOTE PLACE="foot">&THORN;e best &thorn;at were S., &thorn;e best Sl.</NOTE> in any countree:</L>
<L>In &thorn;is we[r]ld were non her pere,</L>
<L N="32">As fer as any man coude<NOTE PLACE="foot">Als wyde as men myht here S., As fer . . myght Sl.</NOTE> here.</L>
<L>&THORN;ei<NOTE PLACE="foot">And Sl.</NOTE> practised medicynus, wit<NOTE PLACE="foot">be Sl.</NOTE> godus grace,</L>
<L>To saue men lyues<NOTE PLACE="foot">mannes lyf Sl.</NOTE> in many a<NOTE PLACE="foot">in dyuers Sl.</NOTE> place.</L>
<L>Crist &thorn;at made bothe est and west,</L>
<L N="36">Grant her soules in heuen,<NOTE PLACE="foot">Leue here soules haue Sl.</NOTE> good rest,</L>
<L>Euermore in ioy to be</L>
<L>In heuen with god in trinite.<NOTE PLACE="foot">In . . . trinite Sl., <I>om.</I> P.</NOTE></L>
<L N="39">Amen!<NOTE PLACE="foot">Amen P., <I>om.</I> Sl.</NOTE> Amen! for charite.</L>
</LG>
<P>(The verses in the Payne MS. are written in double columns, and the order of the first eight verses is a little confused; so I have corrected it.)</P>
<P>The above agrees very nearly with a poem printed by the Rev. G. Henslow, in his <I>Medical Works of the</I> 14th <I>Century</I>, p. 125 (1899), from Sloane MS. 2584; with variants from Sloane MS. 1314.
<PB REF="00000338.tif" N="288"></P>
<P>At the end are the following verses, which I have not seen elsewhere:&mdash;</P>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>This book hat Ypocras,</L>
<L>Oon of &thorn;e beest surgien &thorn;at evere was;</L>
<L>And Galien his felaw, and Socrates,</L>
<L>To &thorn;is book &thorn;[e]i beren witnesse,</L>
<L>Ffor alle &thorn;ei were felawes &amp; fere</L>
<L>Whil &thorn;ei leveden in erde here;</L>
<L>And &thorn;orw &thorn;e grace of hevene kyng,</L>
<L>&THORN;ei practiseden medicines to helpe manky[n]d.</L>
<L>Prey we alle to ihesu, hevene kyng,</L>
<L>&THORN;at [he] gif her sowles god wonnyng.<NOTE PLACE="end">These verses are at the end of the same treatise (fol. 20<SUP>*</SUP> or page 40), which appears to be quite complete. It refers to "the good Earl of Hereford, that was a noble surgeon"; and I think must have been composed in the 14th century.&mdash;J. F. PAYNE.</NOTE>
</L>
</LG>

</DIV2>
<DIV2 TYPE="poem"><PB REF="00000339.tif" N="289">
<HEAD>The Prentise unto woe,</HEAD>
<HEADNOTE><P>By HENRY BARADOUN, ab. 1483. <I>Hodson MS.</I> 39, <I>leaf</I> 4; 2nd <I>flyleaf.</I> (<I>Mr. Hodson's</I> 3rd <I>MS. of Chaucer's Canterbury Tales.</I>)<NOTE PLACE="foot">Mr. Hodson's Librarian, Miss Constance Belliss, kindly copied the poem for me, and read the proof with the MS.</NOTE></P></HEADNOTE>
<LG N="1" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(1)</HEAD>
<L>Musyng alone, voide of consolacion,<MILESTONE N="4" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>Drown&egrave;d in sorowe, sighyng wondre sore,</L>
<L>I may complayn, with deedly lamentacion,</L>
<L N="4">My tyme evill spent / sith first I was bore;</L>
<L>My yong&euml; yeres, in Courte I haue forlore;</L>
<L>&YOGH;hit, not-withstondyng howe I haue so do,</L>
<L>Vnto more peyne then I was into-fore,</L>
<L N="8">I haue me yoked, as prentice vnto woo.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="2" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(2)</HEAD>
<L>&para; For<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. As for.</NOTE> liberte is laide alone apart;</L>
<L>My will also, hath no dominacion;</L>
<L>And as for eas&euml;, that most nedis depart;</L>
<L N="12">A greuous payn, in myn oppin&iuml;on:</L>
<L>labour &amp; trouble hath predominacion</L>
<L>Of my spiritis, wher-euer I ride or go:</L>
<L>hertis ease &amp; I be not at vnion:</L>
<L N="16">Thus am I yoked / a prentise vnto wo.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="3" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(3)</HEAD>
<L>&para; In the courte, is many noble Roome;</L>
<L>But god knowith, I can noon soch&euml; cacche:</L>
<L>ffrom a maister, I am be-come a grome,</L>
<L N="20">And bonde mysilff to waytyng &amp; to wacche;</L>
<L>With euere gadrin, I stonde behynde the hacche,</L>
<L>Gapyng &amp; staryng / wanderyng to &amp; fro;</L>
<L>&YOGH;hit for all this, no good can I cacche:</L>
<L N="24">Thus am I prentice &amp; seruaunt vnto woo.
<PB REF="00000340.tif" N="290"></L>
</LG>
<LG N="4" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(4)</HEAD>
<L>&para; When I wolde etc, nature for to sustayn,</L>
<L>Or I may haue it / myn appetite is past;</L>
<L>When I wolde slep&euml;, to releve my payn,</L>
<L N="28">I do but slumbre / for I most rise in hast;</L>
<L>When I wolde speke / my lippes be closed fast;</L>
<L>When I wolde sporte with company also,</L>
<L>I dare not out / I am so sore agast:</L>
<L N="32">Thus am I prentice to wrecchidnes &amp; wo.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="5" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(5)</HEAD>
<L>&para; Whan I wolde pray, &amp; serue my heuynly kyng,</L>
<L>(As euery creature is bounde of verrey right,)</L>
<L>Anon ther is some obstacle or thyng</L>
<L N="36">That pullyth me thens, magre of my might;</L>
<L>Soche is my liff, by day and eke by nyght;</L>
<L>And be-side this, my frende well fro my ffo</L>
<L>I can not knowe / this I, most wrecched wight,<MILESTONE N="4b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="40">haue bounde me prentice to misery and wo.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="6" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(6)</HEAD>
<L>&para; Well is he, that can holde hym content</L>
<L>With a meane lif&euml;, voide of gredynes,</L>
<L>Out of trouble leuyng, with litle rent,</L>
<L N="44">beyng at home in perfite stedfastnes,</L>
<L>Wher pompe nor envy is counted for mastres.</L>
<L>Soche a life, not I, but othir moo</L>
<L>Myght haue full wele; but &yogh;hit folissh wilfulnes</L>
<L>Doth bynde ffolkys prentise to wrecchidnes and wo.</L>
<TRAILER>Baradoun henricus traistulit istud opus &thorn;er semet ipsum.
</TRAILER>

</LG>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 TYPE="poem"><PB REF="00000341.tif" N="291">
<HEAD>Hymn to the Virgin.</HEAD>
<HEADNOTE><P>BY WILLIAM HUCHEN.</P><P>[MS. no. cccxx. in the Library of New College, Oxford.]</P><P>THE MS., written about 1460, contains the Psalter in the later Wyclif version (Purvey), and prose translations of various canticles. The hymn, which is on the last page, appears to be in the same handwriting as the rest. Each of the seven stanzas (in "rime royal") is an acrostic on the name <I>Stanlei</I>. The person meant may possibly be Sir Thomas Stanley, who was created Baron Stanley in 1456, and died in 1459.&mdash;HENRY BRADLEY.</P></HEADNOTE>
<LG N="1" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(1)</HEAD>
<L N="1">Swete and benygne moder and may,</L>
<L>Turtill trew, flowre of women alle,</L>
<L>Aurora bryght, clere as the day,</L>
<L>Noblest of hewe, &thorn;us we the calle;</L>
<L N="5">Lyle fragrant eke of the walle;</L>
<L>Ennewid wi&thorn; bemys of blys,</L>
<L N="7">In whom neuer was founden mys.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="2" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(2)</HEAD>
<L N="8">So fayre, so good, was neuer non;</L>
<L>Transcendyng is ther-for &thorn;i place</L>
<L>Aungels alle and seyntis echone;</L>
<L>Next vnto god, such is &thorn;i grace.</L>
<L N="12">Lo, &thorn;i mekenes &thorn;e did purchace</L>
<L>Euer in ioy so to endure</L>
<L>In &thorn;i grete lande [<I>sic</I>], o princes pure.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="3" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(3)</HEAD>
<L N="15">Surmountyng is &thorn;in excellence,</L>
<L>Thou rose of prys, thou flowre of may;</L>
<L>And phebus lyke in his ascence,</L>
<L>Natyff of blys where &thorn;ou art ay,</L>
<L N="19">Lady saunzpere, &thorn;is is no nay.</L>
<L>Empres of helle also of righte,</L>
<L N="21">In &thorn;e is eke owre anker pight
<PB REF="00000342.tif" N="292"></L>
</LG>
<LG N="4" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(4)</HEAD>
<L N="22">Stormys ageyne of cruell syn</L>
<L>That puyssauntlye us do assayle;</L>
<L>And while we &thorn;is world be yn</L>
<L>Now, lady fayre, &thorn;ou us not fayle.</L>
<L N="26">Lat neuer vice on us prevayle.</L>
<L>Entrete &thorn;i babe, so, quene on hie,</L>
<L N="28">In whom to &thorn;e is no denye.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="5" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(5)</HEAD>
<L N="29">Si&thorn; here is nought but myserie;</L>
<L>The fende, &thorn;e fleish, &thorn;e world also,</L>
<L>Assaute us ay wi&thorn;-oute mercy.</L>
<L>Not comfortles &yogh;it is owre wo;</L>
<L N="33">Lady, to &thorn;e resorte we do,</L>
<L>Euyr tristyng thi grace and ayde,</L>
<L N="35">In whom fully owre trist is layde.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="6" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(6)</HEAD>
<L N="36">Sewte and servise we owe, parde,</L>
<L>To &thorn;i hi&yogh;nesse of very due,</L>
<L>As royall most by pedigre,</L>
<L>None lyke of grace ne of vertu,</L>
<L N="40">Louely lady, &thorn;i servauntes trew,</L>
<L>Entrikid wi&thorn; passiouns wylde,</L>
<L N="42">In tyme of nede socour and shilde.</L>
</LG>
<LG N="7" TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(7)</HEAD>
<L N="43">Saue hem fro syn and worldly shame</L>
<L>That &thorn;e worship with humble herte,</L>
<L>And to &thorn;i son, iesus by name,</L>
<L>Not sete (<I>sic</I>) to pray that we not smert.</L>
<L N="47">Lord, &thorn;i iugement we may not sterte;</L>
<L>Euere &thorn;erfor thi grace us hight,</L>
<L N="49">In worship of &thorn;i modere bright.</L>
<SIGNED>By William Huchen.</SIGNED>
</LG>
</DIV2>
